window.CARD_DATA = [
{"id":"cnh-002","num":"二","category":"China · History","question":"In Chinese creation mythology, the primordial giant <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is born inside an egg of chaos and labours for eighteen thousand years to push heaven and earth apart; when he dies his body becomes the world, his eyes turning into the Sun and Moon and his blood into the rivers — a tale first set down by the third-century writer Xu Zheng in the <i>Sanwu Liji</i>.","answer":"Pangu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">First recorded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 3rd century CE — Xu Zheng's <i>Sanwu Liji</i>, Three Kingdoms period</span></div>","traditional":"盤古","hanzi":"盘古","pinyin":"Pángǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pángǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Pangu</b> is the primordial giant of Chinese creation mythology, the first being, born from a chaos shaped like an egg, whose growth and death bring the ordered world into being. He is a fairly late figure, unmentioned in the ancient classics and postdating the creator-goddess Nüwa by about six centuries. His oldest account is the 3rd-century <i>Sanwu Liji</i>, credited to the Eastern Wu Daoist Xu Zheng, while the story of his change into the world survives in a companion fragment, the <i>Wuyun Linian Ji</i>, both now lost and known only from later quotation. He is pictured as a hairy, horned giant in leaves or animal skins and holding a great axe, sometimes attended by four lucky animals: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_dragon\">dragon</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fenghuang\">fenghuang</span>, tortoise, and qilin. His cosmic body remade into the world is the Chinese case of a widespread mythic motif, often compared with the Norse Ymir, the Mesopotamian Tiamat, and the Vedic Purusha, though scholars debate whether these parallels reflect diffusion, southern non-Han traditions, or independent invention. <br><br> At first, heaven and earth lay fused in a formless chaos shaped like the inside of a hen's egg, and within it Pangu came into being. When the egg broke open, the clear <i>yang</i> rose to form the sky and the murky <i>yin</i> sank to form the earth, parted in some tellings by his axe. To hold them apart he stood between them and grew ten feet taller each day for eighteen thousand years, until the heavens reached full height. Worn out, Pangu died, and his body became the world: his breath the wind and clouds, his voice the thunder, his left eye the Sun and right eye the Moon, his blood the rivers, his hair the stars, and his limbs the sacred mountains of the four directions. One strand adds that the creatures on his body, brought to life by the wind, became human beings, the black-haired people, while another makes them animals.","citation":"","answerText":"Pangu"},
{"id":"cnh-003","num":"三","category":"China · History","question":"Traditionally the first of the Three Sovereigns and a serpent-bodied culture-hero of Chinese legend, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is credited with devising the eight trigrams of the <i>Yijing</i> after contemplating the patterns of heaven and earth, with inventing nets for fishing and hunting, and with founding marriage; he is paired in myth with the goddess Nüwa.","answer":"Fuxi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Traditional reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2852–2737 BCE — legendary chronology</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"伏羲","pinyin":"Fúxī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fúxī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Fuxi</b> is a culture-hero and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mythology\">mythical </span>sovereign of early China, listed first among the Three Sovereigns, said to have founded civilization before the dynasties. He is the legendary inventor of the eight trigrams, the <i>bagua</i>, the divination symbols behind the <i>Yijing</i>, and is credited with inventing nets, taming animals, and using fire for cooking, music, and marriage. He is first mentioned only in Warring States texts like the <i>Zhuangzi</i> and <i>Chuci</i>, while the source for his trigrams is the <i>Xici</i>, a commentary added to the <i>Yijing</i> around the 3rd century BCE, far later than the book's Bronze Age core, which never names him. His story was absent from Sima Qian's <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> and came only in the 8th century CE, when the Tang scholar Sima Zhen added an <i>Annals of the Three Sovereigns</i> before the Yellow Emperor. Scholars see him as a composite figure slowly turned into history, not a real king, formed when a separate eastern god, Taihao, merged with him and he was paired with the goddess Nüwa. <br><br> In the <i>Xici</i> account, Fuxi looked up to the heavens and down to the earth, studied the markings of birds and beasts, and made the eight trigrams to grasp the world. Another tradition says the design was shown to him on a dragon-horse from the river, later called the River Map, though sources disagree whether it was the Yellow River or the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_River\">Luo</span>. From the same trigrams he is said to have drawn the woven net, teaching people to catch fish and game, and the symbols began to replace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Knotted-cord_record-keeping\">knotted-cord records</span> as a step toward writing. Fuxi is shown with a human upper body and a serpent's tail, entwined with the serpent-tailed Nüwa, called his sister, wife, or both. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han </span>funerary art the pair hold emblems of cosmic order, Fuxi a carpenter's square and Nüwa compasses, from second-century reliefs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Liang_Shrine\">Wu Liang shrine</span> in Shandong.","citation":"","answerText":"Fuxi"},
{"id":"cnh-004","num":"四","category":"China · History","question":"A serpent-bodied creator-goddess of Chinese mythology, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is said to have fashioned the first human beings from yellow clay and, after the water-god Gonggong shattered a pillar of heaven, to have patched the broken sky with stones of five colours; she is often paired with Fuxi as his sister or wife.","answer":"Nüwa","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">First attested</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Warring States — the <i>Tianwen</i> of the <i>Chuci</i>, c. 3rd century BCE</span></div>","traditional":"女媧","hanzi":"女娲","pinyin":"Nǚwā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nǚwā</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Nüwa</b> is a serpent-bodied mother-goddess of Chinese mythology, honored as the divine creator of humankind and the mender of a broken heaven. She is among the earliest deities in the written record, named in Warring States material such as the <i>Tianwen</i> of the <i>Chuci</i>, centuries before the late creation-figure Pangu was first written down. Besides shaping the first people, she was credited with inventing marriage and worshipped as a goddess of matchmaking, the mother-ancestress from whom all humanity descended. She is often paired with Fuxi, the two shown as serpent-tailed figures with entwined tails, she holding a compass for the heavens and he a carpenter's square for the earth, in a bond texts call brother-and-sister, husband-and-wife, or both. Modern scholars read Nüwa as a creation-goddess who acts alone in the oldest layers, with some proposing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Totem\">totemic</span> origins in a snake or a frog and a matriarchal stage into which Fuxi was later added. <br><br> In the human-creation myth, best known from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>-era <i>Fengsu Tongyi</i>, Nüwa shaped the first people from yellow earth, and when she tired she trailed a cord through the mud and flicked the drops into the common folk. The story also explained social rank, the hand-shaped figures becoming the noble and the cord-spattered droplets the lowly. Her other great deed, told in the <i>Huainanzi</i>, comes after a disaster in which the sky's four pillars collapsed, fire and flood raged, and beasts devoured the helpless. Nüwa smelted stones of five colours to mend the azure sky, cut the legs from a giant turtle to prop up its corners, slew a black dragon to calm the waters, and dammed the flood with the ashes of burnt reeds. Later tradition blamed the ruin on the water-god Gonggong, who had butted his head against the heaven-pillar of Mount Buzhou, tilting the world ever after toward the northwest above and the southeast below, a slope her repairs could ease but never undo.","citation":"","answerText":"Nüwa"},
{"id":"cnh-005","num":"五","category":"China · History","question":"In a fit of rage after losing a contest for the throne of heaven, the destructive water-god <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> smashed his head against Mount Buzhou, snapping the pillar that propped up the sky and tilting the cosmos so that the heavens lean to the northwest and the rivers run to the southeast — the very disaster the goddess Nüwa was left to repair.","answer":"Gonggong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">First attested</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Warring States — the <i>Chuci</i>'s <i>Heavenly Questions</i>, before 221 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"共工","pinyin":"Gònggōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gònggōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Gonggong</b> is a water-god of ancient Chinese mythology, a destructive bringer of floods who was blamed for one of the great disasters of the cosmos. People pictured him as a serpent-bodied being with a copper human head, an iron brow, and red hair, and his given name is recorded as <b>Kanghui</b>. The stories disagree about whom he fought before his rampage, naming his rival as the high god Zhuanxu, the fire-god Zhurong, or others, but every version agrees that he lost a struggle for power and lashed out in fury. Cast as a villain, he was remembered as one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Perils\">Four Perils&nbsp;</span>whom the sage-king Shun banished to the far north, and his flood-spreading minister was the venomous nine-headed serpent Xiangliu, slain in some accounts by Yu the Great. Later scholars have read Gonggong as the memory of a clan of water-engineers, and his myth as an echo of real struggles over flood control in early China. <br><br> The myth that defines him tells how the beaten and enraged Gonggong hurled himself head-first at Mount Buzhou, the towering pillar that held up the northwestern corner of the sky. The blow snapped the pillar and tore the cords that moored the earth, so the heavens tipped down toward the northwest and the ground sagged away to the southeast. People offered this imbalance as the reason the sun, moon, and stars all slide toward the northwest, while China's great rivers run away to the southeast. The fullest version, in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>-era <i>Huainanzi</i>, names his opponent as Zhuanxu, but he is already blamed for knocking the world off its axis in the Warring States poem <i>Heavenly Questions</i>, his earliest appearance. The ruin he caused is the very disaster that the goddess Nüwa then set right, smelting five-coloured stones to patch the torn sky and propping it on the severed legs of a giant turtle.","citation":"","answerText":"Gonggong"},
{"id":"cnh-006","num":"六","category":"China · History","question":"Tamer of the Great Flood and traditional founder of China's first dynasty, the Xia, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> succeeded where his father Gun had failed by dredging channels to drain the waters to the sea rather than damming them, labouring for thirteen years and passing his own door three times without ever entering.","answer":"Yu the Great","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Traditional reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2070 BCE — legendary founding of the Xia dynasty</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"大禹","pinyin":"Dà Yǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Yǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yu the Great</b> is a legendary culture-hero of ancient China, remembered for taming the Great Flood and honoured as the founder of the Xia, traditionally the country's first dynasty. Tradition places him at the end of the age of sage-kings, receiving the throne from Shun through the virtuous abdication that had passed rule from Yao to Shun by merit rather than birth. When Yu handed power to his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(deity)\">Qi</span> instead of a chosen minister, that abdication gave way to hereditary succession, the pattern to govern China for millennia. He was remembered as a model of selfless service, said to have toiled at the flood works for thirteen years and to have passed his door three times without stepping inside. Scholars debate whether he was real, since no record survives from his age and his name first appears on bronzes nearly a thousand years later, leading some to read him as a myth or a god later made into history. <br><br> His father Gun was first charged with stopping the flood, but tried to wall the waters out with dikes and dams, failed, and was killed or banished for it. Yu reversed the plan, dredging the silted riverbeds and cutting channels to lead the waters to the sea rather than hold the flood back. Around this practical core gathered legend, among them a helping yellow dragon and black turtle and the magic square of the Luoshu, said to have come from the Luo River on a turtle's shell. Having mastered the rivers, Yu was credited with dividing the realm into the Nine Provinces listed in the <i>Tribute of Yu</i> and casting the Nine Tripod Cauldrons as tokens of his rule. The earliest datable mention is an inscription on a ninth-century-BCE bronze vessel where Heaven commands Yu to spread the land and tame the waters, though a study linking the myth to a real Yellow River flood around 1920 BCE remains disputed.","citation":"","answerText":"Yu the Great"},
{"id":"cnh-007","num":"七","category":"China · History","question":"Traditionally the first dynasty of China, said to have been founded by the flood-queller Yu the Great and to have fallen when its tyrant Jie was overthrown by Tang of Shang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> left no contemporary writing and is known only from much later texts, so scholars still debate whether it truly existed.","answer":"Xia dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2070–1600 BCE — conventional, much disputed</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"夏朝","pinyin":"Xià cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xià cháo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xia dynasty</b> is the name traditional Chinese history gives to the first dynasty of China, the earliest of the three foundational dynasties before the Shang and the Zhou. Its usual dates of about 2070 to 1600 BCE come from a modern state chronology project and are disputed, with rival schemes differing by centuries. Whether the Xia ever existed is debated, since no record from its time survives, it is absent from the Shang oracle bones, the oldest Chinese writing, and it is first named only in texts written centuries later under the early Zhou. Most Chinese archaeologists link the Xia to the Bronze-Age Erlitou culture of western Henan, with its rammed-earth palaces and earliest bronze workshops, but many Western scholars say a nameless culture cannot be matched to a textual dynasty without writing from the time. Some suggest the Zhou built up the dynasty to justify their conquest, the fall of a wicked first house giving a model for the Mandate of Heaven, yet the Xia stands as a cornerstone of Chinese identity through the name <i>Huaxia</i>. <br><br> In the traditional story the dynasty was founded by Yu the Great, the hero who tamed the flood and to whom the sage-king Shun gave the throne for his merit. When Yu's son Qi took power in place of the minister his father meant to succeed, rule by virtuous abdication gave way to inheritance by birth, and family dynasties became the pattern. The line ran through seventeen kings over four and a half centuries, including a famous collapse in which a usurper seized the throne before the exiled heir Shaokang restored it. Its last ruler, the tyrant Jie, was remembered as a cruel and dissolute king whose misrule cost the dynasty Heaven's favour. Tang of Shang defeated Jie at the Battle of Mingtiao, ending the Xia and starting the Shang, in what later tradition called the first turning of the dynastic cycle.","citation":"","answerText":"Xia dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-008","num":"八","category":"China · History","question":"A grandson of the Yellow Emperor and the second of the Five Emperors, the sovereign <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is remembered above all for ordering his officials Chong and Li to sever the free communication between heaven and earth, ending the age when any mortal could ascend to the gods; in five-phase cosmology he became the Black Emperor of the north.","answer":"Zhuanxu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Tradition</span><span class=\"dt-v\">second of the Five Emperors — a legendary 78-year reign</span></div>","traditional":"顓頊","hanzi":"颛顼","pinyin":"Zhuānxū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhuānxū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhuanxu</b> is a legendary sovereign of high antiquity, counted in Sima Qian's history as the second of the Five Emperors and a grandson of the Yellow Emperor, and also known by the clan-name <b>Gaoyang</b>. Modern scholars treat him and the other figures of that age as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mythology\">mythological </span>or euhemerized rulers rather than real kings, since no record from his time names him and his traditional 78-year reign rests only on far later sources. He loomed large as a great ancestor, claimed as forefather by the royal houses of both Qin and Chu, and the lineage descending from him also produced the flood-tamer Yu the Great. In the cosmology of the Five Phases he was assigned to the north and to water, becoming the <b>Black Emperor of winter</b>, whose star is Mercury, and the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> named an ancient calendar after him. He also appears in the cosmic battle in which the water-god Gonggong, defeated in a struggle for supremacy, struck Mount Buzhou and tilted the heavens, though only one of several rival traditions names Zhuanxu as that opponent. <br><br> His most celebrated act was the severing of the communication between heaven and earth, his answer to a chaotic age when gods and mortals mingled freely and all could reach the spirits. Zhuanxu gave the task to two officials, setting Chong over heaven and its spirits and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Zhuanxu_myth)\">Li </span>over the earth and its people, so the two realms were drawn apart. Afterward ordinary people could no longer ascend to the gods at will, and only the sovereign and his ritual specialists kept the power to mediate between the worlds. Scholars read the story as a charter for centralized religious authority, a monopoly over access to heaven that mirrors a stratified society. The reform is told most fully in the <i>Guoyu</i>, which alone names Zhuanxu as its author, while the <i>Book of Documents</i> credits the deed only to an unnamed sovereign.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhuanxu"},
{"id":"cnh-009","num":"九","category":"China · History","question":"First of the Five Emperors and revered as the common ancestor of the Chinese people, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the legendary sovereign who defeated the Flame Emperor and then crushed the war-leader Chiyou at the Battle of Zhuolu — building a south-pointing chariot to find his way through Chiyou's magical fog — and whose very name marks the earth-coloured centre of the cosmos.","answer":"Yellow Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Traditional reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2697–2597 BCE — legendary, first of the Five Emperors</span></div>","traditional":"黃帝","hanzi":"黄帝","pinyin":"Huángdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huángdì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yellow Emperor</b>, or Huangdi in Chinese, is foremost of the legendary Five Emperors, and Sima Qian chose him to open his history of China. His title comes from the cosmology of the Five Phases, in which yellow is the colour of earth and the centre, making him sovereign of the cosmic middle who commands the four directions. Scholars see him not as a real king but as a legendary figure, likely a god at first and later made a man, first attested in a bronze inscription of the 4th century BCE. With his rival-turned-kinsman the Flame Emperor he is the common ancestor of the Chinese, who still call themselves descendants of Yan and Huang, a claim that became a symbol of national identity in the early 20th century. In Daoism he was honoured as a sage and immortal, paired with Laozi in the Huang-Lao school of the early Han, and at his death was said to rise to heaven on a descending dragon. <br><br> Tradition credits him with two great wars, first beating the Flame Emperor at Banquan and merging their peoples, then destroying the bronze-headed war-leader Chiyou at the Battle of Zhuolu. When Chiyou raised a blinding fog over the field, he built a south-pointing chariot to find his way clear, then called down his daughter Ba, the goddess of drought, to burn off the enemy's storm. His victories were remembered as uniting the warring tribes of the northern plain into the people who became the Huaxia Chinese. A vast body of invention was heaped on him and his court, from his minister Cangjie devising the written characters to his wife Leizu discovering silk, along with the calendar, boats, carts, and music. Above all his name lent authority to the <i>Inner Canon of the Yellow Emperor</i>, the foundational text of Chinese medicine, cast as his dialogue with the physician Qibo but compiled around the Han, long after his supposed age.","citation":"","answerText":"Yellow Emperor"},
{"id":"cnh-010","num":"十","category":"China · History","question":"In the legendary clash known as the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the Yellow Emperor defeated the bronze-headed war-leader Chiyou — navigating the magical fog Chiyou raised with a south-pointing chariot and calling on the drought goddess Ba to dry up his storms — a victory traditionally seen as founding the Huaxia Chinese nation.","answer":"Battle of Zhuolu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Traditional date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2500 BCE — legendary, the Five Emperors age</span></div>","traditional":"涿鹿之戰","hanzi":"涿鹿之战","pinyin":"Zhuōlù zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhuōlù zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Battle of Zhuolu</b> is the legendary war in which the Yellow Emperor defeated Chiyou, the fearsome leader of the Nine Li tribes. It is known only from texts written long after its time and filled with figures of the mythic Five Emperors age, and is placed around 2500 BCE in the wilderness of Zhuolu in northern Hebei. Coming after his earlier win over the Flame Emperor at Banquan, it was the second and decisive of two wars by which he bound the warring tribes of the northern plain into the confederation that became the Huaxia Chinese. Chiyou is a monster with a bronze head and iron brow, an inventor of weapons and metalworking later worshipped as a god of war, so both Qin Shi Huang and the founder of the Han sacrificed to him. His people fled southward and gave rise to the Miao and Hmong, who honour him as a great ancestor, so modern accounts sometimes rank him beside the Yellow and Flame Emperors as a third national forefather. <br><br> The fighting is full of marvels, beginning when Chiyou wrapped the field in fog that blotted out the sun and left the imperial army lost for days. To escape it the Yellow Emperor built a south-pointing chariot, whose pointer always held to one direction, guiding his troops clear of the murk. Chiyou then called up the wind god and the rain master to lash the field with storm, until the Yellow Emperor summoned his daughter, the drought goddess Ba, whose parching heat scattered the wind and rain. This duel of dragon and drought is told in the ancient <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, and ends with the winged dragon Yinglong helping bring Chiyou down, the killing blow given in some tellings to the dragon or to Ba. So great was the power that neither Ba nor Yinglong could return to heaven, and both left drought wherever they wandered.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Zhuolu"},
{"id":"cnh-011","num":"十一","category":"China · History","question":"Traditionally the first of the Yellow Emperor's two great wars, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw him defeat the Flame Emperor after three engagements — leading, the histories say, columns of bears and tigers into the fight — after which their two tribes merged into the people who would call themselves the descendants of Yan and Huang.","answer":"Battle of Banquan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Traditional date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2500 BCE — legendary, the Five Emperors age</span></div>","traditional":"阪泉之戰","hanzi":"阪泉之战","pinyin":"Bǎnquán zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bǎnquán zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Battle of Banquan</b> is the legendary war in which the Yellow Emperor beat the Flame Emperor, the first of two conflicts said to have joined the early tribes into one people. The Flame Emperor, also called Yandi, led the old line of Shennong the Divine Farmer, whose rule had weakened as its lords fought one another, and the last of that line was named Yuwang. Like the rest of the Five Emperors story, this is a fully legendary episode, and it survives only in texts written down much later, the fullest being Sima Qian's <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>. Where it happened is unclear, since the name Banquan is claimed by sites in Hebei, in Beijing, and in Shanxi, and the war is usually placed around 2500 BCE. Its lasting importance is the merger it created, because joining the two peoples founded the Yanhuang confederation that grew into the Huaxia, which is why the Chinese still call themselves the descendants of Yan and Huang. <br><br> In that account, the rising Yellow Emperor, then called Xuanyuan, built up his virtue and gathered his forces as the Shennong order fell apart. He met the Flame Emperor on the field of Banquan and won only after three separate battles, taking victory at last on the third. The same source says he led bears, tigers, and other fierce creatures into the fight, a phrase scholars read either as truly trained beasts or as clans marching under animal totems, with the Yellow Emperor's own people bearing the sign of the bear. The beaten Flame Emperor gave in and handed over his place, and the Yellow Emperor took up the role of overlord instead. Their tribes then merged into one and spread along the Yellow River, going on together to crush the war-leader Chiyou at Zhuolu, the second and final war of the founding.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Banquan"},
{"id":"cnh-012","num":"十二","category":"China · History","question":"Co-ancestor of the Chinese people alongside the Yellow Emperor, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the legendary fire-and-south sovereign widely identified with Shennong the Divine Farmer, who taught agriculture and tasted a hundred herbs, and who was defeated by his rival at the Battle of Banquan.","answer":"Yan Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">炎帝 — 'flame emperor', the Red Emperor of fire and the south</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"炎帝","pinyin":"Yándì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yándì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yan Emperor</b>, called Yandi in Chinese and the Flame Emperor in English, is a legendary ruler of China's pre-dynastic age whose name itself means flame or blaze. In the cosmology of the Five Phases he stands for fire and the south, the Red Emperor of summer whose star is Mars, set against the Yellow Emperor of the central earth. Like all the figures of that distant age he belongs to legend rather than record, and scholars now read him as a god or culture-hero later turned into a king. Tradition widely identifies him with Shennong the Divine Farmer, but this equation is truly debated, since another reading treats Yan Emperor as a hereditary title borne by a line of rulers over many generations. Whatever his exact identity, he is paired with the Yellow Emperor as a joint forefather of the Chinese, who still call themselves the descendants of Yan and Huang. <br><br> Under the name Shennong he is honored as the founder of farming, said to have made the plough and taught the people to sow the five grains as one of the Three Sovereigns of high antiquity. He is remembered most for tasting plant after plant on his own body to learn which could heal and which could kill, so he became the patron of herbal medicine and the legendary author of its first great classic, the <i>Divine Farmer's Materia Medica</i>. The same lore credits him with discovering tea, an antidote to the poisons he swallowed, and says he died at last from a yellow-flowered herb that tore his bowels before he could reach his cure. In the political legend his line had fallen into decline when the rising Yellow Emperor met its last ruler, Yuwang, in the field of Banquan and beat him in three engagements. The defeated Yan Emperor submitted, and his people merged with the victor's into the Yanhuang confederation that grew into the Huaxia Chinese.","citation":"","answerText":"Yan Emperor"},
{"id":"cnh-013","num":"十三","category":"China · History","question":"Born in the state of Lu around 551 BCE, the philosopher and teacher <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> taught a way of benevolence, ritual, and virtuous government that he cast as a revival of ancient wisdom; his disciples gathered his sayings into the <i>Analects</i>, and the school he founded became the moral and political orthodoxy of imperial China for two thousand years.","answer":"Confucius","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Lifespan</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 551–479 BCE — Spring and Autumn period, state of Lu</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"孔子","pinyin":"Kǒngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kǒngzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Confucius</b> is the Latinized name Jesuit missionaries coined for <b>Kong Fuzi</b>, or '<b>Master Kong,</b>' the honorific of the Chinese philosopher and teacher <b>Kong Qiu</b>. He lived from about 551 to 479 BCE in the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span>, in the closing years of the Spring and Autumn period, when the Zhou order was breaking into rival states. He saw himself as a transmitter, not a maker, claiming only to revive the wisdom of the early Zhou and its sage the Duke of Zhou, yet the school he founded, Confucianism, shaped Chinese thought for over two thousand years. His teachings survive most reliably in the <i>Analects</i>, sayings his disciples gathered and edited after his death, not a book he wrote. Tradition also credited him with editing the Five Classics and composing the chronicle called the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, but most scholars doubt he had much to do with them. <br><br> Born to modest means and orphaned of his father young, he became a teacher who took pupils of any background and drew a reported three thousand students. He held office in Lu, rising by tradition to minister of crime, but his hopes of reform went unmet, and he spent fourteen years wandering from state to state seeking a ruler who would heed him before returning home to teach until his death. At the heart of his thought lay <i>ren</i>, a humane benevolence, and <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span></i>, the rites and propriety that order conduct and society, with the cultivated <i>junzi</i> or gentleman as its moral ideal above the petty, self-seeking man. He prized filial devotion to parents and ancestors, urged rule by virtue rather than fear and punishment, and taught the rectification of names, that ruler, minister, father, and son each live up to their station. He gave the world one of its earliest statements of the Golden Rule, in the negative: do not do to others what you would not want done to yourself.","citation":"","answerText":"Confucius"},
{"id":"cnh-014","num":"十四","category":"China · History","question":"Named after a terse chronicle of the state of Lu, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> opened in 770 BCE when the Zhou kings fled east to Luoyang and dwindled into figureheads, leaving the great regional lords to vie as 'hegemons'; it was the age of Confucius and the first stirrings of Chinese philosophy, and the first half of the long Eastern Zhou.","answer":"Spring and Autumn period","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 770–476 BCE — first half of the Eastern Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"春秋時代","hanzi":"春秋时代","pinyin":"Chūnqiū shídài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chūnqiū shídài</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Spring and Autumn period</b> is the name for the first half of the Eastern Zhou dynasty, running by convention from 770 to about 476 BCE, though scholars date its close in different ways. It takes its name from the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, a terse year-by-year chronicle of the state of Lu that tradition says Confucius himself edited. It began in 770 BCE, after marauders sacked the Zhou capital in the west and killed the king. His successor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Ping_of_Zhou\">King Ping</span>, then moved the court east to Luoyi near modern Luoyang. From that move the Zhou king kept his sacred prestige but little real power, ruling only a small domain while the regional lords grew into all-but-independent states. <br><br> Across the period these states warred and swallowed one another, and the chronicles name some 148 of them, most of which were absorbed by the four greatest, Jin, Chu, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span>, and Qin. Real leadership fell instead to a line of overlords called hegemons, strong rulers whom the Zhou king licensed to marshal the other states under the banner of revering the king and repelling the barbarians. Tradition counts Five Hegemons, though the lists differ, and the first and clearest was Duke Huan of Qi, raised to dominance by the reforms of his able minister Guan Zhong. Warfare was still largely an aristocratic affair of chariots fought by ritual conventions, but it grew steadily larger and harsher as the old Zhou order broke down. Late in the period lived Confucius, and with him began the great flowering of thought later called the Hundred Schools, the seedbed of classical Chinese philosophy, and the age ended when the mighty state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_(state)\">Jin </span>was partitioned among three of its noble families into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>, Zhao, and Wei, opening the harsher era of the Warring States.","citation":"","answerText":"Spring and Autumn period"},
{"id":"cnh-016","num":"十六","category":"China · History","question":"China's second traditional dynasty and the first confirmed by its own writing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> left tens of thousands of oracle bones at its capital near Anyang, ruled there over a great Bronze Age culture of ritual vessels and ancestor worship, and fell when its last king was overthrown by the Zhou at the Battle of Muye.","answer":"Shang dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1600–1046 BCE — second dynasty, after the Xia</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"商朝","pinyin":"Shāng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shāng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shang dynasty</b> was the second dynasty of traditional Chinese history, following the Xia and preceding the Zhou, and is also called the Yin after its last capital. It is dated to about 1600 to 1046 BCE with roughly 31 kings, and is the earliest Chinese dynasty confirmed by archaeology and by records written in its own time, unlike the still-unproven Xia. Tradition says Tang founded it by overthrowing the tyrant Jie of Xia at the Battle of Mingtiao, and its kings moved their capital often until Pan Geng fixed it at Yin, near modern Anyang in Henan. The inscriptions dug from that site matched the list of Shang kings that Sima Qian recorded centuries later in his <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>, proving the dynasty real. It fell around 1046 BCE when its last king, Di Xin, remembered as cruel though scholars suspect the charges grew in the retelling, was defeated by King Wu of Zhou at the Battle of Muye, which the Zhou justified by the Mandate of Heaven. <br><br> The dynasty is known above all for the oracle bones, ox shoulder-blades and turtle shells on which its kings recorded their divinations, the oldest surviving Chinese writing. A diviner would heat a bone until it cracked, read the cracks as the ancestors' answer, and carve the question, and sometimes its outcome, beside them, asking about war, harvest, weather, the hunt, childbirth, and sacrifice. The bones were first noticed in 1899, when inscribed dragon bones sold as medicine were recognized as ancient script, and traced to the ruins of Yin, which have yielded over a hundred thousand fragments. The Shang were master bronze-casters, building ritual vessels such as the three-legged <i>ding</i> from clay moulds and offering food and wine to their royal ancestors. Their religion centred on a high god, Di, reached only through the dead kings, and their tombs, like that of warrior-queen Fu Hao, held bronzes, jades, and human sacrifices.","citation":"","answerText":"Shang dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-017","num":"十七","category":"China · History","question":"The longest-lived of all Chinese dynasties, lasting nearly eight centuries from about 1046 BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> overthrew the Shang and justified the conquest with the new doctrine of the Mandate of Heaven, until the state of Qin extinguished it in 256 BCE.","answer":"Zhou dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1046–256 BCE — third dynasty, the longest in Chinese history</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"周朝","pinyin":"Zhōu cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Zhou dynasty</b> was the third of the great dynasties of ancient China, succeeding the Shang, and at nearly eight hundred years it was the longest-lasting in all Chinese history. The Zhou had once been a vassal people of the Wei River valley in the west, until their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span> finished the work of his father King Wen and overthrew the last Shang king at the Battle of Muye around 1046 BCE. To justify toppling their overlords, they proclaimed the Mandate of Heaven, the idea that Heaven gives rule to a virtuous Son of Heaven and takes it from a wicked one, which became the charter for every later change of dynasty. When King Wu died soon after, his brother the Duke of Zhou ruled as regent for the boy-king, crushed a great revolt, and laid down the rituals and institutions for which later Confucians honored him as a sage. The kings handed their conquered lands to kinsmen and allies as hereditary lords under a system called <i>fengjian</i>, a decentralized order often likened, imperfectly, to European feudalism. <br><br> Historians divide the dynasty into a strong Western Zhou, ruling from a capital near modern Xi'an, and the long, weak Eastern Zhou that came after. The Western Zhou fell in 771 BCE when nomads sacked the western capital and killed King You, so his heir moved the court east to Luoyang and the Zhou king shrank into a mostly symbolic figurehead. From then on real power lay with the regional states, across the centuries historians call the Spring and Autumn and the Warring States periods. Out of this disorder came the dynasty's most enduring legacy, the Hundred Schools of Thought, the classical golden age of Chinese philosophy that gave rise to Confucius and Laozi, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohists </span>and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalists</span>. The shrunken Zhou survived as a ceremonial house until 256 BCE, when the rising state of Qin swallowed its last remnant and soon united all of China.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhou dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-018","num":"十八","category":"China · History","question":"Following the Spring and Autumn era, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the violent final stretch of the Zhou, when seven great states, their rulers each now styling themselves king, waged ever-larger wars of annihilation until the Legalist state of Qin swallowed them all and founded China's first empire in 221 BCE.","answer":"Warring States period","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 475–221 BCE — second half of the Eastern Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"戰國時代","hanzi":"战国时代","pinyin":"Zhànguó shídài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhànguó shídài</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Warring States period</b> is the name historians give to the violent second half of the Eastern Zhou, running by convention from about 475 to 221 BCE. It takes its name from the <i>Strategies of the Warring States</i>, a later collection of the diplomatic intrigues of the age, and is usually said to begin when the powerful state of Jin broke apart into three. The earlier Spring and Autumn era had held scores of small states, but this age was ruled by seven great powers: Qin, Chu, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span>, Yan, and the three Jin successors Han, Zhao, and Wei. The Zhou king had shrunk to a powerless figure who tended little but rituals, and one by one the rulers of the great states threw off the old order and claimed the royal title of king for themselves. Their long struggle ended only in 221 BCE, when Qin had devoured the last of its rivals and its king proclaimed himself the First Emperor of a united China. <br><br> The wars themselves changed, as the chariots and chivalry of old gave way to mass armies of conscripted peasants armed with iron weapons and the crossbow, fighting long campaigns meant to destroy the enemy outright. The scale was staggering, and tradition holds that after the Battle of Changping the Qin general Bai Qi had hundreds of thousands of surrendered Zhao soldiers put to death, a figure historians believe is greatly exaggerated. To fight such wars, the old aristocratic order gave way to centralized states that registered their people, taxed them directly, and promoted men by merit rather than birth. The most ruthless of these were the Legalist reforms of Shang Yang, which forged Qin into a disciplined war machine and set it on the road to conquest. Amid the upheaval the Hundred Schools of Thought reached their height, the golden age of Chinese philosophy that produced thinkers such as Mencius, Zhuangzi, and the Legalist Han Fei.","citation":"","answerText":"Warring States period"},
{"id":"cnh-019","num":"十九","category":"China · History","question":"The first half of the Zhou dynasty, ruled from a western capital near modern Xi'an, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the high age of classical Zhou kingship and bronze inscriptions, governing through a web of enfeoffed kinsmen until nomads sacked the capital and killed its last king in 771 BCE, forcing the court to flee east.","answer":"Western Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1046–771 BCE — first half of the Zhou dynasty</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"西周","pinyin":"Xī Zhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xī Zhōu</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Western Zhou</b> is the name historians give to the first half of the Zhou dynasty, which lasted from the conquest of the Shang around 1046 BCE until 771 BCE. It is called western because the royal seat lay in the west, at the twin capital of Fenghao in the Wei River valley near modern Xi'an, the Zhou homeland, unlike the eastern capital of the later Eastern Zhou. The dynasty was founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span>, but it was secured by his brother the Duke of Zhou, who ruled as regent for the boy-king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Cheng_of_Zhou\">Cheng</span>, crushed a great rebellion, and built the institutions of the realm. Later people saw the reigns of Cheng and his son Kang as a golden age of peace, when the kingdom expanded and its order took shape. To hold their conquests, the kings handed out land and people to royal kinsmen and allies as hereditary lords, the kin-based network known as <i>fengjian</i> that bound the regional states to the throne. <br><br> Much of what is known of the period comes from its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ritual_bronzes\">ritual&nbsp;bronzes</span>, since the Zhou cast long inscriptions inside their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ritual_vessel\">vessels </span>recording royal gifts, land grants, appointments, and campaigns, the richest record of the age. Over time the bonds of kinship slackened and the dynasty weakened, until the harsh and censorious King Li was driven from his throne by a popular uprising. The regency that ruled in his absence, called the Gonghe, began in 841 BCE and opens the first stretch of precisely dated, year-by-year history in China, before which no event can be fixed to an exact year. King Li's son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Xuan_of_Zhou\">King Xuan</span> won back some of the lost authority, but the recovery did not hold. In 771 BCE the last king, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_You_of_Zhou\">You</span>, was killed when the Quanrong nomads, called in by a wronged marquess, sacked the western capital, and his heir left it to move the court east to Luoyang, ending the Western Zhou.","citation":"","answerText":"Western Zhou"},
{"id":"cnh-020","num":"二十","category":"China · History","question":"The Grand Historian at the court of Emperor Wu of Han and the father of Chinese historiography, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> wrote the monumental <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>; rather than die after he was condemned for defending a disgraced general, he chose the shame of castration so that he might live to finish it.","answer":"Sima Qian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Lifespan</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 145 – c. 86 BCE — Western Han, court of Emperor Wu</span></div>","traditional":"司馬遷","hanzi":"司马迁","pinyin":"Sīmǎ Qiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sīmǎ Qiān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sima Qian</b> was a historian of the Western Han dynasty, honoured ever since as the father of Chinese historiography. He served at the court of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> as Grand Historian, an office that combined keeping records with astronomy and the calendar. He inherited this post from his father Sima Tan around 108 BCE. His life's work was the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>, a vast history his father began and he finished to fulfil a deathbed charge, covering some two and a half thousand years from the legendary Yellow Emperor to his own age. Running to about a hundred and thirty chapters and over half a million characters, it became the first of the Twenty-Four Histories, the official chronicles of imperial China. <br><br> Sima Qian invented for it the annals-biography form, weaving the past from dynastic annals, chronological tables, topical treatises, hereditary houses, and biographies, a design every later dynastic history would follow. His name is also bound up with a famous act of endurance, for in 99 BCE he alone spoke up at court to defend the general Li Ling, who had surrendered to the Xiongnu after a hopeless stand. The furious Emperor Wu condemned him to death, and he could escape only by paying a ruinous fine he could not afford or by accepting castration. Castration was the deepest disgrace, a shame a gentleman was expected to answer by suicide, yet Sima Qian chose to live on to finish his father's history, and in the celebrated <i>Letter to Ren An</i> he declared that a man dies but once, a death that may weigh as much as a mountain or as little as a feather. As a historian he worked from archives, documents, and his own travels, sifting legend from fact, writing beyond kings of merchants, assassins, and scholars, and judging even his own emperor with a candour that set the standard for those who came after.","citation":"","answerText":"Sima Qian"},
{"id":"cnh-021","num":"二十一","category":"China · History","question":"China's last imperial dynasty, the Manchu-led <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> seized Beijing in 1644 and grew under its great emperors into the largest empire China had ever known, before a century of Opium Wars and rebellions sapped it and a revolution forced the boy-emperor Puyi to abdicate in 1912, ending two thousand years of monarchy.","answer":"Qing dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1644–1912 — China's last imperial dynasty, Manchu-led</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"清朝","pinyin":"Qīng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Qing dynasty</b> was the last of China's imperial dynasties, and it ruled from 1644 until 1912. It was founded not by the Han Chinese but by the Manchus, a people of the northeastern frontier whose chief Nurhaci had united the Jurchen tribes, and whose son Hong Taiji proclaimed the dynasty of the <b>Great Qing</b> in 1636. When the Ming collapsed to a rebel army in 1644, a Ming general opened the Great Wall's eastern gate to the Manchus, who seized Beijing and over the following decades conquered all of China. They were a small ruling minority over a huge Han majority, so they forced Chinese men to shave their foreheads and wear the braided queue as a badge of submission. Under three long-reigning emperors, Kangxi, Yongzheng, and Qianlong, the Qing entered a golden age and pushed its borders out across Mongolia, Tibet, and Xinjiang to forge the largest empire in Chinese history, while the population swelled past three hundred million. <br><br> The 19th century brought disaster, as Britain laid bare the empire's military weakness in the First Opium War of 1839 to 1842. The defeat forced the Qing to give up Hong Kong and sign the first of the so-called unequal treaties, opening the era Chinese nationalists would later call the Century of Humiliation. At the same time the empire was torn apart by the Taiping Rebellion, a civil war that raged from 1850 to 1864 and killed tens of millions, making it one of the bloodiest conflicts in all of history. Through these crises the court fell more and more under the control of the Empress Dowager Cixi, and further humiliations followed, among them the foreign suppression of the anti-Western Boxer uprising. In 1911 a revolution swept the country, and the next year the child emperor Puyi abdicated, ending the Qing and with it more than two thousand years of imperial rule, in favour of a republic.","citation":"","answerText":"Qing dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-022","num":"二十二","category":"China · History","question":"Founded in 1368 by a peasant rebel who drove out the Mongols, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the last Han-Chinese imperial dynasty; it built the Forbidden City and most of today's Great Wall, sent the eunuch admiral Zheng He on great ocean voyages, and fell in 1644 when a rebel took Beijing and the Manchus seized power.","answer":"Ming dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1368 — 1644</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"明朝","pinyin":"Míng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Míng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Ming dynasty</b> ruled China from 1368 to 1644, the last imperial dynasty governed by the ethnic Han Chinese. It was founded by Zhu Yuanzhang, born into a poor peasant family, who rose through rebellion to drive the Mongols and their Yuan dynasty out of China. He took the throne as the Hongwu Emperor with his capital at Nanjing, and he ruled with a heavy, suspicious hand. He abolished the office of chancellor to gather all power into the throne, a centralizing autocracy that shaped the whole dynasty. His son the Yongle Emperor seized the throne in a civil war, moved the capital north to Beijing, and raised the vast palace of the Forbidden City. <br><br> Yongle also sent the Muslim eunuch admiral Zheng He on seven enormous treasure voyages that reached India, Arabia, and the coast of East Africa, while the Ming rebuilt most of the Great Wall that still stands today, in brick and stone, to hold off the Mongols on the northern frontier. The state was run by a Confucian scholar-bureaucracy recruited through the gruelling imperial examinations and their notorious eight-legged essays, though real power often slid to palace eunuchs and their secret police. It was a brilliant age for arts and commerce, famed for its blue-and-white porcelain and for vernacular novels such as <i>Journey to the West</i>, and bound into a global economy that drew vast quantities of silver from Japan and the Americas. By the early 17th century the dynasty was failing, beset by court faction, a starving treasury, and the famines and epidemics of a colder climate that drove desperate peasants into revolt. In 1644 the rebel Li Zicheng captured Beijing and the last Ming emperor hanged himself on a hill behind his palace, so the Manchus swept in with a defecting Ming general to take the capital and found the Qing, while loyalist Ming princes fought on in the south for nearly twenty years.","citation":"","answerText":"Ming dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-023","num":"二十三","category":"China · History","question":"Founded by Kublai Khan, a grandson of Genghis, the Mongol <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> completed the conquest of the Song in 1279 to reunite China as the first non-Han dynasty to rule it all; ruling from Dadu, now Beijing, it ranked its subjects by ethnicity and drew Eurasian traders like Marco Polo, before the Red Turban revolt and the rising Ming drove it back to the steppe in 1368.","answer":"Yuan dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1271–1368 — the Mongol dynasty, founded by Kublai Khan</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"元朝","pinyin":"Yuán cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuán cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Yuan dynasty</b> was the Mongol-ruled dynasty of China, lasting from 1271 to 1368, and it formed the eastern heart of the vast Mongol Empire. Kublai Khan, a grandson of Genghis Khan, founded it in 1271 when he gave his realm the Chinese dynastic name <b>Great Yuan</b>, a word meaning 'origin' that he took from the <i>I Ching</i>. By 1279 his armies had crushed the Southern Song and drowned its last boy-emperor at sea, reuniting north and south China under one ruler for the first time in some three hundred years. This made the Yuan the first dynasty in which a non-Han people ruled all of China, and its emperors governed from a grand new capital at Dadu, the Khan's city on the site of modern Beijing. They were both Chinese sovereigns and Mongol Great Khans, binding China into a Eurasia-wide empire, though the dynasty itself lasted under a hundred years. <br><br> The Mongols ranked their subjects in a strict four-class order, with themselves at the top, then the foreign, often Central Asian Semu officials who staffed the bureaucracy, then the northern Chinese, and at the bottom the conquered southerners of the former Song. They long suspended the old Confucian examinations and sidelined the Chinese scholar-gentry, while showing broad religious tolerance and favouring Tibetan Buddhism at court. Under the Mongol peace the Silk Road grew safe enough that goods, ideas, and travellers flowed across Eurasia, among them the Venetian Marco Polo, who claimed to have served Kublai's court. The Yuan made paper money its main currency and is remembered as a golden age of Chinese theatre, its <i>zaju</i> dramas the era's great literary achievement. But succession feuds, ruinous inflation from over-printing money, and a mid-century wave of Yellow River floods and famine sparked the Red Turban Rebellion, out of which Zhu Yuanzhang founded the Ming and seized Dadu in 1368, driving the Mongol court back onto the steppe.","citation":"","answerText":"Yuan dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-024","num":"二十四","category":"China · History","question":"A golden age of commerce, art, and invention — the era of the first paper money, gunpowder weapons, and the navigational compass — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> reunified China in 960 and governed through Neo-Confucian scholar-officials, yet, weaker in arms than its steppe neighbours, it lost the north to the Jurchens in 1127 and was finally destroyed by the Mongols in 1279.","answer":"Song dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">960–1279 — Northern Song to 1127, then Southern Song</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"宋朝","pinyin":"Sòng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sòng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Song dynasty</b> ruled China from 960 to 1279 and is remembered as one of the high points of premodern Chinese civilization. The general Zhao Kuangyin founded it and reunited most of the country after the disorder of the Five Dynasties. To prevent the warlordism that had wrecked the Tang, he deliberately placed the army under the control of civil officials. The dynasty was often weaker in war than its steppe neighbours, so rather than conquer them it bought peace with yearly payments of silver and silk to the Khitan Liao and the Tangut Western Xia. In 1127 the Jurchen Jin overran the north, sacked the capital at Kaifeng, and carried off two emperors, so the court fled south and ruled from Hangzhou as the Southern Song. <br><br> That southern remnant held out with fierce resistance for another century and a half until it too fell, overwhelmed at last by Kublai Khan's Mongols in 1279. The Song is famous above all for a commercial revolution, when its cities swelled past a million people, its ships traded as far as East Africa, and its markets used the world's first government paper money, the <i>jiaozi</i>. Champa rice from the south fed a population that climbed toward a hundred million, the largest China had yet known. It was also a golden age of invention, when the compass was first turned to navigation, gunpowder was first put to war, and Bi Sheng devised movable-type printing around the year 1040. The state was run by a large, merit-based class of scholar-officials chosen through a greatly expanded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">examination system</span>, which became the ladder into government and the replacement for the old aristocracy, while the revived philosophy of Neo-Confucianism, brought to its lasting form by Zhu Xi, flowered alongside a celebrated age of landscape painting, lyric poetry, and exquisite porcelain.","citation":"","answerText":"Song dynasty"},
{"id":"cnh-025","num":"二十五","category":"China · History","question":"The southwestern and weakest of the Three Kingdoms, founded in 221 by Liu Bei, who claimed to be restoring the fallen Han, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ruled from Chengdu under the famed chancellor Zhuge Liang and, cast as the righteous side in later legend, became the first of the three states to fall when Wei conquered it in 263.","answer":"Shu Han","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Dates</span><span class=\"dt-v\">221–263 CE — one of the Three Kingdoms</span></div>","traditional":"蜀漢","hanzi":"蜀汉","pinyin":"Shǔ Hàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shǔ Hàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shu Han</b> was one of the three states of the Three Kingdoms, founded in the fifth month of 221 by Liu Bei, a distant Han prince's descendant who rose from selling straw sandals and mats to command an army. In 220 Cao Pi deposed the last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> emperor, Xian, and founded the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Wei</span>, so Liu Bei declared himself emperor and heir of the fallen Han. It called itself simply <b>Han</b>, but historians name it Shu Han after Shu, the old name of its Sichuan heartland. Ruling from Chengdu in Yi Province, it was the smallest and poorest of the three, caught between Cao Wei to the north and Sun Quan's Eastern Wu down the Yangtze. It rose with the 208 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Red Cliffs victory</span>, where Liu Bei and Sun Quan turned back Cao Cao, but fell at Yiling in 222 when Liu Bei's revenge war for Guan Yu was crushed by Wu, and he died at Baidicheng the next year. <br><br> Shu lasted until 263, when a Wei army under Deng Ai crossed into Sichuan and its last ruler, Liu Shan, surrendered, the first of the three to fall. Its fame rests on its heroes: Liu Bei's brotherly generals Guan Yu and Zhang Fei, and his chancellor Zhuge Liang, styled Kongming. Zhuge Liang drew Liu Bei toward empire with the Longzhong Plan after the three visits to his cottage, then after 223 ruled as regent for Liu Shan and led five failed northern campaigns against Wei before dying in 234. Centuries later these heroes filled the fourteenth-century Ming novel <i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i>, seven parts fact and three parts fiction, which cast Shu Han as the righteous line and Cao Cao as the villain. It made Zhuge Liang a near-supernatural strategist and Guan Yu a god of war worshipped across China, and invented much that passes for history, above all the Peach Garden oath binding the three as brothers.","citation":"","answerText":"Shu Han"},
{"id":"cnh-026","num":"二十六","category":"China · History","question":"The primordial chaos of Chinese myth, personified in the <i>Zhuangzi</i> as a faceless emperor who died when two friends bored the seven holes of sense into him, and demonized elsewhere as one of the Four Perils, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was at once the Daoist ideal of undivided wholeness and a fiend of disorder.","answer":"Hundun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Myth</span><span class=\"dt-v\">混沌 — Hùndùn; the primordial chaos of Chinese myth — a faceless emperor in the <i>Zhuangzi</i>, and a monster among the Four Perils</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"混沌","pinyin":"Hùndùn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hùndùn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hundun</b> is the primordial chaos of Chinese myth, but the one name covers three intertwined figures who share a single strange feature, their lack of any face or form. At its root Hundun is the formless, undivided whole that existed before heaven and earth were parted, the shapeless origin out of which the ordered world at last emerged. Its most famous story, told in the <i>Zhuangzi</i>, gives this chaos a shape, or rather the want of one, as an emperor. Hundun was the faceless ruler of the Centre, whom the emperors of the South and North, named Shu and Hu, loved for his kindness; noting that all beings have seven openings by which to see, hear, eat, and breathe, and that he had none, they bored him one hole each day to repay him. On the seventh day, when the last was made, Hundun died, a warning that to carve distinctions into the natural, undivided whole is to destroy it. <br><br> Yet in sterner books Hundun is no gentle emperor but a monster of disorder. The old chronicle called the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i> counts him among the Four Perils, four wicked beings whom the sage-king Shun drove out to the corners of the earth. The <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> pictures a faceless, fiery, bag-shaped thing with six legs and four wings that somehow sings and dances, a creature later readers took for Hundun, while a still later book paints him a blind, deaf beast that fawns upon the wicked and savages the good. So the same chaos was loved and feared at once, to the Daoists a sacred and simple wholeness one longs to return to, to the moralists a fiend of blind disorder to be cast out. Whether whole or wicked, faceless emperor or formless deep, Hundun endured as China's image of the world before all order, from which, some later said, creation hatched like an egg.","citation":"","answerText":"Hundun"},
{"id":"cnh-027","num":"二十七","category":"China · History","question":"Meaning 'without limit,'&nbsp;<span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Daoist name for the boundless, undifferentiated primordial void; the Song philosopher Zhou Dunyi placed it at the head of the cosmos, the Limitless from which arises the Supreme Ultimate that then divides into yin and yang and generates the ten thousand things.","answer":"Wuji","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">無極 — 'without a ridgepole', the limitless void</span></div>","traditional":"無極","hanzi":"无极","pinyin":"Wújí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wújí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wuji</b> is the Chinese cosmological principle of <b>the Limitless</b> or <b>Boundless</b>, the ultimate of non-being, the undifferentiated void out of which existence arises, its name joining the word for 'without' with a character meaning 'ridgepole' or 'extreme point.' The idea is Daoist in origin, appearing in the 28th chapter of the <i>Daodejing</i>, which counsels a return to the limitless, and in the <i>Zhuangzi</i> and <i>Liezi</i> as a name for the infinite and inexhaustible. In these earliest uses it named the boundless, unformed potential of things before any distinction had emerged. Scholars dispute whether such passages already carried the full metaphysical weight later loaded onto the term. It became a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cosmology\">cosmological </span>cornerstone only in the 11th century, when the Northern Song philosopher Zhou Dunyi, a founder of Neo-Confucianism, set it at the head of his cosmos in the <i>Explanation of the Diagram of the Supreme Ultimate</i>, whose opening phrase <i>Wuji er Taiji</i>, the Limitless and yet the Supreme Ultimate, binds the void to the generative pole from which polarity flows. <br><br> In Zhou Dunyi's scheme the Supreme Ultimate, the <i>Taiji</i>, arises from the limitless Wuji and, through alternating movement and stillness, generates yang and yin. From the interplay of yin and yang come the Five Phases of metal, wood, water, fire, and earth, and from these at last the myriad things and human beings of the world. The pairing became fundamental to Neo-Confucian metaphysics after Zhu Xi placed Zhou's essay at the head of his influential anthology and made it orthodox teaching. Yet the relationship of the two ideas sparked a famous dispute, for Zhu Xi held that Wuji named the same ultimate reality as the Taiji while his rival Lu Jiuyuan objected that the word Wuji should never have entered the text at all. Beyond philosophy the term endures in the practice of tai chi, whose opening posture of empty, undivided stillness before any movement is called the Wuji stance.","citation":"","answerText":"Wuji"},
{"id":"cnh-028","num":"二十八","category":"China · History","question":"The 'Supreme Ultimate' of Chinese cosmology, the source from which the two forces of yin and yang divide and, through them, the whole world of change, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is named in the <i>I Ching</i> as the origin of the trigrams, lends its name to the flowing martial art of tai chi, and is pictured in the familiar swirling yin-yang emblem.","answer":"Taiji","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">太極 — 'supreme pole', the Supreme Ultimate</span></div>","traditional":"太極","hanzi":"太极","pinyin":"Tàijí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tàijí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Taiji</b> is <b>the Supreme Ultimate</b> of Chinese cosmology, the highest and most basic principle, the undivided absolute from which the whole ordered world unfolds, and its name joins a word for 'great' or 'supreme' with one for 'ridgepole' or 'extreme point.' Its classic source is the Great Commentary added to the <i>Yijing</i>, the <i>Book of Changes</i>, which says that in the Changes there is the Supreme Ultimate and that it gives birth to the two forms. Those two forms are yin and yang, whose back-and-forth the passage carries on into the four images and then the eight trigrams, from which the 64 hexagrams of divination are built. Chinese thought treats these opposites not as enemies locked in struggle but as balanced, relative, and dependent on each other, each one arising from and completing the other. The concept therefore names the single source of all difference, the pivot where undivided unity turns into the endless interplay of complementary forces. <br><br> The Supreme Ultimate became the cornerstone of Neo-Confucian cosmology in the 11th century, given its classic form by the Northern Song philosopher Zhou Dunyi. In his account it issues from the limitless <i>Wuji</i> and, through cycles of movement and rest, generates yin and yang, then the Five Phases, and at last the myriad things, a scheme that Zhu Xi later made orthodox teaching. The idea is pictured in the <i>taijitu</i>, the Diagram of the Supreme Ultimate, a name shared by Zhou Dunyi's layered chart and by the far more famous swirling emblem of black and white known the world over as the sign of yin and yang. It also gives its name to the martial art of <i>taijiquan</i>, the tai chi whose slow, flowing movements embody the endless alternation of the two forces. In all these forms, from divination diagrams to the modern exercise yard, the Taiji names the generative origin of the yin-yang polarity that runs through Chinese thought.","citation":"","answerText":"Taiji"},
{"id":"cnh-029","num":"二十九","category":"China · History","question":"Named for the shaded and sunlit slopes of a hill and pictured in a swirling black-and-white emblem, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are the complementary, interdependent cosmic forces of dark and light, receptive and active, earth and heaven, whose endless alternation the <i>Yijing</i> identifies with the Dao itself.","answer":"Yin and Yang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">陰陽 — 'shady side and sunny side', the complementary cosmic forces</span></div>","traditional":"陰陽","hanzi":"阴阳","pinyin":"Yīnyáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yīnyáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yin and Yang</b> are the paired complementary forces Chinese thought traces through the cosmos, a dark, receptive, contracting side set against a bright, active, expanding one, their names taken from the shaded northern and sunlit southern slopes of a hill. From that plain image the pair grew into a web of correspondences, yin gathering the moon, cold, water, night, and the female, and yang the sun, heat, fire, day, and the male. They are seen not as enemies but as partners, each giving way to the other and holding a seed of its opposite, so neither can exist alone. Both form out of primordial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(force)\">qi</span>, the vital breath whose clear part rises as yang and whose heavy part settles as yin, a natural principle rather than a moral judgement. Their endless turning is pictured in the <i>taijitu</i>, the circle of interlocking black and white, each half cradling a dot of the other colour. <br><br> This pairing took shape in the Warring States period, and the sinologist Joseph Needham dated its philosophical use to the start of the 4th century BCE. Its scriptural home is the <i>Yijing</i>, the <i>Book of Changes</i>, whose hexagrams are built from broken yin and unbroken yang lines and whose Great Commentary calls the alternation of yin and yang the Dao. The 3rd-century-BCE thinker Zou Yan systematized the doctrine as chief figure of the School of Yin and Yang, the <i>Yinyang jia</i>, binding it to the Five Phases of wood, fire, earth, metal, and water. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>, Dong Zhongshu wove the pair into a cosmology linking heaven, ruler, and society, the <i>Huainanzi</i> gave the fullest account of a world condensing out of qi, and the Song thinker Zhou Dunyi later set them beneath the Supreme Ultimate. Beyond cosmology the pair became the framework of Chinese medicine in the <i>Huangdi Neijing</i>, where health is their balance, and it underpins divination, fengshui, and the martial art of tai chi.","citation":"","answerText":"Yin and Yang"},
{"id":"cnh-030","num":"三十","category":"China · History","question":"Devised in legend by the sage Fuxi and pictured as stacked broken and unbroken lines, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are the eight three-line symbols of Chinese cosmology that pair up to form the 64 hexagrams of the <i>Yijing</i> and still guide divination and feng shui today.","answer":"Eight Trigrams","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">八卦 — 'eight symbols', the eight trigrams</span></div>","traditional":"八卦","hanzi":"八卦","pinyin":"Bāguà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bāguà</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Eight Trigrams</b>, the <i>bagua</i>, are the eight three-line symbols at the heart of Chinese cosmology and divination, each built of three stacked lines that are either broken for yin or unbroken for yang. Since each line can be one of two kinds, there are exactly eight combinations, together thought to model the basic forces of the world. Each trigram stands for a natural image and a family member: Qian is heaven and the father, Kun is earth and the mother, and the rest are Zhen for thunder, Kan for water, Gen for mountain, Xun for wind, Li for fire, and Dui for lake. They grow out of the interplay of yin and yang, following the Great Commentary of the <i>Yijing</i>, in which the Supreme Ultimate produces the two forces, these produce the four images, and the four images produce the eight trigrams. Tradition credits their invention to the sage Fuxi, said to have drawn them after studying the patterns of heaven and earth, or to have copied a design carried from a river by a dragon-horse. <br><br> The trigrams are set out in two classic orders: the Earlier Heaven arrangement linked to Fuxi, with heaven at the top and earth at the bottom, and the Later Heaven arrangement credited to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen of Zhou</span>, used on the feng shui compass. Stacking two trigrams produces the 64 six-line figures called hexagrams, which form the core of the <i>Yijing</i>, the ancient manual known in English as the <i>Book of Changes</i>. To consult the oracle a diviner built a hexagram by casting yarrow stalks or coins, then read the meaning of the resulting lines. Beyond fortune-telling they run through Chinese life, guiding the placement of homes and graves in feng shui through the <i>luopan</i> compass and naming the martial art of <i>Baguazhang</i>. Four of them, Qian, Kun, Kan, and Li, even surround the red-and-blue <i>taijitu</i> at the centre of the flag of South Korea.","citation":"","answerText":"Eight Trigrams"},
{"id":"cnh-031","num":"三十一","category":"China · History","question":"The Chinese god of fire and of the south, famous for a heaven-shaking battle with the water god Gonggong and honoured as an ancestor of the royal house of Chu, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lends his name today to a peak on Mount Heng and to the rover China landed on Mars in 2021.","answer":"Zhurong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">祝融 — the fire god of the south</span></div>","traditional":"祝融","hanzi":"祝融","pinyin":"Zhùróng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhùróng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhurong</b> is the god of fire and of the south in Chinese mythology, a bright, burning spirit tied to summer, heat, and the red planet Mars, which the Chinese called the Fire Star. He is named in early texts such as the <i>Huainanzi</i> and the writings of the philosopher Mozi, and he goes by other names too, among them <b>Chongli </b>and <b>Zhu Ming</b>, the Red-Bright. Tradition remembers him as the being who first gave people the use of fire and taught them how to control it. In myth he belongs to the line of the sky god Zhuanxu, also called Gaoyang, whose family also produced Gun and his son Yu the Great, the tamer of the great flood. From Zhurong the royal house of the southern state of Chu traced its descent through eight lineages, and he is often pictured as a fierce figure riding a pair of dragons. <br><br> His most famous story is a clash with the water god Gonggong, a battle of fire against water fought across the heavens for days on end. In the best-known telling Zhurong wins, and the beaten Gonggong in his rage smashes his head against Mount Buzhou, a pillar holding up the sky, tilting the heavens and the earth ever after. The old genealogies do not agree, however, for the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> instead makes Gonggong a descendant of Zhurong rather than his enemy. Alongside the myths he was also treated as a real official, appearing in Sima Qian's <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> as a Minister of Fire, an office tied to the ancient charge of Chong and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Zhuanxu_myth)\">Li</span> to separate heaven from earth. His name still marks both land and sky, given to Zhurong Peak, the highest point of the southern sacred mountain Heng, and to the Zhurong rover that China landed on Mars in 2021.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhurong"},
{"id":"cnh-032","num":"三十二","category":"China · History","question":"In Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the pillar-mountain that held up the sky in the far northwest, until the water god Gonggong lost a struggle for power and smashed his head against it, tilting the heavens and forcing the goddess Nüwa to mend the broken sky.","answer":"Mount Buzhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">不周 — 'incomplete', the broken pillar of heaven</span></div>","traditional":"不周山","hanzi":"不周山","pinyin":"Bùzhōu Shān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bùzhōu Shān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mount Buzhou</b> is a legendary mountain of Chinese cosmology, believed to stand in the far northwest near the Kunlun range and to serve as one of the great pillars that held up the sky. Old belief divided the world into eight directions, each with a mountain propping up the heavens at its edge, and Buzhou was the pillar of the northwest. Its very name means incomplete or not whole, a fitting title for the mountain whose breaking would leave the world forever lopsided. The mountain is famous for one catastrophe, told most fully in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han </span>encyclopaedia the <i>Huainanzi</i>, when the water god Gonggong, having lost a struggle for power, flew into a rage and rammed his head against it. In that version his rival is the sky god Zhuanxu, though other tellings pit Gonggong against the fire god Zhurong, and either way the blow snapped the heavenly pillar and tore the cords that bound the earth. <br><br> With the pillar broken, the heavens tilted down toward the northwest, which is why the Chinese said the sun, the moon, and the stars all drift and set in that direction. The earth meanwhile sank and was left incomplete in the southeast, so that ever after the rivers of China run downhill toward the eastern sea. The disaster is the reason given for the great repair carried out by the goddess Nüwa, who patched the shattered sky with stones of five colours and cut the legs from a giant turtle to prop up its four corners. The story runs through the earliest literature, from the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, which sets Buzhou in the northwest near the Jade Mountain, to the verses of Qu Yuan in the <i>Songs of Chu</i>. As a myth it explains why the heavens seem to lean one way while the great rivers all flow the other, toward the rising sun.","citation":"","answerText":"Mount Buzhou"},
{"id":"cnh-033","num":"三十三","category":"China · History","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are the tripartite cosmos of Chinese mythology and folk religion, stacked as the heaven of the gods above, the mortal world of the living in the middle, and the underworld of the dead below.","answer":"Three Realms","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三界 — 'three realms', Heaven, the human world, and the Underworld</span></div>","traditional":"三界","hanzi":"三界","pinyin":"Sānjiè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānjiè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Three Realms</b> is the name given to the layered universe of Chinese mythology and folk religion, a cosmos stacked in three levels, with Heaven above, the human world in the middle, and the Underworld below. Heaven is the home of the gods and immortals, and in later popular religion it is ruled by the Jade Emperor, who governs the sky much as an emperor governs an empire, through a vast bureaucracy of divine officials. The middle realm is the mortal world of the living, the ordinary earth where people are born, work, and die. Below it lies the Underworld, often called <i>Diyu</i>, where the souls of the dead are brought before Yama, known in Chinese as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yanluo_Wang\">Yanluo</span>, and judged in a series of ten courts. The three levels are not sealed off, for gods descend to help or punish mortals, the dead sink to be judged, and souls are sent back up to be reborn, so the whole cosmos turns as one connected system. <br><br> The picture blends several traditions layered over many centuries, joining the ancient Chinese sense of Heaven and Earth with ideas from Daoism and Buddhism. The Underworld in particular fuses the Buddhist judge Yama with a very Chinese vision of the afterlife as a court bureaucracy, complete with magistrates, records, and sentences. The same phrase, <i>Sanjie</i>, also carries a strictly Buddhist meaning, naming the three planes of rebirth: the realm of desire, the realm of form, and the realm of formlessness, through which beings pass until they escape into nirvana. These are really two different maps of the cosmos sharing one name, one stacking Heaven, earth, and the dead in space, the other ranking states of mind and being. In its mythological sense the Three Realms became the great stage of Chinese storytelling, above all the novel <i>Journey to the West</i>, whose monkey hero Sun Wukong throws all three into uproar.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Realms"},
{"id":"cnh-034","num":"三十四","category":"China · History","question":"In Chinese mythology, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the underworld, a vast underground maze of courts and hells where the souls of the dead are judged, punished for the sins of their lives, and then sent on to be reborn.","answer":"Diyu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">地獄 — 'earth prison', the underworld of the dead</span></div>","traditional":"地獄","hanzi":"地狱","pinyin":"Dìyù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dìyù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Diyu</b> is the underworld of Chinese mythology, a name meaning earth prison, imagined as a vast maze of chambers hidden underground, where the souls of the dead are taken to atone for the wrongs they did in life. It is a blend of several traditions, joining the Buddhist idea of <i>Naraka</i>, a world of hells, with older Chinese beliefs about the dead and popular additions built up over the centuries. Unlike the eternal hell of some religions, Diyu is more a purgatory, for the time a soul spends there depends on the weight of its sins and eventually ends. Once the punishment is complete the soul is sent on to be reincarnated, so that death here is a passage rather than a final destination. The idea grew out of still older Chinese pictures of the afterlife, in which the dead went down to the Yellow Springs or gathered at the sacred peak of Mount Tai. <br><br> In its most popular form Diyu is organized like a government, divided into Ten Courts, each ruled by one of the Ten Kings who judge and sentence the dead, though other tellings count eighteen levels or even thousands of hells. Its most famous ruler is Yama, called Yanluo in Chinese, who presides as a stern chief judge over the fifth of the ten courts. A newly arrived soul is first shown all its past deeds in a great mirror, then handed to the beast-headed guards Ox-Head and Horse-Face and led through punishments matched to each crime. At the very end the soul crosses the Bridge of Helplessness, where an old woman named Meng Po serves a soup that wipes away every memory before it is born again. This grim machinery filled temple paintings and morality books like the <i>Jade Record</i>, and folk belief fixed its earthly capital at the ghost city of Fengdu, a real town on the Yangtze.","citation":"","answerText":"Diyu"},
{"id":"cnh-035","num":"三十五","category":"China · History","question":"The Chinese god of death and dread judge of the underworld, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a form of the Buddhist King Yama who weighs the souls of the dead against the Register of Life and Death.","answer":"Yanluo Wang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">閻羅王 — 'King Yama', judge of the dead</span></div>","traditional":"閻羅王","hanzi":"阎罗王","pinyin":"Yánluó Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yánluó Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yanluo Wang</b> is the god of death and the ruler of <i>Diyu</i>, the Chinese underworld, where he sits in judgement over the souls of everyone who dies. His name is a Chinese form of the Sanskrit Yama Raja, or King Yama, and is often shortened to Yan Wang, King Yan. He began as Yama, the lord of the dead in ancient India, taken into Buddhism as ruler of its hells and then carried into Chinese belief with the rest of the underworld. When a person dies, the beast-headed guards Ox-Head and Horse-Face drag the soul before his court, where the dead are judged by their deeds in life. To weigh each case he consults the Register of Life and Death, a set of books recording the lifespan and deeds of every living person, and from it he sets the punishment and the shape of the next life. <br><br> In the developed system of the Ten Courts, which took shape from the Tang dynasty onward, Yanluo is only one of ten kings, each ruling a court under the authority of the Jade Emperor. Tradition says he was once the supreme lord of the dead but was demoted to rule the fifth court, punished for being too soft and merciful in his judgements. The Chinese also liked to imagine that the post was filled by famous upright officials, above all the incorruptible Song judge Bao Zheng, who was said to try the living by day and the dead by night. He is pictured as a huge, stern figure with a scowling red face, bulging eyes, and a long beard, in the robes and cap of a magistrate, the cap marked with the character for king. His court is a favourite scene in temple art and in stories, most famously in <i>Journey to the West</i>, where the monkey Sun Wukong bursts in and strikes his own name out of the Register to cheat death.","citation":"","answerText":"Yanluo Wang"},
{"id":"cnh-036","num":"三十六","category":"China · History","question":"The old woman of the Chinese underworld, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> waits at the Bridge of Helplessness and feeds each departing soul a broth of oblivion, erasing all memory of its past life before it is reborn.","answer":"Meng Po","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孟婆 — 'Granny Meng', the lady of forgetfulness</span></div>","traditional":"孟婆","hanzi":"孟婆","pinyin":"Mèng Pó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mèng Pó</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Meng Po</b> is the old woman of the Chinese underworld, a goddess of forgetfulness known as Granny Meng, whose task is to wipe the memories of the dead before they are born again. She keeps her station at the very edge of <i>Diyu</i>, beside the Bridge of Helplessness, the Naihe Bridge that every soul must cross on its way out of the underworld toward a new life. There she ladles out her famous broth, the Meng Po soup, a bowl of oblivion that each departing spirit is made to drink. The soup is said to carry all five flavours at once, the sweet, sour, bitter, spicy, and salty of a whole human life, and a single mouthful brings instant and lasting forgetfulness. Once it is swallowed the soul loses every memory of the life just ended and of the underworld itself, so that it can be reborn clean, without the weight of the past. <br><br> Her work is a necessary part of the endless wheel of reincarnation, for without forgetting, the fears and griefs and grudges of one life would follow a person into the next. The old stories do not agree on who she was before she took up the ladle, and the legends of her origin differ from telling to telling. In one she was a virtuous woman who never harmed a living thing and was appointed by Heaven to serve the soup; in another she was a widow so broken by grief that she brewed the broth to spare other souls the same pain. Folk belief also whispers of those who somehow slip past her, and small children who speak with strange knowledge are said to be souls that dodged the bowl and kept the memories of a life before. In this way Meng Po stands as the gentle, sorrowful gatekeeper between death and new birth, the reason no one remembers where they were before they were born.","citation":"","answerText":"Meng Po"},
{"id":"cnh-037","num":"三十七","category":"China · History","question":"The two beast-headed guardians of the Chinese underworld, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, one bearing the head of an ox and the other of a horse, seize the newly dead and drag them before the courts of Yanluo Wang.","answer":"Ox-Head and Horse-Face","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">牛頭馬面 — 'Ox-Head and Horse-Face', guardians of the underworld</span></div>","traditional":"牛頭馬面","hanzi":"牛头马面","pinyin":"Niútóu Mǎmiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Niútóu Mǎmiàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ox-Head and Horse-Face</b> are the two monstrous guardians of <i>Diyu</i>, the Chinese underworld, a pair of jailers with the bodies of men but the heads of beasts, one an ox and the other a horse. Their Chinese name, <i>Niutou Mamian</i>, simply pairs the two, Ox-Head and Horse-Face, and they almost always appear together as a matched set. They are the very first beings a person meets after death, the grim escorts who seize the newly dead soul and drag it down to the underworld to be judged for the deeds of its life. There they serve as the henchmen and messengers of Yanluo Wang, the king of the dead, standing guard over his courts, hauling in escaped souls, and carrying out his sentences. In temple paintings and statues they loom as fierce figures, usually armed with tridents or clubs and dragging heavy chains, a Chinese answer to the reaper who comes to collect the dying. <br><br> The pair came into China along with the Buddhist picture of hell, in which animal-headed wardens torment the damned, and they took firm root in popular religion. One story explains Ox-Head as a hardworking ox that had laboured all its life, whom the king of the underworld took pity on after its death and made into one of his faithful servants. They spread far beyond China, appearing in Japan as Gozu and Mezu and in Vietnam under their own names, and their statues still guard underworld shrines from Fengdu to Taiwan. They are among the most familiar characters in Chinese stories of the dead, and in <i>Journey to the West</i> the monkey Sun Wukong beats them both when his soul is dragged below. Their fearsome faces even passed into everyday speech, for to call a crowd of people <i>Niutou Mamian</i> is to say they are a pack of ugly, villainous rogues.","citation":"","answerText":"Ox-Head and Horse-Face"},
{"id":"cnh-038","num":"三十八","category":"China · History","question":"The two soul-escorting deities of the Chinese underworld, together called <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, are one tall and pale with a lolling tongue and the other short and dark-faced, and they fetch the newly dead away for judgement.","answer":"Heibai Wuchang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黑白無常 — 'Black and White Impermanence', escorts of the dead</span></div>","traditional":"黑白無常","hanzi":"黑白无常","pinyin":"Hēibái Wúcháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hēibái Wúcháng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Heibai Wuchang</b>, the Black and White Impermanence, are a pair of ghostly deities who escort the souls of the newly dead down to the underworld for judgement. Their name comes from the Buddhist idea of impermanence, the truth that all things must pass, and the two together stand as the very face of death. White Impermanence is the tall one, pale-faced and dressed in white, with a long tongue lolling from his mouth and a tall hat that promises good fortune to any who meet him, so he is even honoured as a bringer of wealth. Black Impermanence is his short, dark-faced companion in black, sterner and grimmer, the punisher standing beside the rewarder. They serve the king of the dead, Yanluo Wang, much as Ox-Head and Horse-Face do, and they also attend the City God as officers who hunt down wandering and wicked spirits. <br><br> In the best-loved story the two were sworn brothers and constables who agreed to meet beneath a bridge in Fuzhou. When a sudden storm flooded the river, the short one, whose name was Fan Wujiu, kept his promise and waited there until he drowned, while the tall Xie Bi'an, gone to fetch an umbrella, came back to find him dead and hanged himself in grief. Heaven rewarded their loyalty by making them gods, which is why the drowned Fan is black and short while the hanged Xie is white, tall, and long-tongued. In Fujian and Taiwan they are beloved figures known as the Seventh and Eighth Lords, paraded at the Ghost Festival as towering costumed giants, the tall white one gliding while the short black one darts and spins. The writer Lu Xun devoted a warm essay in his memoir <i>Dawn Blossoms Plucked at Dusk</i> to the White Impermanence, praising him as the one being in the whole afterlife both a ghost and truly humane, showing the dead a pity no living official ever did.","citation":"","answerText":"Heibai Wuchang"},
{"id":"cnh-039","num":"三十九","category":"China · History","question":"A reanimated stiff corpse of Chinese folklore, the&nbsp;<span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is so rigid with death that it lurches forward in stiff hops as it drains the life-breath of the living.","answer":"Jiangshi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">僵屍 — 'stiff corpse', the hopping vampire</span></div>","traditional":"僵屍","hanzi":"僵尸","pinyin":"Jiāngshī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiāngshī</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>jiangshi</b> is a reanimated corpse of Chinese folklore, a name that means stiff corpse and that the West often translates as the <b>Chinese hopping vampire</b>. Locked with the rigor of death, it cannot bend its limbs, so it travels in a series of stiff hops with its arms thrust out straight before it. It is not a flesh-eater like the zombies of Western films, but a drinker of life, killing the living to absorb their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(force)\">qi</span>, the vital breath, and growing stronger the more it feeds. In its familiar modern form it wears the robes and round cap of a Qing official, with greenish, mould-blotched skin, long claws, and wild hair, though this costume comes mostly from twentieth-century films rather than old belief. A corpse was thought to rise as a jiangshi when it was left unburied too long, when a cat leaped over its coffin, or when its spiritual soul departed while the bodily soul clung on. <br><br> The image of the hopping dead may come from a real custom of western Hunan called corpse-driving, in which bodies were carried home for burial over great distances. The corpses were stood upright and tied to long bamboo poles, and as the poles flexed while men bore them by night, the dead seemed to hop along in single file. Against a jiangshi people turned to Taoist priests, who pinned a paper talisman to its forehead to freeze it in place, and to charms like sticky rice, peachwood swords, mirrors, and the blood of a black dog. Because the creature is blind and hunts by the breath of the living, the surest defence was simply to hold one's breath until it passed by. Stories of such corpses fill Qing collections like Ji Yun's <i>Notes of the Thatched Abode</i>, and in the 1980s the jiangshi hopped into fame through Hong Kong comedy-horror films such as <i>Mr. Vampire</i>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jiangshi"},
{"id":"cnh-040","num":"四十","category":"China · History","question":"The humble but everywhere-worshipped local earth god of Chinese folk religion, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a kindly, bearded old man who guards a single village, field, or shop and brings it good harvests and wealth.","answer":"Tu Di Gong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">土地公 — 'Lord of the Land', the local earth god</span></div>","traditional":"土地公","hanzi":"土地公","pinyin":"Tǔdì Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tǔdì Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Tu Di Gong</b>, the <b>Lord of the Land</b>, is a local earth god of Chinese folk religion, the guardian spirit of a single small place such as a village, a field, a street, or a shop. He is the humblest of the gods, ranking at the very bottom of the heavenly order, yet he is by far the most common, for almost every patch of ground has its own. People picture him as a kindly, smiling old man with a long white beard, dressed in the robes and cap of a minor official and holding a staff or a lump of gold. His task is to watch over his little corner of the world, protecting the people who live there, guarding the fields, and making sure the harvest comes in. Because he is believed to bring prosperity and good fortune, he is especially dear to farmers and merchants, who honour him under the grander title <i>Fude Zhengshen</i>, the <b>Righteous God of Blessing and Virtue</b>. <br><br> In the great bureaucracy of the gods he is only a village-level official, answering to the City God above him, who governs a whole town. His countless little shrines stand everywhere, at roadsides and village gates, in the corners of homes and shops, and out among the crops. Shopkeepers make him offerings on the second and sixteenth days of every month, and his birthday on the second day of the second month is a busy festival. He is often shown beside his wife, Tu Di Po, the Grandmother of the Soil, and his image also guards graves, for the land god receives and watches over the local dead. Many places believe their Tu Di Gong was once a real person, a good and loyal man who served his community so well that he became its god after death.","citation":"","answerText":"Tu Di Gong"},
{"id":"cnh-041","num":"四十一","category":"China · History","question":"The divine magistrate <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> guards a Chinese city, wards off its disasters, and judges the souls of its recently dead from a temple laid out like a court of law, ranking just above the local earth god.","answer":"City God","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">城隍 — 'wall and moat', the god of a city</span></div>","traditional":"城隍","hanzi":"城隍","pinyin":"Chénghuáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chénghuáng</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>City God</b> is the guardian deity of a Chinese city or town, a heavenly magistrate who watches over both the living and the dead within his walls. His name in Chinese, <i>Chenghuang</i>, joins the words for a city wall and its moat, for he began as the spirit of the very defences that kept a city safe. Every city has its own, honoured in a grand temple laid out like a court of law, where the god sits enthroned as a stern official, and in many places he is a real upright man of the past raised to godhood after death. He protects his people from disasters like flood, drought, and plague, hears their pleas, and above all judges the souls of those who have just died in his district. The newly dead are said to report to him first, so that he keeps the registers of birth and death and passes each soul on toward the underworld. <br><br> In the great bureaucracy of the gods he sits like a real magistrate, ranking above the humble earth god Tu Di Gong below him and answering to higher powers above. There were City Gods for counties, for prefectures, and for the capital, their ranks matching the levels of the imperial government they mirrored. The Ming founder, the Hongwu Emperor, promoted the cult across the empire around 1370, ordering a City God temple in every city, built to match the local government office, and treating the god as a watchful check on dishonest officials. His temple is a whole court of the underworld, filled with painted judges and the fearsome soul-catchers Ox-Head and Horse-Face and the Black and White Impermanence. Each year, above all at the Ghost Festival, the City God is carried out in procession to inspect his territory and drive off the wandering, hungry dead.","citation":"","answerText":"City God"},
{"id":"cnh-042","num":"四十二","category":"China · History","question":"The shape-shifting demons and monsters of Chinese folklore, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are animals or objects that gain magic over long ages and learn to take human form, from beguiling fox spirits to the monsters the Monkey King fights.","answer":"Yaoguai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">妖怪 — 'demon-monster', a shape-shifting spirit</span></div>","traditional":"妖怪","hanzi":"妖怪","pinyin":"Yāoguài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yāoguài</span></div>","abstract":"The<b> Yaoguai</b> are the demons and monsters of Chinese mythology, a vast and varied host of uncanny creatures with strange powers, whose very name joins words for the bewitching and the weird. Most are not born as spirits but made, for an animal, a plant, or even a stone can slowly gain magic and a mind of its own after living for many hundreds of years. Such a creature grows in power by cultivating its energy and drinking in the essence of the sun and moon, and in time it learns to take on human shape. The most famous are the fox spirits, beautiful shapeshifters that bewitch and deceive, along with snake demons like the White Snake and skeletons like the White Bone Lady. They differ from ghosts, which are the souls of dead people, and from the gods above, for a yaoguai is a living thing that has turned into something more. <br><br> Chinese tales treat them less as pure evil than as wild and unpredictable, so that a single yaoguai may prey on people one moment and fall in love with a mortal the next. The wicked ones hunt humans to feed, devouring flesh to gain immortality, draining the life force of the living, or luring victims with a lovely disguise. They crowd the pages of Chinese literature, above all the novel <i>Journey to the West</i>, in which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Wukong\">Monkey King</span> battles one monster after another on the long road to India. They also fill Pu Songling's ghost-story collection <i>Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio</i> and the ancient bestiary of the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>. To be rid of one, people called on Taoist priests and Buddhist monks armed with talismans and spells, and the same creatures, under the same written name, became the <i>yokai</i> of Japan.","citation":"","answerText":"Yaoguai"},
{"id":"cnh-043","num":"四十三","category":"China · History","question":"The four mythical guardian beasts of the Chinese sky are together called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>: the Azure Dragon of the east, the Vermilion Bird of the south, the White Tiger of the west, and the Black Tortoise of the north.","answer":"Four Symbols","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">四象 — 'four images', the four celestial guardians</span></div>","traditional":"四象","hanzi":"四象","pinyin":"Sìxiàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sìxiàng</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Four Symbols</b> are the four mythical animals that guard the four directions of the sky in Chinese astronomy, dividing the band of stars into four great quarters, so that they are also known as the <b>Four Guardians</b>. Chinese astronomers grouped the stars into 28 lunar lodges, and each of the four beasts rules a block of seven of them, one for every point of the compass. In the east coils the Azure Dragon, the creature of spring and of the element wood, its colour the blue-green of new leaves. The south belongs to the Vermilion Bird, a flame-red creature of summer and fire, and the west to the White Tiger, the fierce beast of autumn and of metal. In the north broods the Black Tortoise, a turtle entwined with a snake, the emblem of winter and water, the beast the Chinese called <i>Xuanwu</i>, the Dark Warrior. <br><br> Together they map the four seasons onto the heavens, so that watching which quarter climbed the evening sky told farmers and priests the turning of the year. Sometimes a fifth is added at the centre, a Yellow Dragon standing for the earth, to complete the five directions and the five elements. On the ground the same four shape the art of feng shui, in which the ideal site has the dragon on its left, the tiger on its right, the bird before it, and the tortoise at its back. The Black Tortoise of the north was in time worshipped as a great Daoist god, Zhenwu the Perfected Warrior, honoured on the holy peaks of Wudang. The beasts are very old, a dragon and tiger picked out in shells beside a body in a tomb more than six thousand years ago, and by the Han dynasty they adorned tomb walls, roof tiles, and bronze mirrors across the empire.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Symbols"},
{"id":"cnh-044","num":"四十四","category":"China · History","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the blue-green celestial dragon of the east, guardian of spring among the Four Symbols, whose seven star-mansions trace a dragon across the sky and whose rising each spring is greeted as the festival Dragon Raising its Head.","answer":"Azure Dragon","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青龍 — 'blue-green dragon', guardian of the East</span></div>","traditional":"青龍","hanzi":"青龙","pinyin":"Qīnglóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīnglóng</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Azure Dragon</b> is the great sky-dragon of the east, one of the four beasts that guard the quarters of the Chinese heavens, and the emblem of spring, of the rising sun, and of the element wood. Its name comes from <i>qing</i>, the deep blue-green of new growth, and it is also called the <b>Blue Dragon of the East</b>. The dragon is drawn from seven star groups strung across the eastern sky, the lunar mansions named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Horn_mansion\">Horn</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neck_mansion\">Neck</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Root_mansion\">Root</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Room_mansion\">Room</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heart_mansion\">Heart</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tail_mansion\">Tail</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Winnowing_Basket_mansion\">Winnowing Basket</span>, which together outline its long body. The bright red star Antares forms the beast's beating Heart, while the star Spica marks the tip of its Horn. As the earth warms each spring the dragon seems to lift its head above the eastern horizon, an event the Chinese still mark on the second day of the second month as the festival called Dragon Raising its Head. <br><br> Like all Chinese dragons it is a lord of rain and water and a bringer of growth and good fortune, a wholly benevolent and lucky creature tied to the vigour of yang. In the art of feng shui it takes the honoured place on the left, so that a well-sited home or grave has the Azure Dragon to its east and the White Tiger to its west. In Taoism the dragon became a guardian god, painted on temple gates to ward evil away from the eastern side. Its image was set on the eastern walls of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> tombs and on roof tiles and city gates, and it travelled across East Asia as the <i>Seiryu</i> of Japan and the <i>Cheongnyong</i> of Korea. It even flew on China's first national flag under the last dynasty, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, whose banner bore a blue dragon chasing a red pearl on a yellow field.","citation":"","answerText":"Azure Dragon"},
{"id":"cnh-045","num":"四十五","category":"China · History","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the fiery red bird of the south, guardian of summer and fire among the Four Symbols, whose seven star-mansions outline a bird across the sky and whose name graced the great southern gate of Tang-era Chang'an.","answer":"Vermilion Bird","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">朱雀 — 'vermilion bird', guardian of the South</span></div>","traditional":"朱雀","hanzi":"朱雀","pinyin":"Zhūquè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhūquè</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Vermilion Bird</b> is the fiery red bird of the south, one of the four beasts that guard the quarters of the Chinese heavens, and the emblem of summer, of heat, and of the element fire. It is pictured as a graceful, pheasant-like creature with five-coloured plumage, forever wreathed in flame. People often confuse it with the <i>fenghuang</i>, the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Phoenix\">phoenix</span> that rules over all birds, but the Vermilion Bird is something else, a spirit of the southern stars. That quarter of the sky is made of seven star groups, the lunar mansions named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well_mansion\">Well</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghost_mansion\">Ghost</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Willow_mansion\">Willow</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Star_mansion\">Star</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extended_Net_mansion\">Extended Net</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wings_mansion\">Wings</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chariot_mansion\">Chariot</span>, which together outline the shape of a great bird. Like its fellow guardians it is a lucky and benevolent creature, tied to the sun, to the warmth of summer, and to the rising force of yang. <br><br> In the art of feng shui the Vermilion Bird belongs at the front of a good site, facing south over open ground or water, with the Black Tortoise guarding the rear to the north. Because south was the direction an emperor faced from his throne, the bird gave its name to the grandest gates and streets of the old capitals. The main southern gate of Tang-era&nbsp;Chang'an and the broad avenue leading up to the palace were both named the Vermilion Bird, and Japan copied them as the Suzaku Gate and Suzaku Avenue of its capital at Kyoto. In Taoism the bird served as a guardian god of the southern side, painted on temple gates to keep evil away. Its image was set on the southern walls of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> tombs and on roof tiles and banners, and it flew across East Asia as the <i>Suzaku</i> of Japan and the <i>Jujak</i> of Korea.","citation":"","answerText":"Vermilion Bird"},
{"id":"cnh-046","num":"四十六","category":"China · History","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the fierce white beast of the west, guardian of autumn and metal among the Four Symbols and a god of war whose seven star-mansions hold the Pleiades and Orion.","answer":"White Tiger","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">白虎 — 'white tiger', guardian of the West</span></div>","traditional":"白虎","hanzi":"白虎","pinyin":"Báihǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Báihǔ</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>White Tiger</b> is the great white beast of the west, one of the four guardians of the Chinese heavens, and the emblem of autumn, of the setting sun, and of the element metal. Its quarter of the sky is made of seven star groups, the lunar mansions named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legs_mansion\">Legs</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_mansion\">Bond</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stomach_mansion\">Stomach</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hairy_Head_mansion\">Hairy Head</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Net_mansion\">Net</span>,<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turtle_Beak_mansion\"> Turtle Beak</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Stars_mansion\">Three Stars</span>, which together trace the shape of a crouching tiger. Among them shine famous stars, for the Hairy Head mansion is the cluster of the Pleiades and the Three Stars mansion is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Orion's_Belt\">belt of Orion</span>. Where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Azure_Dragon\">Azure Dragon</span> of the east stands for spring and new life, the White Tiger of the west stands for the metal of blades and the killing chill of autumn. It was therefore a god of war and punishment, fierce and dangerous, for autumn was the Chinese season of the harvest and of executions and military campaigns. <br><br> Yet the tiger was also a protector that drove off evil spirits, and a pure white one was said to appear only when a ruler governed with perfect virtue and the land was at peace. In feng shui it takes the right-hand place, so that a good site has the White Tiger to its west and the Azure Dragon to its east, the fierce tiger kept the lower of the two. The tiger was the king of beasts, marked on its brow with the character for king, and generals carried tiger-shaped bronze tallies that gave the power to command an army. In Taoism the White Tiger became a guardian general, painted beside the dragon on temple gates and on the western walls of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> tombs to keep that side safe from harm. In folk fortune-telling, though, the same beast could turn baleful, a White Tiger star blamed for quarrels and misfortune, and across East Asia it prowled as the <i>Byakko</i> of Japan and the <i>Baekho</i> of Korea.","citation":"","answerText":"White Tiger"},
{"id":"cnh-047","num":"四十七","category":"China · History","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the dark guardian of the north among the Four Symbols, a tortoise entwined with a snake whose name means the Dark Warrior and who grew into the mighty Taoist god Zhenwu.","answer":"Black Tortoise","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">玄武 — 'dark warrior', guardian of the North</span></div>","traditional":"玄武","hanzi":"玄武","pinyin":"Xuánwǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xuánwǔ</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Black Tortoise</b> is the dark guardian of the north, the last of the four beasts that watch over the quarters of the Chinese heavens, and the emblem of winter, of water, and of the cold and darkness. Its Chinese name, <b>Xuanwu</b>, means <b>the Dark Warrior</b>, and unlike the other three it is not a single animal but a pair, a tortoise wound about by a snake. The turtle and the serpent were both creatures of long life, and their coiling union stood for endurance, water, and the hidden power of the yin. Its quarter of the sky is made of seven star groups, the lunar mansions named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dipper_mansion\">Dipper</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ox_mansion\">Ox</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Girl_mansion\">Girl</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emptiness_mansion\">Emptiness</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rooftop_mansion\">Rooftop</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encampment_mansion\">Encampment</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wall_mansion\">Wall</span>, which together trace the shape of the turtle and snake. In the art of feng shui the Black Tortoise guards the back, so that a good site rests against a hill to the north with the Vermilion Bird open before it to the south. <br><br> Of all four beasts this one rose the highest, for the Dark Warrior grew into one of the greatest gods of Taoism. In the Song dynasty his old name was changed from Xuanwu to <b>Zhenwu, the Perfected Warrior</b>, to avoid an emperor's forbidden name, and he was pictured as a barefoot, long-haired swordsman standing upon a turtle and a snake. His holy home is the Wudang Mountains, and the Ming emperor Yongle covered those peaks with temples, believing the god had helped him seize the throne. The north gate of the Tang capital was named for him, and it was there in the year 626 that the prince Li Shimin killed his brothers and made himself the next emperor. The same turtle-snake guarded the northern walls of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> tombs and travelled across East Asia as the <i>Genbu</i> of Japan and the <i>Hyeonmu</i> of Korea.","citation":"","answerText":"Black Tortoise"},
{"id":"cnh-048","num":"四十八","category":"China · History","question":"The fabled island-paradise of the immortals in the eastern sea, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, is where white beasts roam among towers of gold and the herb of eternal life grows, the very isle the First Emperor sent fleets in vain to find.","answer":"Mount Penglai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蓬萊 — 'Penglai', the isle of the immortals</span></div>","traditional":"蓬萊","hanzi":"蓬莱","pinyin":"Pénglái","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pénglái</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mount Penglai</b> is the fabled island-paradise of the immortals in Chinese mythology, a magic mountain rising from the sea off the eastern coast where the deathless <i>xian</i> are said to dwell. It is the most famous of a cluster of holy isles floating in the eastern Bohai Sea, usually counted as three, Penglai, Fangzhang, and Yingzhou, though older tellings name five. On the island everything is strange and wonderful: the birds and beasts are pure white, the towers are gold and jade, and jewels hang like fruit from the trees. Whoever eats that fruit never grows old or dies, the wine cups and rice bowls are never empty, and there is no cold, no pain, and no winter. Best of all the herb of immortality grows on its slopes, which drew many seekers, even though the island was almost impossible to reach, receding like a mirage or sinking away as boats drew near. <br><br> An old story in the <i>Liezi</i> tells how the floating mountains were anchored by giant sea-turtles, until a giant fished six up and two of the islands drifted off and sank. The dream of Penglai gripped even emperors, and the First Emperor, Qin Shi Huang, sent fleets to search the sea for it and for the elixir that would let him live forever. Most famous was the wizard Xu Fu, who around 219 BCE sailed east with thousands of young men and women and never came back, giving rise to a much later legend that he had reached Japan. Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Wu of Han</span>&nbsp;took up the same hopeless quest, and rulers built miniature Penglais as islands in their garden lakes, a fashion that shaped Chinese and Japanese gardens ever after. A real town on the Shandong coast still bears the name, crowned by the Song-era Penglai Pavilion and famous for the shimmering sea mirage that seems to raise a phantom city above the waves.","citation":"","answerText":"Mount Penglai"},
{"id":"cnh-049","num":"四十九","category":"China · History","question":"The great sacred mountain of the far west in Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a cosmic pillar joining earth to heaven and the home of the Queen Mother of the West with her peaches of immortality.","answer":"Kunlun Mountain","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">崑崙山 — 'Kunlun', the western mountain of the gods</span></div>","traditional":"崑崙山","hanzi":"昆仑山","pinyin":"Kūnlún Shān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kūnlún Shān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kunlun Mountain</b> is the great sacred mountain of the far west in Chinese mythology, a towering paradise where the gods and immortals make their home. It was imagined as the pillar at the centre of the world, a cosmic axis whose tiers climbed skyward to join earth to heaven. Its ruler is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Mother_of_the_West\">Queen Mother of the West</span>, who keeps her palace behind golden walls and guards the peaches of immortality that ripen only once in thousands of years. The mountain was said to be the source of the Yellow River and of three other great rivers flowing to the four directions, and its slopes held jade trees, a tree of immortality, and hanging gardens beside a pool of jasper. It was ringed by dangers, among them the Weak River whose waters were too thin to float a feather, and it was watched over by strange guardians and by three-legged birds that carried the Queen Mother's messages. <br><br> Kunlun fills the oldest books of Chinese wonder, above all the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, along with the <i>Huainanzi</i> and the <i>Songs of Chu</i>. The most famous tale is that of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Mu_of_Zhou\">King Mu of Zhou</span>, who is said to have driven his chariot far to the west to feast with the Queen Mother upon her mountain. Together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Penglai\">Penglai</span>, the isle of the immortals out in the eastern sea, Kunlun formed the pair of great Chinese paradises, one in the west on land and one in the east upon the water. Over time, touched by ideas from India, the mountain took on the features of the Buddhist world-mountain Sumeru, and Taoists came to see it less as a deadly wilderness than as a blissful heaven. Its name belongs also to a real range, the Kunlun Mountains that wall off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span> in China's far west, a land long famous for its precious jade.","citation":"","answerText":"Kunlun Mountain"},
{"id":"cnh-050","num":"五十","category":"China · History","question":"The great Chinese goddess who dwells on Kunlun and keeps the peaches of immortality, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was once a wild, tiger-toothed goddess of plague and later a gracious queen of eternal life.","answer":"Queen Mother of the West","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">西王母 — 'Queen Mother of the West', goddess of immortality</span></div>","traditional":"西王母","hanzi":"西王母","pinyin":"Xīwángmǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīwángmǔ</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Queen Mother of the West</b>, known in Chinese as <b>Xiwangmu</b>, is one of the greatest goddesses of China, the highest of the female deities and the keeper of the secret of immortality. She dwells far in the west on Mount Kunlun, in a palace beside the Jasper Pool, where she tends a garden of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peaches_of_immortality\">magic peaches</span> that ripen only once in thousands of years and grant eternal life to whoever eats them. In her oldest form, in the ancient <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, she was a wild and terrible being, a tiger-toothed, leopard-tailed goddess of plague and death who howled from her cave and sent down heavenly punishments. Three blue birds fetched her food, and she ruled over the wild beasts and the calamities of the world. Over the centuries, above all under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>, this fearsome creature was reimagined as a beautiful, gracious queen, a giver of long life and the patron of women who sought the immortal way. <br><br> Her palace became the setting of the Peach Banquet, the great feast at which she serves her immortality peaches to the assembled gods, the very feast that the monkey Sun Wukong wrecks in <i>Journey to the West</i>. It was her elixir that the archer Houyi won and his wife Chang'e stole before flying up to live on the moon. Kings and emperors longed to reach her: legend tells how <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Mu_of_Zhou\">King Mu of Zhou</span> drove his chariot west to feast and trade poems with her, and how she descended to the palace of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span>. Yet neither ruler kept her teachings, and both died as mortals, for immortality was hers to give and not theirs to seize. In the balance of the cosmos she was the great female power of the west, paired with the King Father of the East, and in later folk religion she became the wife of the Jade Emperor himself.","citation":"","answerText":"Queen Mother of the West"},
{"id":"cnh-051","num":"五十一","category":"China · History","question":"The god of the east and yang counterpart of the Queen Mother of the West, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is lord of the male immortals and was largely invented in the Han to balance her.","answer":"King Father of the East","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">東王公 — 'King Father of the East', lord of the male immortals</span></div>","traditional":"東王公","hanzi":"东王公","pinyin":"Dōngwánggōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dōngwánggōng</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>King Father of the East</b>, called <b>Dongwanggong </b>in Chinese, is the god of the east and the male partner of the Queen Mother of the West. Where she is the great female power of the west, he is the male power of the east, the yang to her yin, and he bears the title <b>Duke of Wood</b>, for wood and the east belong to spring and the rising sun. Just as the Queen Mother rules the women who become immortal, the King Father keeps the rolls of the male immortals, and every man who wins eternal life pays him homage. He dwells in the paradise of the far east, and in some tellings he and the Queen Mother are the divine father and mother whose union first brought forth humankind. Together, the Wood Duke of the east and the Golden Mother of the west, they stand as the great parents of the immortals and the balance of male and female in the world. <br><br> Yet the King Father is a much later and lesser figure than his partner, for the Queen Mother was worshipped for centuries before anyone thought to give her a husband. He was largely invented under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han </span>to supply a male, eastern, yang counterweight to her female, western, yin, and appears beside her on bronze mirrors from as early as the year 106. The old <i>Classic of the Divine and the Strange</i> paints him as a giant ten feet tall, snow-white of hair, with a bird's face and a tiger's tail, riding a black <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bear\">bear</span>. There he passes the time pitching sticks into a pot with a jade maiden, and whenever he missed his throw, it was said, Heaven laughed with a flash of lightning. In later Taoism he was honoured under the grander name <b>Donghua Dijun</b>, the <b>Sovereign Lord of the Eastern Florescence</b>, and counted among the first teachers of the immortals.","citation":"","answerText":"King Father of the East"},
{"id":"cnh-052","num":"五十二","category":"China · History","question":"The supreme ruler of Heaven and head of the celestial bureaucracy in Chinese folk religion, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> commands the lesser gods much as an emperor commands his officials, though Taoism sets him below the Three Pure Ones.","answer":"Jade Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">玉皇大帝 — 'Jade August Emperor', ruler of Heaven</span></div>","traditional":"玉皇大帝","hanzi":"玉皇大帝","pinyin":"Yùhuáng Dàdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yùhuáng Dàdì</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Jade Emperor</b> is the supreme ruler of Heaven and the highest of the gods in Chinese folk religion, the divine emperor who reigns over the whole of the cosmos. He governs through a vast heavenly court modeled exactly on the imperial government of China, appointing and commanding the countless lesser gods much as an earthly emperor commands his officials. From his throne he rules the Three Realms of heaven, earth, and the underworld, receiving the reports of gods like the City God and the local earth god and rewarding or punishing spirits and mortals alike. Ordinary people simply called him <b>Grandfather Heaven</b>, for to them he was Heaven itself, the power that watches over all things and keeps the order of the world. In the deeper theology of Taoism, however, he is not the ultimate god but the great administrator, ranking below the Three Pure Ones, the transcendent embodiments of the Dao. <br><br> Legend says he was not always divine but began as a mortal prince who gave up his kingdom and cultivated the Dao through countless ages until he attained the highest godhood. His worship grew greatest under the Song dynasty, whose emperors heaped grand titles upon him and identified him with Shangdi, the ancient supreme god of the sky. In folk religion he is sometimes paired with the Queen Mother of the West as his consort, and once a year the Kitchen God of every home flies up to his court to report how the family has behaved. He is most famous in the novel <i>Journey to the West</i>, where the rebellious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Wukong\">Monkey King</span> throws his heaven into uproar until the Buddha himself is called to subdue him. His birthday falls on the ninth day of the first lunar month, a great festival at which worshippers set out offerings to Heaven and give thanks to the Jade Emperor.","citation":"","answerText":"Jade Emperor"},
{"id":"cnh-053","num":"五十三","category":"China · History","question":"Grown by the Queen Mother of the West on Kunlun and ripening only once in thousands of years, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grant eternal life to whoever eats them and are served to the gods at her great Peach Banquet.","answer":"Peaches of immortality","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蟠桃 — 'flat peach', the fruit of immortality</span></div>","traditional":"蟠桃","hanzi":"蟠桃","pinyin":"Pántáo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pántáo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Peaches of immortality</b> are the magic fruit of Chinese myth that grant eternal life to whoever eats them, the food by which the immortals keep their deathlessness. They grow in a heavenly orchard tended by the Queen Mother of the West on the far western mountain of Kunlun. The trees bloom and fruit only once in thousands of years, and the oldest are the most potent, so that in one scheme peaches ripening every three thousand years give long life, those of six thousand grant flight and youth, and those of nine thousand make the eater as ageless as the sun and moon. When the fruit at last ripens, the Queen Mother holds her great Peach Banquet, a feast at which the gods and immortals gather to eat the peaches and renew their endless lives. In everyday China the peach became the emblem of long life, so that the God of Longevity is shown holding a giant peach and peach-shaped buns are served at birthdays to wish an old person long years. <br><br> Their most famous appearance is in the novel <i>Journey to the West</i>, where the mischievous Monkey King is made guardian of the sacred orchard. Left alone among the trees, he gorges himself on every ripe peach, then gatecrashes the Peach Banquet to which he was never invited, one of the outrages that set all Heaven against him. Older tales tell of the jester Dongfang Shuo, who was said to have slipped into the garden and stolen the Queen Mother's peaches, winning himself an impossibly long life. In another story she descended from the heavens to visit Emperor Wu of the Han and gave him a few of the precious peaches, warning him that they ripen but once in three thousand years. Through all these legends the peaches stand as the sweetest promise of Chinese immortality lore, the simple fruit that turns a mortal into a deathless being.","citation":"","answerText":"Peaches of immortality"},
{"id":"cnh-054","num":"五十四","category":"China · History","question":"The giant sea turtle <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, whose four legs the goddess Nüwa cut off to make new pillars for the broken sky, also carries the drifting isles of the immortals upon its back in other tales.","answer":"Ao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鰲 — the great sea turtle of myth</span></div>","traditional":"鰲","hanzi":"鳌","pinyin":"Áo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Áo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ao</b> is the great sea turtle of Chinese mythology, a giant creature said to have swum the ocean since the very making of the world. Its most famous moment comes in the story of the goddess Nüwa, who had to mend the sky after a catastrophe cracked it open and knocked down the pillars that held up heaven. To rebuild those broken supports, Nüwa killed the giant turtle Ao and cut off its four great legs, standing them upright at the four corners of the earth as new pillars for the sky. In that way the huge turtle became the four props of the heavens, holding up the roof of the world in place of the shattered mountains. The tale is told in the old book the <i>Huainanzi</i>, where Nüwa also patched the torn sky with stones of five colours, one of the classic accounts of how the ruined cosmos was set right. <br><br> Another tradition keeps Ao alive and swimming in the eastern Bohai Sea, where it bears the floating islands of the immortals upon its back. There it and its fellow turtles carry the fairy mountains of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Penglai\">Penglai</span>, Fangzhang, and Yingzhou, holding those drifting paradises steady, until in one tale a giant hauled several turtles from the sea and two other isles floated away and sank. In later ages the giant turtle blurred into the dragon, and Ao is often pictured as a beast with a turtle's body and a dragon's head, able to bear enormous weights. This dragon-turtle inspired the stone Bixi that kneel beneath memorial tablets all over China and East Asia, carved to carry the heaviest steles. The creature even left its mark on the language, for to come first in the imperial examinations was to <i>stand alone on the ao's head</i>, an image of triumph drawn from a carved turtle on the palace steps.","citation":"","answerText":"Ao"},
{"id":"cnh-055","num":"五十五","category":"China · History","question":"The god-kings and culture-heroes of Chinese legend collectively called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, from Fuxi and Nüwa to the Yellow Emperor, Yao, and Shun, are said to have ruled at the dawn of civilization before the first dynasty.","answer":"Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三皇五帝 — the semi-legendary dawn of China</span></div>","traditional":"三皇五帝","hanzi":"三皇五帝","pinyin":"Sānhuáng Wǔdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānhuáng Wǔdì</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors</b> are the god-kings and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Culture_Hero\">culture-heroes</span> of Chinese legend who ruled at the dawn of civilization, in the semi-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mythology\">mythical </span>age before the first dynasty, the Xia. The three <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereign_(ruler)\">sovereigns </span>are the older and more divine, most often named as Fuxi, the creator-goddess Nüwa, and the divine farmer Shennong, though other lists put the fire-bringer Suiren or the Yellow Emperor in Nüwa's place. Each is remembered for a gift to human life: Fuxi devised the eight trigrams and taught fishing with nets, Nüwa moulded the first people from clay and mended the broken sky, and Shennong gave the plough and found herbal medicine by tasting hundreds of plants. The five emperors who followed were fixed by the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han </span>historian Sima Qian as the Yellow Emperor, Zhuanxu, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ku_(sage_king)\">Emperor Ku</span>, Yao, and Shun. Under them the Chinese gained writing, the calendar, and silk and were shaped into a settled people, though here too the lists in other books differ. <br><br> The most admired of these rulers passed their thrones not to their sons but to the worthiest man alive: Yao gave the throne to the commoner Shun, and Shun to Yu, the flood-tamer who founded the Xia. This ideal of virtuous succession became the model for the Mandate of Heaven, by which later dynasties claimed the right to rule. Sima Qian began his <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>, the model for all later dynastic histories, not with the fabulous sovereigns but with the Yellow Emperor, judging the earlier figures too legendary for real history. The sovereigns were only added to the orthodox canon centuries afterward, when the Tang scholar Sima Zhen wrote a new set of annals to fill the gap before him. Old chronologies date the Yellow Emperor to around 2697 BCE, yet modern scholars read the whole line not as royal history but as layered myth, even as archaeologists dig for whatever faint memory it holds.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors"},
{"id":"cnh-056","num":"五十六","category":"China · History","question":"The ox-headed Divine Farmer of Chinese legend, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave humanity farming and founded herbal medicine by tasting hundreds of plants, dying at last from a poison too deadly even for him.","answer":"Shennong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">神農 — 'Divine Farmer'</span></div>","traditional":"神農","hanzi":"神农","pinyin":"Shénnóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shénnóng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shennong</b>, whose name means <b>Divine Farmer</b>, is one of the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Culture_Hero\">culture-heroes</span> of Chinese legend, counted among the Three Sovereigns who ruled before the dawn of history. He is also known as the Yan Emperor, the Flame Emperor, and together with the Yellow Emperor he is honoured as an ancestor of the Chinese people, who still call themselves the descendants of Yan and Huang. In old pictures he is a strange, powerful figure with the horned head of an ox on a human body, often coloured a fiery reddish bronze. His first great gift was farming, for he is said to have invented the plough, dug the first wells, and taught people to sow the grain and to hold markets to trade what they grew. For this the Chinese have worshipped him ever since as the god and father of agriculture, offering him pigs and sheep but never the ox that shares his likeness. <br><br> His second great gift was medicine, which he founded by tasting hundreds of wild plants one by one to learn which could heal and which could kill. Legend says he was poisoned as many as seventy times in a single day, but survived because his belly was transparent, letting him watch how each herb worked inside him. It was while testing plants that he is said to have discovered tea, when a few leaves drifted into his boiling water and washed the poison away. The knowledge he gathered was written down, long after his day, in the <i>Divine Farmer's Materia Medica</i>, the oldest Chinese book of herbal medicine, which lists 365 remedies. In the end a plant too deadly even for him tore his insides apart before he could swallow his cure, and having died for the good of all people he is remembered as the <b>Medicine King</b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Shennong"},
{"id":"cnh-057","num":"五十七","category":"China · History","question":"The Chinese Prometheus, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the Fire-Driller who taught humankind to make fire by twirling wood, ending the age when people ate their food raw.","answer":"Suiren","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">燧人 — 'the fire-driller'</span></div>","traditional":"燧人","hanzi":"燧人","pinyin":"Suìrén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Suìrén</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Suiren</b>, <b>the Fire-Driller</b>, is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Culture_Hero\">culture-hero</span> of Chinese legend, honoured as <b>the Great Fire-maker</b>, who gave humankind the gift of fire. His name comes from the <i>sui</i>, the fire-drill, the little tool of twirled wood by which he taught people to kindle a flame whenever they wished, whether by boring into wood or striking sparks from stone. In the earliest days, the old stories say, people ate their food raw and often fell ill from the rank and rotten flesh they swallowed. Suiren changed all that, for once he had shown them how to make fire they could cook their meat and warm themselves, and the age of rawness came to an end. For this gift he is the Chinese counterpart of Prometheus, the Greek bringer of fire, and grateful people were said to have made him their ruler. <br><br> One old legend tells how, in a distant land called Suiming, he watched an owl-like bird peck at a great fire-tree, striking bright sparks from the wood. Copying the bird, he bored into a stick until it smoked and caught fire, and so the fire-drill was born. He belongs to a line of inventor-heroes who built up civilization step by step, from the nest-builder who taught shelter, to Suiren with fire, to Fuxi and Shennong who followed. Because fire came before farming, some old lists count Suiren among the Three Sovereigns in place of the goddess Nüwa and set him first of them all, and a few even make him the father of Fuxi, the sovereign who came after. The philosopher Han Fei told his story long ago, of a sage who drilled wood to make fire and was crowned king by a thankful world, and tradition places him at the very dawn of time, before Fuxi, granting him a reign of 110 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Suiren"},
{"id":"cnh-058","num":"五十八","category":"China · History","question":"The Nest-Builder of Chinese legend, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> taught the first people to escape the wild beasts by building nest-like shelters up in the trees, making him the inventor of the house.","answer":"Youchao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">有巢氏 — 'the Nest-Builder'</span></div>","traditional":"有巢氏","hanzi":"有巢氏","pinyin":"Yǒucháoshì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yǒucháoshì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Youchao</b>, whose name means the Nest-Builder, is the culture-hero of Chinese legend who taught people how to build houses. In the earliest age, the old stories say, human beings had no shelter and lived out in the open, where they were hunted by wild beasts and bitten by snakes and insects. To keep them safe, Youchao showed them how to weave branches and wood into nests high up in the trees, out of the reach of the animals below, just as the birds do, in place of the damp caves where people had once cowered. In this way he gave the world its first dwellings, and the Chinese honour him as the inventor of the house and of building itself. So grateful were the people that they are said to have made him their ruler and named him for the nests he taught them to make, and old tables even grant him a reign of some two hundred years. <br><br> Youchao stands at the very beginning of a line of inventor-heroes who lifted humanity out of the wild one step at a time. He came first with shelter, followed by Suiren, who brought fire, and then by Fuxi and Shennong, who gave marriage, the trigrams, farming, and medicine. His story is told in the <i>Han Feizi</i>, the book of the Legalist philosopher Han Fei, which describes how a sage framed nests of wood to save the people from harm and was crowned king. For giving people their first protection from the dangers of nature, some old lists count him among the Three Sovereigns, the earliest and most divine of China's rulers. Tradition places his reign at the dawn of the human age, long before the first dynasty, in a time when people were only beginning to learn even the simplest arts of living, from making fire to growing food.","citation":"","answerText":"Youchao"},
{"id":"cnh-059","num":"五十九","category":"China · History","question":"The legendary empress and wife of the Yellow Emperor, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is said to have discovered silk when a cocoon fell into her teacup and unwound, and she taught China the art of raising silkworms.","answer":"Leizu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">嫘祖 — the empress who discovered silk</span></div>","traditional":"嫘祖","hanzi":"嫘祖","pinyin":"Léizǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Léizǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Leizu</b> is the legendary empress of Chinese myth who is said to have discovered silk and given China the art of making it. She was the chief wife of the Yellow Emperor, the great sovereign of high antiquity, and she is also known by her clan name <b>Xilingshi</b>, the <b>Lady of Xiling</b>. The famous story tells how, as she sat drinking tea in her garden, a silkworm's cocoon dropped from a mulberry tree into her hot cup. When she reached in to fish it out, the cocoon began to unwind into a single long, fine thread, and she saw at once that this shimmering fibre could be spun and woven into cloth. From that discovery she learned to raise the silkworms on mulberry leaves, to reel the silk from their cocoons, and to weave it, and she taught these skills to her people. <br><br> Tradition credits her not only with sericulture but also with inventing the silk reel and the loom, the machines on which the fine thread was wound and turned into fabric. Because silk became one of China's greatest treasures, carried westward along the roads that later took its name, she is honoured as the goddess of silk, <b>the Silkworm Mother</b>, or <b style=\"\">Can Nainai</b> in Chinese. For centuries the empresses of China performed a yearly ceremony in her honour, tending silkworms and offering sacrifice, just as the emperor ploughed a field to honour the first farmer Shennong. She bore the Yellow Emperor two sons, Shaohao and Changyi, and through Changyi she was counted an ancestor of the emperor Zhuanxu. Her discovery is placed by tradition in the 27th century before our era, though no one knows how much of the tale is true, for archaeology proves the Chinese were weaving silk long before any empress could have taught them.","citation":"","answerText":"Leizu"},
{"id":"cnh-060","num":"六十","category":"China · History","question":"The four-eyed historian of the Yellow Emperor, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the legendary inventor of Chinese writing, said to have created the first characters after studying the tracks of birds and beasts.","answer":"Cangjie","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">倉頡 — 'the inventor of writing'</span></div>","traditional":"倉頡","hanzi":"仓颉","pinyin":"Cāngjié","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cāngjié</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Cangjie</b> is the legendary inventor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanzi\">Chinese writing</span>, honoured as the father of the characters that the Chinese have used for thousands of years. In the myths he was the record-keeper and historian of the Yellow Emperor, the great sovereign of high antiquity. Before his day, the story goes, people kept their records only by tying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Knotted-cord_record-keeping\">knots in cords</span>, a clumsy way that could not hold all that needed remembering. Sent to find something better, Cangjie studied the shapes of things in nature, the tracks of birds and beasts, the veins of a turtle's shell, and the patterns of the stars, and saw that each left a mark all its own. From this he understood that a thing could be caught in a sign of its own, and so he drew the first characters, one for each thing in the world. <br><br> So great was his gift of sight that he is pictured with four eyes, able to perceive the hidden patterns of Heaven and earth that ordinary people could not. When he first showed his writing to the world, the <i>Huainanzi</i> says, Heaven was so astonished that it rained down grain, and the ghosts wailed through the night. Some say the spirits wept because writing would let people record lies and lawsuits, ending the age of innocence, while the grain fell because scholars would now neglect the fields for their books. In truth no single person invented Chinese writing, which grew slowly over many centuries, its oldest form the marks scratched on Shang oracle bones more than a thousand years after Cangjie's supposed legendary time. Yet he is still honoured with temples and tombs across China, and his name lives on both in an ancient character primer, the <i>Cangjiepian</i>, and in the modern Cangjie method used to type Chinese on a keyboard.","citation":"","answerText":"Cangjie"},
{"id":"cnh-061","num":"六十一","category":"China · History","question":"The bronze-headed war-god of Chinese legend, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> forged the first metal weapons and led the Nine Li against the Yellow Emperor, who defeated him at the Battle of Zhuolu.","answer":"Chiyou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蚩尤 — the war-god defeated at Zhuolu</span></div>","traditional":"蚩尤","hanzi":"蚩尤","pinyin":"Chīyóu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chīyóu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chiyou</b> is the terrible war-god of Chinese legend, the chieftain who led the Nine Li tribes against the founders of the Chinese people. He is drawn as a monster, with a bronze head and an iron brow, the horns of a bull, four eyes and six arms, the hindquarters of a bear, and a body that fed on sand and stones. By tradition he was a descendant of the Flame Emperor, and he commanded a host of 81 fierce brothers or clans as terrible as himself. His greatest gift, and his most dangerous, was the making of weapons, for he is remembered as the first to forge swords, spears, and halberds of metal. Armed with these, his people were the most feared warriors of the ancient world, and he set out to conquer all under heaven. <br><br> He first beat the Flame Emperor, then turned on the Yellow Emperor, and the two clashed in the long and terrible Battle of Zhuolu. Chiyou breathed out a great fog to blind his enemies and called up wind and rain to lash them, but the Yellow Emperor found his way with a south-pointing chariot, drove off the storm with the drought-goddess Ba, and at last struck him down, so that it rained blood afterward. Even in defeat he was not forgotten, for he was worshipped ever after as a god of war, the Lord of Weapons, and both the First Emperor and the founder of the Han offered him sacrifice before they went to fight. His scattered people are remembered as ancestors of the Miao and Hmong, who honour Chiyou to this day as a great and wise king, the <i>Txiv Yawg</i>. In modern China he is sometimes set beside the Yellow and Flame Emperors as a third forefather of the nation, so that even the old enemy is claimed as an ancestor.","citation":"","answerText":"Chiyou"},
{"id":"cnh-062","num":"六十二","category":"China · History","question":"The great winged dragon of Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> killed the monster Chiyou for the Yellow Emperor and later carved the river channels with his tail to help Yu the Great tame the flood.","answer":"Yinglong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">應龍 — 'the responding dragon', the winged dragon</span></div>","traditional":"應龍","hanzi":"应龙","pinyin":"Yìnglóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yìnglóng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yinglong</b>, the Responding Dragon, is the great winged dragon of Chinese mythology, a master of rain and water and one of the mightiest of all dragons. Unlike the other dragons of China, which fly without wings, Yinglong bears a pair of wings, the mark of the oldest and most powerful of the breed. In one account a creature must live for many ages to become such a dragon, rising from a water-snake to a scaled dragon and only after a thousand more years growing its wings. Because he made the clouds and the rain, he was a giver of water, but he could also turn that power into a weapon of war. When the Yellow Emperor fought the monster Chiyou, it was Yinglong who gathered up the floodwaters and struck him down, and he killed the sun-chasing giant Kuafu as well. <br><br> But having slain these mighty beings, Yinglong was too stained to climb back into heaven, and so he stayed below in the far south. With the rain-dragon gone from the sky, the land was struck by long droughts, and to end them people would fashion dragons out of clay in his image and beg him for rain. Long after, when the world was drowned in the great flood, the <i>Songs of Chu</i> tell how Yinglong came to the aid of Yu the Great as he laboured to tame the waters. Dragging his long tail across the earth, the dragon traced out the lines of the river channels, showing Yu where to dig so that the floodwaters could run away to the sea. His winged shape is drawn in the ancient <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, and so the same dragon appears at the two great turning points of the mythical age, the taming of Chiyou and the taming of the flood.","citation":"","answerText":"Yinglong"},
{"id":"cnh-063","num":"六十三","category":"China · History","question":"The headless giant of Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was beheaded for challenging the gods but fought on with his nipples for eyes and his navel for a mouth, brandishing shield and axe as a symbol of undying defiance.","answer":"Xingtian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">刑天 — 'the beheaded one'</span></div>","traditional":"刑天","hanzi":"刑天","pinyin":"Xíngtiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xíngtiān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xingtian</b> is the headless giant of Chinese mythology, the great symbol of a defiance so fierce that not even death can stop it. His story is told in the ancient <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, where he dares to challenge the supreme god himself for the mastery of Heaven. The god strikes him down and cuts off his head, burying it deep beneath a mountain called Changyang so that the giant can never come back to life. But Xingtian refuses to fall, and rises again to fight on without a head, turning his two nipples into eyes and his navel into a mouth. Grasping a shield in one hand and a great battle-axe in the other, he brandishes them in the steps of an ancient war-dance, an endless and furious battle against the heavens. <br><br> The oldest text names his enemy only as the supreme god, but a later and popular tradition makes him a champion of the Flame Emperor, fighting on against the victorious Yellow Emperor to avenge his fallen lord. His very name means the one whose head was cut off, a fitting title for a warrior defined by the loss of his head and his refusal to yield. Above all it was the poet Tao Yuanming who made him immortal in his <i>Reading the Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, writing that Xingtian still brandishes his shield and axe and that his fierce will endures forever. In that same poem the headless giant is paired with the little bird Jingwei, who tried to fill the sea, as twin emblems of a courage that never gives up. To this day Xingtian stands in China for the unbroken spirit of the defeated, the fighter who battles on though the cause is lost and the head is gone, and modern writers have made him a hero of the oppressed who refuse to bow.","citation":"","answerText":"Xingtian"},
{"id":"cnh-064","num":"六十四","category":"China · History","question":"The giant of Chinese myth who tried to chase and catch the sun, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drank the Yellow and Wei rivers dry to quench his thirst but died on the way to a distant lake, his staff becoming a forest of peach trees.","answer":"Kua Fu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">夸父 — the giant who chased the sun</span></div>","traditional":"夸父","hanzi":"夸父","pinyin":"Kuāfù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kuāfù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kua Fu</b> is the giant of Chinese mythology best remembered for a single mad and magnificent deed: he set out to chase and catch the sun. A descendant of the earth god Houtu, he belonged to a race of giants, and one day he resolved to run down the sun itself. He raced it across the sky from the east to the west, but the closer he drew the more the sun's heat burned him, and a terrible thirst took hold. To quench it he bent down and drank the Yellow River and the Wei River completely dry, yet still his thirst was not slaked. So he turned north toward a great lake, hoping to drink his fill there, but he collapsed and died of thirst on the way, just short of his goal. <br><br> As he fell, the wooden staff he carried dropped from his hand and grew into a vast forest of peach trees, the Deng Forest, to give shade and fruit to any who might come the same way after him, while in some tellings his body became a range of mountains. The Chinese have long argued over what his desperate story is meant to teach. To some he is a warning against folly and pride, a giant who overreached and threw his life away on an impossible task, so that the phrase <i>Kuafu zhu ri</i>, chasing the sun, became a byword for those who bite off more than they can chew. To others he is a hero, a symbol of the unbending will to strive after light and to press on toward a dream even when it cannot be reached, dying in the attempt rather than turning back. In another old story his people sided with the monster Chiyou against the Yellow Emperor, and Kua Fu was slain by the winged dragon Yinglong in that great war.","citation":"","answerText":"Kua Fu"},
{"id":"cnh-065","num":"六十五","category":"China · History","question":"A legendary son of the Yellow Emperor and the White Emperor of the West, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is famous for a reign in which a phoenix appeared and every one of his officials was named after a bird.","answer":"Shaohao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">少昊 — the White Emperor of the West</span></div>","traditional":"少昊","hanzi":"少昊","pinyin":"Shàohào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shàohào</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shaohao</b> is a legendary sovereign of ancient China, remembered above all as the king whose court was run by birds. By tradition he was a son of the Yellow Emperor and his silk-discovering wife Leizu, and his name means the Lesser Bright, set against the Great Bright of an earlier age. In the cosmology of the Five Phases he became the White Emperor of the West, the god of autumn, of the metal element, and of the White Tiger that guards the western sky, so that he was also called <i>Jin Tian</i>, the Golden Heaven. Some old lists count him among the Five Emperors who ruled after the Yellow Emperor, though the historian Sima Qian left him out and passed straight on to Zhuanxu. He is said to have ruled the Eastern Yi peoples for 84 years from a capital at Qufu in the land of Shandong. <br><br> The strangest and most famous thing about his reign was the way he ordered his government, giving every one of his officials the name of a bird. When he came to the throne a phoenix appeared as a sign of his favour, and so the birds became his ministers. The phoenix itself was set over the calendar and the seasons, while a hawk kept the laws, a pigeon saw to teaching, and flocks of lesser birds took charge of the crafts, the farming, and the ordering of the common people. This bird-named court reflected his people's worship of birds, for the tribes of the east held the bird as their sacred sign and their ancestor. When he died the throne passed to his nephew Zhuanxu, and long afterward a great stone tomb shaped like a pyramid was raised in his honour near Qufu, beside the spot the Chinese pointed to as the Yellow Emperor's own birthplace.","citation":"","answerText":"Shaohao"},
{"id":"cnh-066","num":"六十六","category":"China · History","question":"The fifth and central beast of the Chinese sky, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stands for the earth at the middle of the four directions and is the living form of the Yellow Emperor, from whom it became the emblem of imperial power.","answer":"Yellow Dragon","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黃龍 — the dragon of the centre, emblem of the emperor</span></div>","traditional":"黃龍","hanzi":"黄龙","pinyin":"Huánglóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huánglóng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yellow Dragon</b>, or <i>Huanglong</i>, is the great dragon of the centre in Chinese cosmology, the fifth and most senior of the sky's guardian beasts. To the four creatures that watch the four directions, the Azure Dragon, the Vermilion Bird, the White Tiger, and the Black Tortoise, it adds a fifth at the middle, the still point around which they all turn. Its place is the centre, its season the turning between the seasons, its element the earth, and its colour the yellow of the soil. Above all it is the living form of the Yellow Emperor himself, the great sovereign of high antiquity, so that dragon and emperor are one and the same. In one story the Yellow Dragon rose hornless from the River Luo before the sage Fuxi and taught him the beginnings of writing. <br><br> At the end of his long reign, the old books say, the Yellow Emperor cast a great bronze cauldron, and when it was finished a yellow dragon came down to carry him up to heaven, his ministers clinging to its whiskers as it rose, so that his people are still called the children of the dragon. From him the dragon became the emblem of every emperor who followed, the sign of the Son of Heaven and of imperial power itself. Yellow, the colour of the dragon and of the earth at the centre of the world, became the colour reserved for the emperor alone. So it was that China's last dynasty, the Qing, flew a great banner called the Yellow Dragon Flag, its field the imperial yellow of the throne. In every age the appearance of a yellow dragon was taken as a sign of a virtuous ruler and of Heaven's favour, the most auspicious of all the dragons.","citation":"","answerText":"Yellow Dragon"},
{"id":"cnh-067","num":"六十七","category":"China · History","question":"The sun goddess of Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the mother of the ten suns and drove one of them across the sky each day, until nine were shot down by the archer Houyi.","answer":"Xihe","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">羲和 — the sun goddess, mother of the ten suns</span></div>","traditional":"羲和","hanzi":"羲和","pinyin":"Xīhé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīhé</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xihe</b> is the sun goddess of Chinese mythology, the divine mother of the sun, or rather of the ten suns of the ancient world. By her husband, the high god Di Jun, she bore ten children, each of them a sun in the shape of a three-legged crow. The ten suns lived together in a giant mulberry tree, the <i>Fusang</i>, that grew far away in the eastern sea, nine of them roosting in the lower branches while one waited at the top, ready to rise. Every morning Xihe would bathe one of her sun-children in a gulf of sweet water in the far east and set it in her carriage. Then she would drive it across the whole width of the sky, from the mulberry tree in the east to the tree at the world's western edge, so that only one sun shone each day. <br><br> This orderly turn was broken on the terrible day when all ten suns rose into the sky at once, their heat scorching the crops, drying up the rivers, and beginning to burn the world to ashes. The earth was saved only when the great archer Houyi shot down nine of the ten sun-crows, leaving the single sun that lights the world today. Xihe had a sister-wife named Changxi, another consort of Di Jun, who in the same way was mother to the twelve moons and bathed them in the western waters. As the driver of the sun's chariot she was called upon by poets, and Qu Yuan in his <i>Li Sao</i> once begged her to slow her horses and hold back the setting of the sun. In a much later tradition her name was given instead to the officials of the sage-king Yao who watched the heavens and fixed the calendar, and today it belongs to China's first satellite sent to study the sun.","citation":"","answerText":"Xihe"},
{"id":"cnh-068","num":"六十八","category":"China · History","question":"A shadowy supreme god of the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the husband of the sun and moon goddesses and the lord who sent the archer Houyi down against the ten suns.","answer":"Di Jun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">帝俊 — the high god of the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i></span></div>","traditional":"帝俊","hanzi":"帝俊","pinyin":"Dìjùn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dìjùn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Di Jun</b> is a supreme god of the oldest Chinese mythology, the shadowy Lord Jun who ruled as one of the highest deities in the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>. In that ancient book he stands at the head of a vast family of gods, though today he is far less famous than the Yellow Emperor who later overshadowed him. His two wives were the great goddesses of the sky: Xihe, mother of the ten suns, and Changxi, mother of the twelve moons. Through them, in a sense, Di Jun was the father of the sun and the moon themselves and of much of the host of heaven. He was also reckoned the ancestor of many peoples and inventors, among them his son Houji, the lord of grain from whom the royal house of Zhou traced its descent, and others who were said to have invented the boat, the cart, and music. <br><br> The most famous thing he did was to send the great archer Houyi down to the world of men. When the ten suns rose together and burned the earth, Di Jun gave Houyi a red bow and white arrows and sent him below to bring relief to the suffering people. Scholars have long puzzled over who exactly he was, for his figure blurs into others, and he is often identified with the sage-emperor Ku, with the good king Shun, and with the high god Shangdi worshipped by the Shang dynasty. Many believe he was in truth the chief god of the eastern peoples and of the Shang, perhaps once pictured with the head of a bird, the supreme power of an older tradition of belief. In the histories that later became orthodox that older god faded away, his glory passing to the Yellow Emperor, so that the once-mighty Di Jun is now half-forgotten.","citation":"","answerText":"Di Jun"},
{"id":"cnh-069","num":"六十九","category":"China · History","question":"The greatest archer of Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> shot down nine of the ten suns that were scorching the earth, and his wife Chang'e later stole his elixir of immortality and flew to the moon.","answer":"Hou Yi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">后羿 — the archer who shot down the suns</span></div>","traditional":"后羿","hanzi":"后羿","pinyin":"Hòuyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hòuyì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hou Yi</b> is the great archer of Chinese mythology, the peerless marksman who saved the world from destruction by the sun. Long ago, in the age of the sage-king Yao, the ten suns that should have crossed the sky one at a time all rose together and began to burn the earth to a cinder. The gods gave Hou Yi a mighty red bow and a quiver of white arrows and sent him down to set things right. One after another he shot the suns out of the sky, and as each was struck it fell to earth as a dead three-legged crow, until only a single sun was left to light the world. He went on to rid the land of a host of monsters that preyed on the people, from the giant boar Fengxi and a vast man-eating serpent to a fanged beast and a nine-headed horror that breathed water and fire. <br><br> For his services Hou Yi was given the elixir of immortality, won from the Queen Mother of the West on her far western mountain. But his wife Chang'e swallowed the potion herself and floated up into the sky, where she became the goddess who lives on the moon. The Chinese still remember her flight at the Mid-Autumn Festival, gazing up at the full moon where she is said to dwell with a jade rabbit that pounds the herbs of immortality. Hou Yi's own end was grim, for in the tellings where he grew proud and cruel he was beaten to death with a club of peachwood by his own pupil, the archer Feng Meng. His story became tangled with that of a later Lord Yi, a real chieftain who, the <i>Bamboo Annals</i> record, seized the throne of the young Xia dynasty, so that hero and usurper share a single name.","citation":"","answerText":"Hou Yi"},
{"id":"cnh-070","num":"七十","category":"China · History","question":"The goddess of the moon in Chinese myth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> swallowed her husband Hou Yi's elixir of immortality and floated up to live forever on the moon, where she is honoured each Mid-Autumn Festival.","answer":"Chang'e","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">嫦娥 — the goddess of the moon</span></div>","traditional":"嫦娥","hanzi":"嫦娥","pinyin":"Cháng'é","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cháng'é</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chang'e</b>, known in older tales as <i>Heng'e</i> until her name was changed to avoid the forbidden name of a Han emperor, is the goddess of the moon in Chinese mythology and one of the best-loved of all the deities. She was the wife of the great archer Hou Yi, who won an elixir of immortality as his reward for shooting down the nine extra suns that scorched the world. One day, while Hou Yi was away, his treacherous apprentice Feng Meng broke in and tried to seize the precious elixir for himself. Rather than let it fall into his hands, Chang'e swallowed the whole draught at once, and at once her body grew light and began to rise. Up and up she floated past the clouds, and of all the places in heaven she chose the moon, so as to stay as near as she could to her husband below. <br><br> There she has lived ever since in a cold and lonely palace, the Palace of Vast Cold, cut off forever from Hou Yi. Her only companions are a jade rabbit that pounds the herbs of immortality in a mortar, and a woodcutter who is doomed to hack forever at a tree that heals itself as fast as he can cut. Every autumn the Chinese remember her at the Mid-Autumn Festival, gathering with their families under the full moon to eat round mooncakes and make her offerings of fruit. In this way the sad tale of a wife parted from her husband became one of the tenderest and most familiar of all Chinese stories. Her name lives on in the modern age, for China has named its whole fleet of moon probes Chang'e and the little rover they carried the Jade Rabbit, and the crew of Apollo 11 were even teased about watching for her before they touched down.","citation":"","answerText":"Chang'e"},
{"id":"cnh-071","num":"七十一","category":"China · History","question":"Seen in the dark markings of the full moon, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the companion of the goddess Chang'e who forever pounds the elixir of immortality in a mortar on the moon.","answer":"Moon Rabbit","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">玉兔 — 'jade rabbit', the rabbit of the moon</span></div>","traditional":"玉兔","hanzi":"玉兔","pinyin":"Yùtù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yùtù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Moon Rabbit</b>, better known in China as the Jade Rabbit, is the rabbit that people have always seen in the face of the full moon, for the Chinese were one of many peoples across the world to picture a hare among its shadows. The dark patches on the moon's surface were imagined as a rabbit, standing with a mortar and pestle in its paws. In Chinese myth this rabbit is the companion of the moon goddess Chang'e, sharing her cold palace in the sky. There it works without rest, pounding the herbs of the elixir of immortality in its mortar, the same magic potion that first carried Chang'e up to the moon. The same rabbit is seen across East Asia, though in Japan and Korea it is pounding not the drug of long life but the soft rice cakes eaten at the harvest moon. <br><br> The oldest story of how the rabbit came to the moon is a Buddhist tale of self-sacrifice. A rabbit, a monkey, an otter, and a jackal once vowed to give alms, and when a starving old beggar came to them, the others brought him food, but the rabbit had only grass to give. So the little rabbit threw itself into a fire to offer its own flesh, and the beggar, who was really a god in disguise, was so moved that he set the rabbit's image on the moon for all time. Ever since, the rabbit has stood for selflessness and for long life, and it is loved at the Mid-Autumn Festival, when children in old Beijing were given clay figures of the Rabbit God, <i>Tu'er Ye</i>. In our own day China named its little moon-rovers Yutu, the Jade Rabbit, sending the creature of legend to roll at last across the real face of the moon, one of them even reaching the hidden far side.","citation":"","answerText":"Moon Rabbit"},
{"id":"cnh-072","num":"七十二","category":"China · History","question":"A former heavenly marshal banished for lusting after Chang'e and reborn half-pig, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the gluttonous, rake-wielding pig disciple who follows the monk in <i>Journey to the West</i>.","answer":"Zhu Bajie","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">豬八戒 — 'Pig of the Eight Precepts', the pig disciple</span></div>","traditional":"豬八戒","hanzi":"猪八戒","pinyin":"Zhū Bājiè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhū Bājiè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhu Bajie</b>, known in English as <b>Pigsy</b>, is the comical pig-man of the great Chinese novel <i>Journey to the West</i>. He is the second of the three disciples who guard the monk Tang Sanzang on his long pilgrimage to fetch the Buddhist scriptures from India. Once he had been a grand figure in heaven, the <b>Marshal Tian Peng</b>, commander of the 80,000 sailors of the heavenly river. But at a feast of the gods he drank too much and made drunken advances to the moon goddess Chang'e, and for this the Jade Emperor had him beaten and cast down to the earth. Worse still, he was reborn in the wrong body, coming back to the world as a monster half man and half pig, with a snout, big flapping ears, and a great fat belly. <br><br> He was living as a man-eating monster in a place called Gao Village when the Monkey King, Sun Wukong, beat him and the bodhisattva Guanyin sent him to join the journey and atone for his sins. In battle he swings a mighty nine-toothed iron rake, once used to guard the gates of the Jade Emperor's own palace in heaven, though he is far weaker than his brother the Monkey King. Zhu Bajie is the very picture of human weakness, forever hungry, lazy, and greedy, easily tempted by pretty women and quick to suggest giving up and going home. Yet he is also warm-hearted and cheerful, and for all his grumbling he stays loyal to the monk to the very end of the road. When the pilgrims at last reach the Buddha, Zhu Bajie is too fond of his pleasures to be made a saint, and is given instead the fitting post of Cleanser of the Altars, free to eat all the leftover offerings he wants.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhu Bajie"},
{"id":"cnh-073","num":"七十三","category":"China · History","question":"Condemned to chop forever at a self-healing osmanthus tree on the moon, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the woodcutter of Chinese myth whose endless, futile labour has earned him the nickname the Chinese Sisyphus.","answer":"Wu Gang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">吳剛 — the woodcutter of the moon</span></div>","traditional":"吳剛","hanzi":"吴刚","pinyin":"Wú Gāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wú Gāng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu Gang</b> is the woodcutter of the moon in Chinese mythology, a man doomed to a task that can never be finished. High on the moon there grows a giant tree, and Wu Gang must chop it down, but every time his axe bites the trunk the wound closes at once and the tree stands whole again. So he swings his axe forever and gets nowhere, which is why people today call him the Chinese Sisyphus, after the Greek doomed to roll a boulder uphill for all time. The tree is the osmanthus, a sweet-smelling plant that flowers in autumn, though older tellings often call it a cassia instead. His story is first written down in a book of strange tales from the Tang dynasty, the <i>Youyang Zazu</i> of the 9th century, which says only that a man named Wu Gang from Xihe chops a moon tree 500 zhang tall that heals as fast as he cuts. <br><br> That old book gives no real reason for his punishment beyond saying that he made some fault while studying to become an immortal. Later storytellers filled in the gap in several different ways, and there is no single agreed version of his crime. In one telling he grew lazy and gave up his search for immortality half done, in another he killed his wife's lover and was banished to the moon by an angry god, and in a third he could never finish any lesson his teacher set. Whatever the reason, Wu Gang shares the moon with the goddess Chang'e and her jade rabbit, and his tree ties him to the Mid-Autumn Festival, when families drink osmanthus wine and eat osmanthus cakes beneath the full moon. He even appears in a famous 1957 poem by Mao Zedong, in which Wu Gang comes forward on the moon to offer cups of osmanthus wine to the spirits of the dead.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu Gang"},
{"id":"cnh-074","num":"七十四","category":"China · History","question":"Benevolent lord of rain and water and the ancient emblem of the emperor, the Chinese dragon — known in Chinese as <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — is a wingless, scaled serpent that flies by its own magic and embodies the yang male force of the world.","answer":"Long","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">龍 / 龙 — lóng, the Chinese dragon</span></div>","traditional":"龍","hanzi":"龙","pinyin":"Lóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lóng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>long</b> is the <b>Chinese dragon</b>, the most powerful and best-loved creature in all of Chinese mythology, quite unlike the fire-breathing monster of European tales. It is drawn as a long, scaled serpent with four legs, and though it has no wings it flies into the clouds by its own magic. Old writers made it a patchwork of nine animals, giving it a stag's horns, a camel's head, a snake's neck, a carp's scales, an eagle's claws, and a tiger's paws. Rather than a beast to fear, the dragon brings good fortune and rules all water, the rivers, lakes and seas, and sends the rain, so that people prayed to it in times of drought and flood. It stands for yang, the bright male force of the world, and for centuries it was the emblem of the emperor, who sat on a dragon throne and was called the True Dragon, the Son of Heaven. <br><br> Only the emperor's dragon could have five claws on each foot, while nobles and commoners made do with four or three, a rule fixed under the Yuan dynasty and kept by the Ming and Qing. In folk religion the dragon became the Dragon King, a god who lived beneath the sea and sent the rain, with a separate king for each of the four seas. A famous saying gives the dragon nine sons, strange creatures whose images still decorate Chinese buildings, among them a tortoise-like one that carries heavy stone tablets and another that perches on the rooftops. Since nine was a lucky and heavenly number, these nine sons stand for a great many rather than an exact count, and the old lists never quite agree on their names. The dragon is also the fifth animal of the Chinese zodiac, and today the Chinese call themselves the descendants of the dragon, a proud phrase made popular only in the 20th century by a hit song.","citation":"","answerText":"Long"},
{"id":"cnh-075","num":"七十五","category":"China · History","question":"Ruler of all birds and paired with the dragon as the emblem of the empress, the Chinese phoenix — known in Chinese as <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — is a splendid, deathless omen-bird that appears only in ages of peace and virtuous rule.","answer":"Fenghuang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鳳凰 / 凤凰 — fènghuáng, the Chinese phoenix</span></div>","traditional":"鳳凰","hanzi":"凤凰","pinyin":"Fènghuáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fènghuáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Fenghuang</b> is the Chinese phoenix, the most splendid of all birds and ruler over every other bird. Its name once held two birds in one, for the male was the <i>feng</i> and the female the <i>huang</i>, but over the centuries the two joined into a single creature thought of as female. As a female it was set beside the male dragon, and while the dragon stood for the emperor, the phoenix stood for the empress, so a dragon and phoenix together became a sign of a happy marriage still seen at weddings. Old books describe the bird as a patchwork of animals, with the beak of a rooster, the neck of a snake, the back of a tortoise, and the sweeping tail of a fish. Its feathers shone with the five colours, and it was said to carry in its body the five great virtues of the good person, such as kindness, honesty, and good manners. <br><br> The phoenix was above all a lucky sign, believed to appear only when the land was at peace under a wise ruler and to vanish in times of disorder. Confucius himself, grieving over the troubles of his day, sighed that the phoenix did not come, and took its absence as a sign that his age had gone wrong. Unlike the phoenix of Western tales, the Chinese phoenix does not burn itself and rise from its ashes, and was pictured not as dying and being reborn but as simply never dying. That fiery rebirth was tied to the fenghuang only in modern times, when the poet Guo Moruo borrowed the idea from the West for a famous 1920 poem, and the two birds are now often confused. Along with the dragon, the unicorn-like <i>qilin</i>, and the tortoise, the fenghuang is one of the four sacred creatures of China, and a scene of a hundred birds honouring it stands for a realm at peace.","citation":"","answerText":"Fenghuang"},
{"id":"cnh-076","num":"七十六","category":"China · History","question":"A gentle chimera with a dragon's head, a deer's body, and flesh-tipped horns that treads so lightly it crushes no insect, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the auspicious Chinese unicorn whose coming heralds a sage or a virtuous ruler.","answer":"Qilin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">麒麟 — qílín, the gentle beast of good omen</span></div>","traditional":"麒麟","hanzi":"麒麟","pinyin":"Qílín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qílín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qilin</b> is a gentle magical beast of Chinese myth, counted with the dragon, the phoenix and the tortoise as one of the four sacred creatures. In English it is called the Chinese unicorn, but the name fits loosely, for it is no single-horned horse but a mixture of many animals, often shown with a pair of horns. It has the scaled body of a deer, the tail of an ox, the hooves of a horse, and a head somewhat like a dragon's, with a flowing mane and beard. Artists drew it differently over the ages, at first a graceful deer-like animal with one horn, later a dragon-like beast covered in scales and wreathed in flames. Above all it is a creature of perfect gentleness, said to walk so softly that it bends no grass and crushes no insect, with horns tipped in soft flesh so that it harms nothing. <br><br> Because it is so pure, the qilin appears only in a good age, its coming believed to mark the birth or death of a great sage or ruler. Legend says one appeared to the mother of Confucius before his birth, and in 481 BC a qilin was caught and hurt by hunters in his home state of Lu. The old story tells that Confucius wept to see so lucky a beast come in a cruel age only to be killed, and took it as a sign his own work was ending, closing his chronicle, the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, at that event. The strangest chapter came in 1414, when the fleets of the admiral Zheng He brought home a giraffe from Africa, and the long-necked animal, with its skin-covered horns, was presented at court as a living qilin. That memory still lives in language, for the same word, <i>kirin</i> in Japanese and <i>girin</i> in Korean, is used to this day for both the mythical qilin and the real giraffe.","citation":"","answerText":"Qilin"},
{"id":"cnh-077","num":"七十七","category":"China · History","question":"A fierce winged beast with a dragon's head and a lion's body that devours gold and jewels but can never pass them out again, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese guardian creature prized for drawing in wealth and driving off evil.","answer":"Pixiu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">貔貅 — píxiū, the winged guardian of wealth</span></div>","traditional":"貔貅","hanzi":"貔貅","pinyin":"Píxiū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Píxiū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Pixiu</b> is a fierce winged beast of Chinese myth, a mighty guardian believed to bring its owner wealth and to keep evil away. It is stitched together from several animals, most often with the head of a dragon, the body of a lion, sharp teeth, feathered wings, and a low split tail. Old books tell of two kinds marked apart by their horns: the single-horned <i>Tianlu</i>, whose name means heavenly reward and who gathers in riches, and the twin-horned <i>Bixie</i>, whose name means to drive off evil. The beast first appears in the histories of the Han dynasty, under the older name <i>Tao ba</i>, counted among the strange animals of the western lands. Its name was also a word for brave soldiers, and the fiercest warriors and their banners were once likened to the pixiu as a mark of courage. <br><br> What makes the pixiu so loved is the belief that it feeds hungrily on gold, silver and jewels but has no way to let them out again, so any wealth it swallows it keeps forever. A favourite tale explains this by saying the beast once broke a law of Heaven, and the Jade Emperor struck it so hard that its rear was sealed shut for good. Ever since, people have kept carved pixiu of jade or gold in their homes and shops and worn them as charms, hoping the creature will draw in money and never let it slip away. In popular belief it is even counted one of the sons of the dragon, and it stays a favourite good-luck symbol among businesspeople and gamblers today. In ancient times its stone image also guarded the dead, and huge winged lions of this kind, some three or four metres long, still line the paths to the old imperial tombs near Nanjing.","citation":"","answerText":"Pixiu"},
{"id":"cnh-078","num":"七十八","category":"China · History","question":"A fox that gains magic and many tails with age and can take the shape of a beautiful woman, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the shapeshifting Chinese fox spirit that may be a deadly seductress or a devoted, loving wife.","answer":"Huli Jing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">狐狸精 — húlijīng, the fox spirit</span></div>","traditional":"狐狸精","hanzi":"狐狸精","pinyin":"Húlijīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Húlijīng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Huli Jing</b> is the fox spirit of Chinese folklore, a fox that has lived so long it gains magical powers and can change shape, most often into a beautiful young woman. Such a spirit grows stronger over the centuries, feeding on the essence of the sun and moon and on the breath of living people, and in darker tales stealing the very life force of the men it seduces. As it ages it sprouts more tails, up to nine, and the greatest is the golden nine-tailed celestial fox, said to serve in the palace of the sun and moon. Yet the fox spirit is not simply a monster, for it could be either wicked or good, a deadly seductress in one story and a loyal, loving fox-wife in the next. The Qing writer Pu Songling filled his famous book of strange tales with such gentle foxes, clever and faithful women often kinder than the humans they loved. <br><br> In the oldest books the fox wore a different face, for the nine-tailed fox of the ancient <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> was a lucky sign that appeared in times of peace and good rule. A white nine-tailed fox was even said to bless the marriage of Yu the Great, its nine tails standing for a home crowded with children. Only later, from about the Tang dynasty on, did the fox darken in people's minds into the dangerous, bewitching demon we picture today. The most famous fox spirit of all was Daji, the beautiful consort blamed for the fall of the Shang dynasty over three thousand years ago. Later stories, above all a great Ming novel, turned this half-legendary queen into a wicked nine-tailed fox sent by the goddess Nüwa to ruin the last Shang king, though history knows only a human woman.","citation":"","answerText":"Huli Jing"},
{"id":"cnh-079","num":"七十九","category":"China · History","question":"A blue, beaked, bat-winged god who beats a drum to make the thunder and strikes the wicked with his chisel, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese Duke of Thunder who punishes hidden crimes at Heaven's command.","answer":"Lei Gong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">雷公 — Léi Gōng, the Duke of Thunder</span></div>","traditional":"雷公","hanzi":"雷公","pinyin":"Léi Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Léi Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lei Gong</b>, the Duke of Thunder, is the thunder god of Chinese religion, a dreaded figure who hurls his bolts at the wicked. He is pictured as a fearsome creature, blue-skinned and muscular, with the sharp beak of a bird, the claws and leathery wings of a bat, and nothing on but a loincloth. The rolling sound of a storm is the noise of his drum, which he beats with a mallet, while in his other hand he grips a chisel to strike down evildoers. His special task is to punish secret sins that no human court can reach, killing those guilty of hidden crimes and any evil spirits who have used dark magic to harm people. He acts only on the orders of Heaven, for he is not the highest of the thunder gods but a servant of its great Ministry of Thunder, whose sentences he carries out. <br><br> Working at his side is his wife Dianmu, the Mother of Lightning, who holds up flashing mirrors to light the target so her husband can see his mark and never strike an innocent by mistake. This is why the lightning is seen before the thunder is heard, and why the pair are always shown together in the storm. A well-loved legend tells that Lei Gong once made just such a mistake, killing a young woman he wrongly thought was wasting food, and the Jade Emperor made amends by reviving her as the lightning goddess and giving her to him as his bride. In the oldest books the thunder god wore a different shape, a beast with the body of a dragon and the head of a man who made thunder by drumming on his own belly. By the Song dynasty, Daoist priests claimed they could summon Lei Gong and his fellow thunder gods in special rites to drive off demons, cure the sick, and call down rain.","citation":"","answerText":"Lei Gong"},
{"id":"cnh-080","num":"八十","category":"China · History","question":"Flashing a mirror in each hand to light his target so he strikes only the guilty, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese goddess of lightning and the wife of the thunder god Lei Gong.","answer":"Dianmu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">電母 / 电母 — Diànmǔ, the Mother of Lightning</span></div>","traditional":"電母","hanzi":"电母","pinyin":"Diànmǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Diànmǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Dianmu</b>, whose name means the Mother of Lightning, is the Chinese goddess of the lightning and the wife of Lei Gong, the thunder god. She is pictured as a graceful woman in bright, flowing robes, holding up a polished mirror in each hand. From these mirrors she flashes the bolts of lightning that split the sky, and with their light she shows her husband exactly where to aim his thunder. Her task is to make sure the thunder god strikes only the guilty, lighting up each target so that no innocent person is killed by mistake. This is the reason, the myth explains, that a flash of lightning is always seen a moment before the crash of thunder is heard. <br><br> A well-loved legend tells how Dianmu was once an ordinary mortal woman, struck dead by Lei Gong when he wrongly believed she was wasting good food. In truth she had only thrown away rice husks too coarse for her aged mother to eat, so that her death was a cruel error and the killing of an innocent. To right the wrong, the Jade Emperor brought her back to life and raised her to be the goddess of lightning, giving her the very task of lighting each target so such a mistake could never happen again. In the beginning the Chinese pictured the lightning spirit as a male god, and only later did the gentler Mother of Lightning take his place, worshipped as a goddess in her own right by about the Tang and Song dynasties. She works within a whole team of storm gods, alongside the thunder god, the rain master, the earl of wind, and the god of clouds, and in one great Ming novel she even appears under another name, the Holy Mother of Golden Light.","citation":"","answerText":"Dianmu"},
{"id":"cnh-081","num":"八十一","category":"China · History","question":"A legendary sage-king and great-grandson of the Yellow Emperor, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was one of the Five Emperors and the common ancestor of both the Shang and Zhou royal houses as well as the father of Yao.","answer":"Emperor Ku","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">帝嚳 / 帝喾 — Dì Kù, the sage-king of the Gaoxin clan</span></div>","traditional":"帝嚳","hanzi":"帝喾","pinyin":"Dì Kù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dì Kù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Ku</b>, also called Gaoxin, is one of the legendary Five Emperors, the wise rulers said to have governed China in the golden ages before the first dynasties. By tradition he was a great-grandson of the Yellow Emperor and came to the throne after his kinsman Zhuanxu, though he belongs wholly to legend rather than to recorded history. The old histories praise him as a model king, clear-sighted and fair, gentle yet commanding, who knew the needs of his people and won their willing obedience. He was remembered above all for ordering the calendar, carefully following the movements of the sun and the moon so that the seasons and the farming year could be reckoned. Some scholars suspect that this human sage-king was once the same figure as Di Jun, the shadowy high god of the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, split in later ages into a god and a man. <br><br> Ku's true fame rests on his remarkable children, for from him sprang the royal houses of both the Shang and the Zhou, the two great dynasties of early China. His son Xie became the ancestor of the Shang kings, and legend told that Xie was conceived when his mother swallowed the egg of a dark bird that fell from the sky. Another son, Houji, the god of millet and farming, became the ancestor of the Zhou kings, and was said to have been conceived when his mother trod in the giant footprint of a god. Ku was also the father of the great sage-emperor Yao, whose elder brother Zhi first took the throne but was soon set aside as unworthy in Yao's favour. One strange tale of his reign tells of Panhu, a five-coloured dog who killed the emperor's enemy and won his daughter in marriage, becoming the honoured ancestor of several peoples of southern China.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Ku"},
{"id":"cnh-082","num":"八十二","category":"China · History","question":"The model sage-king of the Five Emperors who fixed the calendar and faced a great flood, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is most famed for passing over his own son to hand the throne to the worthy commoner Shun.","answer":"Emperor Yao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">堯 / 尧 — Yáo, the sage-king Fangxun</span></div>","traditional":"堯","hanzi":"尧","pinyin":"Yáo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yáo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Yao</b> is one of the legendary Five Emperors of ancient China and, to later ages, the very model of the perfect ruler. A son of Emperor Ku, he was remembered as wise, tireless and humble, a king who lived so simply, in a thatched hut on plain food, that he became a model of modesty. So golden was his reign thought to be that the reign of Yao and Shun became a byword for a peaceful and virtuous age, though the man himself belongs to legend, not history. He is said to have set the year in order, sending his astronomers Xi and He to watch the sun, moon and stars and fix a calendar of 366 days, kept right by adding a leap month. During his reign a terrible flood drowned the land, and the minister Gun he set to tame it toiled for nine years building dams and dikes, only to fail. <br><br> Yao's most famous act was to choose his successor by worth rather than by blood, for he judged his own son Danzhu unfit to rule. Passing over his own child, he handed the throne to a poor but deeply dutiful commoner named Shun, whom he tested for years and gave his two daughters in marriage. This peaceful surrender of power to the worthiest man became the great Confucian ideal of good government, praised down the ages as the noblest way to pass on a crown. Yet not every old book tells so gentle a story, for some, like the <i>Bamboo Annals</i>, claim instead that Shun seized power by force and shut the aged Yao away until he died. Many fond legends grew up around his light rule, such as the tale of the hermit Xu You, who was so appalled at being offered the empire that he ran to a river to wash the words from his ears.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Yao"},
{"id":"cnh-083","num":"八十三","category":"China · History","question":"The son of Emperor Yao judged too unworthy to rule, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was passed over for the commoner Shun, and legend says his father invented the game of Go to reform him.","answer":"Danzhu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">丹朱 — Dān Zhū, the passed-over son of Yao</span></div>","traditional":"丹朱","hanzi":"丹朱","pinyin":"Dān Zhū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dān Zhū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Danzhu</b> was the son of the great sage-king Emperor Yao, and he is remembered as the classic bad heir whose own father would not let him rule. In the accepted story, Yao judged his son proud, quarrelsome and idle, and so unfit that he passed over his own child and gave the throne instead to the humble commoner Shun. Yao reasoned that to crown Danzhu would please one man but harm the whole world, and he said he would not injure the empire for the sake of a single person. This became the founding example of handing power to the worthiest man rather than to one's own son, the ideal that later ages praised so highly. Yet Danzhu's black reputation may be partly unfair, for it grew up to justify that choice, and a few old writings still give him the title of emperor as though he had reigned after all. <br><br> The most famous tale about him is that Yao invented the board game of Go in order to teach and settle his restless son. A book written long afterward records that the wise king designed the game to sharpen the boy's mind and calm his temper, though another version says it was really Shun who invented Go for a dull son of his own. Since the true beginnings of Go are lost in the deep past, this charming story is only a legend, not real history. What became of Danzhu is told in different ways: in the kind version Shun let him keep his own land and honour his ancestors, while darker books say he was banished, or even that Shun seized power by force. One eerie legend adds that after rebelling and drowning himself he turned into a strange owl-like bird whose appearance was a sign that officials would soon be sent into exile.","citation":"","answerText":"Danzhu"},
{"id":"cnh-084","num":"八十四","category":"China · History","question":"The humble commoner whose perfect devotion to a family that tried to kill him made him China's model of filial piety, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was chosen by Yao as the last of the Five Emperors.","answer":"Emperor Shun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">舜 — Shùn, the sage-king Chonghua</span></div>","traditional":"舜","hanzi":"舜","pinyin":"Shùn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shùn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Shun</b> is the last of the legendary Five Emperors and, above all, the great Chinese model of filial piety, the loving duty a child owes its parents. Though descended from the Yellow Emperor long before, he was born a poor commoner who farmed, fished, and made pots. His own family hated him and again and again tried to kill him, his blind father, his scheming stepmother, and his greedy younger half-brother Xiang. Once they set fire to a barn roof he was mending, but he floated to the ground holding two broad sunhats like wings; another time they buried him alive in a well, but he escaped through a tunnel dug in secret. Through it all Shun never stopped loving and serving them, bearing no grudge, and for this he is honoured as the first of the Twenty-four Filial Exemplars. <br><br> So great was his virtue that wherever he settled the quarrelsome grew gentle, and a place he lived in would swell within a few years from a hamlet into a city. Hearing of him, Emperor Yao gave him his two daughters in marriage to test him, and at last passed over his own son to hand Shun the throne. As emperor he ruled through wise ministers, divided the land into twelve provinces, and chose Yu the Great to tame the great flood; in the end he too gave the crown not to his own son but to the worthy Yu. Not all old books call this a peaceful gift, however, for some claim that Shun in fact seized power from Yao by force, just as Yu was later said to have done to Shun. Tradition says Shun died far away in the south, where his two grieving widows wept until their tears speckled the riverside bamboo, then drowned themselves in the Xiang River and became its goddesses.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Shun"},
{"id":"cnh-085","num":"八十五","category":"China · History","question":"The wicked younger half-brother who plotted to murder Emperor Shun for his wives and wealth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was forgiven by the ever-dutiful Shun and later made a lord despite his crimes.","answer":"Xiang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">象 — Xiàng, 'elephant', the wicked brother of Shun</span></div>","traditional":"象","hanzi":"象","pinyin":"Xiàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiàng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xiang</b> was the younger half-brother of the sage-king Emperor Shun, and he is remembered as the very picture of the wicked, jealous younger brother in Chinese legend. He was the son of Shun's blind old father and his cruel stepmother, and his name, fittingly for so heavy a villain, means elephant. Proud and grasping, Xiang joined his parents in plotting again and again to murder the gentle Shun, whose goodness he could not bear. What he wanted was Shun's wealth and, above all, Shun's two wives, the lovely daughters of Emperor Yao. Twice the family nearly killed him, once setting a barn ablaze while Shun was on the roof and snatching away his ladder, once burying him alive in a deep well, yet each time Shun escaped unharmed. <br><br> After the well was filled in, Xiang was so sure his brother was dead that he shared out the family's spoils, leaving his parents the cattle and grain stores and claiming Shun's house, his lute, and his two wives for himself. But Shun was alive, and when the brothers met again, the guilty Xiang could only stammer that he had merely been missing him. Astonishingly, Shun bore his brother no grudge at all but went on loving him, glad when Xiang was glad and grieved when he grieved, for, as the philosopher Mencius later explained, a good man keeps no anger against his own brother. When Shun became emperor he did not punish Xiang but made him a lord, granting him the fief of Youbi, while quietly sending officials to govern it so that the wicked brother could never harm its people. The tale became a favourite Confucian lesson in brotherly love, and because Xiang's name means elephant, a few scholars have even wondered whether he began, in the oldest stories, as a beast that Shun tamed.","citation":"","answerText":"Xiang"},
{"id":"cnh-086","num":"八十六","category":"China · History","question":"The two wives of Emperor Shun who wept until their tears speckled the bamboo and then drowned themselves in grief, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the goddesses of a river in southern China and are honoured in the ancient <i>Nine Songs</i>.","answer":"Xiang River goddesses","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">湘水神 — Xiāngshuǐshén, the Xiang goddesses Ehuang and Nüying</span></div>","traditional":"湘水神","hanzi":"湘水神","pinyin":"Xiāngshuǐshén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiāngshuǐshén</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xiang River goddesses</b> is the name given to the two spirits of the Xiang River in southern China, who are most often said to be the sisters Ehuang, the elder, and Nüying, the younger. These two were the daughters of the sage-king Yao, who married them both to his humble successor Shun to test whether the good man could keep peace in his household. They proved loving and wise wives, and in some tales even helped Shun escape the murderous plots of his own family. When at last the aged Shun died far away on a journey through the southern wilds, the two sisters were overcome with grief. They hurried south and wept for him beside the Xiang, and their falling tears splashed the green bamboo along the banks and stained it forever with dark spots. <br><br> To this day that speckled 'goddess bamboo' still grows by the river, above all on Junshan Island in Lake Dongting, where a shrine to the two consorts stands, and in Chinese poetry its spots are always the tears of the grieving wives. Unable to bear their loss, the sisters drowned themselves in the Xiang and became its goddesses, and their sad story has been loved and retold ever since. The oldest hymns to the river spirits are two of the beautiful <i>Nine Songs</i> of the ancient south, verses attributed to the poet Qu Yuan and addressed to the Lord and the Lady of the Xiang. Whether those two spirits are truly Shun's wives is an old question, for that link was drawn only later, and some early readers thought the Lord of the Xiang was instead a male river-god. Even so, the picture of the faithful sisters and their tear-stained bamboo has stayed a favourite image for poets down to modern times, echoed as late as a famous poem by Mao Zedong.","citation":"","answerText":"Xiang River goddesses"},
{"id":"cnh-087","num":"八十七","category":"China · History","question":"Begun in the reign of Emperor Yao and finally tamed by Yu the Great through patient dredging, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese deluge that heroes conquered by engineering rather than survived in an ark.","answer":"Great Flood","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">大洪水 — Dà Hóngshuǐ, the flood tamed by Gun and Yu</span></div>","traditional":"大洪水","hanzi":"大洪水","pinyin":"Dà Hóngshuǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Hóngshuǐ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Great Flood</b> is the central deluge story of Chinese myth, a catastrophe that drowned the land in the days of the sage-king Yao and raged on for two whole generations. It was quite unlike the flood of Noah in the West, for it was not sent by a god to punish and wipe out mankind, and no one was saved in an ark. Instead it was a disaster to be conquered by human skill and hard engineering, so the story is really about taming the waters and building good government. Yao first gave the task to a man named Gun, who tried to hold the flood back with great dikes and dams and, the old myths say, even stole a magical self-growing soil from heaven to build them. But water cannot be walled out forever, and after nine years of failure Gun's barriers still burst, and he was put to death at Feather Mountain by Yao's successor Shun. <br><br> The work then passed to Gun's son, the hero Yu the Great, who saw that his father's way was wrong. Rather than block the water, Yu worked with it, dredging the riverbeds and cutting channels to lead the floods gently down to the sea. So tireless was he that he laboured for thirteen years and, as the famous tale goes, passed the door of his own house three times without once stopping to go in. In the end he mastered the flood and marked out the drained land into the Nine Provinces, and for this great service he was made emperor, founding the Xia, remembered as China's first dynasty. Some scientists have even wondered whether a real flood on the Yellow River, thousands of years ago, lies behind the story, though the idea is much disputed.","citation":"","answerText":"Great Flood"},
{"id":"cnh-088","num":"八十八","category":"China · History","question":"A magical soil that swells and grows endlessly of its own accord, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the ever-expanding earth that Gun stole from the gods to dam back the Great Flood.","answer":"Xirang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">息壤 — xīrǎng, the self-growing soil</span></div>","traditional":"息壤","hanzi":"息壤","pinyin":"Xīrǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīrǎng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xirang</b> is a wonderful magical soil in Chinese myth, an earth that grows and swells of its own accord and never runs out. A single lump of it will keep spreading and rising by itself, so that a mere handful can be piled up without end into hills, dams and dikes. Its very name holds its magic, for the word <i>xi</i> means both to breathe and to grow or multiply, and <i>rang</i> means soil, giving an earth that seems to breathe and increase forever. Because it is so strange, English writers have translated it in many ways, calling it the self-renewing soil, the breathing earth, the swelling mould, or the living earth. Such a soil was exactly what was needed against the Great Flood, whose waters rose higher and higher and could never be walled out with ordinary dirt. <br><br> In the oldest telling, found in the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i>, the hero Gun stole the xirang from the supreme god to dam back the flood, taking it without the god's leave. Enraged at the theft, the god sent the fire-god Zhurong to put Gun to death on Feather Mountain, though later histories say instead that it was the emperor Shun who had him killed. So the soil that might have saved the world became the cause of its keeper's ruin, for Gun was punished not for failing but for stealing a treasure of heaven. Gun's son, the great flood-tamer Yu, is sometimes said to have been given the same soil openly and lawfully, using it to plug the springs that fed the flood. Yet Yu is remembered far more for mastering the waters by digging channels than by piling up magic earth, and it is Gun's daring theft that the xirang is best known for.","citation":"","answerText":"Xirang"},
{"id":"cnh-089","num":"八十九","category":"China · History","question":"A venomous nine-headed serpent whose every resting place turned to poison marsh, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the monstrous minister of the flood-god Gonggong, slain at last by Yu the Great.","answer":"Xiangliu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">相柳 / 相繇 — Xiāngliǔ, the nine-headed serpent</span></div>","traditional":"相柳","hanzi":"相柳","pinyin":"Xiāngliǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiāngliǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xiangliu</b> is a monstrous nine-headed serpent of ancient Chinese myth, one of the great villains of the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> and the wicked minister of the flood-god Gonggong. That old book describes him as an enormous green snake, his nine heads each bearing a human face, his long body coiled among the mountains. So huge and greedy was he that his nine hungry mouths could feed from nine different mountains all at once, so that famine and ruin followed wherever he went. He was a creature of pure poison, and everywhere he lay down, breathed, or spat, the ground was turned to a foul and bitter marsh in which no plant or animal could live. He appears in the text under two different names, Xiangliu in one chapter and Xiangyao in another, but both tell of the very same dreadful beast. <br><br> At last the great hero Yu, tamer of the Great Flood, hunted the serpent down and slew him as he laboured to lead the drowned world's waters back to the sea. But even in death Xiangliu poisoned the earth, for his blood stank so foully that the soaked ground could bear no grain and sank into stinking swamp. Three times Yu tried to fill in the ruined land with soil, and three times it caved in beneath him, until he gave up and dug the whole place out into a deep pool. With the earth he had dug free, the gods raised a high terrace of their own upon that spot, far away in the north of the world. His master Gonggong was himself a great destroyer, a water-spirit blamed for the floods, and in our own day Xiangliu has returned as a tragic serpent-demon in the hit television drama <i>Lost You Forever</i>.","citation":"","answerText":"Xiangliu"},
{"id":"cnh-090","num":"九十","category":"China · History","question":"The father of Yu the Great and the first to battle the Great Flood, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> failed by trying to dam the waters and was put to death at Feather Mountain for his defeat.","answer":"Gun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鯀 / 鲧 — Gǔn, father of Yu the Great</span></div>","traditional":"鯀","hanzi":"鲧","pinyin":"Gǔn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gǔn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Gun</b> is a tragic hero of Chinese myth, the father of the flood-tamer Yu the Great and the very first man to battle the Great Flood. A descendant of the Yellow Emperor, he was chosen for the task, on his advisers' urging, by the emperor Yao, though only with great reluctance, for Yao warned that Gun was stubborn and would bring harm to his own people. To fight the rising waters, Gun tried to wall them out, raising great dikes and dams to hold the flood back. In the myths he even stole from heaven a magical soil that grew of its own accord, the <i>xirang</i>, and piled it up into ever-higher barriers. But blocking the water was the wrong way, and after nine long years his dikes still broke and burst, and the flood was as fierce as ever. <br><br> For his failure, and for stealing the sacred soil, Gun was banished and put to death at Feather Mountain, though the old books disagree over who ordered it, some naming Yao's heir Shun and others the fire-god Zhurong. Yet many later writers pitied Gun, blaming not the man but the impossible task he was set, and told that his body lay three whole years without rotting away. In one strange and famous tale his son Yu was cut living from Gun's belly, so that the hero who would finish the work was born from the body of the one who had failed it. Gun himself, they said, did not truly die but changed into a beast, a yellow bear in some tellings, a yellow dragon or a three-legged turtle in others, and slipped away into the deep. It was left to his son Yu to master the flood at last by the opposite path, not damming the water but dredging channels to guide it down to the sea.","citation":"","answerText":"Gun"},
{"id":"cnh-091","num":"九十一","category":"China · History","question":"The proud and dangerous god of the Yellow River who was humbled by the boundless sea in a famous tale of Zhuangzi, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was worshipped with human brides until the magistrate Ximen Bao put an end to the sacrifices.","answer":"He Bo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">河伯 — Hébó, the Earl of the Yellow River</span></div>","traditional":"河伯","hanzi":"河伯","pinyin":"Hébó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hébó</span></div>","abstract":"<b>He Bo</b> is the god of the Yellow River, the great and dangerous waterway of northern China, and his title means simply the Earl of the River. Legend made him a mortal man, Feng Yi, who drowned in the river and was raised up by heaven to become its god. He was pictured riding across the waves in a chariot drawn by two dragons, with the white face of a man on the body of a fish, and he could turn himself into a white dragon. Like the river he ruled, he was a mixture of good and ill, kindly and life-giving one moment, greedy, proud and cruelly destructive the next. His most famous story is a lesson in humility, told in the ancient book of the philosopher Zhuangzi. <br><br> When the autumn rains swelled his waters so wide that one could not tell an ox from a horse on the far bank, He Bo grew proud and believed that all the beauty of the world was his. But when he floated down at last to the boundless sea and met Ruo, the spirit of the Northern Ocean, he saw how tiny his river truly was and was humbled, learning that a frog in a well can know nothing of the sea. In darker days he was cruelly worshipped, for in one town girls were drowned in the river each year as brides for He Bo, until the bold magistrate Ximen Bao ended it by flinging the cheating witches into the water to carry his message to the god. He could himself be brought low, for the great archer Yi once shot him in the left eye as he swam about disguised as a white dragon. When He Bo complained to the supreme god, he was told he had earned the arrow by wandering the world in the shape of a beast.","citation":"","answerText":"He Bo"},
{"id":"cnh-092","num":"九十二","category":"China · History","question":"A monkey-shaped water demon of immense strength who flooded the Huai River, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was chained beneath a mountain by Yu the Great's men and is thought by some to be a forerunner of the Monkey King Sun Wukong.","answer":"Wuzhiqi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">無支祁 / 无支祁 — Wúzhīqí, the monkey demon of the Huai</span></div>","traditional":"無支祁","hanzi":"无支祁","pinyin":"Wúzhīqí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wúzhīqí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wuzhiqi</b> is a fearsome monkey-like water demon of Chinese myth, the wild spirit of the Huai River, blamed for its terrible floods. He first appears in a Tang-dynasty tale, which paints him as an ape with a snub nose and high brows, a white head, golden eyes, and teeth as white as snow. His neck could stretch out a hundred feet, and his strength was greater than that of nine elephants, so that no one could hold him. He was swift and cunning beyond watching, and a whole host of lesser water-spirits and goblins gathered to do his bidding. Raising winds and waves at will, he churned the Huai into raging floods that drowned the fields and villages along its banks, for he knew every shallow and deep of the great river. <br><br> When Yu the Great came to tame the floods, he could not master the demon himself, and the officers he first sent against Wuzhiqi all failed one after another. Only one of them, a god named Gengchen, at last overpowered the monster after a great struggle. They bound him with a huge iron chain, pierced his nose and hung a golden bell upon it, and locked him away beneath Turtle Mountain on the bank of the Huai, so that the river might run in peace. This tale of a mighty monkey-demon, chained for his crimes under a mountain, sounds strikingly like the story of Sun Wukong, the Monkey King of the novel <i>Journey to the West</i>, later pinned beneath the Five-Elements Mountain by the Buddha for five hundred years. For that reason some scholars, such as Lu Xun, have argued that Wuzhiqi was the native Chinese ancestor of the Monkey King, while others traced him instead to the Indian monkey-god Hanuman, a question still not settled.","citation":"","answerText":"Wuzhiqi"},
{"id":"cnh-093","num":"九十三","category":"China · History","question":"Cast by Yu the Great from the tribute bronze of the Nine Provinces, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> were the legendary vessels whose possession meant holding the Mandate of Heaven and the right to rule all China.","answer":"Nine Tripod Cauldrons","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Made by</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Yu the Great, or his son Qi</span></div>","traditional":"九鼎","hanzi":"九鼎","pinyin":"Jiǔ Dǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiǔ Dǐng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Nine Tripod Cauldrons</b> were nine great bronze vessels that stood, in Chinese tradition, as the supreme symbol of the right to rule all of China. Legend says they were cast by Yu the Great after he tamed the flood and divided the land into the Nine Provinces, though some tell instead that it was his son Qi who made them. The bronze was gathered as tribute from every province, and one mighty cauldron was cast for each of the nine. Upon them were pictured all the strange creatures and spirits of the land, so that the people might learn to tell the kindly beings from the dangerous ones. Whoever held these cauldrons was believed to hold the Mandate of Heaven itself, the god-given right to rule the whole world. <br><br> So they were handed down as the greatest treasure of the state, passing from the Xia dynasty to the Shang and then to the Zhou as each in turn won power. In a famous tale, an ambitious lord, the King of Chu, marched to the Zhou border and asked how big and heavy the cauldrons were, hinting that he meant to seize them for himself. But the Zhou king's envoy rebuked him, saying the right to rule lay in a ruler's virtue, not in the cauldrons, and from this came the saying 'to ask about the cauldrons,' meaning to covet the throne. In the end they were lost as the Zhou fell; tradition says they sank into the Si River, and the First Emperor of Qin sent a thousand men to dredge for them in vain. No such cauldrons have ever been dug up, and they remain a legend, yet real bronze cauldrons were prized treasures, and by ancient rule only the king might own a set of nine.","citation":"","answerText":"Nine Tripod Cauldrons"},
{"id":"cnh-094","num":"九十四","category":"China · History","question":"Hundun, Qiongqi, Taowu, and Taotie — four evil monsters each embodying a vice like chaos or greed — make up the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the wicked beasts that the sage-king Shun banished to the ends of the earth.","answer":"Four Perils","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">四凶 — sì xiōng, the four evil beasts</span></div>","traditional":"四凶","hanzi":"四凶","pinyin":"Sì Xiōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sì Xiōng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Four Perils</b> are the four wicked monsters of Chinese myth, each the living shape of a different vice, whom the sage-king Shun drove out to the four corners of the world. They were Hundun, the beast of chaos and stupidity; Qiongqi, the beast of cruelty and injustice; Taowu, the beast of stubborn ignorance; and Taotie, the beast of bottomless greed. Shun banished them to the far frontiers of the land, there to face the goblins and evil spirits that haunted its edges. They should not be muddled with another group of four that Shun also cast out, the Four Criminals, who were wicked ministers and rebels of human kind rather than monsters. Old books tell of the perils in two ways, some as evil men descended from the ancient clans, others as fearsome beasts. <br><br> Qiongqi was the strangest of all, a winged tiger that fed on people yet dealt out good and evil the wrong way about. It would devour the honest and the loyal, but to a wicked man it would bring a fresh kill as a reward. Hundun was a faceless creature, all confusion, that fawned on the wicked and shunned the good, while Taowu, a beast with a human face, tiger's feet and a boar's tusks, was so stubborn and dull that no one could teach or reason with it. So hated was Taowu that the state of Chu named its book of history after the beast, to record men's evil deeds as a warning to later ages. Taotie, the glutton, was pictured as a great head with no body, forever devouring, and it later gave its name to the staring animal-mask, with its huge eyes and no lower jaw, that glares out from the ancient bronze ritual vessels of the Shang and Zhou.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Perils"},
{"id":"cnh-095","num":"九十五","category":"China · History","question":"The Chinese monster of insatiable greed whose gaping face became the famous staring mask on ancient bronze vessels, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is one of the Four Perils and a byword for gluttony.","answer":"Taotie","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">饕餮 — tāotiè, the glutton monster</span></div>","traditional":"饕餮","hanzi":"饕餮","pinyin":"Tāotiè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tāotiè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Taotie</b> is the monster of greed and gluttony in Chinese myth, so bound up with hunger that its very name became the ordinary word for a glutton. It is one of the Four Perils, the four wicked beasts banished by the sage-king Shun, and the oldest books call it the greedy son of an ancient clan in the days of the Yellow Emperor. A strange early tale says the taotie was all head and no body, a mouth that ate people without ever being filled. But the taotie is famous above all as a face in bronze, the great staring mask that decorates the ritual vessels of the Shang and Zhou dynasties. It shows a fierce animal head seen from the front, perfectly matched left and right, with huge round eyes and curling horns but no lower jaw, and it looks out from countless ancient cauldrons and cups. <br><br> Yet no one truly knows what that mask meant to the people who cast it thousands of years ago, for they left no word of it. The very name taotie was only fixed to the design a thousand years later, and it may not be what its makers called it at all. Scholars still argue over its purpose, guessing that it warded off evil, or helped men speak with the ancestors at sacrifices, or warned against greed, while some believe it was only a pattern with no meaning behind it. In later ages the taotie was counted among the nine sons of the dragon, the hungry one whose image belongs on pots and food vessels. Its fearsome face is one of the best-loved images of ancient China, and in our own time it even lent its name to the alien monsters of a modern film about the Great Wall.","citation":"","answerText":"Taotie"},
{"id":"cnh-096","num":"九十六","category":"China · History","question":"A winged tiger of Chinese myth that eats the honest and rewards the wicked, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Four Peril that embodies injustice, turning right and wrong upside down.","answer":"Qiongqi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">窮奇 / 穷奇 — Qióngqí, the beast of injustice</span></div>","traditional":"窮奇","hanzi":"穷奇","pinyin":"Qióngqí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qióngqí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qiongqi</b> is a monster of Chinese myth, one of the Four Perils, and the beast that stands for deceit and perverse injustice. Its name means something like 'utterly strange,' it understands the speech of men, and the old books, written across many ages, cannot even agree on how it looked. In one telling it is a winged tiger that flies down and devours people head-first, leaving its victims with their hair torn loose; in another it is a shaggy ox-like beast covered in a hedgehog's bristles, that howls like a dog and eats men as well. The oldest account makes Qiongqi a wicked man rather than a beast, a worthless son of the ancient Shaohao clan who betrayed trust, scorned loyalty, and dressed up lies and slander as the truth. For his crimes the sage-king Shun cast him out, with the other three Perils, to the far frontiers of the world, there to face the demons of the wild. <br><br> But Qiongqi is remembered above all for the cruel way it turned right and wrong upside down. When it hears two men quarreling, it hunts down and eats the one who is in the right; when it hears of an honest and loyal man, it flies to him and eats his nose. Yet to a wicked man it is kind, killing a beast and bringing it to him as a gift, so that always it rewards the wicked and punishes the good. In this way it became the very image of a corrupt world, where the honest suffer and the cruel and the false prosper. Strangely, in another old tradition the same fearsome creature was called upon for good, summoned each year in the great winter festival of exorcism to hunt down and devour evil spirits and the poison of witchcraft.","citation":"","answerText":"Qiongqi"},
{"id":"cnh-097","num":"九十七","category":"China · History","question":"An unteachable, pig-headed beast whose very name the state of Chu gave to its book of history, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Four Peril that embodies blind stubbornness and reckless folly.","answer":"Taowu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">檮杌 / 梼杌 — Táowù, the beast of stubbornness</span></div>","traditional":"檮杌","hanzi":"梼杌","pinyin":"Táowù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táowù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Taowu</b> is one of the Four Perils of Chinese myth, the beast that stands for blind stubbornness, arrogance, and reckless folly. Its very name means a block stump, a lump of dead wood, and marks it out as a hopeless blockhead who can be neither taught nor turned. The oldest books tell of Taowu not as a monster but as a man, the worthless son of the ancient emperor Zhuanxu, so arrogant and pig-headed that he would heed no good advice and could not be corrected. For this the sage-king Shun cast him out, along with the other three Perils, to the far frontiers of the world. Only in later tales did Taowu take the shape of a fearsome beast, with a human face, the legs of a tiger, the tusks of a boar, and a hugely long tail, and it was also called the Proud-and-Fierce and the Hard-to-Train. <br><br> The strangest thing about Taowu is that its name was given not only to the beast but to a book. The great teacher Mencius records that each state kept its own chronicle, and while Jin called its record the <i>Sheng</i> and Lu called its own the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, the southern state of Chu named its history the Taowu. Later scholars explained that a history was named after so wicked a creature on purpose, to set down the evil deeds of the past as a warning to the men of later days. The name stuck to the idea of a cautionary history, and centuries afterward a Song writer borrowed it again for his own chronicle of the vanished kingdoms of Shu. In time the word Taowu passed into common speech as well, a name for any violent, stubborn, and incorrigible person, much as its fellow Peril Taotie became the everyday word for a glutton.","citation":"","answerText":"Taowu"},
{"id":"cnh-098","num":"九十八","category":"China · History","question":"An aquatic flood dragon of the deep pools that the old books cannot agree how to define, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the scaly water-serpent that Zhou Chu battled as one of his village's three scourges.","answer":"Jiaolong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蛟龍 / 蛟龙 — jiāolóng, the flood dragon</span></div>","traditional":"蛟龍","hanzi":"蛟龙","pinyin":"Jiāolóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiāolóng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jiaolong</b>, often called the flood dragon, is a fierce water-dragon of Chinese myth that lurks in deep rivers and pools and was blamed for sudden floods. It is one of the murkiest creatures in the whole tradition, for the old books cannot agree on what it even is. Some call it a scaly dragon, some a hornless one, some a small or young dragon not yet grown, and some hardly a dragon at all but a kind of crocodile. In shape it is usually drawn as a great snake with four short legs, a small head on a slender neck, and a white patch or tassel at the throat. The jiao was thought to be the lord of the fishes, and one old book says that when the fish in a pool grow to three thousand six hundred, a jiao comes to lead them and carry them off into the sky. <br><br> In one telling the jiao is only a stage in a long climb toward becoming a true dragon. A water-snake, it was said, turns into a jiao after five hundred years, and the jiao in turn becomes a full dragon after a thousand more, at last rising into the heavens. For this reason the flood dragon came to stand for a person of great but hidden talent, waiting like a jiao in its pool for the chance to soar. Its most famous appearance is in the tale of Zhou Chu, a wild young bully whose village named three plagues that tormented them: a man-eating tiger, a jiao in the river, and Zhou Chu himself. He killed the tiger and battled the jiao in the water for three days and nights, and when he came home to find the people celebrating his death, he saw at last how hated he was, and reformed into a good man.","citation":"","answerText":"Jiaolong"},
{"id":"cnh-099","num":"九十九","category":"China · History","question":"A giant serpent of the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> that swallowed elephants whole and spat out their bones three years later, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave China its famous image of insatiable greed, the snake that tries to swallow an elephant.","answer":"Bashe","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">巴蛇 — Bāshé, the elephant-swallowing serpent</span></div>","traditional":"巴蛇","hanzi":"巴蛇","pinyin":"Bāshé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bāshé</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Bashe</b> is a monstrous serpent of ancient Chinese myth, a giant snake of the old southern land of Ba, in what is now Sichuan, famous above all for swallowing whole elephants, python-like, into its belly. The <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> tells that the Bashe would devour an elephant whole, and only after three long years would it disgorge the beast's picked-clean bones. It adds a strange note that a gentleman who took it as medicine would never after suffer any ailment of the heart or belly. The old book paints the creature in four colours at once, green, yellow, red and black, though another version calls it a black snake with a green head. No length is given in the text, only that it was vast beyond measure, huge enough to take a full-grown elephant down its throat, and later writers stretched it to fabulous and impossible sizes, longer than any real snake could ever grow. <br><br> Because of this fearsome greed the Bashe gave China one of its favourite sayings about wanting too much. To picture a snake trying to swallow an elephant became the very image of a heart that is never satisfied, forever grasping for more than it can hold. A later tale tells how the great archer Yi hunted down a huge man-eating serpent that troubled the people at Lake Dongting in the south. That long serpent, which later story came to call the Bashe, was slain, and its heaped bones are said to have formed a hill by the lake, still known long afterward by the old name of Baling, the early name of the city of Yueyang. Even the ancient poems wondered at the beast, one of them asking how a snake that could gulp down an elephant could ever manage to swallow its bones.","citation":"","answerText":"Bashe"},
{"id":"cnh-100","num":"一百","category":"China · History","question":"The supreme trinity of Daoism, emanations of the Dao that rank even above the Jade Emperor and include the deified Laozi, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are the three highest gods of the Daoist heaven.","answer":"Three Pure Ones","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三清 — Sānqīng, the three highest Daoist gods</span></div>","traditional":"三清","hanzi":"三清","pinyin":"Sānqīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānqīng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Pure Ones</b> are the three highest gods of Daoism, the supreme trinity that sits at the very summit of the whole heavenly host. They are understood not as ordinary gods but as the first pure forms taken by the Dao itself, the nameless source of all things, as the One breath divided into Three at the dawn of creation. The first and greatest is the Heavenly Lord of the Primordial Beginning, from whom the other two proceed like light from a single flame. The second is the Heavenly Lord of the Numinous Treasure, and the third the Heavenly Lord of the Way and its Virtue, also called the Supreme Elder Lord. Each dwells in one of the three highest heavens, the shining pure realms of Jade Clarity, of the Upper Clarity, and of the Grand Clarity, one heaven for each. <br><br> This third Pure One is the most familiar of the three, for he is the deified form of the great sage Laozi, the reputed founder of Daoism and author of its holy book, the <i>Daodejing</i>. In the earliest days of the Daoist religion the deified Laozi was himself the supreme god, and only later was the Primordial Beginning raised above him to complete the trinity. Lofty and remote, the Three Pure Ones stand even above the Jade Emperor, who for all his glory is only their servant, the ruler and manager of heaven's vast bureaucracy. Yet because they are so abstract and distant, ordinary worshippers pray far more often to the Jade Emperor and the lesser gods than to the pure and silent Three. In Daoist temples the Three sit side by side in the Hall of the Three Pure Ones, each robed in majesty and bearing his own emblem, a pearl, a scepter, or a fan.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Pure Ones"},
{"id":"cnh-101","num":"一百零一","category":"China · History","question":"The highest of the Three Pure Ones and the supreme god of Daoism, formed from the purest breath before Heaven and Earth, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ranks even above the Jade Emperor, to whom he handed the government of heaven.","answer":"Yuanshi Tianzun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">元始天尊 — Yuánshǐ Tiānzūn, the Primordial Beginning</span></div>","traditional":"元始天尊","hanzi":"元始天尊","pinyin":"Yuánshǐ Tiānzūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuánshǐ Tiānzūn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yuanshi Tianzun</b>, the Heavenly Lord of the Primordial Beginning, is the first and highest of the Three Pure Ones and the supreme god of Daoism. In Daoist belief he has no beginning and no end, having formed himself out of the purest breath of the universe before Heaven and Earth were made. Formless and eternal, he is thought of less as a person than as the very origin of all things, the pure source from which the whole world flowed. He dwells in the loftiest of the three heavens, the shining realm of Jade Purity, above every other god and spirit. Long ago he ruled all of heaven himself, but he handed its daily government to his helper the Jade Emperor, and so stands high above that busy lord of the sky. <br><br> His greatest work is the giving of wisdom, for at the birth of each new age of the world he reveals the holy scriptures to the lesser gods, who pass their teachings down to mankind. He was not always reckoned the highest god, for in the older Daoist faith that place belonged to the deified Laozi. Only later, as the religion grew, was Yuanshi Tianzun raised above him to the very top of the heavenly ranks, a change fixed by the scholar Tao Hongjing around fifteen hundred years ago. In pictures he is often shown holding a shining pearl, the Pearl of Creation, though some held him too formless and pure ever to be shown at all, and would worship him only through a written tablet bearing his name. He also plays a grand part in the Ming novel <i>Investiture of the Gods</i>, where he leads the immortals of one great sect and hands his disciple the magic list by which the heroes of the war are made into gods.","citation":"","answerText":"Yuanshi Tianzun"},
{"id":"cnh-102","num":"一百零二","category":"China · History","question":"The Heavenly Lord of the Numinous Treasure and keeper of the sacred scriptures, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the second of the Three Pure Ones, who in the Daoist creation myth parted the yin from the yang.","answer":"Lingbao Tianzun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">靈寶天尊 / 灵宝天尊 — Língbǎo Tiānzūn, the Numinous Treasure</span></div>","traditional":"靈寶天尊","hanzi":"灵宝天尊","pinyin":"Língbǎo Tiānzūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Língbǎo Tiānzūn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lingbao Tianzun</b>, the Heavenly Lord of the Numinous Treasure, is the second of the Three Pure Ones, the middle figure of the supreme Daoist trinity that crowns the whole pantheon. He proceeds from the great Yuanshi Tianzun above him, as the primal One divides into Two, and so takes his place just below the highest god of all. He dwells in the second of the three pure heavens, the realm of Upper Clarity, ruling from a rank beneath the topmost heaven of Jade. In the Daoist story of creation it was Lingbao Tianzun who did the great sorting of the world, parting the yang from the yin, the clear from the murky, and setting the elements each in their order. To him also belongs the reckoning of time, which he divides into the long ages and epochs through which the universe turns. <br><br> Above all he is the keeper of the holy books, the guardian of the sacred scriptures, and he bears the fitting title of the Treasure of the Scripture. In temple images he sits at the side of the Primordial Lord, most often holding a curved ruyi scepter, the sign of his authority. His name is shared by one of the great streams of the Daoist religion, the Numinous Treasure tradition, whose scriptures took shape about sixteen hundred years ago and shaped much of Daoist ritual, though the god and the school are not quite the same thing. Like his two fellow Pure Ones, Lingbao Tianzun stands far above the Jade Emperor, the mere ruler and clerk of heaven's affairs. Yet of the three he is the most shadowy and abstract, a lofty principle rather than a person, with none of the earthly life that made the third Pure One, the human sage Laozi, so beloved.","citation":"","answerText":"Lingbao Tianzun"},
{"id":"cnh-103","num":"一百零三","category":"China · History","question":"The third of the Three Pure Ones and the divine teacher who brings the Way to mankind, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the deified form of the sage Laozi, who wrote the <i>Daodejing</i> and rode west on an ox.","answer":"Daode Tianzun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">道德天尊 — Dàodé Tiānzūn, the deified Laozi</span></div>","traditional":"道德天尊","hanzi":"道德天尊","pinyin":"Dàodé Tiānzūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàodé Tiānzūn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Daode Tianzun</b>, the Heavenly Lord of the Way and its Virtue, is the third of the Three Pure Ones, the supreme trinity of Daoism. Better known by his other name, the Supreme Elder Lord, he is the great teacher among the three, the god who brings the Way down to mankind and preaches its law to the world. He dwells in the third and lowest of the pure heavens, the realm of Grand Clarity, nearest of the three to the world of living men. For the Daoists believed that this god had taken human shape again and again through the ages to teach the sages and kings of the earth. His most famous human life of all was as the old philosopher Laozi, the reputed founder of the Daoist faith. <br><br> In that life, disgusted with a corrupt age, Laozi rode away west out of China on the back of an ox to end his days as a hermit. At the last mountain pass the gatekeeper begged the old sage to leave some wisdom behind, and so Laozi wrote down the little book of five thousand words called the <i>Daodejing</i>, the Classic of the Way and Virtue, before he vanished for ever into the west. In the earliest Daoist religion this deified Laozi was himself the highest of all the gods, and only later was he placed third, below the Primordial Beginning. So great was his fame that the emperors of the Tang dynasty claimed him as their own ancestor, while a bitter old story, made up to spite the Buddhists, even declared that after going west he had become the Buddha himself. Like his fellow Pure Ones he ranks far above the Jade Emperor, and he is pictured as a serene white-bearded old man, sometimes still seated upon his faithful ox.","citation":"","answerText":"Daode Tianzun"},
{"id":"cnh-104","num":"一百零四","category":"China · History","question":"A band of beloved Daoist saints — a scholar, a beggar, a woman, an old man on a backward donkey, and more — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> famously crossed the sea, each using their own magic emblem, in a tale that became a proverb for showing one's own talents.","answer":"Eight Immortals","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">八仙 — Bāxiān, the eight Daoist immortals</span></div>","traditional":"八仙","hanzi":"八仙","pinyin":"Bāxiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bāxiān</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Eight Immortals</b> are a band of eight beloved Daoist saints of Chinese legend, drawn from every walk of life, whose adventures are among the best-loved tales in the land. Their leader is the scholar Lü Dongbin with his demon-slaying sword, taught by the jolly, fat-bellied Zhongli Quan, who carries a fan said to raise the dead. With them go the lame beggar Li Tieguai, leaning on an iron crutch and holding a gourd of medicine, and the aged Zhang Guolao, who rides his donkey backwards and folds it away like paper. The others are the courtier Cao Guojiu with his jade tablets, the flute-playing youth Han Xiangzi, the flower-carrying Lan Caihe, and He Xiangu, the woman of the group, who bears a lotus bloom. Old and young, rich and poor, man and woman, they show that immortality lies open to every kind of person, and they are said to dwell on the fairy isle of Penglai in the eastern sea. <br><br> Their most famous exploit is the day they crossed the sea, when instead of riding the clouds each immortal cast a magic emblem upon the water and floated across on it. This gave China a favourite saying, that the Eight Immortals cross the sea, each showing their own special powers, meaning that everyone brings their own gifts to a task. The crossing plunged them into a great battle with the Dragon King of the Eastern Sea, whose son had seized one of their number and stolen a treasure. Their eight emblems, drawn on their own, form a lucky pattern called the Hidden Eight Immortals, painted on everything from fans to birthday gifts as a wish for long life and good fortune. Though some of the eight were dreamed up long before, they were gathered into their familiar company only in the Ming dynasty, and they have delighted Chinese art and opera ever since.","citation":"","answerText":"Eight Immortals"},
{"id":"cnh-105","num":"一百零五","category":"China · History","question":"The most famous of the Eight Immortals, a sword-carrying Daoist scholar who dreamed a whole empty lifetime while a pot of millet cooked, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave up his worldly ambitions to seek immortality under the immortal Zhongli Quan.","answer":"Lü Dongbin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">呂洞賓 / 吕洞宾 — Lǚ Dòngbīn, the immortal scholar</span></div>","traditional":"呂洞賓","hanzi":"吕洞宾","pinyin":"Lǚ Dòngbīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǚ Dòngbīn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lü Dongbin</b> is the most famous of the Eight Immortals, and the only one worshipped as a great god in his own right, apart from the group. He began, half in history and half in legend, as a Tang-dynasty scholar and poet named Lü Yan, known by his Daoist title Pure Yang. He is pictured as a gentleman in a scholar's robes, with a horsehair fly-whisk that lets him ride the clouds and a magic sword slung across him. That sword was said to be a gift from a fire-dragon, and with it he slew demons and monsters wherever he found them. But the blade carried a deeper meaning too, for it stood for the cutting away of a man's own greed, anger, and folly. <br><br> His path to immortality began at a roadside inn, where he met the merry old immortal Zhongli Quan while a pot of yellow millet was set to cook. Dozing off, Lü dreamed a whole lifetime — he rose to high office, grew rich, raised a great family, then fell into ruin and disgrace and died — and woke to find the millet still not done. Seeing in a flash how empty all worldly glory was, he gave up his ambitions and followed Zhongli Quan, who first tested him with ten temptations before teaching him the secrets of the Dao. This famous 'yellow millet dream' was borrowed from an older Tang story and fastened onto Lü, who in folk tales is a merry, wine-loving rogue as often as a solemn saint. He grew so beloved that the great school of Complete Perfection honoured him as one of its founding patriarchs, his grand temple still stands in the hills of Shanxi, and he is the patron of scholars and, oddly, of barbers.","citation":"","answerText":"Lü Dongbin"},
{"id":"cnh-106","num":"一百零六","category":"China · History","question":"The oldest of the Eight Immortals, a lame and ragged beggar whose soul entered a dead man's body after his own was burned too soon, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> leans on an iron crutch and carries a gourd of healing medicine.","answer":"Li Tieguai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">李鐵拐 / 李铁拐 — Lǐ Tiěguǎi, Iron-Crutch Li</span></div>","traditional":"李鐵拐","hanzi":"李铁拐","pinyin":"Lǐ Tiěguǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Tiěguǎi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Tieguai</b>, whose name means Iron-Crutch Li, is counted the oldest and most senior of the Eight Immortals of Daoism, a band of saints who belong to legend rather than to true history. He is the strangest-looking of that merry company, for he goes about as a lame, filthy, ill-tempered old beggar with a matted beard and a blackened face. He hobbles along on an iron crutch, and slung at his side he carries a bottle-gourd filled with wonder-working medicine. Ugly and ragged though he is, he has a kind heart, wandering the world to cure the sick and help the poor, and in the immortals' most famous adventure he floats across the sea upon his iron crutch. For his healing gifts the Chinese honour him as a patron of medicine, and his gourd was long hung as a sign above the doors of apothecaries and druggists. <br><br> He was not always so hideous, for the legend tells that he began as a handsome man, in some tales named Li Xuan, deeply learned in the secret arts of the Way. So great was his skill that his soul could leave his body and fly abroad, and one day it departed to meet the great sage Laozi upon a sacred mountain. Before setting out he told a disciple to guard his lifeless body for seven days, and to burn it only if he had not returned by then. But the disciple was called away by his dying mother and, believing his master truly dead, burned the body a day too early, so that the returning soul came back to find no home to enter. In its distress it slipped into the only corpse near at hand, that of a starved and lame old beggar, and it was Laozi himself who consoled the dismayed spirit and gave him the iron crutch and the gourd of elixir that have been his emblems ever since.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Tieguai"},
{"id":"cnh-107","num":"一百零七","category":"China · History","question":"Once a heavenly general cast down for smashing a crystal cup, the dark-faced river-ogre <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the calm and loyal third disciple who carried the baggage and kept peace between the Monkey and the Pig on the pilgrimage to fetch the Buddhist scriptures.","answer":"Sha Wujing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">沙悟淨 / 沙悟净 — Shā Wùjìng, Sand Awakened to Purity</span></div>","traditional":"沙悟淨","hanzi":"沙悟净","pinyin":"Shā Wùjìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shā Wùjìng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sha Wujing</b>, whose name means Sand Awakened to Purity, is the third and most junior of the disciples who guard the monk Tang Sanzang in the great Ming novel <i>Journey to the West</i>. He is a fearsome sight, a towering ogre with a dark indigo face, flame-red hair standing on end, round eyes that shine like lamps, and a voice that rolls like thunder. About his neck he wears a grim necklace of nine skulls, and in his hands he carries a heavy demon-subduing staff. Yet for all his monstrous looks he is the gentlest of the three, a calm, honest, and hard-working soul who shoulders the baggage, minds the horse, and keeps the peace between the quarrelsome Monkey and Pig. Born of the water, he is the strongest swimmer of the band, able to fight in rivers and seas where his brothers flounder. <br><br> He had not always been a monster, for in Heaven he served as the Curtain-Lifting General, a marshal who attended the Jade Emperor himself. But at a great banquet he let a precious crystal cup slip from his hands and shatter, and for this the furious emperor had him beaten with eight hundred lashes and cast down to earth. There he became a man-eating fiend of the Flowing-Sands River, tormented by a flying sword that pierced him again and again, and the nine skulls he wore were those of pilgrims he had devoured. The mercy of the bodhisattva Guanyin at last redeemed him, for she gave him his holy name and bade him wait for the pilgrim who would come seeking the scriptures. When Tang Sanzang arrived, the skulls were strung together into a raft to ferry the travelers across the river, and at the journey's end the Buddha rewarded the faithful Sha Wujing by raising him to a Golden-Bodied Arhat.","citation":"","answerText":"Sha Wujing"},
{"id":"cnh-108","num":"一百零八","category":"China · History","question":"The most beloved bodhisattva of Chinese Buddhism, the merciful white-robed <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> hears the cries of the suffering world and sprinkles sweet dew from a willow branch, being the Chinese form of the Indian bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara.","answer":"Guanyin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">觀音 / 观音 — Guānyīn, short for Guānshìyīn, Perceiver of the World's Sounds</span></div>","traditional":"觀音","hanzi":"观音","pinyin":"Guānyīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guānyīn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guanyin</b> is the bodhisattva of compassion, the best-loved holy figure in all of Chinese Buddhism, known to Western visitors as the Goddess of Mercy. Her name means Perceiver of the World's Sounds, for she hears the cries of every suffering creature and hastens to their aid. She is the Chinese form of the Indian bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara, an enlightened being who delays his own final peace to save all others. In India this bodhisattva was shown as a man, but through the Tang and Song dynasties the Chinese came to picture Guanyin as a graceful woman, though a bodhisattva is held to be beyond fixed gender and able to take any shape. She is most often robed in white, holding a willow branch and a vase of sweet dew to sprinkle upon the world's pain, and in another form she bears a thousand arms, each palm set with an eye, to reach every soul in need. <br><br> A cherished Chinese legend tells that she once lived as the princess Miaoshan, who defied her cruel father's demand that she marry and chose a holy life instead. When the king later fell mortally ill, only a medicine made from the eyes and hands of one free of anger could cure him, and Miaoshan gave up her own to save him. For this boundless mercy she was revealed as Guanyin, and the story is often told to explain her thousand-armed image, though those arms truly stand for her power to aid all beings at once. Her earthly home is said to be the island of Mount Putuo in the eastern sea, and in art she is attended by the pilgrim boy Shancai and the dragon king's daughter Longnü. Known as Kannon in Japan and Gwaneum in Korea, she is worshipped across East Asia, and people pray to her for mercy, for children, and for safety from every danger.","citation":"","answerText":"Guanyin"},
{"id":"cnh-109","num":"一百零九","category":"China · History","question":"Divided by the Milky Way and allowed to meet just once a year on a bridge of magpies, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is China's best-loved tale of star-crossed lovers, celebrated each seventh night of the seventh moon at the Qixi festival.","answer":"The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">牛郎織女 / 牛郎织女 — Niúláng Zhīnǚ, the Cowherd and the Weaver Girl</span></div>","traditional":"牛郎織女","hanzi":"牛郎织女","pinyin":"Niúláng Zhīnǚ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Niúláng Zhīnǚ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl</b> is one of China's Four Great Folktales, a tender love story spun from two stars that face each other across the night sky. Niulang, the cowherd, was a poor herdboy who lived alone with a faithful old ox, while Zhinü, the weaver girl, was a heavenly maiden who wove the drifting clouds and silks of the sky. One day the fairy came down to bathe in an earthly river, and with the help of his wise ox the cowherd won her love, so that she stayed on earth to be his wife. For a few happy years they lived as a simple farming and weaving couple with two children, a boy and a girl, until Heaven discovered that a goddess had wed a mortal. In the best-known telling the Queen Mother of the West tore them apart and scratched a great river across the heavens with her hairpin, setting the Milky Way between them for ever. <br><br> That heavenly river is the one the Chinese call the Silver River, and on its far banks the lovers still shine as real stars, the cowherd as Altair and the weaver as Vega. Yet their sorrow was not endless, for they may meet just once each year, on the seventh night of the seventh moon, when a flock of magpies flies up and forms a bridge across the river of stars. This yearly reunion is kept as the festival of Qixi, the Double Seventh, when girls once prayed to the weaver for nimble fingers and skill at needlework and weaving. In modern times the day has become a kind of Chinese Valentine's Day for sweethearts, though its older heart was this begging for skill. The star-names are very old and appear in the ancient <i>Classic of Poetry</i>, but the full romance of marriage, parting, and the magpie bridge only grew up in the centuries that followed.","citation":"","answerText":"The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl"},
{"id":"cnh-110","num":"一百一十","category":"China · History","question":"The kindly old god who binds every destined couple together with an unbreakable red thread tied about their feet, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese god of marriage, who reads the fated matches of the whole world from his book by the light of the moon.","answer":"Yue Lao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">月老 / 月下老人 — Yuè Lǎo, the Old Man Under the Moon</span></div>","traditional":"月老","hanzi":"月老","pinyin":"Yuè Lǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuè Lǎo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yue Lao</b>, whose name means the Old Man Under the Moon, is the beloved Chinese god of marriage and the matchmaker of all the world. He is pictured as a smiling, white-bearded old man who sits in the moonlight with a great book of marriages open before him and a bag of red cords at his side. In that book are written all the destined unions of humankind, and when he finds a fated pair he ties an invisible red thread about the feet of those meant to wed. Once that cord is tied the marriage cannot be escaped, for no distance, no difference of rank, and no hatred between families can ever undo the bond he has made. Though he does his quiet work beneath the moon, he is a god of love and marriage, not of the moon itself. <br><br> His story is first told in a collection of strange tales from the Tang dynasty, in which a young bachelor named Wei Gu meets the old man reading his register by moonlight at a roadside inn. When Wei Gu asks who his own wife will be, the old man points out the little daughter of a poor woman in the market, a plain child of only three. Furious at so lowly a match, Wei Gu sends a servant to kill the girl, but the man only wounds her between the eyebrows and runs away. Many years later Wei Gu weds a lovely young woman who always hides a small scar upon her brow, and he learns to his amazement that she is that very child, for the red thread had held after all. From this tale the red thread of fate became one of the dearest symbols of love in China and across East Asia, and the lonely still pray to Yue Lao for a good spouse, while his name is used for any matchmaker at all.","citation":"","answerText":"Yue Lao"},
{"id":"cnh-111","num":"一百一十一","category":"China · History","question":"Welcomed into homes and shops with firecrackers at the Lunar New Year, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is not one god but a title for the Chinese god of wealth, most often the black-tiger-riding marshal Zhao Gongming, who showers prosperity on all who honour him.","answer":"Caishen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">財神 / 财神 — Cáishén, the God of Wealth</span></div>","traditional":"財神","hanzi":"财神","pinyin":"Cáishén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cáishén</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Caishen</b> is the Chinese god of wealth, one of the best-loved figures in the folk religion and Taoism of China and the great patron of the Lunar New Year. Yet Caishen is really a title rather than a single person, a heavenly office of riches that has been filled by several different gods across the ages. These wealth gods are divided into two kinds, the civil gods, who are calm robed officials, and the military gods, who are armoured warriors. By far the most worshipped is the martial marshal Zhao Gongming, a dark-faced general who rides a fierce black tiger and carries an iron whip, and who commands riches for those he favours. His fame as a bringer of wealth was spread by the Ming novel <i>Investiture of the Gods</i>, in which he is slain in battle and afterwards raised to be the lord of a company of wealth gods. <br><br> The gentler civil gods of wealth are two famous men of old raised to heaven for their virtue. One is Bi Gan, the loyal minister whose heart was torn out by a wicked king, and who, being now without a heart, is thought to share out riches with perfect fairness and no favouritism. The other is Fan Li, a wise statesman of the Spring and Autumn age who left high office, made a great fortune in trade, and gave his money away again and again to the poor. The god is most often shown among heaps of gold, holding the boat-shaped ingot called the yuanbao, the very emblem of Chinese money and good fortune in business. At the New Year families and shopkeepers welcome him into their homes with firecrackers and incense, on the second or the fifth day of the first month according to the region, calling out the wish gongxi facai, that all may grow rich.","citation":"","answerText":"Caishen"},
{"id":"cnh-112","num":"一百一十二","category":"China · History","question":"Deified from a pious fisherman's daughter who could foresee storms and guide ships to safety, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese goddess of the sea, the beloved protector of sailors whom emperors crowned at last the Empress of Heaven.","answer":"Mazu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">媽祖 / 妈祖 — Māzǔ, Mother-Ancestor, goddess of the sea</span></div>","traditional":"媽祖","hanzi":"妈祖","pinyin":"Māzǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Māzǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mazu</b> is the great Chinese goddess of the sea, the protector of sailors, fishermen, and all who trust their lives to the water. Unlike most gods she began as a real woman, a fisherman's daughter of Meizhou island in Fujian, traditionally born around the year 960 in the early Song dynasty. She was called Lin Moniang, the Silent Girl, because it was said she never cried as a baby, and she grew into a pious, clever child who could swim well and foretell the weather. In her most famous legend she fell into a trance at her loom and sent her spirit out across the stormy sea to save her father and brothers, but her mother woke her too soon, and one of them was lost. She herself died young and unwed, and folk say she climbed a mountain and rose up into heaven in a beam of shining light. <br><br> After her death she was said to watch over ships from heaven, appearing to sailors in the storm as a glowing light at the masthead to steer them safely home. At her side stand two guardians she once tamed from demons: Qianliyan, whose Thousand-Mile Eyes spot any ship in danger, and Shunfeng'er, whose Wind-Following Ears catch the faintest cry for help. As her fame spread along the coast, one dynasty after another heaped honours upon her, the Yuan naming her Heavenly Consort and the Qing at last crowning her Tianhou, the Empress of Heaven. Her worship spread from Fujian across Taiwan and wherever Chinese sailors settled overseas, and the city of Macau is said to take its very name from her. Today she remains one of the best-loved of all Chinese deities, worshipped at her mother-temple on Meizhou and in thousands of shrines, and her rites joined the roll of the world's cultural treasures in 2009.","citation":"","answerText":"Mazu"},
{"id":"cnh-113","num":"一百一十三","category":"China · History","question":"Fed sticky sweet candy so that he will speak only honeyed words when he flies up to report the family's deeds to the Jade Emperor each new year, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the humble Chinese god of the stove who watches over every household from above the cooking fire.","answer":"Kitchen God","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">灶君 / 灶王爺 — Zàojūn, the Stove Lord, the Kitchen God</span></div>","traditional":"灶君","hanzi":"灶君","pinyin":"Zàojūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zàojūn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Kitchen God</b> is the humble household deity of the stove, the most widespread of all the domestic gods of China. Every family has its own, a spirit who dwells above the cooking fire and quietly watches all that the household does, both its kindnesses and its sins, through the whole year. He is honoured not with a grand temple or statue but with a cheap paper print pasted on the kitchen wall, his wife beside him, renewed afresh each new year. The worship of the hearth is one of the oldest in China, so old that even the <i>Analects</i> of Confucius records an old saying about praying to the god of the stove. For all his lowly station, this little god holds a great power over the family, for once a year he leaves the house to carry his report straight to the throne of the Jade Emperor. <br><br> Near the end of the twelfth month, on the little new year of its twenty-third or twenty-fourth day, he rises to heaven to tell the Jade Emperor all the family's deeds. On that report the ruler of heaven decides whether the home shall meet good fortune or misfortune in the year to come. So the family smears his paper lips with sticky, sweet candy, that he may speak only honeyed words of them, or that his mouth may be glued too tight to tell any tale at all. Then his old image is burned, and the rising smoke bears him up to heaven, while firecrackers speed him on his way and a fresh print is pasted up to welcome him home again. One well-loved tale says he was once a man named Zhang, who left his faithful wife, fell into ruin and blindness, and begged by chance at her door; in his shame he threw himself into the burning stove and so became its god.","citation":"","answerText":"Kitchen God"},
{"id":"cnh-114","num":"一百一十四","category":"China · History","question":"Ruling from a crystal palace on the sea floor and sending the rain at the command of Heaven, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the Chinese dragon god of the waters, of which there is one for every sea, river, and lake in the land.","answer":"Dragon King","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">龍王 / 龙王 — Lóngwáng, the Dragon King, lord of the waters</span></div>","traditional":"龍王","hanzi":"龙王","pinyin":"Lóngwáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lóngwáng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Dragon King</b> is the Chinese dragon god who rules over all the waters of the world and sends down the rain. He is not a single god but a whole order of them, for every sea, river, lake, well, and pool has its own dragon king reigning over it. Because he governs the rain, the storms, the floods, and the droughts, he was among the most important gods to the farmers of old, who prayed to him for good weather and a rich harvest. Yet mighty as he is, the Dragon King is no supreme lord but a servant of Heaven, for the Jade Emperor tells him how much rain to pour on each place, and one who sends too much or too little can be judged and punished. His very title came partly from India, where Buddhism brought the idea of the naga, a serpent-king of the rains, which merged with China's own ancient dragon of the rivers and clouds. <br><br> The greatest of these dragon kings are the four brothers who rule the Four Seas, the chief being Ao Guang, lord of the Eastern Sea. Each dwells in a glittering crystal palace on the sea floor, heaped with treasure and guarded by a whole army of shrimp soldiers and crab generals. He may appear as a great scaled dragon or as a crowned old king with a dragon's head, and he can take human shape to walk on land. The Dragon King fills many famous tales, as when the Monkey King Sun Wukong bullies Ao Guang into giving up the magic iron cudgel that becomes his weapon in <i>Journey to the West</i>. In another beloved story the boy-hero Nezha slays the Dragon King's third son, and the furious father floods the land in revenge until the child gives up his own life to make amends.","citation":"","answerText":"Dragon King"},
{"id":"cnh-115","num":"一百一十五","category":"China · History","question":"Born from a stone egg and armed with a shape-changing iron cudgel, the rebellious Monkey King <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ran riot in Heaven before the Buddha pinned him under a mountain, whence a monk freed him to guard the journey west for the Buddhist scriptures.","answer":"Sun Wukong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孫悟空 / 孙悟空 — Sūn Wùkōng, Monkey Awakened to Emptiness</span></div>","traditional":"孫悟空","hanzi":"孙悟空","pinyin":"Sūn Wùkōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūn Wùkōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sun Wukong</b>, the Monkey King, is the dazzling hero of the great Ming novel <i>Journey to the West</i> and one of the best-loved figures in Chinese story. He was born from a stone egg upon the Mountain of Flowers and Fruit, and won the crown of the monkeys by leaping through a waterfall into a hidden cave. Seeking to escape death, he studied under a wise old patriarch who named him Wukong, the Awakened to Emptiness, and taught him 72 transformations and a cloud-somersault that carries him a hundred and eight thousand miles at a leap. For a weapon he seized a great iron cudgel from the Dragon King's undersea palace, a rod that changes size at his word and shrinks to a needle he tucks behind his ear. Proud and unruly, he ran riot in Heaven itself, devouring the peaches of immortality and the elixir of the gods, naming himself the Great Sage Equal to Heaven and beating back every army sent against him. <br><br> Thrown into a furnace to be destroyed, he came out unharmed with fiery golden eyes that could pierce any disguise. At last the Buddha himself humbled him, wagering that the Monkey could not leap out of his palm, and when Wukong failed he was sealed beneath a mountain for five hundred years. There he waited until the monk Tang Sanzang set him free to become the first and mightiest disciple on the long pilgrimage west to fetch the Buddhist scriptures. To curb his wild temper the bodhisattva Guanyin gave the monk a golden headband that clamped on Wukong's brow and tightened at a spoken spell whenever he misbehaved. Alongside the pig Zhu Bajie and the monk Sha Wujing he fought a host of demons with cudgel and cunning, and when the journey was done the Buddha raised him to be the Victorious Fighting Buddha.","citation":"","answerText":"Sun Wukong"},
{"id":"cnh-116","num":"一百一十六","category":"China · History","question":"A western farming people who rose from a frontier tribe of the Wei valley to topple the Shang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> were the ancestors and pre-conquest chiefs of the Zhou, from the legendary Lord Millet down to the King Wu who won the throne around 1046 BCE.","answer":"Predynastic Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">先周 Xiān Zhōu — the Zhou before c. 1046 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"先周","hanzi":"先周","pinyin":"Xiān Zhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiān Zhōu</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Predynastic Zhou</b> were the Zhou people and their rulers in the long age before they overthrew the Shang and founded the Zhou dynasty around 1046 BCE. They were a farming folk of the Wei River valley in the west, on the edge of the Shang world, and the Shang oracle bones name them as a frontier tribe called the Zhoufang. Their ruling house belonged to the ancient Ji clan and traced its line to a legendary ancestor, Houji, or Lord Millet, the culture-hero said to have taught mankind to farm and later worshipped as a god of the harvest. By legend his mother conceived him after stepping into a giant's footprint and then cast the baby out, so that he was named the Abandoned One, yet was saved by animals and Heaven. From Houji a long half-legendary line of chiefs led down at last to the men who would make the Zhou great. <br><br> The turning point came when the chief Gugong Danfu led his people to settle on the Plain of Zhou below Mount Qi, the place that gave the dynasty its name. His grandson King Wen, the Lord of the West, drew many states to the Zhou and grew so powerful that the last Shang king imprisoned him for a time, where by tradition he pondered the <i>Book of Changes</i>. Yet Wen only laid the foundation and did not finish the work, for he died before the war began. It fell to his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span> to crush the Shang army at the Battle of Muye, around 1046 BCE, and so turn the Zhou from a border state into the rulers of China. Digging at the Plain of Zhou has uncovered their palaces and their own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_oracle_bones\">oracle bones</span>, proof that these western people divined and wrote much as the Shang did, even as they began to claim that Heaven had chosen them to rule.","citation":"","answerText":"Predynastic Zhou"},
{"id":"cnh-117","num":"一百一十七","category":"China · History","question":"Remembered for leading the wandering Zhou back to settled farming and founding their home at Bin, the chieftain <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was a distant descendant of Lord Millet who revived his people's fortunes long before they rose to rule China.","answer":"Gong Liu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">公劉 / 公刘 — Gōng Liú, \"Duke Liu,\" a Zhou forefather</span></div>","traditional":"公劉","hanzi":"公刘","pinyin":"Gōng Liú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gōng Liú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Gong Liu</b> was a chieftain of the early Zhou people, honoured in later ages as one of the great forefathers who prepared the way for the Zhou dynasty many generations later. His title Gong means Duke or Lord, but he was no feudal noble of a later court, only the headman of a small farming tribe of the Ji clan in the west of China. He came many generations after the Zhou's first ancestor, Houji, the Lord Millet who was said to have first taught the people to farm. According to the old histories, the Zhou had by then lost their skill at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture\">agriculture </span>and drifted for years among the Rong and Di peoples, living as herders and wanderers. It was Gong Liu who revived the ancient craft of the fields, gathered his scattered people, and led them back to a settled life of farming and plenty. <br><br> His great work was to lead the Zhou to a new home at Bin, a fertile country north of the Wei River, where they grew strong and numerous once more. Tradition tells how he surveyed the land by the sun and the water, filled the granaries with grain before the journey, and founded a thriving town where the people prospered. These deeds are sung in an ancient hymn that bears his name in the <i>Classic of Poetry</i>, and retold in Sima Qian's <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>. Gong Liu lived long before Gugong Danfu, the later chief who would move the Zhou onward to the Plain of Zhou at Mount Qi. He did not found the dynasty himself, for that lay centuries in the future, but by reviving his people he set the Zhou upon the long road that would lead at last to their rule over all of China.","citation":"","answerText":"Gong Liu"},
{"id":"cnh-118","num":"一百一十八","category":"China · History","question":"Choosing to abandon his old home rather than fight the raiding nomads, the Zhou chieftain <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led his devoted people to a new land at the foot of Mount Qi, the Plain of Zhou that would give the coming dynasty its name.","answer":"Gugong Danfu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">古公亶父 — Gǔgōng Dǎnfù, the Old Duke Danfu; posthumously King Tai 太王</span></div>","traditional":"古公亶父","hanzi":"古公亶父","pinyin":"Gǔgōng Dǎnfù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gǔgōng Dǎnfù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Gugong Danfu</b>, the <b>Old Duke Danfu</b>, was a chieftain of the early Zhou people and a great forefather of the house that would one day rule China. Gugong means simply <b>the Ancient Duke</b>, an honour rather than a name, and only after his death, once the dynasty was founded, did his descendants honor him as <b>King Tai of Zhou</b>. In his own time the Zhou were a small farming folk settled at Bin, where they were harried without end by the raiding Rong and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Di_(people)\">Di</span> nomads. Rather than lead his people into a bloody war over land, tradition says, Danfu chose to give up Bin and depart, and his people loved him so well that they followed him in a great throng. He led them south to the Plain of Zhou below Mount Qi, and there raised walls, houses, and an ancestral temple, founding a settled home whose name, Zhou, would one day belong to the dynasty. <br><br> Danfu had three sons, of whom the youngest was Jili, whose own son Chang seemed to all a child of rare and shining promise. Wishing the leadership to pass down to this gifted grandson, the two elder brothers stepped aside, fleeing far to the south, where the eldest, Taibo, became the honoured founder of the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span>. Confucius himself would later praise their yielding as the very highest of virtues. So the line ran on from Danfu through Jili to that grandson, who became King Wen, and then to King Wen's son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span>, who overthrew the Shang and founded the Zhou dynasty. Danfu did not live to see that day, yet by his move to Mount Qi and his ordering of the state he set the Zhou firmly on the road to greatness, as the ancient hymns of the <i>Classic of Poetry</i> still recall.","citation":"","answerText":"Gugong Danfu"},
{"id":"cnh-119","num":"一百一十九","category":"China · History","question":"The fertile plain below Mount Qi where Old Duke Danfu settled his people and which gave the dynasty its very name, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the ancestral heartland of the Zhou and is today one of China's richest sites for Bronze Age palaces, oracle bones, and inscribed bronzes.","answer":"Zhouyuan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Place</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周原 Zhōuyuán — the Plain of Zhou, below Mount Qi in Shaanxi</span></div>","traditional":"周原","hanzi":"周原","pinyin":"Zhōuyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōuyuán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhouyuan</b>, the <b>Plain of Zhou</b>, is a broad, fertile loess plain below Mount Qi in what is now Shaanxi province, in the Wei River country of the west. It was the ancestral heartland of the Zhou people, the new home to which the chieftain Gugong Danfu led them when he abandoned their older seat at Bin. So closely was this plain bound to the people that it is from its name, Zhou, that both the tribe and the great dynasty they later founded are traditionally said to take their name. Here the Zhou grew strong under Danfu, his son Jili, and his grandson King Wen, in the generations before they overthrew the Shang. Even after the conquest, when the kings ruled from their eastern capitals at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fenghao\">Feng and Hao</span>, this old plain remained the sacred heartland of the royal house, where its ancestral temples and rites endured. <br><br> Today Zhouyuan is one of the greatest treasure-houses of Bronze Age China, dug over by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Archaeology\">archaeologists </span>since the 1970s. Beneath its fields lie the rammed-earth foundations of great halls, such as the Fengchu complex, an early courtyard-plan building that may have served as a palace or an ancestral temple. The plain is most famous for its buried hoards of ritual bronzes, cached in pits by noble families and covered in long inscriptions that are among the rarest firsthand records of the age. One such vessel, the Shi Qiang basin, carries hundreds of characters recounting the deeds of the early Zhou kings and of the family that owned it. In 1977 diggers also found thousands of Zhou oracle bones here, a few hundred inscribed in a minute script, proving that these western people <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divination\">divined</span> and wrote much as the Shang did, though the exact age of the find is still debated.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhouyuan"},
{"id":"cnh-120","num":"一百二十","category":"China · History","question":"A loyal Shang vassal who won the Zhou new power by his wars on the frontier, the chieftain <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew so mighty that a fearful Shang king is said to have had him killed, leaving his son King Wen to carry the Zhou onward.","answer":"Jili","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">季歷 / 季历 — Jì Lì, \"Ji the youngest son\"; posthumously King Ji 王季</span></div>","traditional":"季歷","hanzi":"季历","pinyin":"Jì Lì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jì Lì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jili</b> was a chieftain of the early Zhou people at the foot of Mount Qi, the son and heir of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Tai_of_Zhou\">Old Duke Danfu</span> and a crucial link in the line that would one day rule China. His name means <b>Ji the Youngest</b>, for he was the last of Danfu's three sons, and only after the dynasty was founded did his descendants honour him with the title <b>King Ji of Zhou</b>. In his own lifetime he was no king at all, but a Zhou chief who served the great Shang dynasty as one of its border lords. He came to lead the Zhou because his two elder brothers, Taibo and Zhongyong, had stepped aside in his favour, so that rule might pass to him and to his gifted son. That son was Ji Chang, the future King Wen, borne to Jili by his virtuous wife Tairen, and it was Wen's own son, King Wu, who would at last overthrow the Shang. <br><br> Under Jili the Zhou grew markedly stronger, for he was a bold war-leader who fought the Rong tribes along the northwestern frontier. For these victories the Shang court rewarded him with gifts and high rank, and for many years he was its faithful vassal in the west. Yet as the Zhou swelled in strength and fame, the Shang came to fear them, and a loyal servant began to look like a rival. According to the old <i>Bamboo Annals</i>, the Shang king Wen Ding turned at last upon Jili and had him seized and starved to death, though the histories are not agreed on how he died. His killing only deepened the bitterness between the two houses, and the work he had begun was carried on by his son King Wen and finished by his grandson, who broke the Shang for ever.","citation":"","answerText":"Jili"},
{"id":"cnh-121","num":"一百二十一","category":"China · History","question":"The wise and virtuous Lord of the West who was jailed by the Shang tyrant yet drew most of the realm to the Zhou, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> laid the foundation for the conquest of the Shang that his son King Wu would finish at Muye.","answer":"King Wen of Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周文王 — Zhōu Wén Wáng, the Cultured King; in life Ji Chang, the Lord of the West</span></div>","traditional":"周文王","hanzi":"周文王","pinyin":"Zhōu Wén Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Wén Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Wen</b> is one of the most honoured figures in all Chinese history, revered ever after as the model of the wise and virtuous ruler. His true name was <b>Ji Chang</b>, and in life he was not a king but the <b>Lord of the West</b>, a vassal of the Shang; the title King Wen, <b>the Cultured King</b>, was granted only after his death by his triumphant son. As lord of the Zhou at Mount Qi he won fame for his benevolence, caring for the old and the poor and gathering wise and able men to his side. The greatest of these was the aged sage Jiang Ziya, whom he is said to have found fishing beside the Wei River and made his chief counsellor and strategist. By war and by justice he brought many neighbouring states under Zhou sway, until most of the realm looked to him, though he still served the Shang. <br><br> His growing power made the last Shang king, the cruel Di Xin, fear him, and the tyrant had him cast into prison at Youli, held there, so the histories say, for seven years. Only when his followers bought his freedom with gifts of treasure and fair women was he set loose and allowed to return home. Tradition holds that in his captivity King Wen composed the 64 hexagrams and their sayings that make up the ancient <i>Book of Changes</i>, though scholars believe the text was truly written long after him. The Zhou believed that in him Heaven had at last withdrawn its blessing from the wicked Shang and granted the Mandate to rule to their own house. Yet King Wen did not live to seize the throne, for he died before the war was won, leaving his son King Wu to overthrow the Shang and another son, the Duke of Zhou, to guide the young dynasty.","citation":"","answerText":"King Wen"},
{"id":"cnh-122","num":"一百二十二","category":"China · History","question":"The eldest son of the Old Duke Danfu, who gave up his right to rule and fled south so that his youngest brother's line could inherit, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded the far-off state of Wu and was praised by Confucius as a man of the highest virtue.","answer":"Taibo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">太伯 / 泰伯 — Tàibó, \"Wu Taibo,\" Taibo of Wu</span></div>","traditional":"太伯","hanzi":"太伯","pinyin":"Tàibó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tàibó</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Taibo</b>, remembered as <b>Wu Taibo</b>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<b>King&nbsp;Taibo of Wu</b>, was the eldest son of the Zhou chieftain Gugong Danfu and one of the most admired examples of virtue in Chinese tradition. As the firstborn he was his father's rightful heir, but Danfu longed for the succession to pass instead to his youngest son Jili, whose own son Chang seemed marked for greatness. Understanding this wish, Taibo and his second brother Zhongyong quietly gave up their claim, stepping aside so that the leadership might descend to Jili and at last to Chang, the future King Wen. For this selfless yielding Confucius praised him in the <i>Analects</i> as a man of the utmost virtue, one who three times gave up the realm so humbly that the people could find no words to thank him. So highly was he honoured that the historian Sima Qian placed the house of Taibo first among all the noble houses in his <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>. <br><br> To make his renunciation final, so that he could never be called back to rule, Taibo fled far to the south, to the wild lands of the lower Yangtze. There, according to the old histories, he cut off his hair and tattooed his body in the fashion of the local people, casting off his northern rank for ever. The people of that country, won over by his goodness, made him their lord, and so he founded the distant state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span>, with his seat near modern Wuxi. Because Taibo left no son, he was succeeded by his brother Zhongyong, and it was from Zhongyong, not Taibo, that the later kings of Wu were descended. That kingdom of Wu grew into a great power only some six centuries afterwards, yet it always traced its royal blood back to the gentle prince who had given up a throne.","citation":"","answerText":"Taibo"},
{"id":"cnh-123","num":"一百二十三","category":"China · History","question":"Made of two cities on opposite banks of the Feng River, one raised by King Wen and one by King Wu, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the western royal capital of the Zhou near modern Xi'an, until nomads sacked it in 771 BCE and drove the court eastward.","answer":"Fenghao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Place</span><span class=\"dt-v\">豐鎬 / 丰镐 — Fēnghào, the Western Zhou twin capital near Xi'an</span></div>","traditional":"豐鎬","hanzi":"丰镐","pinyin":"Fēnghào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fēnghào</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Fenghao</b> was the royal capital of the Western Zhou dynasty for close on three hundred years, standing in the Wei River country near the site of modern Xi'an. Its name joins together the names of two neighbouring cities, <b>Feng and Hao</b>, which faced each other across the banks of the Feng River. The elder city, Feng, was built by King Wen when he moved the seat of the Zhou down from their old home at Mount Qi, while its twin, Hao, was raised on the far bank by his son King Wu. By tradition Feng held the ancestral temples and holy places of the royal house, while Hao was the king's own residence, where he lived and governed. Together the two made up one great capital, which the Zhou called <b>Zongzhou</b>, the <b>Ancestral Zhou</b>, the proud home seat of their kings. <br><br> From here, in the generations after they overthrew the Shang, the Zhou kings held their court, performed the great rites, and received the lords who owed them service, granting the noble appointments that were carved into many a bronze vessel. Fenghao was the western of the dynasty's two capitals, paired with an eastern seat, Chengzhou, built far away near modern Luoyang to watch over the conquered lands. In 771 BCE this proud city met a violent end, when a wronged lord led the Quanrong nomads against it, sacked the palaces, and slew the last western king, King You. A famous old tale says the king had brought his doom upon himself by lighting the war-beacons for sport, to make his silent queen laugh, until no lord would answer them in earnest. Yet the dynasty did not perish, for the heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Ping_of_Zhou\">King Ping</span> fled eastward to Chengzhou, and from that new capital the long age of the Eastern Zhou began.","citation":"","answerText":"Fenghao"},
{"id":"cnh-124","num":"一百二十四","category":"China · History","question":"Born fatherless to a mother who stepped in a god's footprint and abandoned three times as an unlucky child, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew into the master of farming who taught China to grow millet and became both the grain god and the founding ancestor of the Zhou.","answer":"Houji","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">后稷 — Hòujì, \"Lord Millet\"; personal name Qi 棄, \"the Abandoned\"</span></div>","traditional":"后稷","hanzi":"后稷","pinyin":"Hòujì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hòujì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Houji</b>, whose name means <b>Lord Millet</b>, is the legendary hero who taught the Chinese to farm and the founding ancestor from whom the royal house of Zhou traced its descent. His name is really a title, for he was born with the name <b>Qi</b>, which means <b>the Abandoned</b>, in memory of the strange story of his birth. It was said that his mother, Jiang Yuan, had no husband, but conceived him after she trod by chance in the great footprint of the High God. Thinking so uncanny a birth unlucky, she cast the baby out three times, yet each time he was saved, sheltered by the oxen and sheep in a narrow lane, found by woodcutters in a wood, and warmed by the wings of birds upon the cold ice. Seeing that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heaven\">Heaven </span>itself protected him, she took the child back and raised him, and this wondrous tale is told in the ancient <i>Classic of Poetry</i>. <br><br> Even as a little child Houji loved to plant beans and grain, and whatever he sowed grew tall and rich, so that he became the greatest farmer of his age. He taught the people how to till the fields and raise the millet that was the daily bread of the north, and in the days of the sage-kings Yao and Shun he was made the Minister of Agriculture. For this gift he was honoured ever after as the god of grain and of the harvest. His spirit is the grain, the Ji, of the sacred pair called the she-ji, the twin altars of the soil and the grain that together stood as a very symbol of the state. Yet great as he was, Houji did not found the dynasty himself, for he stood only at the head of the long line of Zhou forefathers, whose distant heir King Wu would one day overthrow the Shang.","citation":"","answerText":"Houji"},
{"id":"cnh-125","num":"一百二十五","category":"China · History","question":"Holding that Heaven grants the right to rule only to a just king and strips it from a cruel one, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the Zhou idea that justified their overthrow of the Shang and shaped Chinese politics for three thousand years.","answer":"Mandate of Heaven","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">天命 — Tiānmìng, \"Heaven's Decree\"</span></div>","traditional":"天命","hanzi":"天命","pinyin":"Tiānmìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiānmìng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mandate of Heaven</b> is the ancient Chinese belief that the right to rule over the world is granted by Heaven to a just and worthy king. Heaven here was not a personal god but a supreme moral power over the world, and the ruler who held its favour was honoured as the Son of Heaven. Yet this favour was never given for ever, for it depended wholly upon the king's own virtue and good government, and not upon his birth or bloodline. Should a ruler grow cruel, greedy, or careless of his people, Heaven would take the Mandate away and bestow it on a worthier man, so that the throne itself could pass to a new house. In this the Chinese idea differed sharply from the Western notion of the divine right of kings, for the Mandate was conditional and could be lost, giving the people a right to rise against a tyrant who had forfeited it. <br><br> The doctrine was born among the Zhou, who used it to explain why they had been right to overthrow the older and mightier Shang around 1046 BCE. They taught that the last Shang king had sunk into cruelty and lost his virtue, so that Heaven withdrew its Mandate from him and gave it to the good Zhou kings, Wen and Wu. Tradition credits the wise Duke of Zhou with setting forth this teaching, which was written down in the old <i>Book of Documents</i>. It became the deepest principle of Chinese politics for three thousand years, down to the last emperor in 1912, every dynasty in turn claiming the Mandate and blaming the fallen one for losing it. Later the sage Mencius sharpened it into a bold right of rebellion, declaring that a king who ruined his people was no true king at all, but a mere man whom it was no crime to remove.","citation":"","answerText":"Mandate of Heaven"},
{"id":"cnh-126","num":"一百二十六","category":"China · History","question":"Found fishing with a straight hook by King Wen and made the mastermind of the war on the Shang, the aged sage <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led the Zhou to victory and was rewarded with the eastern state of Qi, becoming China's model of the wise strategist.","answer":"Jiang Ziya","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">姜子牙 — Jiāng Zǐyá; also Lü Shang, Taigong Wang</span></div>","traditional":"姜子牙","hanzi":"姜子牙","pinyin":"Jiāng Zǐyá","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiāng Zǐyá</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jiang Ziya</b>, also called Lü Shang and Taigong Wang, is the most famous of the wise counselors of the early Zhou and China's model of the sage strategist. The best-loved legend of him tells how King Wen, searching for a man of wisdom, came upon a poor old fisherman by the bank of the Wei River. This greybeard fished in a strange way, with a hook straight and held clear above the water, saying that only the fish that truly wished it would come to him. King Wen saw at once that here was no common man but the very sage his forefathers had hoped would come to aid the Zhou, and he took the old man home as his chief adviser. That fisherman was Jiang Ziya, and though his great age and his barbless hook are matters of legend, a real and brilliant strategist stands behind the tales. <br><br> As the chief strategist first of King Wen and then of his son King Wu, Jiang Ziya is remembered as the mastermind of the Zhou's rise against the Shang. Tradition has him command the Zhou army at the Battle of Muye, around 1046 BCE, the great victory that toppled the last Shang king and won the throne for the Zhou. For his service King Wu granted him the eastern land of Qi, and he became the founding lord of a state that would grow, ages after him, into one of the mightiest in all China. He was honoured ever after as the father of Chinese military science, and the old treatise called the <i>Six Secret Teachings</i> was long attributed to his hand. Centuries later the Ming novel <i>Investiture of the Gods</i> made him a Daoist wizard who, at heaven's command, gave out divine offices to the souls of the slain, a thrilling fancy that is pure fiction and no part of his true story.","citation":"","answerText":"Jiang Ziya"},
{"id":"cnh-127","num":"一百二十七","category":"China · History","question":"The last king of the Shang and the great byword for a wicked tyrant, said to have lost his house the favour of Heaven, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — known to history by the hostile name King Zhou — was crushed at the Battle of Muye and burned himself alive as his capital fell.","answer":"Di Xin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">帝辛 — Dì Xīn; infamous as King Zhou 紂王 — note 紂 is not the Zhōu 周 dynasty</span></div>","traditional":"帝辛","hanzi":"帝辛","pinyin":"Dì Xīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dì Xīn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Di Xin</b> was the last king of the ancient Shang dynasty, but he is remembered by the hateful name his conquerors gave him, King Zhou, which brands him a cruel and villainous tyrant. It is vital not to confuse this King Zhou, written with one character, with the Zhou dynasty that destroyed him, written with another, for he was not their king but their enemy, the man they overthrew. In the traditional tale he was a gifted and mighty ruler who turned all his talents to wickedness, sinking into pride, drink, and endless cruelty. He is accused of building a pool filled with wine and a forest hung with meat for his revels, of roasting his enemies alive on a heated bronze pillar, and of tearing out the heart of a loyal minister who reproached him. In these stories a beautiful and cruel favourite named Daji is said to have urged him on to ever darker deeds. <br><br> When the western Zhou rose against him, their armies under King Wu shattered his host at the Battle of Muye around 1046 BCE, and his own soldiers are said to have turned against him. With all lost, tradition tells that he put on his finest robes and jewels and burned himself to death in his treasure-tower, and so the Shang came to an end. The victorious Zhou taught that his wickedness had made the Shang forfeit the favour of Heaven, and his name became the great warning of a ruler who loses his right to rule. Yet many now believe his evil was blackened and exaggerated by the winners over the centuries, for even the sage Zigong warned in the <i>Analects</i> that King Zhou was not as wicked as all that. The oracle bones show him as a fairly ordinary king, and some think his costly wars in the east had worn the Shang down and left it open to the Zhou.","citation":"","answerText":"Di Xin"},
{"id":"cnh-128","num":"一百二十八","category":"China · History","question":"Finishing the work his father King Wen had begun, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led the Zhou to victory over the Shang king Di Xin at the Battle of Muye and founded the Zhou dynasty, though he died only a few years after his great triumph.","answer":"King Wu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1050 — 1046 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"周武王","hanzi":"周武王","pinyin":"Zhōu Wǔ Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Wǔ Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Wu of Zhou</b>, whose given name was <b>Ji Fa</b>, is honoured as the founder of the Zhou dynasty, the mightiest of the early Chinese royal houses. The name Wu means the <b>Martial King</b>, a title given after his death and set beside his father's, King Wen the Civil King, the celebrated founding pair of the Zhou. His father had built up the strength of the Zhou and drawn many states to their side, but died before he could strike, leaving the great task to his son. With the wise old strategist Jiang Ziya at his side, King Wu gathered a host of allied lords and marched against the last Shang king, Di Xin, whom the Zhou condemned as a cruel tyrant fallen from Heaven's favour. At the Battle of Muye, around 1046 BCE, his outnumbered army won a crushing victory when much of the huge Shang host is said to have turned against its own king, and Di Xin burned himself to death as the capital fell. <br><br> So King Wu founded the Zhou dynasty and set his capital at Hao, near his father's old seat in the Wei valley. To hold his broad new realm he parcelled it out among his kinsmen and helpers as lordships, giving Qi to Jiang Ziya and Lu to his own brother, the Duke of Zhou. He did not destroy the fallen Shang, but let a son of Di Xin rule over their people, setting his own brothers to watch that he kept the peace. Yet King Wu did not live to enjoy his conquest, for he fell ill and died only two or three years later, leaving a young son, King Cheng, upon the throne. It was then his brother the Duke of Zhou who, as regent, crushed a great rebellion and truly settled the new dynasty, so that the work of founding was shared between the brothers.","citation":"","answerText":"King Wu"},
{"id":"cnh-129","num":"一百二十九","category":"China · History","question":"Won in a single dawn when the last Shang king's own conscripts turned their spears and fled, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the clash around 1046 BCE at which King Wu's Zhou coalition shattered the Shang and founded a new dynasty.","answer":"Battle of Muye","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">牧野之戰 / 牧野之战 — Mùyě zhī zhàn; c. 1046 BCE, disputed</span></div>","traditional":"牧野之戰","hanzi":"牧野之战","pinyin":"Mùyě zhī Zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mùyě zhī Zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Battle of Muye</b> was the great battle that brought down the Shang dynasty and set the Zhou in its place, fought around the year 1046 BCE. It took its name from Muye, the wild open country near the Shang capital region in what is now Henan, where the two armies met. There King Wu of Zhou, with the aged strategist Jiang Ziya at his side, led a coalition of the Zhou and their allied peoples against the last Shang king, Di Xin. The Shang host was far the larger, but it had been raised in haste and was crowded with slaves and captives who had no wish to die for a hated king. Before the fighting King Wu is said to have sworn a stirring oath to his men, the <i>Speech at Mu</i>, naming the tyrant's crimes and calling upon Heaven to witness his cause. <br><br> As the two sides closed, according to tradition, the front ranks of the Shang turned their spears against their own masters and broke, so that the whole vast army collapsed in a single morning. Di Xin fled back to his capital and is said to have burned himself to death, and with that the Shang were finished and the Zhou dynasty began. The victory became the very model of a just conquest, in which a virtuous ruler overthrows a tyrant who has forfeited the favour of Heaven. The exact year is much disputed, but a bronze vessel called the Li gui, cast only days later by a Zhou officer, records the battle at dawn on a certain day and is its earliest surviving witness. How bloody the fighting really was has long been argued, for the old records speak of blood enough to float the wooden pestles, though later sages doubted so righteous a war could have been so cruel.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Muye"},
{"id":"cnh-130","num":"一百三十","category":"China · History","question":"Built by King Wu across the river from his father's city of Feng, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the royal seat of the Western Zhou kings near modern Xi'an, until nomads sacked it in 771 BCE and the court fled east.","answer":"Haojing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Place</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鎬京 / 镐京 — Hàojīng, King Wu's Western Zhou capital near Xi'an</span></div>","traditional":"鎬京","hanzi":"镐京","pinyin":"Hàojīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hàojīng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Haojing</b>, the city of Hao, was the royal capital of the Western Zhou dynasty, standing on the Feng River in the Wei valley near where Xi'an rises today. It was raised by King Wu, the conqueror of the Shang, on the east bank of the river, across the water from Feng, the city his father King Wen had built. The two together were known as Fenghao, and of the pair it was Hao that served as the seat of the living king. While Feng kept the ancestral temples and holy rites, Hao is remembered as the royal residence and the seat of government, the place from which the Zhou kings ruled their broad realm. The whole western capital was honoured with the proud name Zongzhou, the Ancestral Zhou, the heart of the dynasty's homeland in the west, a name that still appears on the bronze vessels of the age. <br><br> For nearly three centuries the kings held court at Haojing, and to help them govern the conquered lands in the east they kept a second capital, Chengzhou, far away near modern Luoyang. The city's glory ended in the year 771 BCE, when the Quanrong nomads stormed the western capital and killed the last western king, King You. But the dynasty did not die, for his heir fled eastward to Chengzhou, and there the long age of the Eastern Zhou began. Haojing was never a great capital again, and the famous later cities of the region, the Qin capital of Xianyang and the Han and Tang capital of Chang'an, were quite separate places. Its own ruins now lie buried and hard to trace in the fields southwest of Xi'an, for a vast artificial lake dug by a later Han emperor is thought to have drowned much of the old city of Hao.","citation":"","answerText":"Haojing"},
{"id":"cnh-131","num":"一百三十一","category":"China · History","question":"Serving as loyal regent for his boy-nephew after King Wu's early death and giving back the power once the young king grew up, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> crushed a great rebellion, built the eastern capital, and became China's model of the selfless statesman.","answer":"Duke of Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周公 — Zhōugōng, the Duke of Zhou; personal name Ji Dan 姬旦</span></div>","traditional":"周公","hanzi":"周公","pinyin":"Zhōugōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōugōng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Duke of Zhou</b>, whose name was Ji Dan, is honoured in China as the very model of the wise and loyal statesman. He was a son of King Wen and the younger brother of King Wu, who overthrew the Shang and founded the Zhou dynasty; the Duke himself was never a king, but his brother's most trusted helper. When King Wu died only a few years after his conquest, he left a little son, King Cheng, far too young to rule, so the Duke of Zhou took up the government as regent in the child's name. This roused the jealousy of some of his own brothers, set to watch over the conquered Shang, who joined a surviving Shang prince in a great rebellion against him. The Duke marched east and, after hard years of war, crushed the revolt and brought the whole eastern country firmly under Zhou rule. <br><br> To hold these new lands he built a second, eastern capital at Chengzhou, near modern Luoyang, and settled kinsmen and allies as lords across the realm. He is also credited with shaping the belief that Heaven grants its Mandate only to the worthy, and with the great system of rites and music that ordered Chinese society for ages after. But his crowning glory came at the end, for when King Cheng grew to manhood, the Duke gave the power back to him and stepped aside, though he might easily have kept it for himself. By this act of selfless loyalty he became forever the ideal of the good minister who serves his lord and does not usurp. So deeply was he revered that Confucius, five centuries later, took him for his highest hero and lamented in the <i>Analects</i> that he had grown old, for he no longer dreamed of the Duke of Zhou.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke of Zhou"},
{"id":"cnh-132","num":"一百三十二","category":"China · History","question":"The boy who inherited the throne when his father King Wu died young, and for whom his uncle the Duke of Zhou ruled as regent, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the second Zhou king, in whose golden reign the earliest writing of the name Zhongguo was cast in bronze.","answer":"King Cheng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周成王 — Zhōu Chéng Wáng, \"the Accomplished King\"; personal name Ji Song 姬誦</span></div>","traditional":"周成王","hanzi":"周成王","pinyin":"Zhōu Chéng Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Chéng Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Cheng</b>, whose name was Ji Song, was the second king of the Zhou dynasty, son of the great conqueror King Wu. He did not found the dynasty himself but inherited it, coming to the throne as a small child when his father died only a few years after overthrowing the Shang. Because he was too young to rule, his uncle the Duke of Zhou governed as regent in his name, and it was the Duke who did much of the hard work of securing the new dynasty. The Duke crushed a dangerous rebellion, tamed the eastern lands, and set kinsmen of the royal house as lords across the country, before handing the government back to King Cheng when he grew to manhood. Then the young king ruled in his own right, and during his reign the Zhou built a great eastern capital, Chengzhou, near where Luoyang stands today, to hold the conquered east. <br><br> His reign, with that of his son King Kang after him, was long looked back on as a golden age of peace and good order, the happy dawn of the Western Zhou. From his time survives a famous bronze wine-vessel called the He zun, and cut into it are the two oldest written characters for Zhongguo, the name by which China still calls itself. There, though, the word meant only the central land around the new capital, and not yet the great nation it would come to name in the long ages after. A well-loved tale tells how the boy-king once playfully gave his little brother a leaf cut in the shape of a jade tablet, saying he made him a lord. When an official held him to his careless word, insisting that a king may never speak in jest, the brother was truly made a lord, and so was founded the state that grew into mighty Jin.","citation":"","answerText":"King Cheng"},
{"id":"cnh-133","num":"一百三十三","category":"China · History","question":"When King Wu's own brothers, posted to watch the conquered Shang, accused the Duke of Zhou of usurping the throne and joined the Shang prince they guarded in revolt, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the gravest crisis of the young Zhou, until the Duke crushed it in a three-year eastern war.","answer":"Rebellion of the Three Guards","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三監之亂 / 三监之乱 — Sānjiān zhī Luàn; early Western Zhou, c. 1040s BCE</span></div>","traditional":"三監之亂","hanzi":"三监之乱","pinyin":"Sānjiān zhī Luàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānjiān zhī Luàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Rebellion of the Three Guards</b> was a great revolt that shook the Zhou dynasty in its earliest years, soon after the conquest of the Shang. When King Wu had overthrown the Shang, he did not destroy their royal house but let a Shang prince, Wu Geng, rule over the Shang people, setting three of his own brothers to keep watch upon him. These three brothers, Guanshu, Caishu, and Huoshu, all sons of the great King Wen, were the Three Guards from whom the rising took its name. But King Wu soon died, leaving a boy too young to rule, and his brother the Duke of Zhou took power as regent in the child's name. Fearing and accusing the Duke of meaning to steal the throne for himself, the Three Guards turned traitor, joined forces with the very Shang prince they were guarding, and, drawing in the wild tribes of the east, rose in a mighty rebellion. <br><br> This was the deadliest hour of the young dynasty, for the rebels joined Shang loyalists, royal princes, and eastern peoples in one great coalition. The Duke of Zhou marched east at the head of the royal army and, after three hard years of war, utterly crushed the revolt. Wu Geng and Guanshu were put to death, Caishu was driven into exile, and Huoshu was stripped of his rank and reduced to a commoner. Yet the Duke did not wipe out the Shang, for he let their line continue under another and loyal Shang prince, Weizi, whom he made lord of the state of Song. To hold the east for good he built the great eastern capital of Chengzhou and planted many new lordships across the land, so that the crushing of the rebellion became a second founding that made the Zhou secure at last.","citation":"","answerText":"Rebellion of the Three Guards"},
{"id":"cnh-134","num":"一百三十四","category":"China · History","question":"The great colleague of the Duke of Zhou who helped uphold the young dynasty and gave the northern state of Yan its founding line, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was so beloved for his just rule that his people would not cut down the sweet pear tree beneath which he had judged them.","answer":"Duke of Shao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">召公 — Shàogōng, the Duke of Shao; personal name Ji Shi 姬奭</span></div>","traditional":"召公","hanzi":"召公","pinyin":"Shàogōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shàogōng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Duke of Shao</b>, whose name was Ji Shi, was one of the greatest ministers of the early Zhou dynasty and a close kinsman of its royal house. Tradition makes him a son of King Wen, though his exact kinship is uncertain, and he served as the high Grand Protector under Kings Cheng and Kang. He is easily confused with the more famous Duke of Zhou, but the two were different men, colleagues who together upheld the young dynasty as its twin pillars. It was the Duke of Zhou who ruled as regent for the boy-king, while the Duke of Shao stood beside him as chief helper; by tradition the two even divided the realm, one governing the east, the other the west. The Duke of Shao was also made founding ancestor of the northern state of Yan, near where Beijing stands today, though he stayed at court and sent his son to rule it in his place. <br><br> Among his great works, he went ahead to survey the ground and read the omens for the founding of the new eastern capital at Chengzhou. But he is best loved for a gentler tale, that of the sweet pear tree. As he travelled his lands to govern and to judge the people, he would not trouble the villagers by lodging in their homes, but rested and heard their disputes in the open, beneath a wild pear tree. He judged so fairly and cared for the people so kindly that, after he was gone, they could not bear to cut down or harm that tree, and made a tender song about it that is kept in the ancient <i>Classic of Poetry</i>. Ever since, the sweet pear tree has stood in China as the very emblem of a good and beloved official whom the people hold dear.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke of Shao"},
{"id":"cnh-135","num":"一百三十五","category":"China · History","question":"Granting hereditary fiefs to kinsmen and allies who ruled their own states but owed the king tribute and troops, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the Zhou order of decentralized aristocratic rule, often likened to feudalism, that Qin abolished in 221 BCE for a centralized empire.","answer":"Fengjian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">封建 — Fēngjiàn, \"to enfeoff and establish\"</span></div>","traditional":"封建","hanzi":"封建","pinyin":"Fēngjiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fēngjiàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Fengjian</b>, a word meaning to grant land and set up a state, was the system by which the early Zhou dynasty governed its vast realm. Under it the king did not rule the whole land himself, but carved it into many hereditary domains and gave them to kinsmen and trusted allies, who became lords of their own states. In return for their lands these lords owed the king their loyalty, sent him tribute at his court, and marched to war with their soldiers when he called. The whole order was shaped like a pyramid: the king as Son of Heaven at its summit, the ranked lords beneath him, then their lesser nobles and knights, and the farmers at the base. It is often likened to the feudalism of medieval Europe, but the Zhou order was held together above all by ties of kinship and ancestral worship, for most of the great lords were relatives of the royal house. <br><br> The Zhou set up this system after they conquered the Shang, around 1046 BCE, for their small western homeland was far too little to hold the huge conquered country alone. So King Wu and the Duke of Zhou planted loyal lords like garrisons across the land, in states such as Lu, Qi, and Yan, to guard the realm in the king's name. The system held so long as the king was strong, but after the Western Zhou fell in 771 BCE his power withered, and the great states grew independent and warred among themselves for centuries. At last the state of Qin swallowed all the rest, and in 221 BCE the First Emperor abolished the old fengjian, ruling instead through a centralized empire of appointed governors. The choice between such decentralized enfeoffment and central rule became one of the oldest debates in Chinese statecraft, and in modern times the word fengjian was borrowed to brand the whole imperial age as feudal.","citation":"","answerText":"Fengjian"},
{"id":"cnh-136","num":"一百三十六","category":"China · History","question":"Named for the grid shape of the character for a well, under which eight families farmed the outer plots for themselves and together worked the central plot for their lord, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the idealized Zhou land model best known from the writings of Mencius.","answer":"Well-field system","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">井田制 — Jǐngtián zhì; from the grid shape of 井, \"well\"</span></div>","traditional":"井田制","hanzi":"井田制","pinyin":"Jǐngtián zhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jǐngtián zhì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Well-field system</b> was an idealized picture of how farmland was ordered in the days of the Zhou dynasty. It takes its name not from any water well but from the shape of the Chinese character for 'well,' which is drawn as a neat grid of nine squares like a noughts-and-crosses board. In the same way, a square of farmland was imagined divided into nine equal plots, of which the eight around the edge were each worked by a peasant family that kept the harvest to live on. The ninth plot, in the very centre, was the lord's, and the eight families tilled it together, giving their labour there in place of any tax in grain or coin. The land itself belonged in the end to the king and his nobles, not to the farmers, who held their fields but could never buy or sell them. <br><br> Almost all we know of this system comes from the philosopher Mencius, who wrote of it centuries after the Zhou and urged the rulers of his day to restore it as the model of just government. Because his account is so late and so tidy, many scholars doubt whether the fields were ever really laid out in so perfect a grid, treating it more as a beautiful ideal than as sober history. It was imagined as the farming base beneath the Zhou order of lords and fiefs, yet was a thing apart, a way of holding land, not a way of granting power. In the later ages of iron plows and growing trade, land came to be bought and sold, and the old system, if it ever truly existed, broke down and was swept away by the reforms of the state of Qin. Yet the dream of it never died, and for centuries reformers who wished to give every family its fair share of land looked back to the well-fields as their example.","citation":"","answerText":"Well-field system"},
{"id":"cnh-137","num":"一百三十七","category":"China · History","question":"Ruling as the earthly agent of Heaven and holding its Mandate, yet no god himself but a mortal who could lose that favour through misrule, the Chinese king or emperor bore the sacred title <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, lord of all under Heaven from the days of the Zhou down to 1912.","answer":"Son of Heaven","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">天子 — Tiānzǐ, \"Son of Heaven\"</span></div>","traditional":"天子","hanzi":"天子","pinyin":"Tiānzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiānzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Son of Heaven</b> was the sacred title borne by the supreme ruler of China, marking him as the earthly son and chosen agent of Heaven. As Heaven's deputy he was the great link between the powers of Heaven above and the world of men below, charged with keeping the cosmos and the realm in harmony. He alone might offer the highest of all sacrifices, the worship of Heaven itself, and he ruled by Heaven's Mandate, its granted right to govern the world. Yet for all his awe, the Son of Heaven was no god, but a mortal appointed to his office, who could forfeit Heaven's favour and be cast down if he ruled cruelly or ill. The title named the ruler himself, while the Mandate of Heaven was the sacred grant that made his rule lawful; the two went together but were not the same. <br><br> The title was the gift of the Zhou, who, after they overthrew the Shang, needed a new ground for their power. The old Shang kings had claimed the throne through descent from the high god, but the Zhou taught instead that the ruler was Heaven's virtuous son, holding his crown only so long as he deserved it. In theory the Son of Heaven was the single lord of all under Heaven, the very centre of the whole civilized world, to whom lesser kings and distant peoples owed tribute and homage. This was more a grand ideal than a true world-empire, for China never ruled all the earth, yet the vision of one supreme Son of Heaven shaped how the Chinese saw their place among the nations. So mighty was the idea that the title endured for nearly three thousand years, worn first by the kings of Zhou and then by every emperor after them, until the last gave up the throne in 1912.","citation":"","answerText":"Son of Heaven"},
{"id":"cnh-138","num":"一百三十八","category":"China · History","question":"Cast by the piece-mold method to hold offerings of food and wine for the ancestral spirits, and often bearing long inscriptions that are priceless records of the age, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> were the supreme treasures of the Shang and Zhou, marking their owners' rank and power.","answer":"Chinese ritual bronzes","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青銅禮器 / 青铜礼器 — qīngtóng lǐqì, \"bronze ritual vessels\"</span></div>","traditional":"青銅禮器","hanzi":"青铜礼器","pinyin":"qīngtóng lǐqì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">qīngtóng lǐqì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese ritual bronzes</b> were the magnificent cast vessels that crowned the Shang and Zhou dynasties, the height of the Chinese Bronze Age. They were not dishes for everyday meals but sacred vessels, used in the worship of the ancestors to hold and offer food, wine, and water to the spirits of the dead. The Chinese made them by a method of their own, the piece-mold: clay moulds carved with the design were fitted together and molten bronze poured in, unlike the lost-wax casting of the West. Each kind of vessel had its own name and use, from the three-legged ding that held meat and the gui bowl for grain to a family of wine cups and water basins. Their surfaces were covered in dense, powerful ornament, above all a staring animal mask, later called the taotie, set against a ground of tiny squared spirals like rolling thunder. <br><br> To own these bronzes was to display one's rank, for by ritual rule only the king might use a set of nine great ding, a high lord seven, and a lesser noble fewer still. The Shang cast the most splendid vessels of all, bold in shape and rich in wine cups, yet wrote upon them only a few characters, a clan sign or an ancestor's name. The Zhou, by contrast, cast long inscriptions inside their bronzes, sometimes hundreds of characters, recording the king's gifts, grants of office and land, lawsuits, and victories in war. Because these words were cast at the very time of the events, the bronze inscriptions are among the most precious firsthand records of that distant age. The mightiest Shang vessel, the great Houmuwu ding, weighs over eight hundred kilograms, while the Zhou Mao Gong ding bears one of the longest inscriptions of all, a royal charge of some five hundred words.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese ritual bronzes"},
{"id":"cnh-139","num":"一百三十九","category":"China · History","question":"Cast into the hidden inner surfaces of ritual vessels rather than scratched onto bone like the older oracle-bone writing, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are the metal-script texts of the Shang and Zhou that form a priceless firsthand record of the age and a key stage in the growth of Chinese writing.","answer":"Chinese bronze inscriptions","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">金文 — Jīnwén, \"metal script\"; also 鐘鼎文, \"bell-and-cauldron script\"</span></div>","traditional":"金文","hanzi":"金文","pinyin":"Jīnwén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jīnwén</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese bronze inscriptions</b>, known as jinwen or 'metal script,' are the writing on the bronze vessels and bells of the Shang and Zhou dynasties. They must not be confused with the older oracle-bone script, for the two were written in quite different ways and for quite different purposes. The oracle-bone writing was scratched with a knife onto bone and shell, but the bronze inscriptions were cast into the metal, their characters shaped in the clay mould so the words came out as part of the finished vessel. They were usually set on the hidden inner surfaces of the vessel, inside the belly or under the lid, for they were addressed to the ancestors and needed not be seen by living eyes. In the long story of Chinese writing, this script stands midway between the older oracle-bone characters and the later seal script, growing rounder and more regular over the centuries of Zhou rule. <br><br> The Shang cast only a few characters onto their bronzes, a clan sign or the name of an honoured ancestor. The Zhou, however, cast whole paragraphs, some of hundreds of characters, telling of a king's gifts and appointments, of land, lawsuits, and battles, and closing with the wish that the maker's sons and grandsons treasure the vessel for ever. Because these words were fixed in metal at the very moment of the events, and never copied or changed by later hands, they are among the most trustworthy records of those far-off days. This makes them more reliable for the Zhou age than the old classics, which were recopied and altered down the centuries. Many thousands of inscribed bronzes survive, some, like the Mao Gong cauldron with its nearly five hundred words, bearing very long texts, and though scholars have studied them for a thousand years, a few of the oldest characters puzzle readers still.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese bronze inscriptions"},
{"id":"cnh-140","num":"一百四十","category":"China · History","question":"Sent by his father the Duke of Zhou to govern the state of Lu in his stead, and famous for imposing the strict Zhou rites so thoroughly that it took him three years to set the land in order, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded the Lu that would become the great home of Zhou ritual and, long after, of Confucius.","answer":"Bo Qin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">伯禽 — Bó Qín; \"Bo\" marks the eldest son; first Lord of Lu 魯公</span></div>","traditional":"伯禽","hanzi":"伯禽","pinyin":"Bó Qín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bó Qín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Bo Qin</b> was the eldest son of the Duke of Zhou and the founding ruler of the state of Lu, in what is now Shandong, at its seat of Qufu. Lu had been granted as a fief to his father the Duke of Zhou, but the Duke was needed at the royal court to govern for the young King Cheng, so he sent his son Bo Qin to rule it in his place. An old story tells that Bo Qin was three whole years setting Lu in order before he returned to report to his father, because he had laboured to teach the local people the strict rites of the Zhou. Meanwhile the sage Jiang Ziya, sent to the neighbouring state of Qi, had reported back in only five months, for he had simply bent to the customs the people already knew. Hearing this, the Duke of Zhou sighed and foretold that Lu, with its heavy and difficult ways, would end the weaker of the two and one day bow to Qi. <br><br> Yet in one thing Lu became the greatest of the states, for its founder's care made it the faithful keeper of the Zhou rites and music. So carefully were the old ceremonies preserved there that in later ages men said the rites of Zhou were all to be found in Lu. Five centuries later, this land of Lu was the home of Confucius, who honoured the Duke of Zhou above all men and drank deep of the traditions Lu had kept alive. The court records of Lu became the famous chronicle called the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, from which a whole long age of Chinese history takes its name. But just as the Duke of Zhou had foreseen, Lu stayed a small and culturally proud state, weak in war and overshadowed by mighty Qi, until it was swallowed by the state of Chu in 256 BCE.","citation":"","answerText":"Bo Qin"},
{"id":"cnh-141","num":"一百四十一","category":"China · History","question":"A small Zhou vassal state in Shandong, ruled by the royal Ji clan and revered as the faithful keeper of Zhou ritual, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the homeland of Confucius, though its own dukes were long reduced to puppets by three overmighty noble families.","answer":"Lu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">魯 / 鲁 — Lǔ; a Zhou vassal state in Shandong, capital Qufu; 11th c. BCE – 256 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"魯","hanzi":"鲁","pinyin":"Lǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lu</b> was a vassal state of the Zhou dynasty, lying in the south of what is now Shandong, with its capital at Qufu. It was founded in the early Western Zhou by Bo Qin, son of the Duke of Zhou, and its dukes belonged to the royal Ji clan, the very kin of the Zhou kings, which gave the little state great honour. For Lu was small and weak in arms, overshadowed always by its mighty northern neighbour Qi, and lived more by ritual and cunning than by the sword. Yet in the things of the spirit Lu stood highest of all, the faithful keeper of the rites and music of the Zhou, so that men said the rites of Zhou were all to be found there. Above all, Lu was the homeland of Confucius, the cradle of the tradition that grew from his teaching; its court chronicle, the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, said to be shaped by his hand, gave a whole age of Chinese history its name. <br><br> For all its fame, Lu was torn from within, for three great noble houses, the Three Huan, sprung from an early Duke Huan of Lu, seized the real power of the state. They divided its lands and armies among themselves and reduced the dukes to little more than puppets in their own court. Confucius himself, who for a time held office in Lu, is said to have tried to break the grip of these families and restore the duke, but he failed and left his homeland to wander abroad. Weakened within and hemmed in without, Lu shrank through the long wars of later ages until it was swallowed up by the great southern state of Chu, around 256 BCE, its last duke made a commoner. Yet the memory of Lu endures, for to this day the province of Shandong is still nicknamed Lu after the state that cradled the sages.","citation":"","answerText":"Lu"},
{"id":"cnh-142","num":"一百四十二","category":"China · History","question":"The great eastern rival of Lu, founded by the strategist Jiang Ziya and grown rich on salt and sea-trade, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rose under Duke Huan to be the first of the Spring and Autumn hegemons before it fell, last of all the states, to Qin in 221 BCE.","answer":"Qi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">齊 / 齐 — Qí; a great Zhou state in Shandong, capital Linzi; 11th c. BCE – 221 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"齊","hanzi":"齐","pinyin":"Qí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qi</b> was one of the greatest and richest of the many states of the Zhou dynasty, the master of the eastern lands. It lay along the coast in the north and east of what is now Shandong, and its capital, Linzi, grew into one of the largest, wealthiest cities of the ancient world. Qi was founded in the early Western Zhou as the reward of Jiang Ziya, the strategist of the conquest of the Shang, and its ruling house bore the Jiang name, unlike the royal Ji clan of its small ritual-loving neighbour, Lu. Where Lu clung to the old rites, Qi was a practical, trading state, and it drew great wealth from its salt-pans, its fisheries, its iron, and its busy coastal commerce. In later centuries the throne of Qi was seized from the Jiang line by a powerful family, the Tian, though the state kept its old name through the change. <br><br> The proudest age of Qi came under Duke Huan and his brilliant minister Guan Zhong, whose reforms made the state mighty. So great grew Qi's power that Duke Huan became the first of the famous Five Hegemons of the Spring and Autumn age, leading the other lords while claiming to uphold the Zhou king and drive back the barbarians. Qi was also a home of learning, for at Linzi its rulers gathered a great crowd of scholars, the Jixia Academy, where the many rival schools of thought debated and the sage Xunzi once taught. Rich and strong to the very end, Qi outlasted all the other great states as they fell one by one to the rising power of Qin in the west. It was the last to go, yielding to Qin without a real fight in 221 BCE, and with its surrender all of China was at last brought under a single ruler.","citation":"","answerText":"Qi"},
{"id":"cnh-143","num":"一百四十三","category":"China · History","question":"Given his fief, so the legend runs, when his brother the boy-king Cheng jokingly enfeoffed him with a leaf cut like a jade tablet and could not take the words back, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the younger son of King Wu who founded the state of Tang that his own son would rename mighty Jin.","answer":"Shu Yu of Tang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">唐叔虞 — Táng Shū Yú; \"Shu\" marks a younger son; founder of Tang, later Jin 晉</span></div>","traditional":"唐叔虞","hanzi":"唐叔虞","pinyin":"Táng Shū Yú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táng Shū Yú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shu Yu of Tang</b> was a younger son of King Wu, the founder of the Zhou dynasty, and the little brother of the second king, King Cheng. His name tells his place in the family, for Shu marks a younger son, and Tang was the land he was given to rule. A famous old tale, told to teach that a king's word is binding, explains how he came by that fief. One day the boy-king Cheng, playing with his small brother, cut a paulownia leaf into the shape of a jade tablet and gave it to him, saying in jest that with it he made him a lord. An official at court, the Duke of Zhou in one telling and the royal scribe in another, held the king to his careless word, insisting that the Son of Heaven may never speak in play, and so Shu Yu was enfeoffed with the land of Tang. <br><br> Shu Yu settled his new state in the valley of the Fen River, in what is now Shanxi, and after his death his son renamed it Jin, so it is as the founder of Jin that Shu Yu is honoured. This ancient Tang must not be confused with the great Tang dynasty of far later ages, which only borrowed the name of this old region. For centuries after Shu Yu, his state of Jin grew into one of the mightiest powers of China, its Duke Wen becoming one of the great overlords of the age. In the end, though, Jin was carved up between three of its own overmighty noble houses, the Han, the Zhao, and the Wei. That great partition is often taken to mark the beginning of the Warring States, so that from Shu Yu's single fief there sprang, in time, three of the seven kingdoms that fought for the mastery of China.","citation":"","answerText":"Shu Yu of Tang"},
{"id":"cnh-144","num":"一百四十四","category":"China · History","question":"The great northern power of the Spring and Autumn age, founded by Shu Yu and led to supremacy by Duke Wen, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dominated the other states for a century before it was carved up among the three families whose new kingdoms opened the Warring States.","answer":"Jin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">晉 / 晋 — Jìn; a Spring and Autumn state in Shanxi; 11th c. BCE – c. 376 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"晉","hanzi":"晋","pinyin":"Jìn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jìn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jin</b> was one of the mightiest of all the states of the Zhou dynasty, and for much of the Spring and Autumn age the leading power of the north. Its heartland lay in the valley of the Fen River in what is now Shanxi, and from there it spread to command the lands about the great bend of the Yellow River. It was founded in the early Western Zhou by Shu Yu, a brother of King Cheng, first as the state of Tang and then, under his son, as Jin; its ruling house was of the royal Ji clan, the kin of the Zhou kings. Powerful and warlike, Jin was the great shield of the northern states against the rising southern power of Chu. This ancient state of Jin should not be confused with the much later Jin dynasty of the Sima family, nor with the Jurchen Jin written with a wholly different character. <br><br> The greatest of its rulers was Duke Wen, who came home to the throne after nineteen years of exile and made Jin supreme among the states. He became the second of the famous Five Hegemons, after Duke Huan of Qi, and won undying fame by crushing the army of Chu at the great battle of Chengpu. For more than a century Jin led the northern lords, yet in time its dukes lost all real power to a few overmighty ministerial families. These great houses warred among themselves until only a few were left, and three of them at last, the Han, the Zhao, and the Wei, divided the whole of Jin between them. When the Zhou king recognized the three as lords, around 403 BCE, that partition was long taken to mark the start of the Warring States, so Jin itself vanished, replaced by three of the seven great kingdoms that fought for China.","citation":"","answerText":"Jin"},
{"id":"cnh-145","num":"一百四十五","category":"China · History","question":"The northernmost of the great Zhou states, guarding the frontier near where Beijing stands, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rose late to glory under King Zhao before its prince sent the assassin Jing Ke against the King of Qin and it fell, near the last, to Qin in 222 BCE.","answer":"Yan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">燕 — Yān; a northern Zhou state around modern Beijing; 11th c. BCE – 222 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"燕","hanzi":"燕","pinyin":"Yān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yan</b> was the northernmost of the great states of the Zhou dynasty, in the far north around where Beijing now stands, with its capital at Ji. It was a remote frontier land, guarding the border against the nomad peoples of the northern steppe, and it built long defensive walls that were forerunners of the Great Wall. Yan was founded in the early Western Zhou by the Duke of Shao, a royal kinsman who, like the Duke of Zhou before him, stayed at court and sent his son to rule the new state. Weak and far off for much of its history, Yan rose to its brief hour of glory only in the age of the Warring States, under King Zhao of Yan. By tradition King Zhao built a Golden Terrace heaped with gold to draw men of talent, and his general Yue Yi led a coalition that in 284 BCE all but destroyed the mighty state of Qi, though Qi was later restored. <br><br> But Yan is best remembered for a single desperate deed, done as the western state of Qin swallowed the others one by one. The crown prince of Yan sent a brave assassin, Jing Ke, to murder the King of Qin, the man who would soon become the First Emperor of China. Jing Ke came before him bearing a rolled-up map with a poisoned dagger hidden inside, and as the map was unrolled the blade appeared; but his strike missed and he was cut down. The failed attempt only enraged Qin, which fell upon Yan and, near the very last of all the states, conquered it in 222 BCE. Yet the land of Yan won lasting fame for breeding bold and tragic heroes, and Jing Ke, who sang his farewell by the cold waters of the Yi, became the greatest of them.","citation":"","answerText":"Yan"},
{"id":"cnh-146","num":"一百四十六","category":"China · History","question":"A younger brother of King Wu and the Duke of Zhou, given the state of Wey over the conquered Shang heartland and the famous charge to rule its people with bright virtue and sparing punishment, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded the small state that would outlast every other of the old Zhou realms.","answer":"Kang Shu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">康叔 — Kāng Shū; personal name Feng, \"Shu\" marks a younger son; founder of Wey 衞</span></div>","traditional":"康叔","hanzi":"康叔","pinyin":"Kāng Shū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kāng Shū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kang Shu</b>, whose name was Feng, was a younger son of King Wen and a brother of both King Wu and the Duke of Zhou. His title tells his rank in the family, for Shu marks a younger brother, while Kang was the name of an earlier fief he had held before he rose to greatness. His hour came after the Duke of Zhou had crushed the great rebellion of the Three Guards and the Shang prince Wu Geng, when the conquered heartland of the fallen Shang needed a strong and trusted lord. The Duke gave that charge to his able brother, enfeoffing Kang Shu with the state of Wey, set over the old Shang capital and its restless people. There Kang Shu ruled the defeated Shang folk so wisely and kindly that they grew content, and his good government became a model for the age. <br><br> When he first took up his new state, Kang Shu was given a famous charge, the Announcement to Kang, which is still preserved in the old <i>Book of Documents</i>. Spoken by the Duke of Zhou in the young king's name, it taught him to cherish the people, to punish only with the greatest care, and to rule by bright virtue rather than harshness. A companion piece warned him sternly against drunkenness, for the Zhou believed that strong drink had helped to ruin the Shang before him. These noble words are among the oldest and truest of the Zhou writings, and Kang Shu was later called to the royal court to serve as its minister of justice. His little state of Wey was never mighty, but it proved the most enduring of all the old Zhou realms, outliving them every one until the Qin abolished it at last in 209 BCE.","citation":"","answerText":"Kang Shu"},
{"id":"cnh-147","num":"一百四十七","category":"China · History","question":"The unusual Zhou state where the descendants of the fallen Shang carried on their royal line, and the home of the foolish chivalry of Duke Xiang and of the mocked man-of-Song fool of later fables, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lasted until Qi destroyed it in 286 BCE.","answer":"Song","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">宋 — Sòng; the Zhou state of the Shang heirs, capital Shangqiu; 11th c. BCE – 286 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"宋","hanzi":"宋","pinyin":"Sòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sòng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Song</b> was one of the most unusual of the Zhou states, for it was the home of the descendants of the fallen Shang dynasty. When the Zhou overthrew the Shang, they did not wipe out the old royal house but preserved its line in Song, that the Shang kings' family might go on offering the sacrifices to their ancestors. Its rulers were therefore of the ancient Shang royal clan, not the Ji clan of the Zhou kings, and its capital stood at Shangqiu, the Mound of Shang, in eastern Henan. After the Shang prince Wu Geng had rebelled and been killed, it was a loyal Shang prince, Weizi, who was given Song to carry on his people's rites. As the heirs of a former dynasty the lords of Song were honoured as special guests of the Zhou king; but this ancient state must not be confused with the much later Song dynasty of the emperors. <br><br> The most famous of Song's rulers was Duke Xiang, who dreamed of becoming the overlord of the states. But at the Battle of Hong he lost everything through misplaced honour, refusing to strike the Chu army while it was still crossing the river and forming up, and was crushingly beaten for his pains. From this came a proverb, the benevolence of Duke Xiang of Song, meaning a foolish, self-defeating show of chivalry at just the wrong moment. Because they were the remnant of the beaten Shang, the people of Song became the stock fools of later fables, like the farmer who waited by a tree-stump for another rabbit, or the man who pulled up his seedlings to help them grow. Yet by tradition the great Confucius, though a man of Lu, sprang from the old nobility of Song, before Qi at last destroyed the little state in 286 BCE.","citation":"","answerText":"Song"},
{"id":"cnh-148","num":"一百四十八","category":"China · History","question":"The mighty southern kingdom of the Zhou age, ruled by the Mi clan and not the royal Ji, whose King Zhuang once marched north to ask the weight of the Nine Cauldrons, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the largest of the Warring States before Qin conquered it in 223 BCE.","answer":"Chu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">楚 — Chǔ; the great southern state of the Zhou, chief capital Ying; 11th c. BCE – 223 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"楚","hanzi":"楚","pinyin":"Chǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chu</b> was the great power of the south in the Zhou age, a vast realm along the middle Yangtze in what is now Hubei, its chief capital at Ying near modern Jingzhou. Its royal house sprang not from the Ji clan of the Zhou kings but from the ancient Mi clan of the Xiong line, so its kings' names commonly bear it. The northern states looked on Chu as a half-barbarian land of the wild south, yet its people, far from denying it, gloried in the name. So bold were they that Chu was the first Zhou state whose ruler cast off the duke's title to call himself King, under King Wu about 704 BCE, long before the northern lords dared. This ancient kingdom must not be confused with the later regimes that borrowed its name, Xiang Yu's Western Chu or the Ten Kingdoms' Southern Chu. <br><br> Its greatest early king was King Zhuang, a hegemon of the Spring and Autumn age, who about 606 BCE marched to the royal border and asked the weight of the Nine Cauldrons, the sacred vessels of supreme rule. By that insolent question he all but claimed the Zhou throne, and ever since to covet supreme power is called asking about the tripods. Chu rose as high in war, for after Jin beat it at Chengpu in 632 BCE, King Zhuang crushed the Jin army at Bi in 597 BCE. Chu gave China its most famous early poet, Qu Yuan, a loyal minister whose verses fill the <i>Songs of Chu</i> and who by tradition drowned in the Miluo River, mourned yearly at the Dragon Boat Festival. In the Warring States Chu was the largest of the seven kingdoms and Qin's chief rival, yet Qin conquered it in 223 BCE among the last to fall, and the rebels who soon toppled Qin, Chen Sheng, Xiang Yu, and Liu Bang, were all sons of Chu.","citation":"","answerText":"Chu"},
{"id":"cnh-149","num":"一百四十九","category":"China · History","question":"The most enduring of all the Zhou states, founded by Kang Shu over the conquered Shang heartland and famed for the duke who gave his pet cranes official rank, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> outlasted every rival until Qin abolished it in 209 BCE.","answer":"Wey","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">衞 — Wèi, spelled Wey to keep it apart from Wei 魏; the Zhou state of Kang Shu, first capital Zhaoge; 11th c. BCE – 209 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"衞","hanzi":"卫","pinyin":"Wèi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wèi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wey</b> was a small but remarkably long-lived Zhou state, set over the old Shang heartland in northern Henan, its first capital at Zhaoge. Its name is spelled Wey in English to set it apart from the wholly different Warring States power Wei, written with another character but sounding the same in Chinese. It was founded early in the Western Zhou for Kang Shu, a younger brother of King Wu of the royal Ji clan, after the Duke of Zhou crushed the Shang prince Wu Geng's revolt. Its ruling house was thus Zhou kin, not of Shang blood, for the fallen Shang line lived on instead in the neighbouring state of Song. Though never mighty, Wey proved the most enduring of all the Zhou states, outlasting every rival and even the Qin unification, until the Second Emperor abolished it in 209 BCE and made its last lord a commoner. <br><br> Its most famous tale concerns Duke Yi, who by tradition so doted on cranes that he gave the birds official rank and carriages, so that when the Di invaded about 660 BCE his soldiers refused to fight, jeering that the cranes should fight instead. The capital fell, the duke was killed, and the state was all but wiped out, saved and rebuilt only by Duke Huan of Qi, protector of the lesser states. Its name later lived on in the phrase the sounds of Zheng and Wey, by which Confucian moralists condemned seductive, licentious music as the ruin of good order. For all its weakness Wey bred remarkable men who won fame elsewhere: the Legalist reformer Shang Yang, a scion of its ducal house; the general Wu Qi; and the doomed assassin Jing Ke. Confucius himself lodged in Wey in his years of wandering, and its folk songs fill much of the <i>Book of Songs</i>, so this modest state marked Chinese memory far beyond its power.","citation":"","answerText":"Wey"},
{"id":"cnh-150","num":"一百五十","category":"China · History","question":"The third king of the Zhou dynasty, whose reign with that of his father King Cheng is looked back on as the golden age of the early Western Zhou, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> received a grand accession recorded in the <i>Book of Documents</i> and left the great Da Yu ding bronze before the dynasty's slow decline set in under his son.","answer":"King Kang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周康王 — Zhōu Kāng Wáng, \"the Peaceful King\"; personal name Ji Zhao 姬釗; c. 11th–10th c. BCE, dates disputed</span></div>","traditional":"周康王","hanzi":"周康王","pinyin":"Zhōu Kāng Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Kāng Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Kang</b> was the third king of the Zhou dynasty, whose given name was Ji Zhao, the son and heir of King Cheng and grandson of King Wu. His reign and his father's together are remembered as the Rule of Cheng and Kang, the golden age of the early Western Zhou, a time of rare peace and good order. So untroubled were these years, later histories told, that for over forty years the punishments of the law were laid aside and never used. By the time King Kang took the throne the Duke of Zhou was already dead, and two elder statesmen, the Duke of Shao and the Duke of Bi, upheld the king and guided the realm. His title Kang must not be confused with his great-uncle Kang Shu, the founder of Wey, different men who merely shared the word in their names. <br><br> The grandest record of his reign is its beginning, for the old <i>Book of Documents</i> preserves the ceremony of his enthronement, when the dying King Cheng's charge to his ministers passed the realm to his heir before the assembled lords. From his day survives one of the most famous of Chinese bronzes, the great cauldron called the Da Yu ding, cast for an officer named Yu to record a charge from the king. Its inscription warns that the Shang lost Heaven's favour through drunkenness, while the Zhou kept it by sober virtue, the lesson the dynasty never tired of repeating. He also warred on the northern frontier against a people called the Guifang, and another of his bronzes boasts of the host of captives his armies carried home. He was the last king of the Zhou's happy dawn, for under his son King Zhao, who drowned on a ruinous southern campaign, the dynasty's long decline began; Cheng and Kang were ever after held up as the model of peaceful rule.","citation":"","answerText":"King Kang"},
{"id":"cnh-151","num":"一百五十一","category":"China · History","question":"Cast for the noble Yu in the twenty-third year of King Kang and now a treasure of the National Museum of China, the great bronze cauldron called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> bears a famous inscription warning that the Shang had lost Heaven's Mandate through drink.","answer":"Da Yu ding","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">大盂鼎 — Dà Yú dǐng; a bronze ding cast for the noble Yu, 23rd year of King Kang of Zhou; early Western Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"大盂鼎","hanzi":"大盂鼎","pinyin":"Dà Yú dǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Yú dǐng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Da Yu ding</b> is one of the most famous Chinese bronzes, a great cauldron cast under King Kang of Zhou for a noble named Yu, who dedicated it to his ancestor Nan Gong. It is a huge round vessel on three legs, a metre tall and over a hundred and fifty kilograms, its neck and legs wrought with the staring animal masks the Zhou loved. Its glory is hidden inside: a long inscription of some 290 characters cast into the belly, a key royal text of the early Zhou and a prized model of bronze script. In it King Kang charges Yu with office and recalls how the Shang lost Heaven's favour because its kings sank into drunkenness, while the Zhou kept it by sober virtue. This warning against drink is the bronze's own preaching, the lesson the Zhou set down in the Announcement about Drink in the <i>Book of Documents</i>. <br><br> The king then heaps gifts on Yu — robes, a chariot and horses, a war-banner, and, the inscription declares, more than seventeen hundred dependent people to serve him. Cast at the very time, it is a priceless firsthand record of how the early Zhou thought of Heaven's mandate and bound nobles with grants of land and men. The cauldron lay buried nearly three thousand years until it was dug up about 1849 in Shaanxi, the old Zhou heartland. It passed to the collector Pan Zuyin, whose family hid it from the invading Japanese and at last gave it to the nation; it now stands among the treasures of the National Museum of China in Beijing. It ranks with the Da Ke ding and Mao Gong ding among the three greatest inscribed Zhou cauldrons, and must not be confused with a smaller companion made for Yu, the lost Xiao Yu ding, which tells instead of a war.","citation":"","answerText":"Da Yu ding"},
{"id":"cnh-152","num":"一百五十二","category":"China · History","question":"The fourth king of the Zhou dynasty, who led his armies south only to lose the whole royal host on the Han River, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Zhou drowned there on that ruinous campaign, in the reign later marked as the start of the dynasty's long decline.","answer":"King Zhao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周昭王 — Zhōu Zhāo Wáng, \"the Illustrious King\"; personal name Ji Xia 姬瑕; posthumous 昭, a different word from his father King Kang's given name 釗</span></div>","traditional":"周昭王","hanzi":"周昭王","pinyin":"Zhōu Zhāo Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Zhāo Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Zhao</b> was the fourth king of the Zhou dynasty, whose given name was Ji Xia, the son of King Kang and grandson of King Cheng. He came to the throne after the long peace of Cheng and Kang, the golden age of his father and grandfather, and in his reign the bright morning of the Zhou first began to darken. For King Zhao turned the armies of Zhou southward, marching again and again into the valley of the Han and the middle Yangtze against the peoples of the south, the land of Jing that would later be the heart of Chu. His last and greatest expedition ended in ruin, for there on the Han River the whole royal host, the Six Armies of the Zhou, was destroyed. The king himself drowned in the waters, by the sober tradition, and so shameful was the disaster that his death was hushed up and never openly announced. <br><br> A famous later legend, and not the true record, tells that the boatmen of the hostile south gave him a boat cunningly glued together, which came apart in midstream and sank him. Whatever the manner of his end, the loss of a whole royal army was a blow from which the early Zhou never fully recovered, and later ages marked his reign as the turning point where the long decline set in. His son King Mu came after him and steadied the shaken state, yet the days of easy Zhou mastery were passing. This King Zhao of Zhou must not be confused with the far later King Zhao of Yan, a lord of the Warring States who lived more than six centuries afterward and merely shared the royal name. So the fourth king is remembered less for any triumph than for a great catastrophe, the drowning on the Han that closed the springtime of the Western Zhou.","citation":"","answerText":"King Zhao"},
{"id":"cnh-153","num":"一百五十三","category":"China · History","question":"The fifth king of the Zhou dynasty, whose eight steeds bore him west in legend to feast with the Queen Mother of the West, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Zhou reigned longer than any other king of the line and left behind the graded penal code called the Lü Punishments.","answer":"King Mu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周穆王 — Zhōu Mù Wáng, \"the Solemn King\"; personal name Ji Man 姬滿; traditionally reigned some 55 years, early Western Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"周穆王","hanzi":"周穆王","pinyin":"Zhōu Mù Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Mù Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Mu</b> was the fifth king of the Zhou dynasty, whose given name was Ji Man, the son of King Zhao and the great wanderer among the early Zhou kings. By tradition he reigned 55 years, longer than any other Zhou king, and, coming after his father's ruin on the Han, he laboured to steady the shaken realm. Yet the old books also fault him as a restless ruler who longed to leave his chariot-tracks over all the world. His most famous adventure is a legend, told in the romance the <i>Tale of King Mu, Son of Heaven</i>: how he drove far west in a chariot pulled by his eight matchless steeds and driven by the charioteer Zaofu, to feast with the Queen Mother of the West beside her Jade Lake. This dreamlike journey west must not be confused with the famous later novel of that name, the tale of the monk and the Monkey King. <br><br> By another tradition Zaofu was rewarded with the town of Zhao and became forefather of the Zhao clan, the root of one of the great Warring States. In the west he warred on the Quanrong tribes, but the campaign was remembered as a costly folly that won only four white wolves and four white deer and turned the western tribes against him. In the east he faced a rising in the land of Xu under its half-legendary King Yan, which he put down with the help of Chu. To his reign is credited the Lü Punishments, a chapter of the old <i>Book of Documents</i> that set out graded penalties and let a wrongdoer redeem his crime with a fine. His son King Gong came after him; and this King Mu of Zhou must not be confused with the far later Duke Mu of Qin, a Spring and Autumn lord who merely shared the name.","citation":"","answerText":"King Mu"},
{"id":"cnh-154","num":"一百五十四","category":"China · History","question":"Recovered on bamboo slips from an ancient Wei tomb alongside the <i>Bamboo Annals</i>, the semi-legendary travelogue called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> recounts King Mu's chariot journey west to feast with the Queen Mother of the West.","answer":"Tale of King Mu, Son of Heaven","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">穆天子傳 — Mù Tiānzǐ Zhuàn; a Warring States travelogue of King Mu of Zhou, recovered from the Jizhong tomb c. 279–281 CE</span></div>","traditional":"穆天子傳","hanzi":"穆天子传","pinyin":"Mù Tiānzǐ Zhuàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mù Tiānzǐ Zhuàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Tale of King Mu, Son of Heaven</b> is an ancient Chinese book, a semi-legendary account of the travels of King Mu of Zhou, and is often called the earliest work of travel writing in China. It was written in the Warring States age, long after the tenth-century king it describes, so it is romance more than sober record. Most of it follows King Mu's great expedition into the west, driving his eight fine steeds behind the charioteer Zaofu through many tribes and distant lands, with the stages and distances of the road carefully set down. Its most famous scene, pure legend, is the king's meeting with the Queen Mother of the West, feasting beside her Jade Lake and trading songs before he turns for home. The last of its six scrolls turns to a wholly different tale, the death and lavish funeral of the king's consort Sheng Ji, which some scholars think a separate book later joined to the rest. <br><br> The work was lost for many ages and came to light only when tomb-robbers broke into an old grave. It proved to be the tomb of a king of Wei, opened under the Western Jin about 279 or 281 CE, for the year is disputed; its books were written on bamboo slips in an old script that Jin scholars had to puzzle out. From the very same tomb came another famous discovery, the ancient chronicle known as the <i>Bamboo Annals</i>, a separate work. The tale is prized as one of the oldest Chinese travelogues and an early flowering of storytelling, and though it may echo real contact with the far west, its dreamlike geography cannot be pinned to any place on the map. For all its journeying to the west, it must not be confused with the far later Ming novel of that name, the story of the monk and the Monkey King.","citation":"","answerText":"Tale of King Mu, Son of Heaven"},
{"id":"cnh-155","num":"一百五十五","category":"China · History","question":"The sixth king of the Zhou dynasty, a sparing ruler after his father King Mu's costly reign, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Zhou destroyed the small state of Mi when its lord kept three women against his mother's counsel, and his reign is richly lit by the Qiu Wei bronzes' records of land.","answer":"King Gong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周共王 — Zhōu Gōng Wáng, also written 恭王, \"the Reverent King\"; personal name Ji Yihu 姬繄扈; c. 922–900 BCE, dates disputed</span></div>","traditional":"周共王","hanzi":"周共王","pinyin":"Zhōu Gōng Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Gōng Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Gong</b> was the sixth king of the Zhou dynasty, whose given name was Ji Yihu, the son of the far-roaming King Mu. Coming after his father's long reign of wars and wanderings, which had worn the state thin, he drew back into a quieter, sparing rule, a consolidating king as the early Zhou began its long decline. His most famous story is a moralizing tale in the old <i>Discourses of the States</i>: as the king toured along the Jing River, Duke Kang of the little state of Mi attended him. Three women came to Duke Kang, and his mother warned him to hand them to the king, for such rare and lovely things were too great a fortune for a small lord to keep without ruin. Duke Kang would not give them up, and the next year King Gong destroyed Mi, so that the tale became a warning against a petty man who hoards more than his virtue can bear. <br><br> His reign is among the best-lit of the middle Zhou, richly documented by inscribed bronze vessels. The bronzes of an officer named Qiu Wei record exchanges of land between noblemen, paid in jade and goods and reckoned in cowrie-shells, a rare early glimpse of how Zhou land could change hands. Another famous vessel, the Shi Qiang basin, praises the deeds of the early Zhou kings down to the reigning king, thought to be Gong himself, and so is dated to his reign. His son King Yi came after him as the seventh king, not to be confused with a later ninth king also called King Yi in English but written with a different character. For all these records he was but a minor, passing king, and his name must not be confused with the famous Gonghe regency of a later century, which merely shares the word Gong.","citation":"","answerText":"King Gong"},
{"id":"cnh-156","num":"一百五十六","category":"China · History","question":"The seventh king of the Zhou dynasty and son of King Gong, in whose weakening reign the capital shifted to Quanqiu and the day was said to dawn twice at Zheng, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, whose given name was Jian, was then succeeded not by his son but by his uncle King Xiao.","answer":"King Yi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周懿王 — Zhōu Yì Wáng, \"the Admirable King\"; personal name Ji Jian 姬囏; the 7th Zhou king (懿, not the 9th king 夷); c. 899–892 BCE, dates disputed</span></div>","traditional":"周懿王","hanzi":"周懿王","pinyin":"Zhōu Yì Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Yì Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Yi</b>, whose given name was Ji Jian, was the seventh king of the Zhou dynasty, the son of King Gong and grandson of the far-roaming King Mu. His reign is remembered as the time when the royal house of Zhou began in earnest to weaken, and the old histories tell that poets took to making bitter, satirical songs about the age. By tradition he moved the royal capital away from the Hao heartland to a place called Quanqiu, which he renamed Huaili, in the country to the west. The reason is not certainly known, but it may have been the raids of the Xianyun, a fierce nomad people of the north then pressing hard upon the Zhou frontier. The strangest record of his reign stands in the old <i>Bamboo Annals</i>, which says that in his first year the day dawned twice at a place called Zheng. <br><br> Modern scholars read this double dawn as a solar eclipse at sunrise, when the sky brightens, darkens as the moon hides the sun, and then brightens again, and have used it to fix his first year at about 899 BCE. This remains only a clever guess, yet it is prized as one of the earliest such records and a rare foothold for dating the murky early years of the Zhou. When King Yi died the throne did not pass to his own son but to his uncle, who reigned as King Xiao, the eighth king. Only afterward did it return to King Yi's line, to his son, who became the ninth king and is also called King Yi in English, though his name is written with a wholly different Chinese character. So Ji Jian was but a minor king of the sagging middle Zhou, remembered less for any deed of his own than as a milestone in the dynasty's long, slow decline.","citation":"","answerText":"King Yi"},
{"id":"cnh-157","num":"一百五十七","category":"China · History","question":"The eighth king of the Zhou dynasty and the only one to reign outside the direct passage of the throne from father to son, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Zhou is best remembered for granting the horse-breeder Feizi the frontier town of Qin, planting the seed of the state that would one day unify China.","answer":"King Xiao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周孝王 — Zhōu Xiào Wáng, \"the Filial King\"; personal name Ji Bifang 姬辟方; the 8th Zhou king; c. 891–886 BCE, dates disputed</span></div>","traditional":"周孝王","hanzi":"周孝王","pinyin":"Zhōu Xiào Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Xiào Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Xiao</b> was the eighth king of the Zhou dynasty, whose given name was Ji Bifang. He holds a strange place in the royal line: a son of King Mu and brother of King Gong, he was the only king of the whole Western Zhou to reign outside the direct passage of the throne from father to son. When his nephew King Yi, the seventh king, died, the crown passed not to that king's own son but up a generation to Xiao, for reasons the old records never explain. Only after Xiao's death did the throne return to the senior line, to King Yi's son, who reigned as the ninth king and is also called King Yi in English, though written with a different Chinese character from his father's. Of his own short reign in the failing middle years of the Zhou almost nothing else is remembered. <br><br> Yet King Xiao left one mark greater than any other king of his weak age, for it was he who founded the line of Qin. A man named Feizi bred horses so well for the royal herds, in the country between the Qian and Wei rivers, that the king resolved to reward him. King Xiao granted Feizi the little frontier town of Qin, not as a lord or a full state but as a small dependency, and charged him to carry on the sacrifices of his clan. From that tiny holding there grew, over the six centuries that followed, the mighty state of Qin that swallowed all its rivals and unified China under the First Emperor, as the old <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> traces the line. So this obscure king planted the seed of Qin, and must not be confused with the far later Duke Xiao of Qin, who made that same state a great power five centuries afterward.","citation":"","answerText":"King Xiao"},
{"id":"cnh-158","num":"一百五十八","category":"China · History","question":"A breeder of horses on the western frontier of the Zhou, rewarded by King Xiao with the little town of Qin, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the humble ancestor from whom the royal house of Qin traced its line down to the First Emperor who unified China.","answer":"Feizi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">非子 — Fēizǐ; a horse-breeder of the Ying 嬴 clan, granted the town of Qin by King Xiao of Zhou; founder of the Qin line, c. 9th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"非子","hanzi":"非子","pinyin":"Fēizǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fēizǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Feizi</b> was a man of the ancient Ying clan and the traditional founder of the ruling line of Qin, famed above all as a breeder of horses. He raised horses on the western frontier of the Zhou, in the country between the Qian and Wei rivers, and his herds multiplied so richly that his fame reached the royal court. King Xiao of Zhou, who needed strong horses for his armies on the troubled western frontier, put him in charge of the royal herds, and, pleased with how they thrived, resolved to reward him. The king granted him the small frontier town of Qin, not as a lord or a full feudal state but as a lowly dependency of the Zhou. He was allowed to take up again the ancestral sacrifices of his Ying clan, and was thenceforth called Qin Ying, the Ying of Qin, after his little fief. <br><br> Almost all that is known of Feizi comes from the old <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>, set down many centuries after his day, so his tale is tradition more than certain history. In his own time Qin was only a tiny holding, and it grew into a true feudal state only generations later, when Duke Xiang earned that rank by escorting the Zhou king safely eastward. Yet from that little frontier seed there sprang, over some six centuries, the mighty state of Qin that would in the end conquer all its rivals and unify China under the First Emperor. Feizi himself did nothing so grand and dreamed of no empire, and is remembered simply as the humble horse-keeper from whom the whole royal house of Qin traced its descent. This Feizi of the Ying clan must not be confused with the far later Han Feizi, the great Legalist thinker, whose almost identical name is mere chance.","citation":"","answerText":"Feizi"},
{"id":"cnh-159","num":"一百五十九","category":"China · History","question":"Rising from a despised frontier fief in the western passes and hardened by the Legalist reforms of Shang Yang into a war-machine, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> swallowed its six rivals to unify China in 221 BCE under the First Emperor.","answer":"Qin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">秦 — Qín; the western Ying-clan state, capital Xianyang; c. 770 BCE – 221 BCE, then the Qin dynasty</span></div>","traditional":"秦","hanzi":"秦","pinyin":"Qín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qin</b> was the westernmost great Zhou state, ruled by the ancient Ying clan, and in the end the one that swallowed all the rest to make China's first empire. It began as a lowly frontier fief and became a true state only about 770 BCE, when Duke Xiang of Qin escorted the Zhou king east after nomads sacked the old capital, winning the abandoned Zhou homeland in the west. Its heartland was the fertile Wei River valley within the mountain passes, a natural fortress; yet the eastern states long scorned Qin as a half-barbarian country of the frontier. It rose to early greatness under Duke Mu of Qin, who mastered the western Rong and is counted in some traditions among the hegemons of the Spring and Autumn age. But the decisive change came under Duke Xiao of Qin, when the Legalist Shang Yang, an incomer from the small state of Wey, forged Qin into a centralized war-machine whose ranks were won by battle-merit, not birth, under one harsh law. <br><br> Its people were bent to farming and war and ruled through appointed county officials, so Qin could feed and field larger, better-drilled armies than any rival. With this edge it devoured its neighbours one by one — Han, then Zhao, Wei, Chu, Yan, and last Qi — completing the conquest of all China in 221 BCE under its king Zheng. King Zheng then took a wholly new title as the First Emperor, and the frontier state became the first dynasty ever to rule a united China. Yet the Qin dynasty was astonishingly short-lived: within a few years of the First Emperor's death in 210 BCE it collapsed in rebellion and gave way to the Han. So from a despised frontier fief grew the maker of the first Chinese empire, and from the name of Qin, by the common account, comes the West's very word for China.","citation":"","answerText":"Qin"},
{"id":"cnh-160","num":"一百六十","category":"China · History","question":"The ninth king of the Zhou dynasty, set on the throne by the feudal lords after his granduncle King Xiao, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, whose given name was Xie, boiled Duke Ai of Qi alive and fathered the tyrant King Li.","answer":"King Yi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周夷王 — Zhōu Yí Wáng; personal name Ji Xie 姬燮; the 9th Zhou king (夷), son of the 7th king Yì 懿; c. 885–878 BCE, dates disputed</span></div>","traditional":"周夷王","hanzi":"周夷王","pinyin":"Zhōu Yí Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Yí Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Yi</b>, whose given name was Ji Xie, was the ninth king of the Zhou dynasty. He was the son of an earlier King Yi, the seventh king; English calls the two by the same name, though their Chinese titles are written with wholly different characters, and this is the son, the ninth in the line. He did not simply inherit the throne, for after his father's death it had passed to his granduncle King Xiao, and only when Xiao died did the great lords set Ji Xie up as king, a sign that their power now overtopped the crown. By tradition the royal majesty had so faded in his day that this king came down from his dais to greet the visiting lords in person, rather than receiving them from above as the Son of Heaven ought. Yet for all that fading, King Yi could still strike with terrible force at even a mighty vassal. <br><br> On the slander of the Marquis of Ji, the old <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> tells, he had Duke Ai of the great eastern state of Qi boiled alive in a cauldron. He then set up the dead duke's half-brother in his place, and the deed showed the Zhou king could still deal life and death to the lords of the greatest states. But the killing lit a blood-feud, and generations afterward the state of Qi took its revenge by wiping the little state of Ji from the earth. King Yi was followed by his son King Li, the hated tyrant whose cruelty would at last provoke the great uprising of 841 BCE, the first firmly dated year in Chinese history. So this ninth king is remembered as a minor ruler of the sinking middle Zhou, known for the boiling of Duke Ai, for stepping down from his hall, and above all as the father of the tyrant Li.","citation":"","answerText":"King Yi"},
{"id":"cnh-161","num":"一百六十一","category":"China · History","question":"The tenth king of the Zhou dynasty, a tyrant who seized the people's forests and rivers and silenced all complaint until they dared only glance at one another on the road, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was driven into exile in 841 BCE, the first firmly dated year of Chinese history.","answer":"King Li","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周厲王 — Zhōu Lì Wáng; \"Li\" 厲 a name of censure laid on a tyrant; personal name Ji Hu 姬胡; the 10th Zhou king; fled 841 BCE, d. c. 828 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"周厲王","hanzi":"周厲王","pinyin":"Zhōu Lì Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Lì Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Li</b> was the tenth king of the Zhou dynasty and the son of King Yi; his given name was Ji Hu, and the title Li is a name of shame laid on him to brand a tyrant. By the old histories, on the Duke of Rong's advice, he took for the crown the profits of forest, river, and marsh the people had freely used, deaf to Rui Liangfu's warning against hoarding all gain. When the people cursed him, he set a shaman from Wei to spy them out and put those who spoke against him to death. So great grew the terror that none dared speak, and men who met on the road could only glance at one another with their eyes, the king boasting he had silenced all complaint. But the Duke of Shao of that day warned him, in the old <i>Discourses of the States</i>, that stopping the people's mouths was worse than damming a river, whose bursting drowns many; still he would not listen. <br><br> At last, in 841 BCE, the guoren, the free people of the capital, rose and drove King Li from his palace. He was not killed but fled to a place called Zhi, where he lived in exile until his death. With the throne empty, the realm was ruled for fourteen years by a regency called the Gonghe — whether by the Dukes of Shao and Zhou together or by one lord, the Earl of Gong, the old accounts still dispute. That year, 841 BCE, is the first in Chinese history that can be fixed to an exact date, from which the years run unbroken. Only after King Li died did his son reign as King Xuan and win back some of Zhou's glory; from this kingless age, by the common account, comes the modern Chinese word for a republic, gonghe.","citation":"","answerText":"King Li"},
{"id":"cnh-162","num":"一百六十二","category":"China · History","question":"The fourteen-year interregnum that governed Zhou with no king on the throne after King Li fled into exile, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gives Chinese history its first exactly fixed year, 841 BCE, though whether two dukes or the lord Gongbo He ruled it is still debated.","answer":"Gonghe Regency","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">共和 — Gònghé; a kingless Zhou regency after King Li's exile; 841–828 BCE, its first year the earliest firmly dated in Chinese history</span></div>","traditional":"共和","hanzi":"共和","pinyin":"Gònghé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gònghé</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Gonghe Regency</b> was a strange interlude in Zhou history, fourteen years, from 841 to 828 BCE, in which the realm was governed with no king on the throne. It began when the tyrant King Li was driven into exile by an uprising of the capital's citizens; the land was left kingless not because the king had died but because he lived on, banished, at Zhi. For those years the government carried on without him, until at last King Li died and his son took the throne as King Xuan, who briefly won back some of Zhou's lost strength. The first year of the regency, 841 BCE, holds a special place, for it is the earliest year in all Chinese history that can be fixed to an exact date. From the Gonghe onward the historian Sima Qian could set down the years one by one, whereas every earlier date must be reconstructed and argued over, though much of that older past is otherwise well known. <br><br> What the very name Gonghe means, however, is itself disputed. The old <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> reads it as joint harmony, the shared rule of two ministers, the Dukes of Zhou and Shao — the holders of those titles then, not the famous founders of two centuries before. But the <i>Bamboo Annals</i>, and the recently unearthed Tsinghua slips, name instead a single regent, Gongbo He, He the Earl of Gong, a nobleman famed for his virtue. The buried texts have swung many scholars toward this one-man reading, yet the two-dukes account is still told, and the question stays open. Strangely, the modern word for a republic, gonghe, is drawn from this ancient kingless age, borrowed by nineteenth-century scholars to name a state without a monarch — though the Gonghe was no republic but an aristocratic regency that held the realm until its rightful line was restored.","citation":"","answerText":"Gonghe Regency"},
{"id":"cnh-163","num":"一百六十三","category":"China · History","question":"The eleventh king of the Zhou dynasty and son of the tyrant King Li, whose early reign revived the realm with victories over the Xianyun nomads, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw his restoration fade into defeat before his son King You lost the Western Zhou in 771 BCE.","answer":"King Xuan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周宣王 — Zhōu Xuān Wáng; personal name Ji Jing 姬靜; the 11th Zhou king, of the \"Xuan Restoration\"; r. c. 827–782 BCE (not the later King Xuan of Qi)</span></div>","traditional":"周宣王","hanzi":"周宣王","pinyin":"Zhōu Xuān Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Xuān Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Xuan</b> was the eleventh king of the Zhou dynasty, whose given name was Ji Jing, the son of the hated tyrant King Li. He came to the throne about 827 BCE, when the Gonghe regency that had ruled in his father's absence gave way; and, unlike the shadowy kings before him, his long reign falls within the age of firm dates. His early years are remembered as the Xuan Restoration, a revival of the royal house's power and prestige after his father's ruin, won with the help of able ministers and bold generals. His most famous wars drove back the Xianyun, fierce nomads of the northwest, under captains such as Yin Jifu, and were sung in the odes of the <i>Book of Songs</i> and cut into his bronzes. He fought on other frontiers too, against the Huaiyi and Xu in the southeast and the Rong in the west, and planted kinsmen as lords to guard the marches. <br><br> But the revival did not hold: late in his reign, about 789 BCE, the Jiang Rong crushed his host at the battle of Qianmu, and he lost the great Army of the South. Shaken, he sought to number the people of the north to raise new levies, though his minister Zhong Shanfu warned that it broke the ancient rites. His prestige sank further when he meddled by force in the succession of the state of Lu, angering the other lords. He died about 782 BCE, though a famous legend, told to prove that the dead return, says he was struck down by the ghost of Du Bo, a minister he had wrongly put to death. His son King You came after him, the last Western Zhou king, in whose reign the dynasty fell to the nomads in 771 BCE — so King Xuan's restoration proved but a last bright gleam before the dark.","citation":"","answerText":"King Xuan"},
{"id":"cnh-164","num":"一百六十四","category":"China · History","question":"Bearing the longest inscription of any ancient Chinese bronze, a royal charge appointing its owner Duke Mao to govern the failing late Western Zhou, the great cauldron called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is today a chief treasure of the National Palace Museum in Taipei.","answer":"Mao Gong ding","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">毛公鼎 — Máo Gōng dǐng; a late Western Zhou bronze ding cast for Duke Mao; its ~497-character charge is the longest of all bronze inscriptions; National Palace Museum, Taipei</span></div>","traditional":"毛公鼎","hanzi":"毛公鼎","pinyin":"Máo Gōng dǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Máo Gōng dǐng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Mao Gong ding</b> is a bronze ritual cauldron of the late Western Zhou, famous above all for the longest inscription found on any ancient Chinese bronze. Cast into its rounded belly, in some 32 lines, is a text of nearly five hundred characters, prized as a masterpiece of the old bronze script. It was made for a high minister called Duke Mao, whose title comes from his fief of Mao and has nothing to do with any famous Mao of later ages. The inscription is a royal charge: the Zhou king appoints Duke Mao to help rule the realm, recalls the Mandate won by Kings Wen and Wu, urges him to govern uprightly, and lists the gifts bestowed on him. Most scholars set the charge in the reign of King Xuan, late in the Western Zhou, and read it as a sign of that failing age, when a weakened king handed broad power to a lord. <br><br> The cauldron lay buried nearly three thousand years until it was dug up about 1843, in the Qishan country of Shaanxi, the old Zhou heartland. It passed through famous collectors, above all the scholar Chen Jieqi, who took careful rubbings of its text, and was hidden through the war years to keep it from the Japanese. In the upheavals that followed it was carried to Taiwan, where it now rests among the greatest treasures of the National Palace Museum in Taipei. It is reckoned one of the three greatest inscribed cauldrons of the Zhou, with the Da Yu ding, now in Beijing, and the Da Ke ding, in Shanghai — and of the three its inscription is by far the longest. So the vessel is prized twice over, as a jewel of ancient calligraphy and as a document of the late Zhou, whose long charge shows how the fading kings ruled through their great lords.","citation":"","answerText":"Mao Gong ding"},
{"id":"cnh-165","num":"一百六十五","category":"China · History","question":"Cast for Ke the royal steward and recording the king's grants of land to him, and long a pair with the Da Yu ding under the collector Pan Zuyin, the great bronze cauldron called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is today a treasure of the Shanghai Museum.","answer":"Da Ke ding","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">大克鼎 — Dà Kè dǐng; a large Western Zhou bronze ding cast for Ke the Grand Provisioner; ~290-character charge of royal land grants; mid-to-late Western Zhou; Shanghai Museum</span></div>","traditional":"大克鼎","hanzi":"大克鼎","pinyin":"Dà Kè dǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Kè dǐng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Da Ke ding</b> is one of the greatest Western Zhou bronzes, a huge ritual cauldron among the chief treasures of the Shanghai Museum. It was cast for a noble named Ke, who held the court office of Grand Provisioner, the royal steward who managed the king's household and carried his commands. It is among the largest of its age, near a metre tall and about two hundred kilograms, its deep belly girdled with a broad band of rippling grooves. Inside is an inscription of some 290 characters in two parts: the first praises Ke's grandfather, the worthy minister Shi Huafu, who served the Zhou well, the second sets down the charge the king gave to Ke. With that charge the king gave him robes and chariot fittings and, above all, tracts of land with the households that worked them, so scholars prize it as a rare record of how the Zhou kings granted land to their nobles. <br><br> The cauldron was cast in the middle years of the Western Zhou, most likely in the reign of King Xiao, though the exact date is debated. It was dug up in 1890 in Fufeng, in Shaanxi, in a hoard of bronzes all made for the same Ke, among them a set of smaller ding, the Xiao Ke ding. It came, with the Da Yu ding, to the collector Pan Zuyin, whose family hid the pair from the invading Japanese and at last gave them to the nation. Pan Dayu presented both to the Shanghai Museum about 1951, but in 1959 the Da Yu ding was sent to Beijing while the Da Ke ding stayed behind, so the long-paired cauldrons now rest in different cities. With the Da Yu ding and the Mao Gong ding it forms the three greatest inscribed cauldrons of the Zhou, prized alike as history, calligraphy, and the pride of Shanghai.","citation":"","answerText":"Da Ke ding"},
{"id":"cnh-166","num":"一百六十六","category":"China · History","question":"The oldest anthology of Chinese poetry and one of the Five Classics, its three hundred songs ranging from folk airs to temple hymns and revered by Confucius, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stands at the fountainhead of the Chinese poetic tradition.","answer":"Classic of Poetry","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">詩經 — Shī Jīng; also the <i>Book of Songs</i>; the oldest Chinese poetry anthology and a Confucian Five Classic; ~305 poems, c. 11th–7th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"詩經","hanzi":"诗经","pinyin":"Shī Jīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shī Jīng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The <i>Classic of Poetry</i></b>, also called the <i>Book of Songs</i>, is the oldest collection of poetry in China and one of the Confucian Five Classics. It gathers some three hundred poems, the work of many unknown hands from the early Western Zhou to the Spring and Autumn age, with no single author or date. The poems fall into three kinds: the Airs, folk songs of the regions; the Odes, the ceremonial songs of the court; and the Hymns, chants sung to the ancestors. The Airs, the largest and best-loved part, are earthy songs of love, labour, and complaint, which by tradition the king's officers gathered from the people to gauge the temper of the land. Most lines run to four characters, rich in rhyme and refrain, and the whole opens with the famous <i>Guanju</i>, whose ospreys calling by the river stand for a young man's longing for a bride. <br><br> Confucius loved the Poetry above all books, summing up its songs as thoughts without depravity, and warning that without it a man had nothing to say. Tradition even made him its editor, winnowing three thousand songs down to three hundred, but scholars doubt this, for he championed a collection already ancient rather than making it. As one of the Five Classics it was learned by heart by every scholar and quoted for two thousand years, and it lived on even through the Qin burning of the books. The version that came down is the Mao recension, named for its Han teachers, not any duke, whose old prefaces read even a plain love song as veiled praise or blame of a ruler, though later readers took the Airs simply as songs. It must not be confused with the later <i>Songs of Chu</i>, nor with its fellow classics the <i>Book of Documents</i> and the <i>Classic of Changes</i>, for it stands alone as the fountainhead of Chinese verse.","citation":"","answerText":"Classic of Poetry"},
{"id":"cnh-167","num":"一百六十七","category":"China · History","question":"The prose companion to the <i>Classic of Poetry</i> among the Five Classics, gathering the speeches and proclamations of the ancient kings and serving as the earliest source of the Mandate of Heaven, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> mixes genuinely ancient Zhou announcements with chapters a Qing scholar exposed as forgeries.","answer":"Book of Documents","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">尚書 — Shàngshū, also 書經 Shūjīng; the <i>Book of Documents</i>, or <i>Classic of History</i>; a Confucian Five Classic of ancient royal speeches and proclamations</span></div>","traditional":"尚書","hanzi":"尚书","pinyin":"Shàng Shū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shàng Shū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The <i>Book of Documents</i></b>, also called the <i>Classic of History</i>, is one of the Confucian Five Classics and the oldest collection of ancient Chinese prose. It is not poetry but a gathering of speeches, proclamations, oaths, counsels, and royal charges, the words of the kings and ministers of high antiquity, arranged in four books by dynasty: Yu, Xia, Shang, and Zhou. Its documents claim to reach from the sage-kings Yao and Shun, through Xia and Shang, down to the early Zhou, but the book is a patchwork of very different ages, its early-Zhou announcements genuinely ancient while the chapters on the oldest kings are far later idealizations. It is the great early source of the Mandate of Heaven, the doctrine the Zhou proclaimed to justify overthrowing the Shang, that Heaven grants rule to the virtuous and strips it from the wicked. It holds up the sage-kings as models of upright, people-loving government, and its oldest chapters are in prose so archaic it has daunted readers ever since. <br><br> Tradition made Confucius its editor, gathering and arranging the documents, but scholars doubt this, as they do the like claim for the Poetry. The text was scattered in the Qin burning of the books, and a New Text of some 28 chapters was saved by the aged scholar Fu Sheng, who had kept it by heart; these are its genuine ancient core. But the received book of 58 chapters mixed those with about 25 Old Text chapters that the Qing scholar Yan Ruoqu proved a later forgery, a celebrated feat of Chinese textual scholarship. For all that, it stayed a pillar of the canon, a fountainhead of Chinese political thought and a chief source for Sima Qian. It must not be confused with its sister classic the <i>Classic of Poetry</i>, whose name sounds so near its own: where the Poetry gathers songs, the Documents preserves the words of kings.","citation":"","answerText":"Book of Documents"},
{"id":"cnh-168","num":"一百六十八","category":"China · History","question":"Built from broken and unbroken lines stacked into 64 hexagrams and consulted by casting yarrow stalks, the ancient divination manual and Five Classic called the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became, through its later commentaries, China's great book of cosmic change.","answer":"I Ching","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">易經 — Yìjīng (<i>I Ching</i>); the <i>Classic of Changes</i>; ancient divination core the Zhou Yi 周易, Western Zhou; with the Ten Wings a Confucian Five Classic</span></div>","traditional":"易經","hanzi":"易经","pinyin":"Yì Jīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yì Jīng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The <i>I Ching</i></b>, or <i>Classic of Changes</i>, is one of the Five Classics of the Confucian canon and among the oldest of them, at root a manual of divination that grew into a book of cosmic wisdom. It is built from lines that are either broken or unbroken, gathered by threes into the eight trigrams and, in pairs, into the 64 six-line figures called hexagrams. Each hexagram carries a name, a short and cryptic judgment, and a separate saying for each of its six lines, terse oracle-verses open to endless reading. It was cast for divination: a diviner raised a hexagram by manipulating yarrow stalks, then read its words as counsel, and changing lines could turn one figure into another, whence its name of Changes. Its great theme is change itself, the ceaseless turning of all things through the interplay of yin and yang. <br><br> What lifted the oracle into a book of philosophy was a set of later commentaries, the <i>Ten Wings</i>, above all the <i>Great Commentary</i>, which read the hexagrams as a map of the cosmos and of the moral life. Tradition credits the whole to four sages: the mythical Fuxi, who drew the trigrams; King Wen, who arranged the hexagrams in his Shang prison; his son the Duke of Zhou, who wrote the line-sayings; and Confucius, who added the Wings. But scholars doubt this legend, holding that the divining core took shape in the Western Zhou, while the philosophical Wings were written centuries later, in the age of the Warring States. With those Wings it was raised under the Han into one of the Five Classics, revered ever since as a fathomless book of change. From it flow much of later Chinese cosmology, medicine, and feng shui, and it drew wonder even in the West, though the claim that it gave the world binary numbers goes too far.","citation":"","answerText":"I Ching"},
{"id":"cnh-169","num":"一百六十九","category":"China · History","question":"Not a book of ceremonies but an idealized blueprint of government organized into six ministries, wrongly ascribed to the Duke of Zhou and later the model for the empire's Six Boards, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the administrative classic among the Three Rites.","answer":"Rites of Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周禮 — Zhōulǐ; the <i>Rites of Zhou</i>, one of the Three Rites; an idealized blueprint of government in six ministries; late Warring States, wrongly ascribed to the Duke of Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"周禮","hanzi":"周礼","pinyin":"Zhōu Lǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Lǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The <i>Rites of Zhou</i></b> is one of the three ancient ritual classics of China, and the strangest, for it is not at all what its name suggests. Despite the word rites in its title, it is no book of ceremonies but an idealized blueprint of government, a vast catalogue of the offices of a perfect state and their duties. It arranges that state under six great ministries named for Heaven, Earth, and the four seasons, which oversee administration, education, rites, war, justice, and public works. The sixth section, on public works, was lost early and replaced by the <i>Kaogongji</i>, a treatise on crafts and technology that preserves the plan of the ideal walled capital, a square city with its palace at the heart. It must not be confused with its two sister classics, the <i>Yili</i>, a manual of actual ceremonies, and the <i>Book of Rites</i>, a collection of essays that is the Rites counted among the Five Classics. <br><br> Tradition ascribed the whole design to the Duke of Zhou, the great regent, as his plan for the government of the early dynasty. But scholars reject this, holding it a far later work of the Warring States age, and an idealized dream of perfect order rather than a record of how the Zhou was truly ruled. Yet no imagined system did more to shape the real Chinese state, for its six ministries became the model for the Six Boards that ran the empire for more than a thousand years. And because it passed as the sage Duke of Zhou's own design, ambitious reformers seized on it to justify sweeping change, among them the usurper Wang Mang and, long after, the Song statesman Wang Anshi. So this utopian book of offices, though it never described a government that truly existed, became one of the most consequential blueprints in all Chinese history.","citation":"","answerText":"Rites of Zhou"},
{"id":"cnh-170","num":"一百七十","category":"China · History","question":"The twelfth and last king of the Western Zhou, who set aside his queen and her son for the concubine Baosi and so drove the slighted Marquis of Shen to call in the Quanrong, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was slain when the nomads sacked his capital in 771 BCE.","answer":"King You","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周幽王 — Zhōu Yōu Wáng; \"You\" 幽 a censure name, \"the benighted\"; personal name Ji Gongsheng 姬宮湦; the 12th and last Western Zhou king; r. c. 781–771 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"周幽王","hanzi":"周幽王","pinyin":"Zhōu Yōu Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Yōu Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King You</b> was the twelfth and last king of the Western Zhou, whose given name was Ji Gongsheng, the son of King Xuan; his title You, \"the benighted,\" is a name of shame. In his folly he grew infatuated with a concubine named Baosi, and cast aside his queen and her son the crown prince to raise Baosi and her own son in their place. But the queen he had spurned was the daughter of the powerful Marquis of Shen, and in disinheriting her son he turned that great house into his enemy. The enraged marquis called in the Quanrong, the fierce nomads of the west, who fell upon the Zhou capital near modern Xian in 771 BCE. The city was stormed and King You was slain, by tradition at the foot of Mount Li, and so the Western Zhou came to its bloody end. <br><br> A famous later tale, doubted by historians, explains the disaster by the beacon fires: that to make the humourless Baosi laugh, the king would light the war-beacons in jest and watch the lords come rushing for nothing. When the real foe came and the beacons were lit in earnest, the lords ignored them as another prank; but this is legend, contradicted by buried records, and the true ruin lay in the broken succession. His death ended the Western Zhou, yet not the dynasty itself, for the deposed crown prince was set up as King Ping and led the court eastward to Luoyang. There opened the Eastern Zhou and the long age of the Spring and Autumn, when the kings dwindled into figureheads and the great lords truly ruled. So King You is remembered as the king who lost the west, though the blame heaped on Baosi, as on other famed beauties, is more a moralist's fable than the real cause.","citation":"","answerText":"King You"},
{"id":"cnh-171","num":"一百七十一","category":"China · History","question":"The favourite of King You given him by the little state whose name she bears, famed in legend for a dragon-born birth and a beauty that never smiled, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was blamed for the fall of the Western Zhou beside Mo Xi and Daji, though the ruin was truly the work of kings.","answer":"Bao Si","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">褒姒 — Bāo Sì; the Si-clan woman of the state of Bao, not a given name; favourite consort of King You of Zhou; her legend blamed for the 771 BCE fall of the Western Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"褒姒","hanzi":"褒姒","pinyin":"Bāo Sì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bāo Sì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Bao Si</b> was the favourite consort of King You, the last king of the Western Zhou, remembered above all as the beauty blamed for the dynasty's ruin. Her name is not really her own: Si was her ancient surname, Bao the little state that gave her to the king, and her true given name is lost. Legend gave her an eerie, ill-omened origin: far back in the Xia, two dragons had left their foam at the royal court, and it was sealed in a box for ages. When at last the box was opened, the foam became a black lizard that crept into the women's quarters, and a maid it touched later bore a fatherless child, cast out in fear and raised in Bao. This was Bao Si, who grew into a great beauty but, so the tale runs, almost never smiled. <br><br> Her most famous story, though only legend, is that to win her laughter King You lit the war-beacons in jest, so that when the real enemy came the lords ignored the alarm. In truth her rise brought disaster because the king cast out his queen and heir to set Bao Si and her son Bofu in their place, enraging the queen's father, the Marquis of Shen. The marquis called in the Quanrong, who sacked the capital in 771 BCE and killed the king, ending the Western Zhou; her own fate is unknown, whether she was taken, slain, or died by her own hand. Ever after she was named with Mo Xi of the Xia and Daji of the Shang as the beauties whose charms toppled dynasties, the third in a grim and famous set. But this is a moralist's slander, the old habit of blaming a woman for the follies of kings, for the Zhou fell to broken succession and rebellion, not to a lovely face.","citation":"","answerText":"Bao Si"},
{"id":"cnh-172","num":"一百七十二","category":"China · History","question":"A small Jiang-clan state and marriage-ally of the Zhou kings, whose western marquis, father-in-law to King You, called in the Quanrong to sack the capital in 771 BCE, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> also had a southern branch, planted in Nanyang and later swallowed by Chu.","answer":"Shen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">申 — Shēn; a Jiang-clan Zhou marquisate and marriage-ally of the royal house; a western Shen and a southern Shen in Nanyang; pivotal in the 771 BCE fall of the Western Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"申","hanzi":"申","pinyin":"Shēn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shēn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shen</b> was a small state of the Zhou world, remembered above all as the royal in-laws who brought down the Western Zhou. Its ruling house bore the Jiang surname, like the great state of Qi, and belonged not to the royal Ji clan but to a lineage that gave its daughters as queens to the Zhou kings, binding Shen to the throne by marriage, not blood. There were in truth two states of Shen, whose exact tie scholars still debate: a western Shen on the frontier, and a southern Shen in the Nanyang basin. The lord of the western Shen, the Marquis of Shen, was father-in-law to King You, the last Western Zhou king, father of his queen and grandfather of his heir. When King You cast out that queen and her son for the concubine Bao Si and her own child, the marquis rose in fury. <br><br> He joined with the Quanrong nomads and the little state of Zeng, and in 771 BCE stormed the Zhou capital and killed King You — a revolt led by the king's own kin, not a mere barbarian raid. This ended the Western Zhou, though not the dynasty, for the marquis's grandson was set up as King Ping and the court moved east to begin the Eastern Zhou. The other Shen, in the south, had been planted in Nanyang by King Xuan, who settled there his kinsman Shen Bo to guard the frontier where Chu was rising. That founding is sung in a famous ode of the <i>Classic of Poetry</i>, the <i>Song Gao</i>, praising Shen Bo and the charge the king laid on him. But in time Chu swallowed the southern Shen and made it one of its early counties, so both branches of this modest house passed away, the one famed for toppling a dynasty, the other for a poem.","citation":"","answerText":"Shen"},
{"id":"cnh-173","num":"一百七十三","category":"China · History","question":"A tribal people of the Rong on the Zhou's western frontier, called in by the Marquis of Shen to storm the capital and kill King You in 771 BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended the Western Zhou and left the Wei valley to be reconquered, in time, by Qin.","answer":"Quanrong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">People</span><span class=\"dt-v\">犬戎 — Quǎnróng, the \"Dog Rong\"; a tribal people of the western Rong; sacked the Zhou capital in 771 BCE, ending the Western Zhou</span></div>","traditional":"犬戎","hanzi":"犬戎","pinyin":"Quǎnróng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Quǎnróng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Quanrong</b>, the \"Dog Rong,\" were a tribal people of the far west, one of the many Rong peoples who dwelt beyond the western border of the Zhou. They were no kingdom and had no king, but a loose confederation of herding tribes roaming the marches beyond the Zhou heartland. An old legend in the <i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i> traced them to two white dogs, but this is myth, and their true origins and speech are lost. They were close kin to the western Xianyun, and later writers named them among the forebears of the Xiongnu, though that descent is far from certain. Through the whole Western Zhou they were a thorn in the west; King Mu marched against them but, the old critics said, won only four white wolves and four white deer and drove the distant tribes from his court. <br><br> Their most famous stroke came in 771 BCE, though not as lone invaders, for the Marquis of Shen, King You's slighted father-in-law, called them in, and with the little state of Zeng they stormed the Zhou capital and killed the king. That blow ended the Western Zhou, but not the dynasty, for the heir moved the court eastward and reigned on as the first king of the Eastern Zhou. The Quanrong were left masters of the ravaged western heartland, the rich Wei valley that the Zhou now abandoned for good. The task of winning that land back fell to the state of Qin, whose Duke Xiang had escorted the fleeing king and was rewarded with the Rong-held west, to take it if he could. Over the generations the men of Qin drove the Rong out and made the old Zhou homeland their own, so that from the ruin the Quanrong wrought there rose, in time, the power that would one day rule all China.","citation":"","answerText":"Quanrong"},
{"id":"cnh-174","num":"一百七十四","category":"China · History","question":"The deposed Western Zhou crown prince set on the throne after his father King You was killed, who in 770 BCE moved the capital east to Luoyang and so began the Eastern Zhou, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ruled as a figurehead whose exchange of hostages with Zheng laid bare the collapse of royal power.","answer":"King Ping","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">周平王 — Zhōu Píng Wáng; personal name Ji Yijiu 姬宜臼; the 13th Zhou king and first of the Eastern Zhou; r. c. 770–720 BCE (not King Ping of Chu)</span></div>","traditional":"周平王","hanzi":"周平王","pinyin":"Zhōu Píng Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Píng Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Ping</b>, whose given name was Ji Yijiu, was the thirteenth Zhou king and the first of the Eastern Zhou. He had been the crown prince of the Western Zhou, cast aside when King You favoured the concubine Bao Si and her son, and only after King You died in the sack of 771 BCE did the lords set him on the throne. His crown came from a dark source, for the revolt that killed his father was led by his grandfather, the Marquis of Shen, who had called in the Quanrong — a stain later ages did not forget. With the western capital in ruins and the Quanrong in the Wei valley, in 770 BCE King Ping moved the royal seat east to Luoyang, so the Western Zhou gave way to the Eastern Zhou and the Spring and Autumn age began. Even his title was disputed, for a rival, King Xie, was set up against him and reigned in parallel some twenty years before his backers prevailed. <br><br> From his reign the Zhou kings dwindled into figureheads, their domain shrunk to a small land about Luoyang while the great states grew mighty. So low had the throne fallen that King Ping and the lord of Zheng exchanged hostages as equals, the Son of Heaven sending his son to a vassal, a thing once unthinkable. He owed his throne to the lords who had escorted him east, and rewarded the duke of Qin who aided him with the old Zhou lands in the west, his to win from the Rong. He reigned some fifty years, and since his crown prince died before him, the throne passed to his grandson, King Huan. So King Ping is remembered as the hinge of the Zhou, the king who saved the dynasty by flight but left its rulers mere shadows over the warring lords.","citation":"","answerText":"King Ping"},
{"id":"cnh-175","num":"一百七十五","category":"China · History","question":"Raised to the first place among the lords of the Spring and Autumn age by the reforms of Guan Zhong, the enemy archer he had spared and made his chief minister, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led them to revere the Zhou king and repel the barbarians, yet died starved by the favourites his dying minister had warned against.","answer":"Duke Huan of Qi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">齊桓公 — Qí Huán Gōng; personal name Xiǎobái 小白; ruler of the state of Qi and first hegemon of the Spring and Autumn period; r. c. 685–643 BCE (not Duke Huan of Lu or of Zheng)</span></div>","traditional":"齊桓公","hanzi":"齊桓公","pinyin":"Qí Huán Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qí Huán Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Duke Huan of Qi</b>, whose given name was Xiaobai, ruled the eastern state of Qi and became the first great hegemon of the Spring and Autumn age, when the Zhou king was a figurehead and the strongest lord led the rest. He was no king but a duke, leading the other lords in the Zhou king's name. He won his throne in a race, for when his brother the ruling duke was murdered he and his half-brother Prince Jiu sped home from exile to seize the seat. Tradition tells that Jiu's man Guan Zhong shot an arrow that struck Xiaobai's belt-hook, and that he feigned death to reach Qi first. Once enthroned he spared Guan Zhong on his mentor Bao Shuya's urging, and made his would-be killer chief minister, whose reforms of law, revenue, and army raised Qi to the foremost state. <br><br> As hegemon his watchword was to revere the king and repel the barbarians, upholding the Zhou throne while rallying the Chinese states against the Rong and Di and the southern power of Chu. He gathered the lords in covenant many times, above all at Kuiqiu in 651 BCE, the height of his leadership, and turned back Chu at the Shaoling covenant of 656 BCE. He saved the northern states of Yan, Xing, and Wey from the nomads, so that Confucius, in the <i>Analects</i>, credited Guan Zhong with saving Chinese civilization, saying that but for him they would wear their hair unbound like barbarians. Yet his end was wretched, for by the moralizing tale he ignored the dying Guan Zhong's warning against three fawning favourites, who seized power at his death and set his sons fighting over the throne. By the traditional account they walled up the ailing duke and left him to starve, his body lying unburied for some 67 days, before Qi fell into civil war and lost the leadership that passed at last to Jin.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke Huan of Qi"},
{"id":"cnh-176","num":"一百七十六","category":"China · History","question":"A Ji-clan cadet branch of the royal house set in the Central Plain, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dominated the early Eastern Zhou before it was ground between Jin and Chu and annexed by Han in 375 BCE.","answer":"Zheng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鄭 — Zhèng; a Ji-clan Zhou state of the central plain; founded 806 BCE, capital Xinzheng; annexed by Han in 375 BCE (not Zheng He or Zhengzhou)</span></div>","traditional":"鄭","hanzi":"鄭","pinyin":"Zhèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhèng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zheng</b> was a state of the central plain, a cadet branch of the royal house that dominated the early Eastern Zhou before dwindling to a hard-pressed middle power. Its house bore the royal Ji surname, founded in 806 BCE when King Xuan of Zhou gave the fief to his younger brother, Duke Huan of Zheng. That founder, a minister at the royal court, foresaw the dynasty's fall and shifted his people east from the western capital toward the centre of the realm. Duke Huan died in 771 BCE in the sack that ended the Western Zhou, but his son Duke Wu completed the move, absorbing Guo and Kuai and fixing the capital at Xinzheng, the 'New Zheng.' Because its dukes were close royal kin, they served as chief ministers of the Eastern Zhou court, and Zheng was for a time its strongest support. <br><br> Under Duke Zhuang, who reigned from 743 to 701 BCE, Zheng reached its height, remembered as a 'minor hegemon' who mastered the lords before the formal hegemony of Qi arose. Relations with the throne soured until King Ping and Duke Zhuang traded sons as hostages around 720 BCE, a startling sign that the king now dealt with a vassal as an equal. When King Huan led a royal army against Zheng, Duke Zhuang broke it at the Battle of Xuge in 707 BCE, where a Zheng archer wounded the king with an arrow, yet the duke let him go unpursued. After Zhuang's death Zheng fell to quarrelling heirs, and wedged between the giants Jin and Chu it had to bend to whichever pressed harder, its great days gone. Its minister Zichan had the penal laws cast on bronze in 536 BCE, among the earliest public law codes in China, but in 375 BCE the state fell to Han, its name surviving in the seductive 'tunes of Zheng' that moralists deplored.","citation":"","answerText":"Zheng"},
{"id":"cnh-177","num":"一百七十七","category":"China · History","question":"The early strongman who let his usurping brother overreach and then crushed him, who swore to shun his scheming mother until the Yellow Springs, and whose archer wounded the Zhou king at Xuge in 707 BCE, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Zheng made his small state the 'minor hegemon' of the early Eastern Zhou.","answer":"Duke Zhuang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鄭莊公 — Zhèng Zhuāng Gōng; personal name Wùshēng 寤生; third ruler of the state of Zheng and the early Spring and Autumn \"minor hegemon\"; r. 743–701 BCE (not Duke Zhuang of Lu or Qi)</span></div>","traditional":"鄭莊公","hanzi":"鄭莊公","pinyin":"Zhèng Zhuāng Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhèng Zhuāng Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Duke Zhuang</b> of Zheng, given name Wusheng, was the third lord of Zheng, who raised that small state to mastery of the early Eastern Zhou. His fame rests above all on the opening story of the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i>, a tale of cold patience within his own family. His mother Wu Jiang, the story says, had loathed him since his troubled birth and doted on his younger brother, Gong Shu Duan, pressing the duke to grant him the great city of Jing. Duke Zhuang let Duan fortify and overreach, holding that a man heaping up wrong will destroy himself, and only when his brother rose in revolt did he strike, routing him in 722 BCE and driving him into exile. He then banished his scheming mother, swearing not to see her again until the Yellow Springs, but soon repented and had a tunnel dug to a spring where they met and were reconciled, his oath kept to the letter. <br><br> Like his father, Duke Zhuang served as a chief minister of the Zhou court, at once a mighty vassal and the throne's own officer. When King Ping grew wary of Zheng, the two exchanged sons as hostages around 720 BCE, a startling sign that the king now dealt with a vassal as an equal. Relations broke under King Huan, who marched to humble Zheng, only for Duke Zhuang to shatter his army at the Battle of Xuge in 707 BCE, where the archer Zhu Dan wounded the king with an arrow. Yet the duke forbade pursuit and sent an envoy that night to ask after the king's health, winning without seeming to defy his sovereign. For such strokes he is remembered as a 'minor hegemon,' an early master of the lords before the true hegemony of Qi, though after his death in 701 BCE a war among his sons tore Zheng apart, its brief greatness gone.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke Zhuang"},
{"id":"cnh-178","num":"一百七十八","category":"China · History","question":"Spared by his friend Bao Shuya after serving the losing prince, and honoured as 'Zhongfu' by the ruler he had once shot at, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> so remade the state of Qi that his master Duke Huan rose to be the first hegemon, though the great book of statecraft bearing his name was compiled long after his death in 645 BCE.","answer":"Guan Zhong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Life</span><span class=\"dt-v\">管仲 — Guǎn Zhòng; personal name Yiwu 夷吾; chief minister of Qi under Duke Huan and architect of the first hegemony; c. 720–645 BCE (a statesman, not the Guanzi book or Guan Yu)</span></div>","traditional":"管仲","hanzi":"管仲","pinyin":"Guǎn Zhòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guǎn Zhòng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guan Zhong</b>, whose given name was Yiwu, rose from humble beginnings to become the chief minister of Qi and the architect of the first hegemony of the Spring and Autumn age. His youth gave China its proverb for friendship, for his companion Bao Shuya forgave his every fault, knowing he took the larger share because he was poor and fled from battle because his mother needed him. When Qi fell into strife the two backed rival princes, Guan Zhong serving Prince Jiu against the future Duke Huan, and by tradition he even loosed an arrow that struck the prince's belt-hook. Facing execution after Jiu's death, Guan Zhong was saved by Bao Shuya, who begged Duke Huan to spare his old enemy and make him chief minister, then served beneath the friend he had rescued. Duke Huan honoured him as Zhongfu, a second father, and for some forty years let him remake the state. <br><br> His reforms knit civil rule to military service, so the households that farmed the land also filled the army, and he enriched Qi through trade, farming, and its coastal salt. So armed, Qi became the mightiest of states, and his statecraft let Duke Huan gather the lords as the first hegemon, guarding the Zhou king against the barbarians. Yet he was the minister, never the lord, and the fame of the ruler rested on the genius of his servant. The sprawling <i>Guanzi</i> was later fathered on his name, a work of statecraft and economics that made him a fountainhead of Chinese fiscal thought, though he wrote none of it and merely foreshadowed the later Legalists. Confucius both praised him — but for Guan Zhong, he said, the people would wear their hair unbound like barbarians — and faulted him as extravagant and heedless of ritual; he died in 645 BCE, and the favourites he had warned against soon undid his work.","citation":"","answerText":"Guan Zhong"},
{"id":"cnh-179","num":"一百七十九","category":"China · History","question":"Ruler of Shang-remnant Song who refused to strike the Chu army as it forded the river Hong in 638 BCE, and was routed and mortally wounded for his chivalry, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> left China the proverb of the 'benevolence of Song' for self-defeating mercy and a much-disputed place among the Five Hegemons.","answer":"Duke Xiang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">宋襄公 — Sòng Xiāng Gōng; personal name Zǐfǔ 茲甫; ruler of Shang-remnant Song and a contested \"hegemon\"; r. 650–637 BCE; died of the wound from the Battle of Hong (not the later Song dynasty)</span></div>","traditional":"宋襄公","hanzi":"宋襄公","pinyin":"Sòng Xiāng Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sòng Xiāng Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Duke Xiang</b> of Song, given name Zifu, ruled Song, the realm of the heirs of the fallen Shang, and is remembered as the noblest fool of the Spring and Autumn age. As heir he is said to have offered the throne to his elder half-brother Muyi, who refused and became his wisest counsellor, whose advice he would fatally ignore. When the first hegemon Duke Huan of Qi died in 643 BCE and Qi fell to civil war, Duke Xiang led a coalition that installed the heir as Duke Xiao of Qi. That success went to his head, and though Song was a middling state he dreamed of the hegemony himself, summoning the great lords to his lead. The mighty southern king of Chu had no such intention, and at a covenant in 639 BCE he treacherously seized Duke Xiang and held him prisoner before letting him go. <br><br> Undeterred, Duke Xiang attacked Zheng, an ally of Chu, and when Chu marched to its rescue the two hosts met at the river Hong in 638 BCE. As the larger Chu force struggled across the water, his brother Muyi begged him to strike while they were helpless, and again before they formed their ranks, but the duke refused. A gentleman, the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i> has him declare, does not wound a man twice nor seize the grey-haired nor drum the charge against an unformed foe — so he waited until Chu stood ready, and Song was shattered. Wounded in the thigh, Duke Xiang died of the hurt the next year, in 637 BCE, and his scruples passed into the proverb of the 'benevolence of Song,' a byword for self-defeating folly. Yet for all his mercy he had once had a captive lord sacrificed to the spirits, so later ages recall him as either a preening fool or the last knight of a dying code of honour.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke Xiang"},
{"id":"cnh-180","num":"一百八十","category":"China · History","question":"Home from nineteen years of exile to seize Jin in old age, keeper of his vow to fall back ninety li at the Battle of Chengpu in 632 BCE where he broke Chu, and named leader of the lords by the grateful Zhou king, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Jin was the second and undisputed hegemon of the Spring and Autumn age.","answer":"Duke Wen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">晉文公 — Jìn Wén Gōng; personal name Chóng'ěr 重耳; ruler of Jin and the second of the Five Hegemons; r. 636–628 BCE (not King Wen of Zhou)</span></div>","traditional":"晉文公","hanzi":"晉文公","pinyin":"Jìn Wén Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jìn Wén Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Duke Wen</b> of Jin, whose given name was Chong'er, became the second of the great hegemons of the Spring and Autumn age, winning his crown only after a lifetime of exile. A son of Duke Xian of Jin, he was driven abroad when the concubine Li Ji destroyed the crown prince to raise her own son, and fled with a band of faithful followers. For some nineteen years he wandered from state to state — through the Di, Qi, Cao, Song, Zheng, Chu, and Qin — aging from a fugitive prince into a grey old man. In Chu, feasted by King Cheng, he vowed that should their armies ever meet, he would retreat three stages, a withdrawal of ninety li, in thanks for the welcome. At last Duke Mu of Qin lent him an army, and in 636 BCE Chong'er seized the throne of Jin, an old man of about 62. <br><br> As duke he first restored King Xiang of Zhou, driven from his capital by a rebel brother, a revere-the-king stroke that cloaked his ambition in loyalty. Then he faced Chu at Chengpu in 632 BCE, kept his vow and fell back ninety li before turning to shatter the Chu host, checking its drive northward; the beaten Chu general fell on his sword. The Zhou king himself came to his covenant at Jiantu and named him leader of the lords, the acknowledged hegemon, though the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i> blushed to show a king summoned by a vassal. Legend tells that his follower Jie Zhitui once fed the starving Chong'er with flesh from his own thigh, was later passed over, and burned to death on a mountain the duke set alight — a grief the Cold Food festival is said to mourn. He died in 628 BCE after a reign of but nine years, yet Jin ruled the northern world for more than a century after him.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke Wen"},
{"id":"cnh-181","num":"一百八十一","category":"China · History","question":"Fought in 632 BCE, the first great trial of strength between Jin and Chu — in which Duke Wen kept his exile vow to fall back ninety li, then routed the Chu wings with tiger-skinned horses and a feigned flight — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> broke Chu's northward drive and confirmed Duke Wen of Jin as hegemon.","answer":"Battle of Chengpu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Battle</span><span class=\"dt-v\">城濮之戰 — Chéngpú zhī zhàn; the decisive Jin victory over Chu that sealed Duke Wen's hegemony; 632 BCE (not the Battle of Bi, 597 BCE, which Chu won)</span></div>","traditional":"城濮之戰","hanzi":"城濮之戰","pinyin":"Chéngpú zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chéngpú zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Battle of Chengpu</b>, fought in 632 BCE in the central plain, was the first great clash between the northern states under Jin and the rising southern power of Chu, and the victory that made Duke Wen of Jin the second hegemon. Chu had pushed north for years, and when it besieged Song, an ally of Jin, Duke Wen resolved to help, but by an indirect stroke. Rather than march straight to Song, Jin fell upon Chu's northern allies Cao and Wey, forcing Chu to lift the siege and come north to fight. To its side Jin drew the great states of Qi, Qin, and Song, while Chu marched with its allies Chen, Cai, and others. Before battle Duke Wen drew his army back ninety li, keeping a promise he had made as an exile and guest of King Cheng of Chu — at once an act of honour and a lure. <br><br> The Jin strategist Xian Zhen refused to strike the strong Chu centre, and aimed instead at the weaker wings made of Chu's allies. By the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i>'s account, Jin draped its chariot horses in tiger skins to panic the Chu right, and on the left feigned flight, dragging brushwood to raise a dust-cloud before wheeling to crush the pursuers. Both wings shattered, the Chu centre pulled back in time, and Ziyu, the proud Chu commander who had forced the battle against his king's caution, fell on his sword in disgrace as he retreated. Weeks later Duke Wen gathered the lords at Jiantu, where the Zhou king confirmed him as leader of the lords, the acknowledged hegemon, though still only a duke. Fought largely by strategy and deception rather than brute force, Chengpu checked Chu's advance for a generation and opened a century of Jin-Chu rivalry, in which Chu would take its revenge at the Battle of Bi in 597 BCE.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Chengpu"},
{"id":"cnh-182","num":"一百八十二","category":"China · History","question":"Ruler of western Qin who bought the worthy Baili Xi for five ram-skins, was crushed by Jin at the Battle of Xiao yet turned west to become hegemon of the Rong, and was followed into the grave by 177 victims, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Qin counts in some lists among the Five Hegemons.","answer":"Duke Mu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">秦穆公 — Qín Mù Gōng; personal name Yíng Rènhǎo 嬴任好; ruler of Qin and hegemon of the Western Rong; r. 659–621 BCE (not King Mu of Zhou)</span></div>","traditional":"秦穆公","hanzi":"秦穆公","pinyin":"Qín Mù Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qín Mù Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Duke Mu</b> of Qin, given name Renhao, raised the western frontier state of Qin to power, and though he never held the central plains he is counted by some among the Five Hegemons. His gift was for talent, prizing able men whatever their birth: he won Baili Xi, a captive in servitude, by ransoming him for five ram-skins, a price so low it masked his worth. This 'five ram-skins minister' and his friend Jian Shu, whom he raised up, made Qin strong, and Duke Mu also won the wise Youyu from the Rong. He bound Qin to Jin by marriage, until 'the good of Qin and Jin' became a byword for a wedding alliance, and meddled repeatedly in the Jin succession. He set the treacherous Duke Hui on the Jin throne, crushed and captured him at the Battle of Han in 645 BCE, and later raised the exile Chong'er to be the great Duke Wen. <br><br> When Duke Wen died, Duke Mu reached east for the central plains, sending an army against Zheng though old Jian Shu wept it would never return. He was right: at the Battle of Xiao in 627 BCE the men of Jin ambushed the homeward Qin army in the passes and destroyed it utterly, taking his three generals captive. Barred from the east by Jin, Duke Mu turned west instead, subduing the Rong until he was hailed hegemon of the Western Rong, said to have swallowed a dozen states and opened a thousand li. He died in 621 BCE, and by the grim custom of his house 177 people followed him into the grave, among them three worthy brothers of the Ziche clan. The men of Qin mourned those three in the ode <i>Yellow Bird</i> of the <i>Classic of Poetry</i>, and though Duke Mu had built up his state, Qin's true greatness lay four centuries off, in reforms he never dreamed.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke Mu"},
{"id":"cnh-183","num":"一百八十三","category":"China · History","question":"The self-styled king who woke from three idle years to 'astonish all,' dared ask the weight of the Zhou's sacred cauldrons in 606 BCE, and crushed Jin at Bi to avenge Chengpu, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Chu raised the southern power to its height as one of the Five Hegemons.","answer":"King Zhuang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">楚莊王 — Chǔ Zhuāng Wáng; personal name Xióng Lǚ 熊侶; king of southern Chu and one of the Five Hegemons; r. 613–591 BCE (a self-styled king, not Duke Zhuang of Zheng)</span></div>","traditional":"楚莊王","hanzi":"楚莊王","pinyin":"Chǔ Zhuāng Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chǔ Zhuāng Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Zhuang</b> of Chu, given name Xiong Lü, ruled the great southern state of Chu, raising it to its height as one of the Five Hegemons. Chu was the mighty power of the south, half-barbarian in northern eyes, whose rulers styled themselves kings in defiance of the Zhou throne. For his first three years, the tale runs, he seemed an idle wastrel, until a minister's riddle of a bird that neither flew nor sang drew the vow that once it flew it would soar to heaven, and once it sang, astonish all. So he woke, cut down the corrupt and raised the worthy, and in 606 BCE marched his army to the Zhou border and dared ask the weight of the nine sacred cauldrons of the Mandate. The envoy Wangsun Man rebuffed him — the Mandate lay in virtue, not in cauldrons — and King Zhuang withdrew, though 'to ask the cauldrons' became a byword for coveting the throne. <br><br> His triumph came at the Battle of Bi in 597 BCE, where Chu crushed the army of Jin and reversed the old defeat at Chengpu, making him master of the age. Refusing to pile the enemy dead into a victory-monument, he taught, the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i> records, that the word for the martial joins 'stop' and 'spear,' so true valour lies in ending violence, not slaughter. He was remembered for mercy too — sparing the drunken officer who seized his consort in the dark — though his long siege of Song starved its people until, it was said, they traded their children to eat. King Zhuang died in 591 BCE at the summit of Chu's power, and is counted the most admired of the hegemons. Yet mighty as he was, he never seized the cauldrons nor unseated the Zhou king, who stayed nominal Son of Heaven over a world the southern king could dominate but never replace.","citation":"","answerText":"King Zhuang"},
{"id":"cnh-184","num":"一百八十四","category":"China · History","question":"The terse Confucian classic chronicling the state of Lu from 722 to 481 BCE, whose every clipped word was thought to hide Confucius's praise or blame and which gave a whole era its name, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> survives chiefly through its three commentaries, the narrative Zuo Zhuan foremost among them.","answer":"Spring and Autumn Annals","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">春秋 — Chūnqiū; the year-by-year court chronicle of the state of Lu, one of the Five Classics; covers 722–481 BCE (the book, not the Spring and Autumn period it named, nor its Zuo Zhuan commentary)</span></div>","traditional":"春秋","hanzi":"春秋","pinyin":"Chūnqiū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chūnqiū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Spring and Autumn Annals</b> is the terse court chronicle of the state of Lu, one of the Five Classics of the Confucian canon, and the book that gives the whole Spring and Autumn period its name. Year by year it records the doings of the age under the twelve dukes of Lu, from 722 to 481 BCE, though it notes events across the many states. Its name, 'spring and autumn,' sets down two seasons to stand for the whole turning year, and in time came to mean simply a chronicle or a book of annals. The book is a marvel of brevity: bare, formulaic one-line entries, a date and a bald fact, the whole running to under twenty thousand characters, with no story or speech. So spare is it that it can scarcely be read alone, and its very terseness became its fame. <br><br> Tradition credits its making to Confucius, who is said to have edited the Lu records so that, in Mencius's words, rebellious ministers and unfilial sons trembled — though scholars now doubt his hand in it. For the tradition held that into his bare wording he wove praise and blame, subtle words carrying great meaning, so that the very verb chosen for a killing could brand a ruler's death as foul regicide. This art of the veiled verdict, praise and blame hidden in a phrase, made the little chronicle the model of moral history for all the ages that followed. Because its entries are so cryptic, three commentaries grew up to explain them and supply the missing story — the great narrative <i>Zuo Zhuan</i> chief among them, beside the terse <i>Gongyang</i> and <i>Guliang</i>. By legend the record breaks off where Confucius laid down his brush, at the capture of a qilin, a sacred unicorn caught and killed out of its proper time, an ill omen for a failing age, in 481 BCE.","citation":"","answerText":"Spring and Autumn Annals"},
{"id":"cnh-185","num":"一百八十五","category":"China · History","question":"The oldest and richest of the three commentaries on the terse Spring and Autumn Annals, an independent narrative history matched line by line to that bare chronicle, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fills it with vivid tales of war, ritual, and intrigue and is our chief source for the whole Spring and Autumn age.","answer":"Zuo Zhuan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">左傳 — Zuǒ Zhuàn; the great narrative commentary on the Spring and Autumn Annals and chief source for the period; covers c. 722–468 BCE (traditionally by Zuo Qiuming; not the Annals itself or the Guoyu)</span></div>","traditional":"左傳","hanzi":"左傳","pinyin":"Zuǒ Zhuàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zuǒ Zhuàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Zuo Zhuan</b>, the 'Tradition of Zuo,' is the oldest and greatest of the three commentaries on the <i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i>, and one of the earliest works of narrative history in China. Where the Annals gives only bare, clipped entries, the Zuo Zhuan swells them into full and vivid stories, recounting the battles, embassies, court plots, and speeches behind each terse line. It follows the twelve dukes of Lu across roughly 722 to 468 BCE, running a few years past the Annals' close in 481, and so covers the whole Spring and Autumn age. For that age it is the single most important source, and nearly all we know of the hegemons, the great battles, and the scheming ministers comes down to us through it. In time it was honoured as a classic in its own right, one of the Thirteen Classics of the Confucian canon. <br><br> Tradition ascribes it to Zuo Qiuming, a blind historian of Lu said to be a contemporary of Confucius, though scholars now doubt this and place its making in the 4th century BCE, long after the events it tells. Handed down as a commentary on the Annals, it is really an independent history that was only later matched, line by line, to the terse chronicle. Its pages are thick with war and ritual, omens and prophecies that come true, and grave speeches, and it pauses to pass moral verdicts in the voice of 'the gentleman,' upholding the old Zhou order of propriety. As a masterpiece of terse, powerful prose — above all its battle narratives — it shaped all later Chinese history-writing, not least Sima Qian's <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>. It is a wellspring of the language itself, the source of many a proverb still spoken, and stands apart from the <i>Guoyu</i>, a separate work its supposed author is also said to have penned.","citation":"","answerText":"Zuo Zhuan"},
{"id":"cnh-186","num":"一百八十六","category":"China · History","question":"A short, unsystematic book of 'The Master said' sayings, compiled by his disciples after his death to preserve Confucius's teaching of benevolence, ritual, and the gentleman's virtue, and ranked first of the Four Books, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the backbone of Chinese learning for two millennia.","answer":"Analects","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">論語 — Lúnyǔ; the collected sayings of Confucius and his disciples, central text of Confucianism and one of the Four Books; compiled after Confucius's death (d. 479 BCE), grown into the Warring States (the book, not Confucius the man)</span></div>","traditional":"論語","hanzi":"論語","pinyin":"Lúnyǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lúnyǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Analects</b> is the collected sayings of Confucius, who lived from 551 to 479 BCE, and of his disciples — the central record of the Master's teaching. Confucius wrote none of it himself; his disciples and their followers gathered his remembered words after his death, over generations reaching into the Warring States that followed. Its Chinese title means 'ordered' or 'edited sayings,' and 'Analects,' the Western title, is a Greek word for 'things gathered up,' both alike meaning collected sayings. It is some twenty short books of loosely strung passages, many opening 'The Master said,' aphorisms and brief exchanges rather than any systematic argument. So it is a mosaic of fragments — questions answered, maxims let fall in passing — from which the whole vast edifice of Confucian thought was later drawn. <br><br> Its heart is <i>ren</i>, humane goodness, the supreme virtue, joined to <i>li</i>, the rites and proper conduct that order society. It holds up the <i>junzi</i>, the 'gentleman,' as its moral ideal — a person ennobled by character rather than by birth — and roots all virtue in filial piety, the reverence owed to parents, and a lifelong love of learning. It teaches rule by moral example rather than harsh law, the 'rectification of names' so that each man lives up to the duties of his role, and the golden maxim not to do to others what one would not have done to oneself. Long after, the Song master Zhu Xi ranked it first among the Four Books — beside the <i>Mencius</i>, the <i>Great Learning</i>, and the <i>Doctrine of the Mean</i> — a canon distinct from the older Five Classics. With his commentary it became the core of Chinese education and the civil-service examinations until 1905, and it stands among the most influential books of China and the wider East Asian world for more than two thousand years.","citation":"","answerText":"Analects"},
{"id":"cnh-187","num":"一百八十七","category":"China · History","question":"The semi-legendary 'Old Master' who by tradition rode west on an ox and wrote the five-thousand-character Dao De Jing at a frontier pass before vanishing, teacher of the ineffable Way and of effortless wu wei action, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is revered as the founder of Daoism.","answer":"Laozi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Sage</span><span class=\"dt-v\">老子 — Lǎozǐ, \"the Old Master\"; the semi-legendary founder of Daoism and traditional author of the Dao De Jing; placed by tradition in the 6th century BCE (the sage, not the Dao De Jing text or the god Taishang Laojun)</span></div>","traditional":"老子","hanzi":"老子","pinyin":"Lǎozǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǎozǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Laozi</b>, 'the Old Master,' is the semi-legendary founder of Daoism and the sage to whom tradition credits the <i>Dao De Jing</i>, the fountainhead of Daoist thought. By tradition he was Li Er, also called Lao Dan, a man of Chu who kept the royal archives of the Zhou. Tradition sets him in the 6th century BCE, an older contemporary of Confucius, who is said to have sought him out about the rites and gone away likening him to a dragon. His most famous legend has him ride west on an ox and, at the Hangu Pass, at the gatekeeper Yin Xi's plea, write the five-thousand-character book before vanishing. Yet scholars doubt he was ever one real man — even Sima Qian's ancient biography wavers among several candidates — and the Daoist classic itself was likely pieced together by many hands centuries later. <br><br> His teaching centres on the Dao, the Way — the nameless, ineffable source and flow of all things, for as the classic opens, the Dao that can be spoken is not the eternal Dao. The wise live in accord with it through <i>wu wei</i> — not idle inaction but effortless, unforced action, so that, as he says, one does nothing and yet leaves nothing undone. He prized naturalness and simplicity, the plainness of the uncarved block, and the strange strength of the soft, teaching that yielding water in time wears away the hardest stone. In government he wished the sage to rule by the same light hand, with few laws and little meddling, governing a great realm, he said, as one cooks a small fish. So Laozi became the founder of the Daoist school, one of the great currents of Chinese thought, later taken up by the sage Zhuangzi; and in time religion made him a god, Taishang Laojun, one of the Three Pure Ones.","citation":"","answerText":"Laozi"},
{"id":"cnh-188","num":"一百八十八","category":"China · History","question":"Traditionally ascribed to Laozi but really a Warring States work of many hands, this classic of some five thousand characters and 81 paradoxical chapters expounds the ineffable Dao and effortless wu wei, and the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stands with the Zhuangzi as a founding scripture of Daoism.","answer":"Tao Te Ching","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">道德經 — Dàodéjīng (Tao Te Ching); the \"Classic of the Way and its Power,\" foundational scripture of Daoism, traditionally by Laozi; a Warring States composite, ~5,000 characters in 81 chapters (not the I Ching or the Zhuangzi)</span></div>","traditional":"道德經","hanzi":"道德經","pinyin":"Dàodéjīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàodéjīng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tao Te Ching</b>, the 'Classic of the Way and its Power,' is the short but fathomless foundational text of Daoism and one of the most treasured works of all Chinese thought. Its title is also written Daodejing in pinyin, and the book is often called simply the <i>Laozi</i>, after its traditional author. Tradition credits it to the sage Laozi, but scholars hold the received text a layered work of many hands, gathered over the Warring States, well after his supposed 6th-century age. It runs to some five thousand characters in 81 short chapters, in two parts — the Dao, on the Way, being chapters 1 to 37, and the De, on its inner power, chapters 38 to 81. Its style is terse, rhymed, and deliberately paradoxical philosophical poetry — not a treatise but a web of aphorisms — so cryptic that it has borne countless conflicting readings. <br><br> Its oldest witness, the Guodian bamboo slips of about 300 BCE, holds only a third of the text; the near-complete Mawangdui silks of 168 BCE reverse the halves, setting the De before the Dao. Its heart is the Dao, the nameless Way beyond all words and prior to heaven and earth, for as it opens, the Dao that can be spoken is not the eternal Dao. It counsels <i>wu wei</i>, effortless action that never forces, a return to naturalness and few desires, and the quiet strength of the soft — like water, yielding and low, yet wearing away the hardest stone. It bids the sage-ruler govern with the lightest hand, few laws and little meddling, and has given the world such sayings as that a journey of a thousand li begins with a single step. Together with the <i>Zhuangzi</i> it became the bedrock of Daoism, philosophy and religion alike, and, endlessly rendered anew, it stands today among the most translated books on earth.","citation":"","answerText":"Tao Te Ching"},
{"id":"cnh-189","num":"一百八十九","category":"China · History","question":"The semi-legendary strategist said to have served King Helü of Wu and to have drilled the palace women by beheading two disobedient royal concubines, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is traditionally credited with the thirteen-chapter Art of War, foremost of the Seven Military Classics.","answer":"Sun Tzu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Strategist</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孫子 — Sūnzǐ, \"Master Sun\"; personal name Sun Wu 孫武; the strategist traditionally credited with The Art of War; a general of the late Spring and Autumn period who by tradition served King Helü of Wu (not the later strategist Sun Bin)</span></div>","traditional":"孫子","hanzi":"孫子","pinyin":"Sūnzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūnzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sun Tzu</b>, 'Master Sun,' personal name Sun Wu, is the ancient strategist traditionally credited with writing <i>The Art of War</i>, the most famous of all treatises on war. Tradition places him in the late Spring and Autumn period, a general in the service of King Helü of the southern state of Wu, whose armies he is said to have led against the great power of Chu. His fame rests on Sima Qian's account, set down some four centuries later, whose most celebrated tale is the drilling of the palace women. Asked to prove his art, he formed 180 court ladies into ranks and made the king's two favourite concubines their captains. When they only laughed and would not obey, he had the two beheaded despite the king's plea — a general in the field, he said, need not heed even his lord — and the rest then drilled in silent order. <br><br> Yet whether Sun Wu ever truly lived is doubted, for the great chronicle of the age, the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i>, never names him, and many judge his book a later work of the Warring States. He must not be confused with Sun Bin, a separate strategist of Qi generations later — traditionally his own descendant — who wrote a second and distinct art of war. Their long conflation was undone in 1972, when a Han tomb at Yinqueshan yielded both treatises side by side, proving two distinct works. <i>The Art of War</i>, in thirteen terse chapters, teaches that all warfare is deception, that the highest skill is to subdue the enemy without fighting, and that one who knows both himself and his foe may fight a hundred battles without peril. Foremost of China's Seven Military Classics, it has been pored over for more than two thousand years and carried far beyond the battlefield into politics, business, law, and sport.","citation":"","answerText":"Sun Tzu"},
{"id":"cnh-190","num":"一百九十","category":"China · History","question":"Traditionally ascribed to Sun Tzu but likely a Warring States work, this terse thirteen-chapter treatise teaching that all war is deception and that the supreme skill is to subdue the enemy without fighting, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the foremost of China's Seven Military Classics.","answer":"The Art of War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孫子兵法 — Sūnzǐ Bīngfǎ, \"Master Sun's Military Methods\"; the classic military treatise traditionally by Sun Tzu; ~6,000 characters in 13 chapters; foremost of the Seven Military Classics (a work of strategy, not the I Ching or Tao Te Ching)</span></div>","traditional":"孫子兵法","hanzi":"孫子兵法","pinyin":"Sūnzǐ Bīngfǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūnzǐ Bīngfǎ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>The Art of War</b>, whose Chinese title means 'Master Sun's Military Methods,' is among the most celebrated of all treatises on strategy and the conduct of war. Tradition ascribes it to the strategist Sun Tzu, but scholars often date the received text to the Warring States, later than his supposed age, and take it for the work of more than one hand. It is a short work of about six thousand characters in 13 chapters, each treating a facet of war — the laying of plans, deception, maneuver, terrain, the use of fire, and the use of spies. Its oldest surviving copy was unearthed in 1972 from a Han tomb at Yinqueshan, beside the separate <i>Sun Bin's Art of War</i>, whose co-discovery proved the two 'Master Sun' treatises to be distinct works. Terse and endlessly quotable, it is a soldier's manual that rises to a philosophy of conflict. <br><br> It opens by calling war a matter of vital importance to the state, to be weighed by five factors — the Way, Heaven, Earth, the commander, and method — before ever a sword is drawn. Its watchword is that all warfare is based on deception, and its highest wisdom that the greatest general subdues the enemy without fighting at all. Better to foil the enemy's plans, it teaches, than his alliances, better his alliances than his army, and worst of all to besiege his walled cities. One who knows both himself and his foe, it promises, is never in danger, and victory falls to planning, position, and foreknowledge — bought by spies — rather than brute force, for prolonged war ruins even the victor. Foremost of China's Seven Military Classics, it spread across East Asia and reached Europe through Amiot's French of 1772 and Giles's English of 1910, and is studied still in war colleges and borrowed by business, politics, and sport.","citation":"","answerText":"The Art of War"},
{"id":"cnh-191","num":"一百九十一","category":"China · History","question":"The lower-Yangtze kingdom that under King Helü crushed Chu and seized its capital in 506 BCE, only to be destroyed by its southern rival Yue in 473 BCE when King Fuchai fell to the vengeful Goujian, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rose and fell within a few decades.","answer":"Wu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">吳 — Wú; a Ji-clan southern kingdom of the lower Yangtze (capital Suzhou), a great power under Kings Helü and Fuchai; destroyed by Yue in 473 BCE (not King Wu 武王 of Zhou, nor the later Three Kingdoms Wu)</span></div>","traditional":"吳","hanzi":"吳","pinyin":"Wú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu</b> was a southern state of the lower Yangtze delta, centred on modern Suzhou, which the northern Zhou states held half-barbarian — its people cut their hair and tattooed their skin — and whose rulers styled themselves kings. By tradition its royal house was of the Ji clan, founded by Taibo, an uncle of the future King Wen of Zhou, who yielded his claim to the throne and went south, a yielding Confucius praised in the <i>Analects</i>. Long an obscure frontier land, Wu rose only in the late 6th century BCE, cultivated by the northern state of Jin as an eastern ally to press their common foe Chu from behind. It reached great power under King Helü, whose court drew the Chu exile Wu Zixu — bent on avenging his family, slain by the Chu king — and, by tradition, the strategist Sun Tzu. In 506 BCE Wu shattered the mighty state of Chu at the Battle of Boju and seized its capital Ying, coming closer than any to destroying Chu — the summit of its brief greatness. <br><br> To the south lay its bitter rival Yue, in war with whom King Helü was mortally wounded and died in 496 BCE. His son King Fuchai avenged him, crushing Yue and its king Goujian around 494 BCE, but spared him against Wu Zixu's warning to make an end of him. Goujian, forced to submit, nursed his revenge — the endurance the Chinese remember as 'sleeping on brushwood and tasting gall' — while he secretly rebuilt the strength of Yue. Fuchai meanwhile grew proud, exhausting Wu in northern bids for hegemony, and forced the loyal Wu Zixu, who had foreseen the danger, to take his own life. Then a resurgent Yue fell upon Wu and destroyed it in 473 BCE — Fuchai killed himself, and the state was swallowed by the rival it had once brought low.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu"},
{"id":"cnh-192","num":"一百九十二","category":"China · History","question":"The usurper who seized the throne of Wu by having an assassin stab his cousin at a banquet, then made the state supreme by capturing the Chu capital Ying in 506 BCE with Wu Zixu and Sun Tzu, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> died of a wound fighting Yue in 496 BCE, charging his son Fuchai to avenge him.","answer":"King Helü","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">吳王闔閭 — Wúwáng Hélǘ; personal name Guāng 光; king of Wu who took Chu's capital in 506 BCE and died fighting Yue in 496 BCE; r. 514–496 BCE (a king of the state Wu 吳, not King Wu 武王 of Zhou; father of Fuchai)</span></div>","traditional":"闔閭","hanzi":"闔閭","pinyin":"Hélǘ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hélǘ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Helü</b> of Wu, whose personal name was Guang, was the usurper-king who raised the southern state of Wu from obscurity to its brief greatness. As Prince Guang he believed the throne of Wu was rightly his, and bitterly resented his cousin King Liao, who held it in his place. On the counsel of the Chu exile Wu Zixu, he sent the brave assassin Zhuan Zhu to a banquet, who by tradition drew a dagger hidden in a served roasted fish and stabbed King Liao dead before the guards cut him down. With his cousin slain in 515 BCE, Prince Guang seized the vacant crown the next year and reigned as King Helü. He forged Wu into a mighty military power, served above all by the Chu exile Wu Zixu, and, by tradition, by the strategist Sun Tzu, author of <i>The Art of War</i>. <br><br> In 506 BCE his armies broke the great state of Chu at the Battle of Boju and captured its very capital, Ying, driving out the Chu king — the height of Wu's power. Yet Chu was not destroyed: it was saved by the timely aid of Qin and by the revolt of Helü's own younger brother back home, which together forced the Wu army to abandon its conquest and withdraw. A decade later he turned on the neighbouring southern rival Yue, whose young king Goujian had just risen, but was beaten at the Battle of Zuili and died in 496 BCE of a wound taken in the fighting. As he lay dying of the wound, he charged his son and heir, King Fuchai, to avenge him upon Yue and never to forget the debt. Fuchai did crush Yue in his turn, yet a generation later, in 473 BCE, a resurgent Yue under Goujian destroyed Wu outright — long after Helü's own end.","citation":"","answerText":"King Helü"},
{"id":"cnh-193","num":"一百九十三","category":"China · History","question":"The last king of Wu, who avenged his father Helü by crushing Yue in 494 BCE but then spared its king Goujian against Wu Zixu's counsel, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> overreached for northern glory and was destroyed by that same Goujian in 473 BCE, taking his own life.","answer":"King Fuchai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">吳王夫差 — Wúwáng Fūchāi; son of King Helü and the last king of Wu; spared Goujian in 494 BCE, destroyed by Yue in 473 BCE; r. 495–473 BCE (a king of the state Wu 吳, not King Wu 武王 of Zhou)</span></div>","traditional":"夫差","hanzi":"夫差","pinyin":"Fūchāi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fūchāi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Fuchai</b> of Wu, the son of Helü, was the last king of the southern state of Wu, and his reign is the great cautionary tale of the age. Helü, dying of a wound from Yue, had charged him with revenge, and the <i>Zuo Zhuan</i> tells how Fuchai kept a servant to cry to him daily, 'Have you forgotten that Yue killed your father?' In 494 BCE he made good the vow, crushing Yue and its young king Goujian at the Battle of Fujiao and penning him with a broken remnant on Mount Kuaiji. Yet when Goujian sued for submission, Fuchai spared him — deaf to his minister Wu Zixu, who begged him to destroy Yue, and swayed instead by the bribed courtier Bo Pi. Goujian bent the knee and, by tradition, served for a time as a lowly menial at the Wu court before Fuchai let him go home to nurse his revenge in secret. <br><br> Turning north, Fuchai dug the Han Gou canal to carry his armies, beat the great state of Qi at Ailing, and at the Huangchi conference of 482 BCE vied with Jin for mastery of the lords. But in his pride he forced the loyal Wu Zixu, who had rightly warned that Yue would be his ruin, to fall on his own sword. By later legend Yue also sent him the beauty Xi Shi, to sap his will with pleasure while it secretly rebuilt its strength for revenge. While Fuchai postured before the lords at Huangchi, the rebuilt Yue overran a defenceless Wu and killed his heir, and in 473 BCE, after a long war, it destroyed the kingdom outright. Begging the mercy he had once granted, Fuchai was refused and took his own life — covering his face, it is said, in shame to meet Wu Zixu beyond the grave — and Wu passed forever to Yue.","citation":"","answerText":"King Fuchai"},
{"id":"cnh-194","num":"一百九十四","category":"China · History","question":"The southern coastal kingdom of Zhejiang whose king Goujian, humbled by Wu's Fuchai, endured 'sleeping on brushwood and tasting gall' to rebuild and at last destroy Wu in 473 BCE, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> claimed descent from Yu the Great and was itself swallowed by Chu around 306 BCE.","answer":"Yue","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">越 — Yuè; a southern coastal kingdom of Zhejiang (capital Kuaiji/Shaoxing), King Goujian's state that destroyed Wu in 473 BCE; absorbed by Chu c. 306 BCE (not the Hundred Yue, Nanyue/Vietnam, or the later Wuyue)</span></div>","traditional":"越","hanzi":"越","pinyin":"Yuè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yue</b> was a southern coastal state lying below its rival Wu, centred on Kuaiji, the modern Shaoxing in Zhejiang, and known for its boats and its navy. Like Wu and Chu it lay beyond the Zhou world, a land whose people cropped their hair and tattooed their skin and whose rulers styled themselves kings. Its royal house claimed descent from Yu the Great, the flood-queller, who was said to have set a scion at Kuaiji to tend his tomb — a proud but legendary pedigree, unlike Wu's Zhou-royal line. The men of Yue were master swordsmiths, and the bronze Sword of Goujian, dug from a tomb in 1965 still keen and untarnished, endures as their emblem. Yue's bitter enemy was the neighbouring state of Wu, and in 496 BCE its armies gave Wu's King Helü the wound that killed him — only for Yue to be crushed in vengeance two years on. <br><br> King Goujian, beaten by Helü's son Fuchai at Fujiao in 494 BCE and penned with a remnant on Mount Kuaiji, was forced to submit and serve his conqueror at the Wu court. Freed at last, he steeled himself for revenge, tasting a bitter gall to remember his shame — the endurance later ages named 'sleeping on brushwood and tasting gall.' With his ministers Fan Li and Wen Zhong he secretly rebuilt Yue's strength, and in 473 BCE he destroyed Wu outright, drove Fuchai to suicide, and marched north to lead the states. The victory won, the wise Fan Li slipped away to make a merchant's fortune, but Wen Zhong was made to take his own life — the hound cooked once the hares are caught. Yue's greatness died with Goujian, and through the Warring States it steadily dwindled until, around 306 BCE, the great southern power of Chu broke and swallowed it.","citation":"","answerText":"Yue"},
{"id":"cnh-195","num":"一百九十五","category":"China · History","question":"The king of Yue who, humbled and spared by Wu's Fuchai, tasted gall for twenty years to keep his shame raw before destroying Wu in 473 BCE, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave China its byword for patient revenge, 'sleeping on brushwood and tasting gall.'","answer":"King Goujian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">越王勾踐 — Yuèwáng Gōujiàn; king of Yue, son of Yunchang; endured to destroy Wu in 473 BCE (origin of 卧薪尝胆); r. c. 496–465 BCE (king of the state Yue 越, not Nanyue or Vietnam)</span></div>","traditional":"勾踐","hanzi":"勾踐","pinyin":"Gōujiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gōujiàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Goujian</b> of Yue, the son of King Yunchang, is the most celebrated of the southern kings and the very emblem in China of patient, long-nursed revenge. His Yue defeated Wu at Zuili in 496 BCE, where Wu's King Helü took a mortal wound, so that Helü's son Fuchai came to the throne sworn to avenge his father. Two years later, in 494 BCE, Fuchai crushed Goujian at the Battle of Fujiao and penned him with a broken remnant on Mount Kuaiji. Cornered, Goujian sued for peace and was spared, and by tradition he and his queen went to serve Fuchai as menials, debasing himself utterly to win his captor's trust. This mercy — granted over the warning of Wu Zixu, who begged Fuchai to wipe Yue out — the king of Wu would live bitterly to rue. <br><br> Home again, Goujian nursed his shame, hanging a bitter gall to taste before every meal so as never to forget it — the endurance later ages fused into the idiom 'sleeping on brushwood and tasting gall.' For twenty years, sharing his people's toil in the fields, he rebuilt Yue with his ministers Fan Li and Wen Zhong, while by later legend the beauty Xi Shi was sent to soften Fuchai. When Fuchai went north to contend for the hegemony at Huangchi, Yue struck in his absence and killed the Wu crown prince, and in 473 BCE it destroyed Wu outright and drove Fuchai to suicide. Goujian then marched north himself to be hailed a leader of the lords, yet his shrewd minister Fan Li, judging him a man who could share hardship but not ease, quietly slipped away. Fan Li had warned Wen Zhong to flee as well, but Wen Zhong stayed on and was forced to take his own life — the hound cooked once the hares are caught.","citation":"","answerText":"King Goujian"},
{"id":"cnh-196","num":"一百九十六","category":"China · History","question":"The Chu-born strategist of King Goujian who engineered Yue's destruction of Wu, then wisely quit the court at the peak — warning the doomed Wen Zhong to flee too — and reinvented himself as the merchant Tao Zhu Gong, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is revered as a sage of commerce and a god of wealth.","answer":"Fan Li","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Statesman</span><span class=\"dt-v\">范蠡 — Fàn Lǐ; courtesy name Shaobo; Chu-born strategist of King Goujian of Yue who then retired as the rich merchant Tao Zhu Gong; c. 536–448 BCE (a civil god of wealth, not Wen Zhong, who stayed and died)</span></div>","traditional":"范蠡","hanzi":"范蠡","pinyin":"Fàn Lǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fàn Lǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Fan Li</b>, a man of Chu of humble birth, was the great strategist of Yue and one of the shrewdest minds of the whole Spring and Autumn age. With the minister Wen Zhong he left his native Chu to serve King Goujian of Yue, Fan Li as the master of war and stratagem, Wen Zhong of the state within. After Goujian's crushing defeat by Wu at Fujiao, it was Fan Li who counselled submission and shared his lord's disgrace, and then, over twenty patient years, engineered Yue's slow recovery. His generalship brought the long revenge to its end in 473 BCE, when Yue destroyed the state of Wu and drove its king Fuchai to suicide. A much later tale credits him with recruiting the beauty Xi Shi as a snare for Fuchai, and even with taking her away to love, though the earliest records know nothing of it. <br><br> At the very summit of his victory, when honours were his for the taking, Fan Li did the rarest thing and simply walked away — the classic model of retiring once the work is done. He judged King Goujian, the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> says, a man of long neck and hawk's beak, one to share hardship with but never ease. He warned Wen Zhong to flee as he had, but Wen Zhong stayed on and was forced to his death — the hound cooked once the hares are caught. Sailing off quietly under a new name, Fan Li turned to trade and grew fabulously rich as Tao Zhu Gong, three times, it is said, amassing a great fortune and giving it all away. Revered ever after as a sage of commerce and honoured among the civil gods of wealth, he became China's model of the man who knew both how to win and when to leave.","citation":"","answerText":"Fan Li"},
{"id":"cnh-197","num":"一百九十七","category":"China · History","question":"The foremost of China's Four Beauties, a legendary 'sinking-fish' silk-washer of Yue whom later tales cast as the honey-trap sent by Goujian to ensnare Wu's Fuchai, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is absent from the earliest histories, and her supposed hand in Wu's fall is the invention of much later legend.","answer":"Xi Shi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Legend</span><span class=\"dt-v\">西施 — Xī Shī (also Xizi 西子); the semi-legendary first of China's Four Beauties, a silk-washer of Yue; her epithet is \"sinking fish\"; her beauty-trap on Fuchai is later legend (Wu Yue Chunqiu, ~1st c. CE), absent from the earliest sources</span></div>","traditional":"西施","hanzi":"西施","pinyin":"Xī Shī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xī Shī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xi Shi</b>, traditionally the foremost of the Four Beauties of ancient China, is a figure far more of legend than of history. By tradition she was a peasant silk-washer of the state of Yue, so lovely that the fish, dazzled by her reflection in the stream, forgot to swim and sank — the source of her epithet, 'sinking fish.' With her stand three later beauties, and the four together lend China its very phrase for loveliness — though one of them, Diaochan, is a wholly fictional creation of a much later novel. Her name is old, appearing in the <i>Zhuangzi</i> in the tale of an ugly village woman who copied Xi Shi's pained frown and only made herself the more hideous — the origin of a proverb for foolish imitation. Yet in those oldest books she is no more than a byword for beauty, with no hint of the famous plot that later ages would weave around her. <br><br> The story known today, first told centuries later in a Han chronicle of Wu and Yue, the <i>Wu Yue Chunqiu</i>, makes her a living weapon of the state of Yue. King Goujian and his minister Fan Li, it says, trained the washer-girl and sent her to Wu's King Fuchai, who grew so besotted with her that he let his kingdom rot. Yue did destroy Wu in 473 BCE, but the earliest records — the very histories that tell the war in full — never name Xi Shi, and her hand in that ruin is the legend's own invention. Her end is unknown, told two ways: that she slipped away with Fan Li to a happy obscurity, or that she was drowned once her work was done. Whichever it was, she endures as China's very image of beauty — the 'sinking-fish' girl to whom the poet Su Shi likened the West Lake itself.","citation":"","answerText":"Xi Shi"},
{"id":"cnh-198","num":"一百九十八","category":"China · History","question":"The carving-up of one of the mightiest states of the Spring and Autumn period by its three great ministerial clans, Han, Zhao, and Wei, once they had destroyed the rival Zhi clan in 453 BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is by convention the event that ended that age and opened the Warring States.","answer":"Partition of Jin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Event</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三家分晉 — Sānjiā fēn Jìn; the division of the state of Jin among the clans Han (韓), Zhao (趙), and Wei (魏); de facto 453 BCE, recognized by the Zhou king 403 BCE; the conventional start of the Warring States period (Wei 魏, not the state Wey 卫; Han 韓, not the Han dynasty)</span></div>","traditional":"三家分晉","hanzi":"三家分晉","pinyin":"Sānjiā fēn Jìn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānjiā fēn Jìn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Partition of Jin</b> was the breaking-up of the great northern state of Jin among three of its own ministerial families, Han, Zhao, and Wei — the event that by convention closes the Spring and Autumn age and opens the Warring States. Jin's dukes had long let real power slip to a handful of hereditary minister-clans, who warred among themselves until only four great houses were left standing. The strongest was the Zhi clan, whose lord Zhi Bo demanded lands from the rest and, when Zhao refused, led the others to besiege it at Jinyang, even loosing a river to flood the city. But Zhao whispered to Han and Wei that Zhi Bo would swallow them next, and in 453 BCE the three turned on him and wiped out the Zhi clan. With Zhi destroyed, Han, Zhao, and Wei carved the state between them and left the Duke of Jin a powerless shadow. <br><br> Half a century later, in 403 BCE, the Zhou king bowed to the accomplished fact and formally raised the three heads of Han, Zhao, and Wei to lords in their own right. The historian Sima Guang chose that very moment to open his great chronicle, the <i>Zizhi Tongjian</i>, condemning the Son of Heaven for legitimizing usurpers and so wrecking the ritual order he was sworn to guard. The last shred of the old ducal house of Jin was abolished around 376 BCE, and the state's name lived on only in the phrase 'the Three Jins.' Han, Zhao, and Wei took their place as three of the Seven Warring States, beside Qin, Chu, Qi, and Yan. The partition became the very symbol of subjects overthrowing their ruler, and by shattering the wall Jin had long raised against Qin, it helped, in the end, to clear the road for Qin's conquest of all.","citation":"","answerText":"Partition of Jin"},
{"id":"cnh-199","num":"一百九十九","category":"China · History","question":"The smallest and weakest of the Seven Warring States, a central land carved from Jin that absorbed old Zheng for its capital and gave the age its finest crossbows and its great Legalist thinkers, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the first of the six to fall to Qin in 230 BCE.","answer":"Han","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">韓 — Hán; the smallest of the Seven Warring States, a successor of Jin (with Zhao and Wei); capital Xinzheng; home of the Legalists Shen Buhai and Han Fei; first state conquered by Qin, 230 BCE (the state 韓, not the Han 漢 dynasty)</span></div>","traditional":"韓","hanzi":"韓","pinyin":"Hán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Han</b> was one of the Seven Warring States, born from the break-up of the mighty state of Jin, and it shares its name only in sound with the far later imperial Han dynasty. With Zhao and Wei it was one of the 'Three Jins,' its royal house sprung from one of the great ministerial clans that had torn old Jin apart. It was the smallest and weakest of the Seven, a central land hemmed in on every side by mightier neighbours — Qin to the west, Wei to the north, Chu to the south, and Qi to the east. In 375 BCE it swallowed the old central state of Zheng and took its capital, Xinzheng, the 'New Zheng,' for its own. What it lacked in size it made up in arms, for Han was famed above all others for its keen iron swords and its powerful crossbows. <br><br> Small though it was, Han was also a cradle of the harsh statecraft called Legalism, home to two of its founding minds. Its chancellor Shen Buhai reformed and strengthened the state through his art of 'technique' — the ruler's craft of testing and holding his officials to strict account. The greatest of all Legalist thinkers, Han Fei, was a prince of its royal house, who wove law, technique, and power into a single doctrine — yet his own king ignored him, and he died a prisoner in Qin. Too weak to face Qin in open war, Han turned to cunning, sending the engineer Zheng Guo to lure Qin into a vast and exhausting canal meant to drain it — only for the finished waterway to water Qin's heartland and enrich it instead. So in 230 BCE Han became the first of the six rival states to fall to Qin — the first stone toppled in the conquest that would unite all China.","citation":"","answerText":"Han"},
{"id":"cnh-200","num":"二百","category":"China · History","question":"The northern military power of the Warring States, a successor of Jin whose King Wuling adopted the nomads' cavalry and 'mounted archery,' the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was Qin's last great rival until its army was annihilated at Changping in 260 BCE, and it fell to Qin in 228 BCE.","answer":"Zhao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">趙 — Zhào; a northern Warring State, a successor of Jin (with Han and Wei); capital Handan; King Wuling's cavalry reformer; crushed by Qin at Changping (260 BCE) and conquered 228 BCE, the second of the six to fall (not the later Zhao dynasties)</span></div>","traditional":"趙","hanzi":"趙","pinyin":"Zhào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhào</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhao</b> was one of the Seven Warring States and, with Han and Wei, one of the 'Three Jins' born from the break-up of the state of Jin. Its royal house shared the ancient Ying surname with its deadliest enemy, Qin, though the two were only distant kin, and from its capital at Handan it held the northern marches, facing the steppe nomads. Its greatest king, Wuling, made Zhao a military power by a bold reform, clothing his soldiers in nomad trousers and teaching them the horsemen's art of mounted archery in place of the old war-chariots. This 'Hu dress and mounted archery' gave Zhao the finest cavalry of the age, with which it swallowed the state of Zhongshan and drove back the northern tribes. Yet Wuling came to a wretched end, trapped by his own sons in the Shaqiu palace and left to starve. <br><br> Zhao is remembered too for its worthies — the diplomat Lin Xiangru, who bore its famous jade into Qin's court and by sheer nerve brought it home unbroken, the jade returned whole to Zhao. And the general Lian Po, ashamed of having envied Lin Xiangru's rise, bared his back and carried thorns to beg the minister's pardon — general and statesman putting the state above their pride. But Zhao's power was broken at the terrible Battle of Changping in 260 BCE, when the king cast aside the cautious Lian Po for the untried Zhao Kuo, who knew war only from books. Qin's general Bai Qi drew him out, ringed his army, and starved it into surrender, then, as the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> reports, buried some 400,000 captives alive. Zhao survived even this, saved at Handan by Wei and Chu, and held on until Qin's bribes tricked it into killing its last great general, Li Mu — and in 228 BCE it fell, the second of the six swallowed by Qin.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhao"},
{"id":"cnh-201","num":"二百零一","category":"China · History","question":"The earliest and strongest of the Warring States under Marquis Wen — with the lawgiver Li Kui, the general Wu Qi, and Ximen Bao of the canals — this successor of Jin was later broken by Qi's Sun Bin at Guiling and Maling and, its capital Daliang flooded, the state of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fell to Qin in 225 BCE, the third of six.","answer":"Wei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">State</span><span class=\"dt-v\">魏 — Wèi; the earliest-dominant of the Seven Warring States, a successor of Jin (with Han and Zhao); capitals Anyi then Daliang (\"Liang\"); conquered by Qin in 225 BCE, the third to fall (the state 魏, not Wey 衛, nor the later Cao Wei or Northern Wei)</span></div>","traditional":"魏","hanzi":"魏","pinyin":"Wèi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wèi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wei</b> was one of the Seven Warring States and, with Han and Zhao, one of the 'Three Jins' carved from the old state of Jin, and quite distinct from the small early state of Wey. It lay across the Yellow River in the central plains, ruling first from Anyi and later, from about 361 BCE, from Daliang, whose name gave the state its second name of 'Liang.' Under its great early ruler Marquis Wen, Wei was the first and strongest of the Warring States, raised up by a court of brilliant reformers. His chancellor Li Kui drew up one of China's earliest written law codes and filled granaries against famine; his general Wu Qi forged an elite army and wrested the western lands from Qin; and Ximen Bao ended a cruel river-sacrifice and dug canals to water the fields. So armed, early Wei held Qin penned behind its western river and led the states. <br><br> But its glory was broken by the eastern state of Qi and its crippled strategist Sun Bin — a different man from the earlier Sun Tzu, though by tradition his descendant. When Wei besieged Zhao's capital, Sun Bin saved Zhao not by relieving it but by striking at Wei's own land, so its army rushed home to be ambushed — the famous stratagem of 'besieging Wei to save Zhao.' A decade later, in 341 BCE, he lured Wei's general Pang Juan into a trap by a vanishing army — its cooking-fires fewer each night — and destroyed him at Maling, breaking Wei's power for good. Its King Hui, remembered as the 'King Hui of Liang' whose dialogues open the <i>Mencius</i>, watched Wei sink to a middling power, forever pressed by a rising Qin. At last, in 225 BCE, the Qin general Wang Ben flooded Daliang and forced its surrender — Wei the third of the six kingdoms to fall to Qin.","citation":"","answerText":"Wei"},
{"id":"cnh-202","num":"二百零二","category":"China · History","question":"The founding ruler who made Wei the first superpower of the Warring States, famed for honouring talent — his chancellor Li Kui, his general Wu Qi, his governor Ximen Bao — and for keeping his word even in a storm, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Wei was recognized as a feudal lord in 403 BCE, the conventional dawn of the age.","answer":"Marquis Wen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">魏文侯 — Wèi Wén Hóu; personal name Wèi Sī 魏斯; founding marquis of the Warring State of Wei, who made it the first great power; r. c. 445–396 BCE (a marquis, not a king; not King Wen of Zhou or Duke Wen of Jin)</span></div>","traditional":"魏文侯","hanzi":"魏文侯","pinyin":"Wèi Wén Hóu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wèi Wén Hóu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Marquis Wen</b> of Wei, whose personal name was Wei Si, was the founding ruler who made the state of Wei the first great power of the Warring States. He was a marquis, not a king, for Wei's rulers took the royal title only two generations later, under his grandson King Hui. In 403 BCE the Zhou king formally raised him, with the heads of Han and Zhao, to the rank of feudal lord — the recognition, long after the three had seized old Jin, that by convention opens the Warring States age. Over a reign of near fifty years he made Wei the strongest state of the day by a government of merit and reform, ruling from his capital at Anyi. Above all he was famed for honouring talent, humbling himself before worthy men and gathering to his court a brilliant company of ministers and scholars from wherever he could find them. <br><br> His chancellor Li Kui remade the state, laying down the <i>Canon of Laws</i>, held to be China's earliest written code, and steadying grain prices against famine. His general Wu Qi trained the elite heavy infantry known as the 'Wei footsoldiers' and tore from Qin the rich lands west of the Yellow River. And his governor Ximen Bao, at Ye, put an end to the drowning of brides for the river god and cut canals to green the fields. He honoured the Confucians too, studying under the aged Zixia, a disciple of Confucius himself, and bowing at the gate of a hermit whose wisdom he revered. A byword for a ruler who kept his word — the tale tells he braved a storm to keep a hunting appointment rather than break it — he held the Three Jins together and left Wei, at his death in 396 BCE, the leading power of the age.","citation":"","answerText":"Marquis Wen"},
{"id":"cnh-203","num":"二百零三","category":"China · History","question":"The earliest of the great Legalist reformers, chancellor to Marquis Wen who made Wei the first Warring States power, compiler of the lost Fajing that became the model for later Chinese law, and pioneer of the state granary that steadied grain prices, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is not to be confused with the axe-wielding bandit of the same name.","answer":"Li Kui","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Statesman</span><span class=\"dt-v\">李悝 — Lǐ Kuī; the earliest Legalist reformer, chancellor of Wei under Marquis Wen; compiled the Fajing law code; c. 455–395 BCE (the reformer 李悝, not the Water Margin bandit Li Kui 李逵)</span></div>","traditional":"李悝","hanzi":"李悝","pinyin":"Lǐ Kuī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Kuī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Kui</b> was a statesman of the early Warring States and, by common reckoning, the earliest of the great Legalist reformers — not to be confused with the axe-wielding bandit of the same name in a much later novel. As chancellor to Marquis Wen of the state of Wei, his laws and policies did more than any general to make Wei the first great power of the age. His most lasting work was the Canon of Laws, the <i>Fajing</i>, which tradition calls the first comprehensive written code of law in China. It dealt in six chapters with theft, violence, arrest, imprisonment, and the fixing of penalties, and though the text itself is long lost, its plan shaped every law-code that came after. Shang Yang is said to have carried it west to Qin, so that through Wei's code the laws of Qin and of the Han empire took their shape. <br><br> Li Kui was as bold a reformer of the economy as he was of the law, and here too his ideas outlasted him. He pressed the farmers to 'exhaust the strength of the land' — to till every plot with care and sow many crops against the failure of one — and reckoned, in one of the earliest exercises of economic thought, the whole budget of a peasant household. He set the state to steady the price of grain, buying it up cheaply in fat years and selling it in lean ones — a scheme that guarded farmer and townsman alike and long foreshadowed the 'ever-normal granaries' of later ages. He would grant office and pay by service and merit, stripping idle nobles of their inherited privilege. So this quiet minister, ahead of Shen Buhai, Shang Yang, and Han Fei, stands at the head of the Legalist tradition, the first to govern a state by written law and hard reckoning.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Kui"},
{"id":"cnh-204","num":"二百零四","category":"China · History","question":"The greatest general-reformer of the early Warring States, born in little Wey yet famed for forging Wei's elite footsoldiers and wresting the Xihe from Qin, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> reformed Chu for King Dao and was cut down at the royal funeral in 381 BCE, dying upon the king's corpse so that his killers were doomed.","answer":"Wu Qi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">General</span><span class=\"dt-v\">吳起 — Wú Qǐ; general and statesman-reformer of the early Warring States; served Lu, then Wei, then Chu; forged the Wei Wuzu and is credited with the Wuzi; c. 440–381 BCE (born in Wey 衛, not the state of Wei 魏; not Wu Zixu 伍子胥 or Sun Wu 孫武)</span></div>","traditional":"吳起","hanzi":"吳起","pinyin":"Wú Qǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wú Qǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu Qi</b> was one of the greatest generals and reformers of the early Warring States, a man of rare talent and cold ambition, born in the small state of Wey — not to be confused with the southern state of Wu, whose name he shares. He served three states in turn — first Lu, then Wei, and last Chu — rising in each by his gifts and falling by the enemies his ruthlessness made. The <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> tells that he killed his own wife, a woman of Qi, to win a Lu command, and that he had refused to mourn his mother, for which his teacher cast him off. Such tales are moralizing tradition, not fact, yet all agree he drove back the invading armies of Qi. Passing then to Wei under Marquis Wen, he became the finest commander of the age, by tradition never defeated in the field. <br><br> For Wei he forged the Wei Wuzu, a corps of elite heavy infantry chosen by hard trial, and with them tore from Qin the lands of the Xihe, west of the Yellow River, and governed them. He shared every hardship of his soldiers, and by tradition once sucked the pus from a man's wound to bind them to him. Falling at last from favour, he fled south to Chu, where King Dao made him chancellor and set him to remake the state. There he stripped the hereditary nobles of pensions and titles to strengthen the army, and was cut down at the king's funeral in 381 BCE; by tradition he fell upon the royal corpse so their arrows profaned the dead king, for which his killers were executed. His reforms were soon undone, yet to him is traditionally credited the <i>Wuzi</i>, one of the Seven Military Classics, which joins his name with Sun Tzu's as the twin masters of war.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu Qi"},
{"id":"cnh-205","num":"二百零五","category":"China · History","question":"When the collapse of Zhou authority set rival states scrambling for advantage, wandering scholars roamed from court to court to peddle their competing philosophies — Confucian, Daoist, Legalist, Mohist and more — a golden age of ideas known as the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, which the Qin unification of 221 BCE brought to a close.","answer":"Hundred Schools of Thought","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">諸子百家 — Zhūzǐ Bǎijiā; the flowering of Chinese philosophy across the Eastern Zhou, from the Spring and Autumn period through the Warring States; the 'schools' were classified only later — Sima Tan named six, the Book of Han ten; ended by the Qin unification of 221 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"諸子百家","hanzi":"諸子百家","pinyin":"Zhūzǐ Bǎijiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhūzǐ Bǎijiā</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hundred Schools of Thought</b> was the flowering of Chinese philosophy during the Eastern Zhou, the Spring and Autumn and Warring States eras; its 'hundred' is a figure for 'many,' not a count. It arose from disorder: as Zhou royal authority crumbled after 770 BCE, rival states competed for advantage and, hungry for talent, took in wandering scholars — the <i>shi</i> — who roamed the courts to peddle their statecraft. Some states gathered these thinkers in academies, most famously Qi's Jixia Academy, where masters argued at the ruler's expense. The tidy roster of 'schools' is not how these men saw themselves, but an order imposed later by Han scholars looking back on a messier ferment. Sima Tan, father of Sima Qian, sorted them into six schools — Confucians, Daoists, Legalists, Mohists, the School of Names, and the Yin-Yang cosmologists — and the <i>Book of Han</i> later stretched the list to ten. <br><br> The Confucians, following Confucius, taught <i>ren</i>, benevolence, and <i>li</i>, ritual, holding that a realm is best ruled by moral example and the mending of names. The Daoists of the <i>Tao Te Ching</i> and the <i>Zhuangzi</i> answered with the way of nature and <i>wu wei</i>, effortless action, distrusting the Confucians' busy virtue. The Legalists, whose ideas Han Fei gathered and Qin put to work, trusted not virtue but strict law and the throne's power; the Mohists of Mozi preached impartial love and hatred of aggressive war, while lesser schools weighed logic, alliances, farming, and yin and yang. This contest was silenced when Qin unified China in 221 BCE and, embracing Legalism, burned the books of its rivals — a suppression the histories say was followed by the burying of scholars. Yet the age was the seedbed of all later Chinese thought: the Han raised Confucianism to orthodoxy, and Confucian, Daoist, and Legalist ideas shaped China for two thousand years — though Mohism, once its great rival, faded and all but vanished.","citation":"","answerText":"Hundred Schools of Thought"},
{"id":"cnh-206","num":"二百零六","category":"China · History","question":"An artisan-turned-philosopher who founded the school that most rivalled Confucianism, preaching an 'impartial care' for all and condemning offensive war — and once walking ten days to turn an attack on Song aside — <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led a disciplined brotherhood of defensive siege-engineers in the early Warring States.","answer":"Mozi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Philosopher</span><span class=\"dt-v\">墨子 — Mòzǐ, 'Master Mo'; personal name Mo Di 墨翟; founder of Mohism and great rival of the Confucians; c. 470–391 BCE, traditional and approximate (from Lu or Song; not Mencius 孟子 or the other masters)</span></div>","traditional":"墨子","hanzi":"墨子","pinyin":"Mòzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mòzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mozi</b>, 'Master Mo,' personal name Mo Di, was a philosopher of the early Warring States and the founder of Mohism, in his day the great rival of the Confucians. By tradition his dates are about 470 to 391 BCE, though only approximate, and he likely rose from humble artisan stock, no well-born scholar, from Lu or perhaps Song. His central teaching was <i>jian ai</i>, an impartial care that weighs every person's welfare equally, against the Confucian ideal of graded love that favours one's own kin. From this he argued that offensive war is only murder and theft on a vast scale, yet his followers were no pacifists but famed engineers of city defence. Mohism was less a loose school than a disciplined brotherhood, austere and led by a grandmaster, the <i>juzi</i>, who could send members to shield a threatened state. <br><br> He judged all by its benefit to the people, and so urged advancement by merit, frugality, plain burials over ruinous funerals, and an end to costly court music. He held too that Heaven has a moral will and that spirits reward the good and punish the wicked, and he rejected fatalism as breeding only idleness. His most famous story, told in the <i>Mozi</i>, has him walk ten days to Chu and, in a mock siege fought with his belt for a wall and sticks for engines, defeat the craftsman Gongshu Ban nine times, turning aside Chu's assault on Song. The book that bears his name, compiled by his followers, preserves these doctrines and the later Mohist Canon, whose logic, geometry, and mechanics give one of the earliest accounts of light through a pinhole casting an inverted image. Yet for all its early sway — the Confucian Mencius thought it worth attacking by name — Mohism faded after the Qin unification and all but vanished under the Han, leaving only its text behind.","citation":"","answerText":"Mozi"},
{"id":"cnh-207","num":"二百零七","category":"China · History","question":"Confucianism's fiercest early rival, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> judged every custom by its benefit to the people, tested doctrines against precedent, evidence, and use, and left a canon of logic and optics — yet this austere brotherhood of defensive warriors all but vanished as a living school after the Qin.","answer":"Mohism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">School</span><span class=\"dt-v\">墨家 — Mòjiā; the school founded by Mozi (Mo Di) and the chief early rival of Confucianism; flourished across the Warring States, then all but vanished after the Qin unification (the school 墨家, distinct from Mozi 墨子, the man and the text)</span></div>","traditional":"墨家","hanzi":"墨家","pinyin":"Mòjiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mòjiā</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mohism</b> was the school founded by Mozi and, through the Warring States, the fiercest early rival and critic of the Confucians. What set it apart was its method: it judged every custom, rite, and policy by one hard test — whether it benefited the people, reckoned as their wealth, their numbers, and their order. To judge whether a doctrine was even true, the Mohists applied three standards — its grounding in the deeds of the ancient sage-kings, the witness of the people's own eyes and ears, and the benefit it brought in use — a standard of proof unmatched among the schools. From this austere and practical spirit came its ten teachings, among them impartial care and the condemnation of aggressive war, meritocracy, frugality, and a faith that Heaven and the spirits reward the good. Mohism was no mere circle of scholars but a disciplined, austere brotherhood drawn largely from artisans, its local bands each led by a grandmaster, the <i>juzi</i>, and skilled above all in defending walls. <br><br> Its later followers compiled the <i>Mohist Canon</i>, terse dialectical chapters holding the most developed logic, debate, and definition in early China — a tradition all its own, no borrowing from the Greeks. The same chapters define the geometric point, explain the lever and the balance, and study light — stating, among the world's earliest, that rays crossing a small hole cast an inverted image. These were principles the Canon set down, not devices anyone built, and the work of anonymous disciples rather than Mozi himself. After the master's death the school split into three rival lineages that branded one another 'heretical Mohists,' yet Mohists and Confucians were still named the two most illustrious learnings of the age. Then, once the Qin unified China, Mohism declined and vanished as a living school, for reasons still debated, its canon left so corrupt that scholars pieced it back together only centuries later.","citation":"","answerText":"Mohism"},
{"id":"cnh-208","num":"二百零八","category":"China · History","question":"The 'Second Sage' of Confucianism, who taught that human nature is good — every person born with sprouts of virtue — and that in a state the people matter most and the ruler least, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> wandered the Warring States courts urging benevolent rule long before his book was raised into the Confucian classics.","answer":"Mencius","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Philosopher</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孟子 — Mèngzǐ, 'Master Meng'; personal name Meng Ke 孟軻; the great Confucian of the Warring States, later revered as the 'Second Sage'; c. 372–289 BCE, traditional and approximate (from Zou; not Mozi 墨子 the Mohist, his rival)</span></div>","traditional":"孟子","hanzi":"孟子","pinyin":"Mèngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mèngzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mencius</b>, whose name was Meng Ke, was the greatest Confucian after Confucius himself, a philosopher of the Warring States from the small state of Zou. Like Confucius he wandered court to court, to Liang and Qi, urging kings to rule by virtue; but almost none heeded him, and he turned at last to teaching. His signature teaching was that human nature is good — not that men are born virtuous, but that all carry innate sprouts of goodness that must be nurtured to grow. These he numbered as four — compassion, growing into benevolence; shame, into righteousness; deference, into propriety; and the sense of right and wrong, into wisdom. To prove the first innate, he bid us imagine a child about to tumble into a well: anyone would feel a stab of alarm and pity, not from hope of reward but from a goodness born in the heart. <br><br> Against Gaozi, who held nature morally blank, he insisted it inclines to good as water runs downhill, and spoke of nourishing a vast 'flood-like' moral energy through the steady practice of right. In politics he was boldly people-first: a benevolent government wins all under Heaven without force, and in a state the people are most precious, the altars of land next, and the ruler least. A tyrant who destroys benevolence, he said, is a mere outcast, so to cut him down is no killing of a king — a right of rebellion tied to the Mandate of Heaven that unsettled later emperors. He taught too that only a people with a settled livelihood can keep a settled heart, and he warred on rival schools, damning Yang Zhu's egoism and the Mohists' impartial love as teachings that sank men to beasts. Unheeded in his day, he was raised only centuries later to 'Second Sage,' when the Song scholar Zhu Xi set his book among the Four Books at the core of Confucian learning.","citation":"","answerText":"Mencius"},
{"id":"cnh-209","num":"二百零九","category":"China · History","question":"The second great sage of Daoism after Laozi — a witty spinner of parables who once dreamt he was a butterfly and, offered high office, chose to 'drag his tail in the mud' like a free turtle — <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> taught that all distinctions are matters of perspective and that the wise wander free through a world of ceaseless change.","answer":"Zhuangzi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Sage</span><span class=\"dt-v\">莊子 — Zhuāngzǐ, 'Master Zhuang'; personal name Zhuang Zhou 莊周; the second great Daoist after Laozi and namesake of the <i>Zhuangzi</i> text; c. 369–286 BCE, traditional and approximate (from Meng in Song; the philosopher, not the book or the Zhuang dukes and kings)</span></div>","traditional":"莊子","hanzi":"莊子","pinyin":"Zhuāngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhuāngzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhuangzi</b>, whose name was Zhuang Zhou, was the second great sage of Daoism after Laozi, a philosopher of the Warring States from the town of Meng in Song. Little of his life is certain, but the book that bears his name — among the wittiest, most imaginative works in Chinese literature — carries his spirit in parable and paradox. Where the Confucians and Mohists earnestly ordered the world, he laughed at their striving and taught the way of nature — <i>ziran</i> and effortless <i>wu wei</i>, going along with things rather than forcing them. His most distinctive thought was a playful skepticism: that all our distinctions — right and wrong, useful and useless, even life and death — are only matters of standpoint, no view absolutely true. Seeing this, the sage could 'wander free and easy' beyond care for fame and use, roaming free as the great Peng bird. <br><br> He is loved most for his stories: he dreamt he was a butterfly and woke unsure whether he was a man who had dreamt he was a butterfly, or a butterfly now dreaming it was a man. In another, the cook Ding carves an ox without dulling his blade, sliding it through the natural hollows — skill so at one with the Way that it costs no effort. With his friend and foil Huizi, a master of the School of Names, he argued on a bridge whether he could really know the fish below were happy. He met death calmly: in one tale, when his wife died, he was found drumming on a bowl and singing, seeing death as but a turn in nature's endless change; and, offered high office, he waved it away, prizing his freedom. No system-builder but an elusive poet of freedom, Zhuangzi shaped Chinese poetry, painting, and spirit ever after, his love of spontaneity feeding in time into Chan, or Zen, Buddhism.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhuangzi"},
{"id":"cnh-210","num":"二百一十","category":"China · History","question":"The third of the great classical Confucians, who taught — against Mencius — that human nature is bad and that goodness must be forged by ritual and study, and whose Heaven was a blind natural order deaf to prayer, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is better known as Xunzi and, in a famous irony, taught the Legalists Han Fei and Li Si.","answer":"Xun Kuang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Philosopher</span><span class=\"dt-v\">荀況 — Xún Kuàng, honoured as Xunzi 荀子 ('Master Xun'), also Xun Qing; the third great classical Confucian, of the late Warring States; c. 310–235 BCE, traditional and approximate (from Zhao; a Confucian who held human nature bad, not his Legalist students Han Fei and Li Si)</span></div>","traditional":"荀況","hanzi":"荀況","pinyin":"Xún Kuàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xún Kuàng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xun Kuang</b>, honoured as Xunzi, was the third of the great classical Confucians after Confucius and Mencius, often reckoned the most systematic. A man of Zhao, he was a leading scholar at Qi's Jixia Academy and ended as magistrate of Lanling in Chu, where he wrote the sustained essays — unlike earlier masters' sayings — that fill the book bearing his name. His most famous teaching was that human nature is bad — the very reverse of Mencius — for men are born to selfish appetite that, unchecked, breeds strife and disorder. Yet this was no counsel of despair, for anyone at all could become good, even a sage: goodness is not inborn but made, the work of deliberate effort he called <i>wei</i>. As crooked wood is steamed straight, or blue dye drawn from indigo comes out bluer than the plant, so cultivation reshapes the raw nature into something finer. <br><br> Ritual was the tool of that reshaping, prized above all — the rites and music the sage-kings devised to school desire and bind society — and he opened his book insisting learning must never cease. He was a bold rationalist too, teaching that Heaven is no moral judge but a constant, impersonal order of nature, its course unchanged whether a sage or a tyrant sits on the throne. Eclipses and strange portents, he said, are mere workings of nature, no omens to fear, and men do better to order their world by effort than to pray to the sky. Strangest of all, this devout Confucian taught the two architects of Legalism, Han Fei and Li Si — though he set ritual and the virtuous ruler above cold law. He was long overshadowed by the gentler Mencius, whose good-nature doctrine became orthodoxy, and his tablet was even cast from the Confucian temple — only in modern times restored as the sharpest of the early Confucians.","citation":"","answerText":"Xun Kuang"},
{"id":"cnh-211","num":"二百一十一","category":"China · History","question":"The arch-Legalist who rebuilt backward Qin for Duke Xiao with impartial law, ranks of merit, and a people bent to farming and war, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fell in 338 BCE to the king he had offended — turned away, the story goes, by an inn obeying his own permit-law — yet his system endured to power Qin's conquest of China.","answer":"Shang Yang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Statesman</span><span class=\"dt-v\">商鞅 — Shāng Yāng; born Gongsun Yang or Wei Yang in the small state of Wey 衛; Legalist chief minister who remade Qin under Duke Xiao; c. 390–338 BCE (named for his fief at Shang 商於, not the Shang dynasty; the practitioner of Legalism, where Han Fei was its theorist)</span></div>","traditional":"商鞅","hanzi":"商鞅","pinyin":"Shāng Yāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shāng Yāng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shang Yang</b> was the Legalist reformer who remade Qin — born Gongsun Yang in the small state of Wey, and named to history only late, for his fief at Shang. He began in Wei, whose dying chancellor, tradition says, told the king to employ him or kill him; the king did neither, and Yang went west to Qin, where Duke Xiao had called for men of talent. He drove two waves of reform from about 356 and 350 BCE, winning trust first, the tale runs, by paying gold to the man who carried a pole from the south gate to the north. His published law bound noble and commoner alike — even the crown prince's tutors were punished when the heir offended — and banded households into fives and tens sharing guilt for each other's undenounced crimes. Hereditary privilege yielded to ranks of merit won by enemy heads in battle; farming and weaving were exalted, merchants and idlers punished. <br><br> The second wave gathered Qin into counties under appointed magistrates, standardized weights and measures, taxed undivided families apart, and moved the capital to Xianyang. The <i>Book of Lord Shang</i>, attributed to him though finished by his school, distills the creed: drive the people into tilling and fighting; punish light offenses heavily so crime never arises; and brand rites, music, and the classics parasites upon a state. In 340 BCE he led Qin to defeat Wei, which ceded land west of the Yellow River, and won the fifteen towns of Shang that gave him his name. When Duke Xiao died in 338 BCE the offended new king denounced him; fleeing, by the tradition's perfect irony, he was turned from an inn for want of the permit his own law required, then killed, his corpse torn apart by chariots, his family exterminated. Yet Qin kept his laws, and the pitiless machine he built carried it, a century on, to the conquest of all China.","citation":"","answerText":"Shang Yang"},
{"id":"cnh-212","num":"二百一十二","category":"China · History","question":"Attributed to Qin's great reformer though largely written by his later followers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the earliest classic of Legalism — a blunt manual of statecraft that channels a whole people into farming and war and brands rites, music, and learning as parasites upon the state.","answer":"Book of Lord Shang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Text</span><span class=\"dt-v\">商君書 — Shāngjūnshū; the earliest classic of Legalism, attributed to Shang Yang (Lord Shang) but a composite completed by his school; c. 4th–3rd century BCE, some 24 of 29 chapters surviving (named for his fief at Shang, not the Shang dynasty; the book, not Shang Yang the man, nor the later Han Feizi)</span></div>","traditional":"商君書","hanzi":"商君書","pinyin":"Shāngjūnshū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shāngjūnshū</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Book of Lord Shang</b> is the earliest surviving classic of Legalism, the cold philosophy of law and state power, standing beside the later <i>Han Feizi</i> as its other founding text. It takes its name from Lord Shang — the reformer Shang Yang, so titled for his fief, not the Shang dynasty — and though ascribed to him, the book we have is a composite, enlarged by his followers over the century after his death. The Han imperial catalogue counted 29 chapters, of which about 24 survive, written not as dialogues but as blunt essays and memoranda on how to govern. Its opening chapter stages a court debate at Qin, where the case for reform is argued down conservatives clinging to antiquity. At its heart lies a single stark idea: the whole people driven into just two pursuits, farming and war, the twin roots of a rich state and strong army. <br><br> All else — commerce, learning, the wandering persuaders — is discouraged as a drain on them, and the people are bound by clear, published law binding high and low alike. Punishment, not virtue, is its engine: even light offenses are punished heavily, on the paradox that harsh penalties, faithfully applied, make crime cease — using punishments to abolish punishments. A strong state, it argues, needs a weak people — poor, simple, dependent — and it brands rites, music, the ancient <i>Odes</i> and <i>Documents</i>, and the soft virtues as parasites that sap the will to fight and till. Institutions must change with the times, it insists, so the wise ruler imitates neither the sage-kings nor the past but makes law anew, ruling through system, not his own virtue. Scholars call it the frankest, most unsparing of the statecraft classics; the Legalist program it shares built the Qin machine that swallowed China, and though Confucians reviled it as a byword for tyranny, it was kept and read.","citation":"","answerText":"Book of Lord Shang"},
{"id":"cnh-213","num":"二百一十三","category":"China · History","question":"The boldest reformer-king of the Warring States, who clad his soldiers in nomad trousers and taught them to fight as mounted archers — trading chariots for cavalry and making Zhao a great northern power — <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> of Zhao ended his days starved in a besieged palace after a botched succession.","answer":"King Wuling","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reign</span><span class=\"dt-v\">趙武靈王 — Zhào Wǔlíng Wáng; personal name Zhao Yong 趙雍; king of the Warring State of Zhao and author of the 'Hu dress and mounted archery' cavalry reform; r. c. 325–299 BCE, died 295 BCE ('Wuling' is a posthumous name; the father, not his son King Huiwen)</span></div>","traditional":"趙武靈王","hanzi":"趙武靈王","pinyin":"Zhào Wǔlíng Wáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhào Wǔlíng Wáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Wuling</b>, whose name was Zhao Yong, was the boldest king of Zhao — though 'Wuling' is only his posthumous name, and in life, thinking Zhao not yet strong, he styled himself only 'lord,' not king. His great act, about 307 BCE, was the reform called 'Hu dress and mounted archery': to match the horse-borne nomads, he made his army trade China's robes for nomad trousers and fight as mounted archers. The clothing was only the means; the substance was cavalry — the decisive turn in Chinese warfare from chariot to mounted bowman. Wearing 'barbarian' dress was a scandal, and the court resisted, but Wuling argued it through — by tradition winning over his reluctant uncle, Prince Cheng — that a state must change its tools for new dangers, not slave to custom. With this new cavalry he made Zhao the foremost military power of the age, chief rival to the rising Qin. <br><br> His cavalry drove back the Loufan and Linhu, pushed Zhao's border into the steppe behind new commanderies and a wall, and swallowed the state of Zhongshan long lodged within his own. Then, as strange as his reform was bold, he abdicated in 299 BCE to his younger son, King Huiwen, and took the unheard-of title of 'Lord Father,' keeping command of the armies. But he had first named his elder son heir, then cast him aside, and pity for the wronged prince left him wavering — sowing ruin. In 295 BCE, at the Shaqiu palace, that elder son, Prince Zhang, revolted; the ministers Li Dui and Prince Cheng crushed it and killed him, but Zhang had fled to his father, who sheltered him. Fearing the Lord Father's vengeance for a prince slain in his house, the ministers walled him in his palace, and there one of Zhao's greatest kings slowly starved to death — reduced, the histories say, to robbing sparrows' nests.","citation":"","answerText":"King Wuling"},
{"id":"cnh-214","num":"二百一十四","category":"China · History","question":"A descendant of Sun Tzu who was maimed and branded by his envious fellow-student Pang Juan, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> escaped to Qi and there twice destroyed his betrayer — 'besieging Wei to rescue Zhao,' then luring him to his death with a fleeing army's dwindling campfires — before his own lost treatise surfaced from a tomb in 1972.","answer":"Sun Bin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Strategist</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孫臏 — Sūn Bìn; military strategist of Qi, traditionally a descendant of Sun Wu (Sun Tzu); fl. mid-4th century BCE ('Bin' names the crippling punishment he suffered, not his given name; not his ancestor Sun Wu 孫武)</span></div>","traditional":"孫臏","hanzi":"孫臏","pinyin":"Sūn Bìn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūn Bìn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sun Bin</b> was the greatest strategist of the Warring States, and by tradition a descendant of Sun Wu — the Sun Tzu of the <i>Art of War</i> — a century and a half before him. History knows him only by his mutilation: 'Bin' is not his given name, now lost, but the crippling punishment that maimed his legs, and he was branded on the face besides. The <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> tell that his fellow student Pang Juan, a general of Wei gnawed by envy, lured him to Wei, framed him, and had him crippled to bury him in shame. Smuggled to Qi, so the story goes, by feigning madness, Sun Bin became the strategist behind the general Tian Ji, directing the war from a covered carriage, not the field. He first won favour by a horse race, having Tian Ji lose with his worst horse, then win the next two with his best and second against the king's weaker pair. <br><br> His revenge fell in two battles against Pang Juan. When Wei besieged Zhao's capital, Sun Bin would not march to its relief but struck instead at Wei's own heartland, forcing it home to be ambushed — the classic 'besieging Wei to rescue Zhao,' won at Guiling about 353 BCE. A dozen years later, as Wei fell on Han, he lured Pang Juan by a vanishing army, its cooking-fires fewer each night, until the Wei general, thinking the Qi deserting, gave chase with a light force. At the Maling defile Sun Bin's hidden crossbows cut them down in the dark, and Pang Juan died there, his army destroyed and Wei's supremacy broken forever. Sun Bin left his own military treatise, but it vanished for well over a thousand years — so wholly some doubted he and Sun Tzu were two men — until 1972, when bamboo strips at Yinqueshan in Shandong gave back both books and proved them apart.","citation":"","answerText":"Sun Bin"},
{"id":"cnh-215","num":"二百一十五","category":"China · History","question":"Fought about 341 BCE, when Qi came to Han's aid against the dominant state of Wei, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the strategist Sun Bin feign a fleeing army by his dwindling cook-fires, luring the general Pang Juan into a night ambush that broke Wei's power for good.","answer":"Battle of Maling","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Battle</span><span class=\"dt-v\">馬陵之戰 — Mǎlíng zhī zhàn; the ambush in which Qi's Sun Bin destroyed Wei's army and its general Pang Juan, ending Wei's supremacy; c. 341 BCE (not the earlier Battle of Guiling, c. 353 BCE, fought over Zhao)</span></div>","traditional":"馬陵之戰","hanzi":"馬陵之戰","pinyin":"Mǎlíng zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎlíng zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Battle of Maling</b> was the ambush, about 341 BCE, that shattered the military dominance of Wei, the foremost power of the early Warring States. It began when Wei, under its general Pang Juan, fell upon the smaller state of Han, which appealed to Qi for rescue. Qi, on Sun Bin's counsel, held back until Wei and Han had worn each other down, then sent an army under Tian Ji — not to Han, but driving at Wei's own capital, forcing Pang Juan to break off and race home. As the Qi army drew back before him into Wei, Sun Bin worked his famous deception, having the soldiers' cook-fires counted at a hundred thousand the first night, fifty thousand the next, thirty thousand the third. Pang Juan, who scorned the men of Qi as cowards, read the dwindling fires as proof that their army was melting away in desertion, and took the bait. <br><br> Casting off his foot soldiers, he pursued with a light, picked force by forced marches to catch the fleeing enemy. But Sun Bin had reckoned his speed exactly, and set an ambush of crossbowmen where the road narrowed at Maling, timing it for the fall of night. By the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>, he stripped a great tree of its bark and wrote that Pang Juan would die there; when the general lit a torch to read it, the hidden bows loosed at the light. The Wei army was cut to pieces in the defile; Pang Juan died at Maling, and the Wei crown prince Shen was taken captive, with losses the histories put at a hundred thousand men. With this blow, after its earlier win at Guiling, Qi became the leading power of the east and Wei sank to the second rank — a fall that in time helped clear the road for a rising Qin.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Maling"},
{"id":"cnh-216","num":"二百一十六","category":"China · History","question":"By tradition the master of the 'vertical alliance' that bound the six eastern states against Qin — and the striver who stabbed his own thigh with an awl to stay awake at his books — <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was in truth, the Mawangdui silk texts revealed, a diplomat of a later generation who served as Yan's secret agent against Qi.","answer":"Su Qin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Diplomat</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蘇秦 — Sū Qín; strategist of the 'Vertical and Horizontal' school, famed for the vertical alliance against Qin; died c. 284 BCE (his given name 秦 is the same character as the state of Qin, but no relation; not his rival Zhang Yi)</span></div>","traditional":"蘇秦","hanzi":"蘇秦","pinyin":"Sū Qín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sū Qín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Su Qin</b> was the most celebrated of the wandering persuaders of the Warring States, the silver-tongued strategists of the 'Vertical and Horizontal' school. His name holds an irony: his given name, Qin, is the very character of the western state he made his enemy, though he was no kin to it. The old histories tell a favourite rags-to-riches tale: rejected as an adviser, he came home in rags to be despised by his family — his wife not leaving her loom, his sister-in-law refusing to cook. Stung, he shut himself away to study, and when sleep pressed at night he stabbed his own thigh with an awl to keep awake — long a byword for hard study. He emerged a master of persuasion, and the kin who had scorned him now grovelled, moving him to muse how the world honours only wealth and rank. <br><br> His fame rests on the 'vertical alliance' he is said to have forged, binding the six eastern states — Yan, Zhao, Han, Wei, Qi, and Chu — into a north-south front, lest Qin pick them off singly. By tradition he held the chancellor's seals of all six and kept Qin penned behind its passes, while his rival Zhang Yi worked the 'horizontal' craft, luring them one by one into separate pacts to break the bloc. But much of this is legend: silk manuscripts unearthed at Mawangdui in 1973 showed the standard biography badly tangled in its dates. The real Su Qin lived a generation after Zhang Yi, long dead by then, so their famous duel could never have happened; the true man was a secret agent of Yan, working within Qi to weaken it. He died about 284 BCE, cut down in Qi — and the histories give him a last cunning stroke: bidding the king dismember his body as a traitor's and offer a reward, to lure his killer to his doom.","citation":"","answerText":"Su Qin"},
{"id":"cnh-217","num":"二百一十七","category":"China · History","question":"The wily chancellor of Qin who broke the coalitions ranged against it by his 'horizontal' craft — allying with the eastern states one at a time — and who tricked Chu into a ruinous war by promising six hundred li of land and then delivering six, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the great rival, in tradition, of Su Qin and his vertical alliance.","answer":"Zhang Yi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Diplomat</span><span class=\"dt-v\">張儀 — Zhāng Yí; strategist of the 'Vertical and Horizontal' school and chancellor of Qin, master of the horizontal alliance; a native of Wei; died 309 BCE (his traditional rival Su Qin, whose vertical alliance he opposed; not the later Three Kingdoms generals of the same name)</span></div>","traditional":"張儀","hanzi":"張儀","pinyin":"Zhāng Yí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhāng Yí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhang Yi</b> was the great diplomat of the 'Vertical and Horizontal' school who served Qin, and the master of the 'horizontal' craft of alliance. A poor man of Wei, he owed his rise, so the story goes, to his tongue alone: beaten near to death at a feast on suspicion of stealing a jade, he asked his wife only whether his tongue remained, for with that he could yet make his fortune. And so he did, winning the ear of King Huiwen of Qin, who made him chancellor to direct the state's diplomacy. His method was that 'horizontal' alliance, by which Qin drew the eastern states one at a time into separate pacts — with bribes, flattery, and threats — so they could never form a single front against it. This mirrored the 'vertical' alliance, in which the six eastern states were to unite north to south against Qin — the strategy of Su Qin, his rival in tradition, though the neat duel between them is likely a later invention. <br><br> His most famous stroke was the ruin of Chu. To split Chu from its ally Qi, he promised King Huai six hundred li of Qin land to break the alliance; the greedy king did so, insulting Qi into the bargain. But when Chu came to claim it, Zhang Yi declared he had promised only six li, not six hundred; the cheated king hurled his armies at Qin, only to be crushed at Danyang and stripped of Hanzhong, leaving Chu isolated and broken. By such guile Zhang Yi kept the eastern states divided and weak, helping clear the long road to Qin's mastery of China. When his patron King Huiwen died and the new king turned against him, he slipped away to his native Wei, served briefly as its chancellor, and died there in 309 BCE, his speeches preserved in the <i>Strategies of the Warring States</i>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhang Yi"},
{"id":"cnh-218","num":"二百一十八","category":"China · History","question":"The Warring States masters of persuasion who played the great states against one another — forging the 'vertical' union of the six against Qin, or Qin's 'horizontal' pacts to divide them — the silver-tongued strategists of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lived by eloquence and cunning, and lost their trade when Qin unified China in 221 BCE.","answer":"School of Diplomacy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">School</span><span class=\"dt-v\">縱橫家 — Zònghéngjiā, the 'Vertical and Horizontal' school; the Warring States school of itinerant diplomats and persuaders, named for the vertical (hezong) and horizontal (lianheng) alliance strategies; classified by the Han among the ten schools (a craft of statecraft, not a moral philosophy)</span></div>","traditional":"縱橫家","hanzi":"縱橫家","pinyin":"Zònghéngjiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zònghéngjiā</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>School of Diplomacy</b>, in Chinese the school of the 'Vertical and Horizontal,' was the tradition of the wandering persuaders who advised the warring kings of old on alliances and statecraft. It was no philosophy of ethics or the cosmos, like the Confucians or Daoists, but a practical art of eloquence and calculation — its men rising by their tongues rather than birth, and serving whichever ruler would employ them. Nor was it ever an organized body with a creed: the 'school' is a label the Han laid, looking back, on a type of clever operator, counted among the ten schools of the age. It took its name from the two grand alliance strategies its diplomats devised. The 'vertical' alliance would bind the six eastern states, ranged north to south, into one front against Qin in the west; the 'horizontal' was Qin's answer, allying with the states one by one to break their union. <br><br> Its most famous figures were Su Qin, voice of the vertical union, and Zhang Yi, chancellor of Qin and master of the horizontal — rivals in later legend, though Gongsun Yan was Zhang Yi's true contemporary foe. Tradition traced the whole art to a shadowy master, Guiguzi, the 'Master of Ghost Valley,' whose name marks a surviving manual of persuasion — though the man is half legend and the book of uncertain hand. The dazzling speeches of these persuaders are preserved above all in the <i>Strategies of the Warring States</i>, the great compilation of their words. While the states contended, such men wielded great power despite their lack of rank — though the Confucians scorned them as silver-tongued opportunists loyal to nothing but themselves. Their trade depended on rival states to play against each other, so when Qin unified China in 221 BCE the persuaders lost their stage and the school faded, leaving only their texts and the idiom 'vertical and horizontal.'","citation":"","answerText":"School of Diplomacy"},
{"id":"cnh-219","num":"二百一十九","category":"China · History","question":"Renowned for their thousands of retainers and their stand against Qin — Mengchang of Qi, Pingyuan of Zhao, Xinling of Wei who stole the tiger-tally to save Zhao, and Chunshen of Chu — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> were the great aristocratic patrons of the late 3rd century BCE.","answer":"Four Lords of the Warring States","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Nobles</span><span class=\"dt-v\">戰國四公子 — Zhànguó Sì Gōngzǐ; the four great retainer-keeping lords of the late Warring States — Mengchang of Qi, Pingyuan of Zhao, Xinling of Wei, and Chunshen of Chu; 3rd century BCE ('Lord' 君 is a noble title, not king; a retrospective grouping)</span></div>","traditional":"戰國四公子","hanzi":"戰國四公子","pinyin":"Zhànguó Sì Gōngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhànguó Sì Gōngzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Four Lords of the Warring States</b> were four great noblemen of the 3rd century BCE, each the leading magnate of his state, famed for the crowds of talented retainers he kept. In an age that prized ability, each was said to feed and house some three thousand guest-clients — scholars, strategists, swordsmen, even thieves and tricksters — a following that could rival their own kings. Three were royal kinsmen — Lord Mengchang of Qi, Lord Pingyuan of Zhao, and Lord Xinling of Wei — while the fourth, Lord Chunshen of Chu, was no prince but a minister risen by his gifts. Their names live in famous tales: Mengchang, captive in Qin, escaped by two lowly retainers — one who stole back a fox-fur robe to bribe the king's favourite, and one who crowed like a cock to open the frontier gate at dawn. Pingyuan, seeking allies for besieged Handan, took a delegation to Chu made whole by an overlooked retainer, Mao Sui, who put himself forward and browbeat the Chu king into the alliance. <br><br> The grandest deed was Xinling's. When Qin besieged Handan and Wei's king forbade his army to fight, Xinling had the king's own concubine steal the tiger-tally that commanded it, seized the army — killing its balking general — and marched to save Zhao. That relief of Handan in 257 BCE joined the forces of Zhao, Wei, and Chu and dealt the rising Qin a heavy check; the noblest of the four, Xinling later drove Qin back at the head of a coalition. Chunshen, for his part, had won his lord the throne by smuggling Chu's captive crown prince home from Qin, and ruled as chancellor for a quarter-century. But the schemer Li Yuan had him murdered at the palace gate in 238 BCE — and within a lifetime Qin swept all four states, and such over-mighty lords, away.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Lords of the Warring States"},
{"id":"cnh-220","num":"二百二十","category":"China · History","question":"Fought in 260 BCE between Qin and Zhao, the two mightiest of the Warring States — after Qin's guile lured Zhao into swapping the cautious Lian Po for the untried Zhao Kuo, whom the dread general Bai Qi then surrounded and starved — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended in the slaughter of Zhao's army and the crippling of the last state able to resist Qin.","answer":"Battle of Changping","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Battle</span><span class=\"dt-v\">長平之戰 — Chángpíng zhī zhàn; Qin's annihilation of Zhao's army under Bai Qi, the decisive battle of the Warring States; 260 BCE (not the failed siege of Handan that followed, 259–257 BCE)</span></div>","traditional":"長平之戰","hanzi":"長平之戰","pinyin":"Chángpíng zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chángpíng zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Battle of Changping</b> was the catastrophe of 260 BCE that broke the state of Zhao, the last power able to stand against the rising Qin. It grew from a dispute over Shangdang, a border region its governor handed to Zhao rather than yield to Qin, drawing the two strongest states into war. Zhao's veteran Lian Po, judging open battle too risky, dug in behind strong walls and refused to fight, to wear the invaders down by attrition. But the standoff drained Zhao, and Qin, unable to break the line, turned to guile — spreading word that it feared only young Zhao Kuo and that old Lian Po was a coward, until Zhao's impatient king replaced Lian Po. Zhao Kuo was the well-read but untested son of a famous general, who could talk strategy better than any but had never commanded — his own mother had begged the king against it. <br><br> Qin, learning of the change, secretly gave its army to Bai Qi, its most dreaded general, hiding the switch on pain of death. When Zhao Kuo threw off the defence and marched out, Bai Qi feigned flight, drew him on, then closed two forces behind him — cutting the Zhao army from its supplies and ringing it about. Trapped and starving for some 46 days, the Zhao host made desperate sallies, and Zhao Kuo himself was shot down leading a last breakout. The leaderless army surrendered, and Bai Qi had it slaughtered — the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> say four hundred thousand were put to death, a figure historians think wildly swollen, though mass graves confirm a killing of terrible scale. So Changping shattered Zhao and made Qin's conquest of China all but certain, the decisive battle of the age — yet the cost was heavy, Qin's next assault on Zhao's capital failed, and Bai Qi was soon forced to kill himself.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Changping"},
{"id":"cnh-221","num":"二百二十一","category":"China · History","question":"Qin's undefeated 'Human Butcher,' who crushed Han and Wei at Yique, sacked the Chu capital, and annihilated Zhao's army at Changping, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was at last forced by his own king to fall on his sword in 257 BCE.","answer":"Bai Qi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">General</span><span class=\"dt-v\">白起 — Bái Qǐ, also Gongsun Qi; the peerless Qin general nicknamed the 'Human Butcher,' ennobled Lord Wu'an, victor of Changping; died 257 BCE (served King Zhaoxiang, not Qin Shi Huang; one of the Four Great Generals of the Warring States)</span></div>","traditional":"白起","hanzi":"白起","pinyin":"Bái Qǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bái Qǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Bai Qi</b> was the greatest and most terrible general of the Warring States, a commander of Qin who, by tradition, never lost a battle and earned the grim byword the 'Human Butcher'. Born in Mei of no high birth, he rose through Qin's ladder of military merit under King Zhaoxiang, and later ages counted him among the Four Great Generals of the age. His victories were not defeats of the enemy so much as annihilations of it: at Yique in 293 BCE he shattered the joined armies of Han and Wei, and the histories report 240,000 heads taken. He fell next upon Chu, storming and sacking its capital Ying in 278 BCE, burning the royal tombs and drowning a whole city by damming a river — a blow from which Chu never recovered, and for which he was made Lord Wu'an. More slaughters followed, against Zhao and Wei at Huayang, until every rival had felt his hand. <br><br> His masterpiece was Changping in 260 BCE, where he lured out the army of Zhao under the rash Zhao Kuo, ringed it, and starved it into surrender. Then he had the captives put to death — traditionally four hundred thousand men, a figure surely swollen, though the ground near the field still holds their bones — a massacre that broke Zhao for good. Yet the butcher's fall came swiftly, and not at an enemy's hand. When the chancellor Fan Ju, envying his glory, halted the pursuit and the moment was lost, Bai Qi refused to lead the doomed second assault on Zhao's capital, and his scorn as it failed turned the king against him. In 257 BCE King Zhaoxiang, whom he had served thirty years, sent a sword to Duyou bidding him die — and the histories say he died reflecting that he had earned this end for the host he had slain by treachery at Changping.","citation":"","answerText":"Bai Qi"},
{"id":"cnh-222","num":"二百二十二","category":"China · History","question":"The chief thinker of the Yin-Yang school, who wove the Five Phases and the two cosmic forces into a single grand system, taught that dynasties rise and fall as one phase conquers another, and held China to be but a tiny fraction of a far vaster world, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was courted by kings who swept the road before him.","answer":"Zou Yan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Philosopher</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鄒衍 — Zōu Yǎn; the leading figure of the Yin-Yang school, who systematized the Five Phases into a cosmology and a theory of dynastic change; c. 305–240 BCE, traditional and approximate (of Qi; his works are lost, known through the Shiji; not the statesman Zou Ji)</span></div>","traditional":"鄒衍","hanzi":"鄒衍","pinyin":"Zōu Yǎn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zōu Yǎn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zou Yan</b> was the leading thinker of the Yin-Yang school, who wove the cosmic ideas of his age into one vast system of nature and history. A scholar of Qi's Jixia Academy, he did not invent yin and yang, nor the Five Phases — Wood, Fire, Earth, Metal, Water — but was the first to bind them into a grand, orderly whole. In his cosmology these Phases — forces or agents more than fixed elements — govern the seasons, directions, and colours, so that nature and human affairs could be read as one. From this he drew his famous theory of dynasties: each rules under one Phase, and yields to the next in the order by which the Phases overcome one another, as water quenches fire. By the scheme handed down in his name, Earth ruled under the Yellow Emperor, then Wood, Metal, and Fire under the Xia, Shang, and Zhou — so the next should rule by Water, which the Qin later claimed, honouring black. <br><br> Stranger still was his geography, which made the China of his day but a small part of the world — one of nine such lands, those but one of nine greater continents ringed by a sea. The histories call such teachings 'vast and beyond all proof,' yet in his own day no thinker was more honoured. Kings received him with a sage's rites — one, it is said, sweeping the road before him and building him a palace — courting him far above the Confucians. For beneath the cosmic grandeur his aim was moral, returning always, the histories say, to benevolence, restraint, and the order of ruler and subject. His own writings are all lost, known only through the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i>, yet the system endured: his yin-yang and Five-Phase cosmology, refined by later ages, shaped Chinese medicine, calendars, divination, and the theory by which dynasties claimed the throne.","citation":"","answerText":"Zou Yan"},
{"id":"cnh-223","num":"二百二十三","category":"China · History","question":"The loyal minister of Chu who was slandered and exiled, then drowned himself in the Miluo when Qin sacked his homeland, and whose grief poured into the Li Sao made him China's first great named poet, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the man the Dragon Boat Festival is said to honour.","answer":"Qu Yuan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Poet</span><span class=\"dt-v\">屈原 — Qū Yuán; given name Qu Ping; poet and statesman of Chu, author of the Li Sao and China's first great named poet; c. 340–278 BCE, traditional and approximate (served King Huai; the Dragon Boat Festival, older than he, is traditionally said to commemorate him)</span></div>","traditional":"屈原","hanzi":"屈原","pinyin":"Qū Yuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qū Yuán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qu Yuan</b>, whose given name was Qu Ping, was a nobleman of Chu, a loyal statesman and the first great poet in China to leave his own name on his verse. He served King Huai of Chu as a high minister, and urged him to govern honestly and bind Chu to Qi against the rising Qin. He distrusted Qin's envoy Zhang Yi and warned against his promises, but jealous rivals slandered him, and the misled king cast him from favour. Under Huai's successor he was banished altogether, into the wilds south of the Yangtze, where he wandered in grief for his declining country. When the Qin general Bai Qi stormed the Chu capital, Qu Yuan, in despair at his homeland's ruin, drowned himself in the Miluo River, by tradition on the fifth day of the fifth month. <br><br> The people, the story goes, raced out in boats to seek his body and threw rice to keep the fish from it — and to this the Dragon Boat Festival, older than he but long tied to his name, owes its races and rice dumplings. His fame, though, rests on his poems, wrung from the sorrow of his exile. Where the old <i>Book of Songs</i> of the north was terse and its makers nameless, Qu Yuan founded a new southern verse, the <i>Songs of Chu</i> — lush, dreamlike, thronged with gods, spirit-flights, and fragrant flowers for a pure heart. His masterpiece is the <i>Li Sao</i>, 'Encountering Sorrow,' a long lament in which a wronged, upright man, spurned by a foolish court, roams the heavens seeking an ideal; other works, the <i>Nine Songs</i> and <i>Heavenly Questions</i>, are by tradition his too. So Qu Yuan became China's enduring image of the honest official betrayed and the patriot who dies for his country — and, with the <i>Book of Songs</i>, one of the two wellsprings of later Chinese poetry.","citation":"","answerText":"Qu Yuan"},
{"id":"cnh-224","num":"二百二十四","category":"China · History","question":"Founded by Qu Yuan — the lush, mythic, intensely personal verse of the southern state, full of spirit-journeys, fragrant-flower symbols, and the sighing particle 'xi' — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stands with the Classic of Poetry as one of the two founts of Chinese poetry.","answer":"Chu Ci","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Anthology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">楚辭 — Chǔ Cí, 'Verses of Chu' (Englished 'Songs of the South'); the southern anthology and poetic style centred on Qu Yuan, one of the two fountainheads of Chinese poetry; core poems Warring States, compiled by Liu Xiang in the Han (not the northern Classic of Poetry 詩經)</span></div>","traditional":"楚辭","hanzi":"楚辭","pinyin":"Chǔ Cí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chǔ Cí</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chu Ci</b>, the 'Verses of Chu' or 'Songs of the South,' is both an anthology of ancient poems and the name of the lush southern style they gave to Chinese verse. With the older northern <i>Classic of Poetry</i>, it is counted one of the two fountainheads of Chinese poetry — but where that classic is terse and communal, in short four-beat lines, the Chu Ci is personal, ornate, and the voice of named poets. Its lines are long and irregular, marked by a sighing particle, <i>xi</i>, that falls like a caught breath at the pause of each. Springing from the shaman-haunted culture of the southern state of Chu, its poetry teems with gods and spirit-journeys, flights to the heavens, and river goddesses. Fragrant orchids and herbs stand throughout for a pure heart, rank weeds for corruption, so the verse reads as one long allegory of the good man in an evil age. <br><br> Its heart is Qu Yuan's work — above all the <i>Li Sao</i>, or 'Encountering Sorrow,' whose name came to mark the whole 'sao' style — yet the book is no one man's. It gathers, too, the poems of his follower Song Yu and of later Han imitators, so that only a few pieces are surely Qu Yuan's own. Among its treasures are the <i>Nine Songs</i>, eleven shamanistic hymns despite their name, and the <i>Heavenly Questions</i>, which fires off more than a hundred and seventy riddles of myth and the cosmos — making the anthology one of the richest stores of ancient legend. Though its core poems are of the Warring States, the collection was assembled only later, in the Han, by the scholar Liu Xiang, and given its standard form by Wang Yi soon after. From this southern spring flowed much that followed: the ornate Han rhapsody grew largely from it, and 'the Airs and the Sorrow' became a byword for poetry itself.","citation":"","answerText":"Chu Ci"},
{"id":"cnh-225","num":"二百二十五","category":"China · History","question":"A stammering prince of the doomed state of Han who wove law, statecraft, and raw power into the fullest theory of Legalist rule, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> so dazzled the future First Emperor with his essays that he was summoned to Qin — only to be driven to poison there by his jealous old classmate Li Si in 233 BCE.","answer":"Han Fei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Philosopher</span><span class=\"dt-v\">韓非 — Hán Fēi, honoured as Han Feizi; a prince of the Warring State of Han and the great synthesizer of Legalism; c. 280–233 BCE (the small state 韓, not the Han dynasty 漢; the man, not his book the Han Feizi 韓非子; not his rival Li Si)</span></div>","traditional":"韓非","hanzi":"韓非","pinyin":"Hán Fēi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hán Fēi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Han Fei</b> was the greatest theorist of Legalism, a prince of the small Warring State of Han — not the later dynasty of that name — who gave the school its fullest, coldest form. Where earlier Legalists each pressed one tool, he bound three: the law of Shang Yang, the statecraft of Shen Buhai, and the positional power of Shen Dao — a ruler needing all three. He had studied under the Confucian Xunzi, who held human nature selfish, but drew the reverse lesson: a ruler must trust no one and rule by law and the 'two handles,' punishment and reward, not virtue. The wise ruler keeps his mind unfathomable and lets law and technique run the state, so even a mediocre king rules well. He scorned reverence for the ancient kings — like the farmer who waited by a stump for a second hare — and damned the 'five vermin': scholars, talkers, swordsmen, shirkers, and traders. <br><br> His essays fill the <i>Han Feizi</i>, some 55 chapters of sharp argument — the fullest Legalist work to survive, and keeper of the oldest commentary on the <i>Tao Te Ching</i>. A stammerer and poor speaker but brilliant writer, he had pressed reform on his weak king in vain, and turned his frustration into these pages. By tradition his essays reached the king of Qin — the future First Emperor — who longed to meet their author; when Qin pressed Han, Han Fei was sent there. But his old classmate Li Si, now Qin's minister and fearful of being outshone, is said to have slandered him, jailed him, and sent poison; denied a hearing, Han Fei drank it in 233 BCE, the pardon too late. He never governed, yet his ideas, through Li Si, shaped the Qin state that unified China; and though Legalism was reviled after the Qin fell, its cold arts of law and control stayed within the Confucian state.","citation":"","answerText":"Han Fei"},
{"id":"cnh-226","num":"二百二十六","category":"China · History","question":"The hard-headed rival of Confucianism, which held that a state is ruled not by the virtue of a sage but by strict, impartial law and the whip of reward and punishment — and which, in the hands of Shang Yang and Han Fei, forged the Qin that unified China — <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was reviled after the Qin's fall yet quietly ran the empire ever after.","answer":"Legalism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">School</span><span class=\"dt-v\">法家 — Fǎjiā, 'the school of law and standards'; the Warring States school of realist statecraft — rule by impartial law and punishment under a strong ruler; the ideology of Qin's unification (a retrospective Han label; not the Western theological sense of 'legalism')</span></div>","traditional":"法家","hanzi":"法家","pinyin":"Fǎjiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fǎjiā</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Legalism</b> was the cold, hard-headed school of statecraft that offered the sharpest answer to the Warring States' central question — how to make a state strong. Its answer was not the virtue of a wise ruler, as the Confucians held, but a machinery of clear, impartial law, binding high and low alike, driven by sure rewards and heavy punishments. Its whole aim was the wealth and power of the state — to fill the treasury and strengthen the army — by driving the people to farming and war. It took a bleak view of men, holding them ruled by self-interest and beyond reform by moral example, so that only law and the fear it inspired could hold them to order. So it stood as the great rival of Confucianism — law against virtue, impersonal system against the sage's example, and scorn for the ancient kings against reverence for the past. <br><br> The name 'Legalism' is a label the Han scholars laid, looking back, on a loose company of hard reforming statesmen who never called themselves a school. Later thinkers unravelled it into three threads — the law of Shang Yang, the statecraft of Shen Buhai, and the positional power of Shen Dao — which Han Fei wove into one system in the <i>Han Feizi</i>. Alone among the Hundred Schools, Legalism was actually put to work: it built the disciplined state of Qin and, applied by the chancellor Li Si, carried it to conquer China in 221 BCE. But the Qin empire's harshness and swift collapse disgraced the school; under the Han that followed, Confucianism became the ruling creed and Legalism a byword for tyranny no ruler would openly own. Yet its machinery outlived its disgrace: the bureaucracy, law codes, registers, and arts of control it perfected ran the empire for two thousand years behind a Confucian face — a state, it is often said, Confucian without and Legalist within.","citation":"","answerText":"Legalism"},
{"id":"cnh-227","num":"二百二十七","category":"China · History","question":"The merchant who saw a neglected Qin hostage-prince as 'a rare commodity worth hoarding' and bought him a throne, then ruled as chancellor and 'Second Father' to the boy who became the First Emperor, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sponsored the encyclopedic Lüshi Chunqiu before a palace scandal drove him to poison in 235 BCE.","answer":"Lü Buwei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Statesman</span><span class=\"dt-v\">呂不韋 — Lǚ Bùwéi; the merchant who became chancellor and regent of Qin and patron of the Lüshi Chunqiu; died 235 BCE (chancellor and 'Second Father' to the young King Zheng, later Qin Shi Huang — not the king himself; the paternity tale is doubted legend)</span></div>","traditional":"呂不韋","hanzi":"呂不韋","pinyin":"Lǚ Bùwéi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǚ Bùwéi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lü Buwei</b> was one of the great social climbers of Chinese history — a rich merchant who, in an age that despised his trade, rose to rule the state of Qin. Trading at Handan, the Zhao capital, he met a neglected Qin prince held there as a hostage, Yiren, and judged him, in a phrase the histories preserve, 'a rare commodity worth hoarding'. Spending his own fortune, he groomed the prince and cultivated the childless favourite of Qin's heir, Lady Huayang, until she adopted Yiren — renamed Zichu — as her own son and successor. The gamble paid: Zichu took the throne as King Zhuangxiang and made his backer chancellor and a marquis with a vast fief — a merchant at the summit of the mightiest warring state. When that king died and his boy Zheng — the future First Emperor — succeeded at thirteen, Lü Buwei ruled on as regent, honoured as 'Second Father,' Qin's master in all but name. <br><br> A famous tale, recorded in the histories but doubted as a later slander, holds the boy-king was secretly Lü Buwei's own son — born to a concubine, already pregnant, he had given to Zichu. At his height he kept thousands of scholars, and had them compile a vast encyclopedia, the <i>Lüshi Chunqiu</i>, weaving the teachings of every school into one. So proud of it was he, the story goes, that he hung it at the capital's market gate and offered a thousand gold to any who could better a single word. As King Zheng grew up, his position soured: he had slipped the queen mother, his former lover, a false eunuch named Lao Ai, whose revolt in 238 BCE was crushed and dragged him down. Dismissed and banished, dreading worse, he drank poison and died in 235 BCE — his fall clearing the last obstacle before the king who, within a dozen years, would unify China.","citation":"","answerText":"Lü Buwei"},
{"id":"wh-001","num":"1","category":"World · History","question":"The vast first chapter of prehistory, covering some 99 percent of the human story — the age of chipped-stone tools, hunting and gathering, the mastery of fire, and the first cave art — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave way only when farming began about 12,000 years ago.","answer":"Paleolithic","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">The Old Stone Age; from the first stone tools (c. 3.3–2.6 million years ago) to the end of the last Ice Age (c. 10,000 BCE); from Greek palaios 'old' + lithos 'stone'</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"","pinyin":"","translations":"","abstract":"The <b>Paleolithic</b>, or Old Stone Age, is the earliest and longest stretch of human prehistory, the first great division of the Stone Age. Its name, from the Greek for 'old stone,' was coined in 1865 by John Lubbock, and it is defined by one thing above all: tools of chipped, or knapped, stone. It began with the first such tools, roughly 3.3 to 2.6 million years ago, and ended about 12,000 years ago, as the last Ice Age closed — spanning, by common reckoning, some 99 percent of the human story. Over that span the stoneworking grew steadily finer, from crude Oldowan choppers to the shapely Acheulean hand-axe, the flake tools of the Neanderthals, and at last the slender blades of the late Paleolithic. Through all of it people lived as foragers — hunting wild game, fishing, and gathering plants — in small, wandering bands sheltering in caves and camps, without farms, herds, or settled villages. <br><br> The age was the work not of one people but of many — its toolmakers ranging from early Homo and the far-roaming Homo erectus to the Neanderthals and, from about 300,000 years ago, our own Homo sapiens. Its makers mastered fire for warmth, cooking, and safety, and over the ages spread out of Africa to people almost the whole earth. In its later phase came a flowering of the mind — vivid cave paintings of animals, carved figurines, beads, bone flutes, and the deliberate burial of the dead — signs of art, belief, and language. All of this is known to us only through archaeology and fossils, for the Paleolithic lies wholly before writing, leaving no names, dates, or records of its own. It closed when, in several regions, people began to tame plants and animals and farm — the great turn to agriculture that opened the Neolithic and, in time, the age of villages, cities, and history.","citation":"","answerText":"Paleolithic","i18n":{"es":{"question":"El vasto primer capítulo de la prehistoria, que abarca cerca del 99 por ciento de la historia humana —la época de las herramientas de piedra tallada, la caza y la recolección, el dominio del fuego y el primer arte rupestre—, el <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> solo cedió cuando la agricultura comenzó hace unos 12.000 años.","answer":"Paleolítico","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Época</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La Edad de Piedra Antigua; desde las primeras herramientas de piedra (h. 3,3–2,6 millones de años atrás) hasta el final de la última Edad de Hielo (h. 10.000 a. C.); del griego palaios 'viejo' + lithos 'piedra'</span></div>","abstract":"El <b>Paleolítico</b>, o Edad de Piedra Antigua, es el tramo más temprano y más largo de la prehistoria humana, la primera gran división de la Edad de Piedra. Su nombre, del griego 'piedra vieja', fue acuñado en 1865 por John Lubbock, y se define ante todo por una cosa: herramientas de piedra tallada, o labrada. Comenzó con las primeras de esas herramientas, hace aproximadamente 3,3 a 2,6 millones de años, y terminó hace unos 12.000 años, al cerrarse la última Edad de Hielo, abarcando, según el cómputo común, cerca del 99 por ciento de la historia humana. A lo largo de ese tramo el trabajo de la piedra se volvió cada vez más fino, desde los toscos cantos tallados olduvayenses hasta el elegante bifaz achelense, las herramientas de lasca de los neandertales y, por fin, las esbeltas hojas del Paleolítico tardío. Durante todo ello las personas vivieron como recolectoras —cazando presas salvajes, pescando y recogiendo plantas— en pequeñas bandas errantes que se refugiaban en cuevas y campamentos, sin cultivos, rebaños ni aldeas asentadas. <br><br> La época fue obra no de un solo pueblo sino de muchos, con artesanos que iban desde los primeros Homo y el andariego Homo erectus hasta los neandertales y, desde hace unos 300.000 años, nuestro propio Homo sapiens. Sus autores dominaron el fuego para el calor, la cocina y la seguridad, y a lo largo de las eras se extendieron fuera de África para poblar casi toda la tierra. En su fase tardía llegó un florecimiento de la mente —vívidas pinturas rupestres de animales, figurillas talladas, cuentas, flautas de hueso y el entierro deliberado de los muertos—, señales de arte, creencia y lenguaje. Todo esto lo conocemos solo a través de la arqueología y los fósiles, pues el Paleolítico se sitúa por completo antes de la escritura, sin dejar nombres, fechas ni registros propios. Se cerró cuando, en varias regiones, las personas empezaron a domesticar plantas y animales y a cultivar, el gran giro hacia la agricultura que abrió el Neolítico y, con el tiempo, la era de las aldeas, las ciudades y la historia.","answerText":"Paleolítico"},"fr":{"question":"Le vaste premier chapitre de la préhistoire, couvrant environ 99 pour cent de l'histoire humaine — l'âge des outils de pierre taillée, de la chasse et de la cueillette, de la maîtrise du feu et des premiers arts pariétaux —, le <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ne céda la place qu'avec l'apparition de l'agriculture il y a environ 12 000 ans.","answer":"Paléolithique","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Époque</span><span class=\"dt-v\">L'âge de la pierre taillée ; depuis les premiers outils de pierre il y a env. 3,3 à 2,6 millions d'années jusqu'à la fin de la dernière période glaciaire vers 10 000 av. J.-C. ; du grec palaios « ancien » + lithos « pierre »</span></div>","abstract":"Le <b>Paléolithique</b>, ou âge de la pierre taillée, est la période la plus ancienne et la plus longue de la préhistoire humaine, la première grande division de l'âge de la pierre. Son nom, tiré du grec signifiant « pierre ancienne », fut forgé en 1865 par John Lubbock, et il se définit avant tout par une chose : des outils de pierre éclatée, ou taillée. Il débuta avec ces premiers outils, il y a environ 3,3 à 2,6 millions d'années, et prit fin il y a quelque 12 000 ans, à la clôture de la dernière période glaciaire — embrassant, selon le décompte courant, environ 99 pour cent de l'histoire humaine. Au fil de cette étendue, le travail de la pierre se fit sans cesse plus fin, du grossier chopper oldowayen au biface acheuléen bien proportionné, aux outils sur éclat des Néandertaliens, et enfin aux fines lames du Paléolithique récent. Durant toute cette période, les hommes vécurent en chasseurs-cueilleurs — chassant le gibier sauvage, pêchant et cueillant des plantes — au sein de petites bandes nomades s'abritant dans des grottes et des campements, sans champs, sans troupeaux ni villages sédentaires. <br><br> Cet âge fut l'œuvre non d'un seul peuple mais de beaucoup — ses artisans allant des premiers Homo et de l'Homo erectus au vaste rayon d'action jusqu'aux Néandertaliens et, depuis environ 300 000 ans, à notre propre Homo sapiens. Ses acteurs maîtrisèrent le feu pour se chauffer, cuire les aliments et se protéger, et au fil des âges se répandirent hors d'Afrique pour peupler presque toute la terre. Dans sa phase tardive vint un épanouissement de l'esprit — des peintures pariétales saisissantes d'animaux, des figurines sculptées, des perles, des flûtes en os et l'inhumation délibérée des morts —, signes d'art, de croyance et de langage. Tout cela ne nous est connu que par l'archéologie et les fossiles, car le Paléolithique se situe entièrement avant l'écriture, ne laissant ni noms, ni dates, ni archives qui lui soient propres. Il s'acheva lorsque, dans plusieurs régions, les hommes commencèrent à domestiquer plantes et animaux et à cultiver — le grand tournant vers l'agriculture qui ouvrit le Néolithique et, avec le temps, l'âge des villages, des villes et de l'histoire.","answerText":"Paléolithique"},"de":{"question":"Das gewaltige erste Kapitel der Vorgeschichte, das rund 99 Prozent der Menschheitsgeschichte umfasst — das Zeitalter der geschlagenen Steinwerkzeuge, des Jagens und Sammelns, der Beherrschung des Feuers und der ersten Höhlenmalerei — das <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> wich erst, als vor etwa 12.000 Jahren der Ackerbau begann.","answer":"Paläolithikum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Epoche</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Die Altsteinzeit; von den ersten Steinwerkzeugen (vor etwa 3,3–2,6 Millionen Jahren) bis zum Ende der letzten Eiszeit (etwa 10.000 v. Chr.); von griechisch palaios „alt“ + lithos „Stein“</span></div>","abstract":"Das <b>Paläolithikum</b>, oder die Altsteinzeit, ist der früheste und längste Abschnitt der menschlichen Vorgeschichte, die erste große Untergliederung der Steinzeit. Sein Name, aus dem Griechischen für „alter Stein“, wurde 1865 von John Lubbock geprägt, und es ist vor allem durch eine Sache bestimmt: Werkzeuge aus geschlagenem, also zugehauenem Stein. Es begann mit den ersten derartigen Werkzeugen vor rund 3,3 bis 2,6 Millionen Jahren und endete vor etwa 12.000 Jahren, als die letzte Eiszeit ausklang — und umspannt damit nach gängiger Rechnung rund 99 Prozent der Menschheitsgeschichte. Über diese Zeitspanne wurde die Steinbearbeitung stetig feiner, von groben Oldowan-Choppern über den wohlgeformten Acheuléen-Faustkeil und die Abschlagwerkzeuge der Neandertaler bis hin zu den schlanken Klingen des Jungpaläolithikums. Die ganze Zeit hindurch lebten die Menschen als Wildbeuter — sie jagten Wild, fischten und sammelten Pflanzen — in kleinen, umherziehenden Gruppen, die in Höhlen und Lagern Schutz fanden, ohne Felder, Herden oder feste Dörfer. <br><br> Das Zeitalter war das Werk nicht eines einzigen Volkes, sondern vieler — seine Werkzeugmacher reichten von den frühen Homo und dem weit umherstreifenden Homo erectus über die Neandertaler bis hin, seit etwa 300.000 Jahren, zu unserem eigenen Homo sapiens. Seine Schöpfer beherrschten das Feuer zum Wärmen, Kochen und Schutz und breiteten sich über die Zeitalter aus Afrika aus, um fast die ganze Erde zu besiedeln. In seiner späteren Phase kam ein Erblühen des Geistes — lebendige Höhlenmalereien von Tieren, geschnitzte Figurinen, Perlen, Knochenflöten und die absichtliche Bestattung der Toten — Zeichen von Kunst, Glaube und Sprache. All dies ist uns allein durch die Archäologie und durch Fossilien bekannt, denn das Paläolithikum liegt gänzlich vor der Schrift und hinterließ keine eigenen Namen, Daten oder Aufzeichnungen. Es endete, als in mehreren Regionen die Menschen begannen, Pflanzen und Tiere zu zähmen und Ackerbau zu treiben — die große Hinwendung zur Landwirtschaft, die das Neolithikum einleitete und mit der Zeit das Zeitalter der Dörfer, Städte und der Geschichte.","answerText":"Paläolithikum"},"it":{"question":"Il vasto primo capitolo della preistoria, che copre circa il 99 percento della vicenda umana — l'età degli utensili di pietra scheggiata, della caccia e raccolta, del dominio del fuoco e delle prime pitture rupestri — il <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lasciò il posto ad altro solo quando l'agricoltura ebbe inizio circa 12.000 anni fa.","answer":"Paleolitico","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">L'età della pietra antica; dai primi utensili litici, c. 3,3–2,6 milioni di anni fa, alla fine dell'ultima era glaciale, c. 10.000 a.C.; dal greco palaios 'antico' + lithos 'pietra'</span></div>","abstract":"Il <b>Paleolitico</b>, o età della pietra antica, è il tratto più remoto e più lungo della preistoria umana, la prima grande suddivisione dell'età della pietra. Il suo nome, dal greco per 'pietra antica', fu coniato nel 1865 da John Lubbock, ed è definito soprattutto da una cosa: gli utensili di pietra scheggiata, o lavorata a percussione. Ebbe inizio con i primi utensili di questo tipo, all'incirca 3,3–2,6 milioni di anni fa, e terminò circa 12.000 anni fa, al chiudersi dell'ultima era glaciale — abbracciando, secondo la stima comune, circa il 99 percento della vicenda umana. Nel corso di quel periodo la lavorazione della pietra si fece via via più raffinata, dai rozzi chopper olduvaiani alla ben modellata bifacciale acheuleana, agli utensili su scheggia dei Neanderthal e infine alle sottili lame del Paleolitico superiore. Per tutto questo tempo gli uomini vissero come raccoglitori — cacciando selvaggina, pescando e raccogliendo vegetali — in piccole bande nomadi che trovavano riparo in grotte e accampamenti, senza campi coltivati, greggi o villaggi stabili. <br><br> Quell'età fu opera non di un solo popolo ma di molti — i suoi artefici andavano dai primi Homo e dall'Homo erectus dai lunghi spostamenti fino ai Neanderthal e, da circa 300.000 anni fa, alla nostra stessa specie, l'Homo sapiens. I suoi fabbri dominarono il fuoco per riscaldarsi, cuocere il cibo e proteggersi, e nel corso delle epoche si diffusero fuori dall'Africa fino a popolare quasi l'intera terra. Nella sua fase più tarda giunse una fioritura dell'ingegno — vivide pitture rupestri di animali, statuette scolpite, perline, flauti d'osso e la sepoltura intenzionale dei morti — segni di arte, credenza e linguaggio. Tutto ciò ci è noto solo attraverso l'archeologia e i fossili, poiché il Paleolitico si colloca interamente prima della scrittura, senza lasciare nomi, date o testimonianze proprie. Si concluse quando, in diverse regioni, gli uomini cominciarono ad addomesticare piante e animali e a coltivare la terra — la grande svolta verso l'agricoltura che aprì il Neolitico e, col tempo, l'età dei villaggi, delle città e della storia.","answerText":"Paleolitico"},"nl":{"question":"Het immense eerste hoofdstuk van de prehistorie, dat zo'n 99 procent van het menselijke verhaal beslaat — het tijdperk van bewerkte stenen werktuigen, jagen en verzamelen, de beheersing van het vuur en de eerste grotkunst — het <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> maakte pas plaats voor iets anders toen zo'n 12.000 jaar geleden de landbouw opkwam.","answer":"Paleolithicum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Tijdperk</span><span class=\"dt-v\">De Oude Steentijd; van de eerste stenen werktuigen (ca. 3,3–2,6 miljoen jaar geleden) tot het einde van de laatste ijstijd (ca. 10.000 v.Chr.); van het Griekse palaios 'oud' + lithos 'steen'</span></div>","abstract":"Het <b>Paleolithicum</b>, of de Oude Steentijd, is de vroegste en langste periode van de menselijke prehistorie, de eerste grote onderverdeling van de steentijd. De naam, uit het Grieks voor 'oude steen', werd in 1865 bedacht door John Lubbock, en het wordt vóór alles bepaald door één ding: werktuigen van bewerkte, oftewel afgeslagen, steen. Het begon met de eerste van zulke werktuigen, ruwweg 3,3 tot 2,6 miljoen jaar geleden, en eindigde zo'n 12.000 jaar geleden, toen de laatste ijstijd ten einde liep — en beslaat daarmee, naar gangbare schatting, zo'n 99 procent van het menselijke verhaal. In die tijdspanne werd de steenbewerking gestaag verfijnder, van ruwe Oldowan-hakwerktuigen tot de fraai gevormde Acheuléen-vuistbijl, de afslagwerktuigen van de neanderthalers en ten slotte de slanke klingen van het late paleolithicum. Al die tijd leefden mensen als jager-verzamelaars — ze joegen op wild, visten en verzamelden planten — in kleine, rondtrekkende groepen die schuilden in grotten en kampementen, zonder akkers, veestapels of vaste dorpen. <br><br> Het tijdperk was niet het werk van één mensensoort maar van vele — de werktuigmakers liepen uiteen van vroege Homo en de wijd zwervende Homo erectus tot de neanderthalers en, vanaf zo'n 300.000 jaar geleden, onze eigen Homo sapiens. De makers beheersten het vuur voor warmte, het bereiden van voedsel en veiligheid, en verspreidden zich in de loop der eeuwen vanuit Afrika om bijna de hele aarde te bevolken. In de latere fase kwam er een bloei van de geest — levendige grotschilderingen van dieren, gebeeldhouwde beeldjes, kralen, benen fluiten en het bewuste begraven van de doden — tekenen van kunst, geloof en taal. Dit alles kennen wij enkel door archeologie en fossielen, want het paleolithicum ligt volledig vóór het schrift en liet geen eigen namen, data of geschriften na. Het eindigde toen mensen in verschillende streken planten en dieren begonnen te temmen en aan landbouw te doen — de grote omslag naar de landbouw die het neolithicum inluidde en, na verloop van tijd, het tijdperk van dorpen, steden en geschiedenis.","answerText":"Paleolithicum"},"ru":{"question":"Огромная первая глава доисторической эпохи, охватывающая около 99 процентов человеческой истории, — эпоха орудий из оббитого камня, охоты и собирательства, овладения огнём и первого пещерного искусства, — <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> уступил место лишь тогда, когда около 12 000 лет назад зародилось земледелие.","answer":"Палеолит","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Эпоха</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Древний каменный век; от первых каменных орудий (ок. 3,3–2,6 млн лет назад) до конца последнего ледникового периода (ок. 10 000 г. до н. э.); от греческого palaios «древний» + lithos «камень»</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Палеолит</b>, или древний каменный век, — самый ранний и самый длительный период человеческой предыстории, первое великое подразделение каменного века. Его название, происходящее от греческих слов со значением «древний камень», было предложено в 1865 году Джоном Лаббоком, и определяется он прежде всего одним: орудиями из оббитого, или расколотого, камня. Он начался с первых таких орудий — примерно 3,3–2,6 млн лет назад — и завершился около 12 000 лет назад, с окончанием последнего ледникового периода, охватив, по общепринятым оценкам, около 99 процентов человеческой истории. На этом протяжении обработка камня неуклонно совершенствовалась — от грубых олдувайских чопперов до изящного ашёльского ручного рубила, отщеповых орудий неандертальцев и, наконец, тонких пластин позднего палеолита. Всё это время люди жили как собиратели и охотники — добывая дичь, ловя рыбу и собирая растения — небольшими кочующими группами, укрывавшимися в пещерах и стоянках, без полей, стад и постоянных селений. <br><br> Эта эпоха — дело не одного народа, а многих: её создатели орудий простирались от ранних людей рода Homo и широко расселившегося Homo erectus до неандертальцев и, примерно с 300 000 лет назад, нашего собственного вида Homo sapiens. Её носители овладели огнём ради тепла, приготовления пищи и безопасности и на протяжении веков расселились из Африки, заселив почти всю землю. В его поздней фазе наступил расцвет разума — яркие пещерные росписи с изображением животных, вырезанные фигурки, бусины, костяные флейты и намеренные погребения умерших — признаки искусства, веры и языка. Всё это известно нам лишь по данным археологии и ископаемым находкам, ибо палеолит целиком предшествует письменности, не оставив ни собственных имён, ни дат, ни записей. Он завершился, когда в нескольких областях люди начали одомашнивать растения и животных и заниматься земледелием, — великий поворот к сельскому хозяйству, открывший неолит, а со временем и эпоху селений, городов и истории.","answerText":"Палеолит"},"ar":{"question":"الفصل الأول الهائل من عصور ما قبل التاريخ، الذي يشمل نحو 99 في المئة من قصة الإنسان — عصر أدوات الحجر المشظّى، والصيد والالتقاط، والسيطرة على النار، وأول الفنون الكهفية — لم يفسح <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> المجال إلا حين بدأت الزراعة قبل نحو 12,000 عام.","answer":"العصر الحجري القديم","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">العصر</span><span class=\"dt-v\">العصر الحجري القديم؛ من أول الأدوات الحجرية (نحو 3.3–2.6 مليون سنة مضت) إلى نهاية العصر الجليدي الأخير (نحو 10,000 قبل الميلاد)؛ من اليونانية palaios 'قديم' + lithos 'حجر'</span></div>","abstract":"<b>العصر الحجري القديم</b>، وهو أوّل العصور الحجرية وأقدمها، هو أقدم وأطول حقبة من عصور ما قبل التاريخ البشري، وأول تقسيم كبير من العصر الحجري. واسمه، المشتق من اليونانية بمعنى 'الحجر القديم'، صاغه جون لوبوك عام 1865، وهو يُعرَّف قبل كل شيء بأمر واحد: أدوات من الحجر المشظّى أو المنحوت بالطَّرق. بدأ بأول تلك الأدوات، نحو 3.3 إلى 2.6 مليون سنة مضت، وانتهى قبل نحو 12,000 عام مع انقضاء العصر الجليدي الأخير — مستغرقاً، وفق التقدير الشائع، نحو 99 في المئة من قصة الإنسان. وعلى امتداد تلك الحقبة تحسّنت صناعة الحجر باطّراد، من مقاطع الأولدوان الخشنة إلى الفأس اليدوية الأشولية المصقولة، وأدوات الشظايا لدى إنسان نياندرتال، وأخيراً النِّصال الرفيعة من أواخر العصر الحجري القديم. وطوال ذلك كله عاش الناس جامعين للقوت — يصطادون الطرائد البرية، ويصيدون السمك، ويجمعون النباتات — في جماعات صغيرة متنقّلة تأوي إلى الكهوف والمخيمات، دون مزارع أو قطعان أو قرى مستقرة. <br><br> ولم يكن هذا العصر صنيعة شعب واحد بل شعوب كثيرة — إذ تنوّع صانعو أدواته من أشكال الإنسان الأولى والإنسان المنتصب الواسع الترحال إلى إنسان نياندرتال، ثم، منذ نحو 300,000 عام، نوعنا نحن الإنسان العاقل. وأتقن صانعوه استخدام النار للتدفئة والطهي والأمان، وانتشروا عبر العصور خارج أفريقيا حتى عمروا الأرض كلها تقريباً. وفي طوره المتأخر تفتّق العقل عن إبداع — رسوم كهفية نابضة للحيوانات، وتماثيل منحوتة، وخرز، ونايات عظمية، ودفن الموتى المتعمَّد — دلائل على الفن والمعتقد واللغة. ولا نعرف كل ذلك إلا من خلال علم الآثار والأحافير، إذ يقع العصر الحجري القديم بأكمله قبل الكتابة، فلم يترك أسماء ولا تواريخ ولا سجلات خاصة به. وانتهى حين شرع الناس، في عدة مناطق، في استئناس النبات والحيوان والزراعة — ذلك التحوّل العظيم إلى الفلاحة الذي فتح العصر الحجري الحديث، ثم بمرور الوقت عصر القرى والمدن والتاريخ.","answerText":"العصر الحجري القديم"},"zh":{"question":"史前史宏大的第一章,涵盖了人类历史约99%的时光——这是打制石器、狩猎采集、掌握用火以及最早洞穴艺术的时代——<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>直到约1.2万年前农业兴起时才宣告终结。","answer":"旧石器时代","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">时代</span><span class=\"dt-v\">旧石器时代;从最早的石器——约330万至260万年前——到末次冰期结束——约公元前1万年;源自希腊语 palaios(意为\"旧\")加 lithos(意为\"石\")</span></div>","abstract":"<b>旧石器时代</b>又称旧石器时期,是人类史前史最早也最漫长的阶段,是石器时代的第一个大分期。它的名称源自希腊语\"旧石头\"一词,由约翰·卢伯克于1865年提出,而其最根本的定义在于一件事:打制或敲琢而成的石器。它始于约330万至260万年前最早的这类石器,止于约1.2万年前末次冰期结束之时,按通常的估算,横跨了人类历史约99%的时光。在这段漫长的岁月里,石器制作日益精细,从粗糙的奥杜韦砍砸器,到造型匀整的阿舍利手斧,到尼安德特人的石片工具,最终发展为旧石器时代晚期纤细的石叶。自始至终,人们都以采集狩猎为生——猎取野兽、捕鱼、采集植物——结成小股流动的群体,栖身于洞穴与营地,没有农田、畜群或定居的村落。 <br><br> 这个时代并非某一支人群的作为,而是众多人群共同书写的——其工具制造者从早期人属、四处迁徙的直立人,到尼安德特人,再到约30万年前登场的我们智人。他们掌握了用火来取暖、烹煮和御险,并在漫长的岁月中走出非洲,几乎遍布整个地球。在其晚期,人类的心智迎来一次绽放——栩栩如生的动物洞穴壁画、雕刻的小雕像、串珠、骨笛,以及有意为之的丧葬——这些都是艺术、信仰与语言的印记。所有这一切,我们只能通过考古与化石得知,因为旧石器时代完全处于文字出现之前,没有留下自己的姓名、年代或记录。它的终结,发生在若干地区的人们开始驯化动植物、从事农耕之时——这场伟大的农业转向开启了新石器时代,并最终迎来村落、城市与历史的时代。","answerText":"旧石器时代"}}},
{"id":"wh-002","num":"2","category":"World · History","question":"The earliest and by far the longest of the three subdivisions of the Old Stone Age, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> runs from the first chipped-stone tools to about 300,000 years ago and is defined by two toolkits — the plain Oldowan chopper and the teardrop Acheulean hand-axe — made by early humans such as Homo habilis and Homo erectus.","answer":"Lower Paleolithic","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">The earliest and longest phase of the Old Stone Age; from the first stone tools, c. 2.6 million years ago — or c. 3.3 million years ago on contested evidence — to c. 300,000 years ago, when the Middle Paleolithic began</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"","pinyin":"","translations":"","abstract":"The <b>Lower Paleolithic</b> is the earliest and by far the longest of the three divisions of the Old Stone Age, the opening chapter in the human record of stone tools. It begins with the first flaked-stone tools — conventionally about 2.6 million years ago, though disputed finds from Lomekwi in Kenya may push toolmaking back toward 3.3 million years ago — and it closes roughly 300,000 years ago. The word Paleolithic, from the Greek for old stone, was coined by John Lubbock in 1865, and prehistorians later divided its immense span into a Lower, a Middle, and an Upper phase. As the lowest and oldest of the three, this period alone accounts for nearly nine-tenths of the entire Old Stone Age, a stretch of well over 2 million years. Across all of it people lived as small, wandering bands of hunter-gatherers, without farms, villages, pottery, metal, or any form of writing. <br><br> The age is defined above all by two great traditions of stone tools, each named for the site where it was first recognised. The older is the Oldowan, named for Olduvai Gorge in Tanzania and made of simple cores and sharp flakes struck from pebbles, while the later Acheulean, named for Saint-Acheul in France, produced the symmetrical teardrop hand-axe that became one of the longest-lived tool designs ever made. Its toolmakers were early members of the human family rather than people like us: the Oldowan is usually credited to Homo habilis, while the hand-axe and the great dispersal out of Africa belong above all to Homo erectus, whose fossils at Dmanisi in Georgia are the oldest known outside the continent. Whether these hominins had learned to control fire remains genuinely uncertain, and only the later part of the period offers widely accepted evidence of hearths. The Lower Paleolithic ends not with a sudden change but with a new skill — the shaping of a stone core to strike off a preplanned flake, the prepared-core method that opens the Middle Paleolithic and its later worlds of Neanderthals, blades, burial, and cave art.","citation":"","answerText":"Lower Paleolithic","i18n":{"es":{"question":"La primera y con diferencia la más larga de las tres subdivisiones de la Edad de Piedra Antigua, el <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> se extiende desde las primeras herramientas de piedra tallada hasta hace unos 300.000 años y se define por dos conjuntos de útiles — el sencillo canto tallado olduvayense y el bifaz achelense en forma de lágrima — fabricados por humanos primitivos como Homo habilis y Homo erectus.","answer":"Paleolítico Inferior","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La fase más temprana y más larga de la Edad de Piedra Antigua; desde las primeras herramientas de piedra, hace unos 2,6 millones de años — o hace unos 3,3 millones de años según pruebas discutidas — hasta hace unos 300.000 años, cuando comenzó el Paleolítico Medio</span></div>","abstract":"El <b>Paleolítico Inferior</b> es la primera y con diferencia la más larga de las tres divisiones de la Edad de Piedra Antigua, el capítulo inicial del registro humano de herramientas de piedra. Comienza con las primeras herramientas de piedra tallada — convencionalmente hace unos 2,6 millones de años, aunque hallazgos discutidos de Lomekwi, en Kenia, podrían retrasar la fabricación de útiles hasta cerca de 3,3 millones de años — y se cierra hace aproximadamente 300.000 años. La palabra Paleolítico, del griego que significa piedra antigua, fue acuñada por John Lubbock en 1865, y los prehistoriadores dividieron más tarde su inmenso lapso en una fase inferior, una media y una superior. Como la más baja y antigua de las tres, este período representa por sí solo casi nueve décimas partes de toda la Edad de Piedra Antigua, un lapso de bastante más de 2 millones de años. A lo largo de todo él las personas vivieron como pequeñas bandas errantes de cazadores-recolectores, sin granjas, aldeas, cerámica, metal ni forma alguna de escritura. <br><br> La época se define ante todo por dos grandes tradiciones de herramientas de piedra, cada una nombrada por el yacimiento donde se reconoció por primera vez. La más antigua es la olduvayense, llamada así por la garganta de Olduvai, en Tanzania, y compuesta de núcleos simples y lascas afiladas extraídas de guijarros, mientras que la posterior achelense, llamada así por Saint-Acheul, en Francia, produjo el bifaz simétrico en forma de lágrima que llegó a ser uno de los diseños de herramienta más longevos jamás creados. Sus fabricantes de útiles eran miembros primitivos de la familia humana y no personas como nosotros: el olduvayense se atribuye por lo general a Homo habilis, mientras que el bifaz y la gran dispersión fuera de África corresponden ante todo a Homo erectus, cuyos fósiles de Dmanisi, en Georgia, son los más antiguos que se conocen fuera del continente. Si estos homínidos habían aprendido a controlar el fuego sigue siendo genuinamente incierto, y solo la parte final del período ofrece pruebas ampliamente aceptadas de hogares. El Paleolítico Inferior no termina con un cambio repentino, sino con una nueva destreza — la talla de un núcleo de piedra para extraer una lasca planificada de antemano, el método de núcleo preparado que abre el Paleolítico Medio y sus mundos posteriores de neandertales, hojas, enterramientos y arte rupestre.","answerText":"Paleolítico Inferior"},"fr":{"question":"La plus ancienne et de loin la plus longue des trois subdivisions de l'âge de la pierre taillée, le <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> s'étend des premiers outils de pierre taillée jusqu'à environ 300 000 ans avant le présent et se définit par deux industries lithiques — le chopper oldowayen sommaire et le biface acheuléen en forme de larme — façonnées par des hommes primitifs tels que Homo habilis et Homo erectus.","answer":"Paléolithique inférieur","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Époque</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La phase la plus ancienne et la plus longue de l'âge de la pierre taillée ; des premiers outils de pierre, il y a environ 2,6 millions d'années — ou environ 3,3 millions d'années selon des données contestées — jusqu'à environ 300 000 ans, lorsque débute le Paléolithique moyen</span></div>","abstract":"Le <b>Paléolithique inférieur</b> est la plus ancienne et de loin la plus longue des trois divisions de l'âge de la pierre taillée, le chapitre inaugural de l'histoire humaine des outils de pierre. Il commence avec les premiers outils de pierre taillée — vers 2,6 millions d'années selon la convention, bien que des découvertes contestées à Lomekwi, au Kenya, puissent faire remonter la taille de la pierre jusqu'à environ 3,3 millions d'années — et il s'achève il y a environ 300 000 ans. Le mot paléolithique, formé du grec signifiant pierre ancienne, fut forgé par John Lubbock en 1865, et les préhistoriens en subdivisèrent plus tard l'immense durée en une phase inférieure, une phase moyenne et une phase supérieure. Étant la plus basse et la plus ancienne des trois, cette période représente à elle seule près des neuf dixièmes de tout l'âge de la pierre taillée, un intervalle de bien plus de 2 millions d'années. Durant toute cette étendue, les hommes vécurent en petites bandes errantes de chasseurs-cueilleurs, sans cultures, villages, poterie, métal ni aucune forme d'écriture. <br><br> Cette époque se définit avant tout par deux grandes traditions d'outils de pierre, chacune nommée d'après le site où elle fut reconnue pour la première fois. La plus ancienne est l'Oldowayen, nommé d'après les gorges d'Olduvai en Tanzanie et constitué de simples nucléus et d'éclats tranchants détachés de galets, tandis que l'Acheuléen, plus récent et nommé d'après Saint-Acheul en France, produisit le biface symétrique en forme de larme, qui devint l'un des modèles d'outil les plus durables jamais conçus. Ses artisans étaient des membres primitifs de la famille humaine et non des hommes semblables à nous : l'Oldowayen est habituellement attribué à Homo habilis, tandis que le biface et la grande dispersion hors d'Afrique reviennent avant tout à Homo erectus, dont les fossiles de Dmanissi, en Géorgie, sont les plus anciens connus hors du continent. La question de savoir si ces hominidés avaient appris à maîtriser le feu demeure véritablement incertaine, et seule la fin de la période offre des témoignages largement admis de foyers. Le Paléolithique inférieur s'achève non par un changement soudain mais par un savoir-faire nouveau — le façonnage d'un nucléus de pierre pour en détacher un éclat prédéterminé, la méthode du nucléus préparé qui inaugure le Paléolithique moyen et ses mondes ultérieurs de Néandertaliens, de lames, de sépultures et d'art pariétal.","answerText":"Paléolithique inférieur"},"de":{"question":"Als früheste und mit Abstand längste der drei Unterabteilungen der Altsteinzeit reicht das <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> von den ersten geschlagenen Steinwerkzeugen bis vor etwa 300.000 Jahren und ist durch zwei Werkzeuggruppen gekennzeichnet — den schlichten Oldowan-Chopper und den tropfenförmigen Faustkeil des Acheuléen —, die von frühen Menschenformen wie Homo habilis und Homo erectus hergestellt wurden.","answer":"Altpaläolithikum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Epoche</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Die früheste und längste Phase der Altsteinzeit; von den ersten Steinwerkzeugen vor etwa 2,6 Millionen Jahren — oder vor etwa 3,3 Millionen Jahren nach umstrittenen Belegen — bis vor etwa 300.000 Jahren, als das Mittelpaläolithikum begann</span></div>","abstract":"Das <b>Altpaläolithikum</b> ist die früheste und mit Abstand längste der drei Abteilungen der Altsteinzeit und bildet das Eröffnungskapitel in der menschlichen Geschichte der Steinwerkzeuge. Es beginnt mit den ersten geschlagenen Steinwerkzeugen — herkömmlich vor etwa 2,6 Millionen Jahren, auch wenn umstrittene Funde aus Lomekwi in Kenia die Werkzeugherstellung bis auf etwa 3,3 Millionen Jahre zurückdatieren könnten — und endet vor rund 300.000 Jahren. Das Wort Paläolithikum, aus dem Griechischen für alter Stein, prägte John Lubbock im Jahr 1865, und Vorgeschichtsforscher gliederten seine gewaltige Zeitspanne später in eine untere, eine mittlere und eine obere Phase. Als unterste und älteste der drei umfasst allein dieser Abschnitt fast neun Zehntel der gesamten Altsteinzeit, eine Spanne von weit über 2 Millionen Jahren. Während dieser ganzen Zeit lebten die Menschen als kleine, umherziehende Gruppen von Jägern und Sammlern, ohne Felder, Dörfer, Töpferei, Metall oder irgendeine Form von Schrift. <br><br> Das Zeitalter wird vor allem durch zwei große Traditionen von Steinwerkzeugen bestimmt, jede benannt nach dem Fundort, an dem sie zuerst erkannt wurde. Die ältere ist das Oldowan, benannt nach der Olduvai-Schlucht in Tansania und aus einfachen Kernen und scharfen Abschlägen gefertigt, die von Geröllen abgeschlagen wurden, während das spätere Acheuléen, benannt nach Saint-Acheul in Frankreich, den symmetrischen tropfenförmigen Faustkeil hervorbrachte, der zu einem der langlebigsten Werkzeugentwürfe aller Zeiten wurde. Seine Werkzeugmacher waren frühe Angehörige der Menschheitsfamilie und keine Menschen wie wir: Das Oldowan wird gewöhnlich Homo habilis zugeschrieben, während der Faustkeil und die große Ausbreitung aus Afrika vor allem Homo erectus zukommen, dessen Fossilien in Dmanissi in Georgien die ältesten außerhalb des Kontinents bekannten sind. Ob diese Homininen das Feuer zu beherrschen gelernt hatten, bleibt wirklich ungewiss, und erst der spätere Teil des Zeitraums liefert weithin anerkannte Belege für Feuerstellen. Das Altpaläolithikum endet nicht mit einem plötzlichen Wandel, sondern mit einer neuen Fertigkeit — dem Zurichten eines Steinkerns, um von ihm einen vorab geplanten Abschlag zu gewinnen, der Technik des vorbereiteten Kerns, die das Mittelpaläolithikum und seine späteren Welten der Neandertaler, Klingen, Bestattungen und Höhlenkunst eröffnet.","answerText":"Altpaläolithikum"},"it":{"question":"La più antica e di gran lunga la più lunga delle tre suddivisioni dell'antica età della pietra, il <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> va dai primi utensili in pietra scheggiata fino a circa 300.000 anni fa ed è definito da due industrie litiche — il semplice chopper olduvaiano e il bifacciale acheuleano a goccia — realizzati da esseri umani arcaici come Homo habilis e Homo erectus.","answer":"Paleolitico inferiore","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Epoca</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La fase più antica e più lunga dell'antica età della pietra; dai primi utensili litici, circa 2,6 milioni di anni fa — o circa 3,3 milioni di anni fa secondo prove contestate — fino a circa 300.000 anni fa, quando ebbe inizio il Paleolitico medio</span></div>","abstract":"Il <b>Paleolitico inferiore</b> è il più antico e di gran lunga il più lungo dei tre periodi in cui si divide l'antica età della pietra, il capitolo iniziale della storia umana degli utensili in pietra. Comincia con i primi strumenti in pietra scheggiata — convenzionalmente circa 2,6 milioni di anni fa, sebbene ritrovamenti discussi di Lomekwi in Kenya potrebbero retrodatare la fabbricazione di utensili fino a circa 3,3 milioni di anni fa — e si chiude all'incirca 300.000 anni fa. Il termine Paleolitico, dal greco che significa pietra antica, fu coniato da John Lubbock nel 1865, e in seguito i preistorici divisero il suo immenso arco temporale in una fase inferiore, una media e una superiore. In quanto la più bassa e la più antica delle tre, questa fase da sola rappresenta quasi nove decimi dell'intera antica età della pietra, un intervallo di ben oltre 2 milioni di anni. Per tutta la sua durata gli esseri umani vissero come piccole bande erranti di cacciatori-raccoglitori, senza campi coltivati, villaggi, ceramica, metalli né alcuna forma di scrittura. <br><br> L'epoca è definita soprattutto da due grandi tradizioni di strumenti litici, ciascuna chiamata così dal sito in cui fu riconosciuta per la prima volta. La più antica è l'Olduvaiano, che prende nome dalla gola di Olduvai in Tanzania ed è costituito da semplici nuclei e da schegge taglienti ricavate da ciottoli, mentre il successivo Acheuleano, che prende nome da Saint-Acheul in Francia, produsse il bifacciale simmetrico a goccia, divenuto uno dei modelli di utensile più longevi mai realizzati. I suoi artefici furono membri arcaici della famiglia umana piuttosto che individui simili a noi: l'Olduvaiano è di solito attribuito a Homo habilis, mentre il bifacciale e la grande dispersione fuori dall'Africa appartengono soprattutto a Homo erectus, i cui fossili di Dmanisi in Georgia sono i più antichi conosciuti al di fuori del continente. Se questi ominini avessero imparato a controllare il fuoco resta genuinamente incerto, e solo la parte più tarda del periodo offre prove ampiamente accettate di focolari. Il Paleolitico inferiore non termina con un cambiamento improvviso ma con una nuova abilità — la sagomatura di un nucleo di pietra per staccarne una scheggia predeterminata, il metodo del nucleo preparato che apre il Paleolitico medio e i suoi mondi successivi di Neanderthal, lame, sepolture e arte rupestre.","answerText":"Paleolitico inferiore"},"nl":{"question":"Het vroegste en verreweg langste van de drie onderverdelingen van de Oude Steentijd, het <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> loopt van de eerste geslagen stenen werktuigen tot ongeveer 300.000 jaar geleden en wordt bepaald door twee gereedschapstradities — de eenvoudige Oldowan-chopper en de druppelvormige Acheuléense vuistbijl — vervaardigd door vroege mensen zoals Homo habilis en Homo erectus.","answer":"Vroeg-paleolithicum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Tijdvak</span><span class=\"dt-v\">De vroegste en langste fase van de Oude Steentijd; van de eerste stenen werktuigen, ca. 2,6 miljoen jaar geleden — of ca. 3,3 miljoen jaar geleden volgens betwist bewijs — tot ca. 300.000 jaar geleden, toen het Midden-paleolithicum begon</span></div>","abstract":"Het <b>Vroeg-paleolithicum</b> is het vroegste en verreweg langste van de drie onderverdelingen van de Oude Steentijd, het openingshoofdstuk in de menselijke geschiedenis van stenen werktuigen. Het begint met de eerste geslagen stenen werktuigen — conventioneel ongeveer 2,6 miljoen jaar geleden, hoewel omstreden vondsten uit Lomekwi in Kenia het maken van werktuigen mogelijk terugduwen tot bijna 3,3 miljoen jaar geleden — en het eindigt ruwweg 300.000 jaar geleden. Het woord paleolithicum, van het Grieks voor oude steen, werd in 1865 bedacht door John Lubbock, en prehistorici verdeelden de immense tijdspanne later in een vroege, een midden- en een late fase. Als de laagste en oudste van de drie beslaat deze periode alleen al bijna negen tiende van de gehele Oude Steentijd, een tijdspanne van ruim 2 miljoen jaar. Gedurende dit alles leefden mensen als kleine, rondtrekkende groepen jager-verzamelaars, zonder boerderijen, dorpen, aardewerk, metaal of enige vorm van schrift. <br><br> Het tijdvak wordt vooral gekenmerkt door twee grote tradities van stenen werktuigen, elk genoemd naar de vindplaats waar zij voor het eerst werd herkend. De oudere is het Oldowan, genoemd naar de Olduvaikloof in Tanzania en gemaakt van eenvoudige kernen en scherpe afslagen die van keien werden geslagen, terwijl het latere Acheuléen, genoemd naar Saint-Acheul in Frankrijk, de symmetrische druppelvormige vuistbijl voortbracht die een van de langstlevende gereedschapsontwerpen ooit werd. De makers ervan waren vroege leden van de menselijke stamboom in plaats van mensen zoals wij: het Oldowan wordt gewoonlijk toegeschreven aan Homo habilis, terwijl de vuistbijl en de grote uittocht uit Afrika vooral toebehoren aan Homo erectus, wiens fossielen bij Dmanisi in Georgië de oudste zijn die buiten het continent bekend zijn. Of deze hominiden hadden geleerd vuur te beheersen blijft werkelijk onzeker, en alleen het latere deel van de periode biedt breed aanvaard bewijs van haardvuren. Het Vroeg-paleolithicum eindigt niet met een plotselinge verandering maar met een nieuwe vaardigheid — het vormen van een stenen kern om er een vooraf geplande afslag van te slaan, de methode van geprepareerde kernen die het Midden-paleolithicum inluidt en zijn latere werelden van neanderthalers, klingen, begravingen en grotkunst.","answerText":"Vroeg-paleolithicum"},"ru":{"question":"Самый ранний и, безусловно, самый долгий из трёх подразделов древнего каменного века, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> длится от первых оббитых каменных орудий примерно до 300 000 лет назад и определяется двумя наборами орудий — простым олдувайским чоппером и каплевидным ашёльским рубилом, — которые изготавливали древние люди, такие как Homo habilis и Homo erectus.","answer":"Нижний палеолит","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Эпоха</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Самая ранняя и самая долгая фаза древнего каменного века; от первых каменных орудий, около 2,6 миллиона лет назад — или около 3,3 миллиона лет назад по спорным данным — до примерно 300 000 лет назад, когда начался средний палеолит</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Нижний палеолит</b> — самый ранний и, безусловно, самый долгий из трёх разделов древнего каменного века, начальная глава в истории каменных орудий человечества. Он начинается с первых оббитых каменных орудий — условно около 2,6 миллиона лет назад, хотя спорные находки из Ломекви в Кении, возможно, отодвигают изготовление орудий к 3,3 миллиона лет назад, — и завершается примерно 300 000 лет назад. Слово «палеолит», от греческого «древний камень», ввёл Джон Леббок в 1865 году, а позднее исследователи доисторической эпохи разделили этот огромный промежуток на нижнюю, среднюю и верхнюю фазы. Будучи самым нижним и самым древним из трёх, один этот период охватывает почти девять десятых всего древнего каменного века — промежуток значительно более 2 миллионов лет. На всём его протяжении люди жили небольшими кочующими группами охотников-собирателей, без земледелия, деревень, керамики, металла и какой-либо письменности. <br><br> Эта эпоха определяется прежде всего двумя великими традициями каменных орудий, каждая из которых названа по месту, где была впервые распознана. Более древняя — олдувайская культура, названная по Олдувайскому ущелью в Танзании и представленная простыми нуклеусами и острыми отщепами, сколотыми с галек, тогда как более поздняя ашёльская культура, названная по Сент-Ашёлю во Франции, дала симметричное каплевидное рубило, ставшее одной из самых долговечных конструкций орудий за всю историю. Её создателями были ранние представители человеческого рода, а не подобные нам люди: олдувайскую культуру обычно приписывают Homo habilis, тогда как рубило и великое расселение из Африки принадлежат прежде всего Homo erectus, чьи ископаемые остатки в Дманиси в Грузии — древнейшие из известных за пределами континента. Научились ли эти гоминиды управлять огнём, остаётся по-настоящему неясным, и лишь более поздняя часть периода даёт общепризнанные свидетельства существования очагов. Нижний палеолит завершается не внезапной переменой, а новым умением — приданием каменному нуклеусу такой формы, чтобы сколоть заранее задуманный отщеп, техникой подготовленного нуклеуса, которая открывает средний палеолит и его позднейшие миры неандертальцев, пластин, погребений и пещерной живописи.","answerText":"Нижний палеолит"},"ar":{"question":"بوصفه أقدم الأقسام الفرعية الثلاثة للعصر الحجري القديم وأطولها على الإطلاق، يمتدّ <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> من أولى الأدوات الحجرية المُشظّاة إلى نحو 300,000 سنة مضت، ويُعرَّف بمجموعتين من الأدوات — قاطع الأولدوان البسيط والفأس اليدوية الأشولية على هيئة قطرة الدمع — صنعها بشرٌ أوائل مثل الإنسان الماهر والإنسان المنتصب.","answer":"العصر الحجري القديم الأسفل","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">الحقبة</span><span class=\"dt-v\">أقدم مراحل العصر الحجري القديم وأطولها؛ من أولى الأدوات الحجرية، نحو 2.6 مليون سنة مضت — أو نحو 3.3 مليون سنة مضت وفق أدلّة متنازع عليها — إلى نحو 300,000 سنة مضت، حين بدأ العصر الحجري القديم الأوسط</span></div>","abstract":"يُعدّ <b>العصر الحجري القديم الأسفل</b> أقدم الأقسام الثلاثة للعصر الحجري القديم وأطولها على الإطلاق، وهو الفصل الافتتاحي في سجلّ البشرية للأدوات الحجرية. يبدأ بأولى الأدوات الحجرية المُشظّاة — عُرفاً نحو 2.6 مليون سنة مضت، وإن كانت اكتشافات مثيرة للجدل من لوميكوي في كينيا قد تُرجِع صناعة الأدوات إلى نحو 3.3 مليون سنة مضت — وينتهي عند نحو 300,000 سنة مضت. صاغ جون لوبوك كلمة «العصر الحجري القديم»، المشتقّة من اليونانية بمعنى الحجر القديم، سنة 1865، ثمّ قسّم علماء ما قبل التاريخ مداه الهائل لاحقاً إلى مرحلة أسفل وأوسط وأعلى. وبوصفها أدنى الثلاث وأقدمها، تستأثر هذه الفترة وحدها بنحو تسعة أعشار العصر الحجري القديم بأكمله، وهي حقبة تتجاوز 2 مليون سنة بكثير. وطوال هذه المدّة كلّها عاش الناس في جماعات صغيرة متنقّلة من الصيّادين وجامعي الثمار، بلا مزارع ولا قرى ولا فخّار ولا معادن ولا أيّ شكل من أشكال الكتابة. <br><br> تتحدّد هذه الحقبة قبل كلّ شيء بتقليدين عظيمين من الأدوات الحجرية، سُمّي كلٌّ منهما باسم الموقع الذي عُرف فيه أوّل مرة. أقدمهما الأولدوان، المسمّى نسبةً إلى أخدود أولدوفاي في تنزانيا والمصنوع من نويّات بسيطة ورقائق حادّة تُقتطع من الحصى، بينما أنتج الأشولي اللاحق، المسمّى نسبةً إلى سانت أشول في فرنسا، الفأس اليدوية المتناظرة على هيئة قطرة الدمع التي غدت واحداً من أطول تصاميم الأدوات عمراً على الإطلاق. وكان صانعو أدواتها من أوائل أفراد العائلة البشرية لا من بشرٍ مثلنا: إذ يُنسب الأولدوان عادةً إلى الإنسان الماهر، بينما تعود الفأس اليدوية والانتشار الكبير خارج أفريقيا قبل كلّ شيء إلى الإنسان المنتصب، الذي تُعدّ أحافيره في دمانيسي بجورجيا الأقدم المعروفة خارج القارة. ويبقى من غير المؤكّد حقّاً ما إذا كان أشباه البشر هؤلاء قد تعلّموا التحكّم في النار، ولا يقدّم إلّا الجزء المتأخّر من الفترة أدلّةً مقبولةً على نطاق واسع على مواقد النار. ولا ينتهي العصر الحجري القديم الأسفل بتغيّرٍ مفاجئ بل بمهارة جديدة — تشكيل نويّة حجرية لاقتطاع رقاقة مُخطَّط لها مسبقاً، وهي طريقة النويّة المُهيّأة التي تفتتح العصر الحجري القديم الأوسط وعوالمه اللاحقة من إنسان نياندرتال والنصال والدفن وفنّ الكهوف.","answerText":"العصر الحجري القديم الأسفل"},"zh":{"question":"作为旧石器时代三个分期中最早、也远为最长的一段,<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>从最早的打制石器一直延续到约30万年前,并以两套工具组合为标志——朴素的奥杜韦砍砸器与泪滴形的阿舍利手斧——它们由能人、直立人等早期人类制作。","answer":"旧石器时代早期","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">时代</span><span class=\"dt-v\">旧石器时代最早、最长的阶段;从约260万年前最早的石器开始——或据有争议的证据为约330万年前——直到约30万年前旧石器时代中期开始</span></div>","abstract":"<b>旧石器时代早期</b>是旧石器时代三个分期中最早、也远为最长的一段,是人类石器史的开篇。它始于最早的打制石器——通常认为约在260万年前,尽管肯尼亚洛梅奎有争议的发现可能把制作工具的历史上推至约330万年前——而结束于约30万年前。\"旧石器\"一词源自希腊语,意为古老的石头,由约翰·卢伯克于1865年提出,史前学家后来将这一漫长时段划分为早、中、晚三期。作为三期中最低、最古老的一期,仅这一时期就占据了整个旧石器时代的近九成,时间跨度远超200万年。在其全程之中,人们都以小群流动的狩猎采集者为生,没有农田、村落、陶器、金属,也没有任何形式的文字。 <br><br> 这一时代最主要以两大石器传统为标志,每一传统都以其首次被辨识的遗址命名。较早的是奥杜韦文化,以坦桑尼亚的奥杜瓦伊峡谷命名,由从砾石上打下的简单石核与锋利石片构成;较晚的阿舍利文化则以法国的圣阿舍尔命名,制作出对称的泪滴形手斧,成为有史以来沿用最久的工具样式之一。其制作者是人类家族的早期成员,而非我们这样的人:奥杜韦文化通常归功于能人,而手斧以及走出非洲的大迁徙则首先归属于直立人,其在格鲁吉亚德马尼西的化石是这块大陆以外已知最古老的。这些古人类是否已学会控制火,仍确实存在疑问,只有这一时期的较晚阶段才提供了被广泛接受的炉灶证据。旧石器时代早期的结束并非源于某种突变,而是源于一项新技能——修整石核以打下预先设计好的石片,这种预制石核技术开启了旧石器时代中期,以及其后尼安德特人、石叶、埋葬与洞穴艺术的世界。","answerText":"旧石器时代早期"}}},
{"id":"wh-003","num":"3","category":"World · History","question":"Sitting between the age of the hand-axe and the age of the cave painters, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the middle stretch of the Old Stone Age, running from about 300,000 to 40,000 years ago and marked by the Levallois method of striking a preplanned flake from a shaped core — above all the world of the Neanderthals and their Mousterian tools.","answer":"Middle Paleolithic","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">The middle phase of the Old Stone Age; from the spread of prepared-core Levallois toolmaking, c. 300,000 years ago, to the rise of the Upper Paleolithic, c. 50,000–40,000 years ago; the age of the Neanderthals and the Mousterian</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"","pinyin":"","translations":"","abstract":"The <b>Middle Paleolithic</b> is the central of the three divisions of the Old Stone Age, the long chapter that falls between the hand-axe cultures before it and the blade-and-art cultures after. It runs, by convention, from roughly 300,000 to about 40,000 years ago, though both edges are gradual and shift from region to region rather than marking any single moment. Its opening is defined not by a date but by a technique — the prepared-core, or Levallois, method, in which a stoneworker shapes a core in advance so that a flake of planned size and form can be struck off in a single blow. This Mode 3 toolmaking replaced the older Acheulean hand-axe with lighter, standardised flakes that could be fitted to shafts to make composite tools such as stone-tipped spears. In Europe and western Asia the period is above all the world of the Neanderthals, whose typical toolkit, rich in scrapers and points, is called the Mousterian after the French rock-shelter of Le Moustier. <br><br> Yet the Neanderthals were not alone: the Denisovans ranged across Asia, and early members of our own species, Homo sapiens, were already present, meeting Neanderthals in the Near East at sites such as Skhul and Qafzeh. Because the same Levallois and Mousterian methods were used by both Neanderthals and early modern humans, the stone tools by themselves often cannot reveal which kind of human made them. The matching African record, which belongs to Homo sapiens rather than Neanderthals, is given a separate name, the Middle Stone Age, and it carries the strongest early hints of symbolic life — pieces of ochre engraved with patterns and pierced shell beads from sites such as Blombos Cave. Firm evidence shows they mastered fire and cooking, hunted large game, and glued stone points to shafts with tar, though claims of deliberate burial, art, and ritual remain debated and far less certain. The Middle Paleolithic closes as the Upper Paleolithic begins, about 40,000 years ago, when modern humans spread widely, blade tools and carved ornaments multiplied, and the Neanderthals faded away — the famous figurative cave paintings belong to that later age, not to this one.","citation":"","answerText":"Middle Paleolithic","i18n":{"es":{"question":"Situado entre la época del bifaz y la época de los pintores rupestres, el <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> es el tramo intermedio de la Edad de Piedra Antigua, que abarca desde hace unos 300.000 hasta hace 40.000 años y se define por el método Levallois de extraer una lasca preconcebida de un núcleo tallado —ante todo el mundo de los neandertales y sus útiles musterienses.","answer":"Paleolítico medio","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Época</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La fase intermedia de la Edad de Piedra Antigua; desde la difusión de la talla Levallois de núcleo preparado, hacia hace 300.000 años, hasta el surgimiento del Paleolítico superior, hacia hace 50.000–40.000 años; la época de los neandertales y el Musteriense</span></div>","abstract":"El <b>Paleolítico medio</b> es la división central de las tres que componen la Edad de Piedra Antigua, el largo capítulo que se sitúa entre las culturas del bifaz que lo precedieron y las culturas de las hojas y el arte que lo siguieron. Por convención se extiende desde hace aproximadamente 300.000 hasta cerca de 40.000 años, aunque ambos límites son graduales y varían de una región a otra en lugar de señalar un momento único. Su comienzo no se define por una fecha sino por una técnica —el método de núcleo preparado, o Levallois, en el que el tallador da forma al núcleo de antemano para poder extraer de un solo golpe una lasca de tamaño y forma previstos. Esta talla de Modo 3 sustituyó el antiguo bifaz achelense por lascas más ligeras y estandarizadas que podían enmangarse para fabricar útiles compuestos como lanzas con punta de piedra. En Europa y el oeste de Asia el periodo es ante todo el mundo de los neandertales, cuyo utillaje característico, rico en raederas y puntas, se denomina Musteriense por el abrigo rocoso francés de Le Moustier. <br><br> Sin embargo, los neandertales no estaban solos: los denisovanos se extendían por Asia, y ya estaban presentes los primeros miembros de nuestra propia especie, Homo sapiens, que coincidieron con los neandertales en el Próximo Oriente en yacimientos como Skhul y Qafzeh. Como tanto los neandertales como los primeros humanos modernos emplearon los mismos métodos Levallois y musteriense, los útiles de piedra por sí solos a menudo no permiten saber qué clase de humano los fabricó. El registro africano equivalente, que corresponde a Homo sapiens y no a los neandertales, recibe un nombre distinto, la Edad de Piedra Media, y aporta los indicios tempranos más sólidos de una vida simbólica —fragmentos de ocre grabados con motivos y cuentas de concha perforadas procedentes de yacimientos como la Cueva de Blombos. Pruebas firmes muestran que dominaron el fuego y la cocción, cazaron grandes presas y fijaron puntas de piedra a los mangos con brea, aunque las afirmaciones sobre enterramientos deliberados, arte y ritual siguen siendo objeto de debate y mucho menos seguras. El Paleolítico medio termina cuando comienza el Paleolítico superior, hace unos 40.000 años, cuando los humanos modernos se expandieron ampliamente, los útiles laminares y los adornos tallados se multiplicaron y los neandertales se extinguieron —las famosas pinturas rupestres figurativas pertenecen a esa época posterior, no a esta.","answerText":"Paleolítico medio"},"fr":{"question":"Situé entre l'âge du biface et celui des peintres des cavernes, le <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> est la période médiane du Paléolithique, s'étendant d'environ 300 000 à 40 000 ans avant le présent et caractérisé par la méthode Levallois, consistant à détacher d'un nucléus mis en forme un éclat prédéterminé — avant tout le monde des Néandertaliens et de leur outillage moustérien.","answer":"Paléolithique moyen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Époque</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La phase médiane du Paléolithique ; de la diffusion du débitage Levallois à nucléus préparé, il y a environ 300 000 ans, à l'essor du Paléolithique supérieur, il y a environ 50 000–40 000 ans ; l'âge des Néandertaliens et du Moustérien</span></div>","abstract":"Le <b>Paléolithique moyen</b> est la subdivision centrale des trois grandes divisions du Paléolithique, le long chapitre qui s'insère entre les cultures du biface qui le précèdent et les cultures de la lame et de l'art qui le suivent. Il s'étend, par convention, d'environ 300 000 à quelque 40 000 ans avant le présent, même si ses deux bornes sont progressives et varient d'une région à l'autre plutôt que de marquer un instant précis. Son commencement se définit non par une date mais par une technique — le débitage à nucléus préparé, dit méthode Levallois, où le tailleur met en forme le nucléus à l'avance afin qu'un éclat de dimension et de forme voulues puisse en être détaché d'un seul coup. Ce mode 3 de fabrication remplaça le biface acheuléen plus ancien par des éclats plus légers et standardisés, susceptibles d'être emmanchés pour composer des outils composites tels que des épieux à pointe de pierre. En Europe et en Asie occidentale, cette période est avant tout le monde des Néandertaliens, dont l'outillage caractéristique, riche en racloirs et en pointes, est appelé moustérien d'après l'abri-sous-roche français du Moustier. <br><br> Pourtant, les Néandertaliens n'étaient pas seuls : les Dénisoviens parcouraient l'Asie, et les premiers représentants de notre propre espèce, Homo sapiens, étaient déjà présents, croisant les Néandertaliens au Proche-Orient sur des sites comme Skhul et Qafzeh. Parce que les mêmes méthodes Levallois et moustérienne étaient employées tant par les Néandertaliens que par les premiers hommes modernes, les outils de pierre à eux seuls ne permettent souvent pas de déterminer quel type d'humain les a façonnés. Le corpus africain correspondant, qui relève d'Homo sapiens et non des Néandertaliens, porte un nom distinct, le Middle Stone Age, et livre les indices précoces les plus solides d'une vie symbolique — des morceaux d'ocre gravés de motifs et des perles de coquillage percées provenant de sites comme la grotte de Blombos. Des preuves solides montrent qu'ils maîtrisaient le feu et la cuisson, chassaient le gros gibier et fixaient des pointes de pierre à des manches à l'aide de goudron, même si les affirmations de sépulture délibérée, d'art et de rituel demeurent débattues et bien moins assurées. Le Paléolithique moyen s'achève lorsque commence le Paléolithique supérieur, il y a environ 40 000 ans, quand les hommes modernes se répandirent largement, que les outils sur lame et les ornements sculptés se multiplièrent et que les Néandertaliens s'éteignirent — les célèbres peintures rupestres figuratives appartiennent à cet âge postérieur, non à celui-ci.","answerText":"Paléolithique moyen"},"de":{"question":"Zwischen dem Zeitalter des Faustkeils und dem Zeitalter der Höhlenmaler gelegen, bildet das <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> den mittleren Abschnitt der Altsteinzeit, der von etwa 300.000 bis 40.000 Jahren vor heute reicht und durch die Levalloistechnik geprägt ist, bei der ein vorgeplanter Abschlag von einem zugerichteten Kern geschlagen wird — vor allem die Welt der Neandertaler und ihrer Moustérien-Werkzeuge.","answer":"Mittelpaläolithikum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Epoche</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Die mittlere Phase der Altsteinzeit; von der Ausbreitung der Levalloistechnik mit vorbereitetem Kern, ca. 300.000 Jahre vor heute, bis zum Aufkommen des Jungpaläolithikums, ca. 50.000–40.000 Jahre vor heute; das Zeitalter der Neandertaler und des Moustérien</span></div>","abstract":"Das <b>Mittelpaläolithikum</b> ist der mittlere der drei Abschnitte der Altsteinzeit, jenes lange Kapitel, das zwischen den vorangehenden Faustkeilkulturen und den nachfolgenden Klingen- und Kunstkulturen liegt. Es reicht per Konvention von etwa 300.000 bis rund 40.000 Jahren vor heute, wobei beide Grenzen fließend sind und sich von Region zu Region verschieben, statt einen einzelnen Zeitpunkt zu bezeichnen. Sein Beginn wird nicht durch ein Datum, sondern durch eine Technik bestimmt — die Kernvorbereitungs- oder Levalloistechnik, bei der ein Steinbearbeiter einen Kern im Voraus so zurichtet, dass sich ein Abschlag von geplanter Größe und Form mit einem einzigen Schlag ablösen lässt. Diese Werkzeugherstellung des Modus 3 ersetzte den älteren Faustkeil des Acheuléen durch leichtere, standardisierte Abschläge, die sich an Schäfte anbringen ließen, um zusammengesetzte Geräte wie steinbewehrte Speere herzustellen. In Europa und Westasien ist die Epoche vor allem die Welt der Neandertaler, deren typisches, an Schabern und Spitzen reiches Werkzeuginventar nach dem französischen Abri Le Moustier als Moustérien bezeichnet wird. <br><br> Doch die Neandertaler waren nicht allein: Die Denisova-Menschen waren über Asien verbreitet, und frühe Angehörige unserer eigenen Art, Homo sapiens, waren bereits vorhanden und trafen im Nahen Osten an Fundorten wie Skhul und Qafzeh mit Neandertalern zusammen. Da dieselben Levallois- und Moustérien-Methoden sowohl von Neandertalern als auch von frühen modernen Menschen verwendet wurden, können die Steinwerkzeuge allein oft nicht verraten, welche Menschenform sie hergestellt hat. Der entsprechende afrikanische Befund, der zu Homo sapiens und nicht zu den Neandertalern gehört, trägt einen eigenen Namen, die Middle Stone Age, und liefert die stärksten frühen Hinweise auf ein symbolisches Leben — mit Mustern gravierte Ockerstücke und durchbohrte Muschelperlen von Fundorten wie der Blombos-Höhle. Gesicherte Belege zeigen, dass sie Feuer und Kochen beherrschten, Großwild jagten und Steinspitzen mit Teer an Schäften befestigten, während Behauptungen über absichtliche Bestattungen, Kunst und Rituale umstritten und weit weniger gesichert bleiben. Das Mittelpaläolithikum endet mit dem Beginn des Jungpaläolithikums vor etwa 40.000 Jahren, als sich die modernen Menschen weit ausbreiteten, Klingengeräte und geschnitzter Schmuck sich vermehrten und die Neandertaler verschwanden — die berühmten figürlichen Höhlenmalereien gehören jenem späteren Zeitalter an, nicht diesem hier.","answerText":"Mittelpaläolithikum"},"it":{"question":"Collocato tra l'età del bifacciale e l'età dei pittori delle caverne, il <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> è il tratto intermedio dell'Antica età della pietra, che va da circa 300.000 a 40.000 anni fa ed è contraddistinto dal metodo Levallois, con cui si stacca da un nucleo sagomato una scheggia dalla forma predefinita — soprattutto il mondo dei Neanderthaliani e dei loro utensili musteriani.","answer":"Paleolitico medio","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Era</span><span class=\"dt-v\">La fase intermedia dell'Antica età della pietra; dalla diffusione della lavorazione litica Levallois a nucleo preparato, circa 300.000 anni fa, all'avvento del Paleolitico superiore, circa 50.000–40.000 anni fa; l'età dei Neanderthaliani e del Musteriano</span></div>","abstract":"Il <b>Paleolitico medio</b> è la parte centrale delle tre suddivisioni dell'Antica età della pietra, il lungo capitolo che si colloca tra le culture del bifacciale che lo precedono e le culture della lama e dell'arte che lo seguono. Per convenzione va da circa 300.000 a circa 40.000 anni fa, benché entrambi i limiti siano graduali e mutino da regione a regione anziché segnare un momento preciso. Il suo inizio è definito non da una data ma da una tecnica — il metodo a nucleo preparato, o Levallois, con cui l'artigiano della pietra sagoma in anticipo un nucleo affinché una scheggia di dimensione e forma pianificate possa essere staccata con un solo colpo. Questa lavorazione di Modo 3 sostituì il più antico bifacciale acheuleano con schegge più leggere e standardizzate, che potevano essere fissate a manici per realizzare utensili compositi come le lance con punta di pietra. In Europa e in Asia occidentale il periodo è soprattutto il mondo dei Neanderthaliani, il cui corredo tipico, ricco di raschiatoi e punte, è chiamato Musteriano dal riparo sotto roccia francese di Le Moustier. <br><br> Eppure i Neanderthaliani non erano soli: i Denisoviani si estendevano per l'Asia, e i primi rappresentanti della nostra stessa specie, Homo sapiens, erano già presenti e incontravano i Neanderthaliani nel Vicino Oriente in siti come Skhul e Qafzeh. Poiché gli stessi metodi Levallois e Musteriano erano impiegati sia dai Neanderthaliani sia dai primi uomini moderni, gli utensili litici da soli spesso non permettono di stabilire quale tipo di uomo li abbia fabbricati. La corrispondente documentazione africana, che appartiene a Homo sapiens e non ai Neanderthaliani, porta un nome distinto, Middle Stone Age, e reca i più forti indizi precoci di una vita simbolica — pezzi di ocra incisi con motivi e perline di conchiglia forate da siti come la grotta di Blombos. Prove solide mostrano che padroneggiavano il fuoco e la cottura, cacciavano grossa selvaggina e fissavano punte di pietra ai manici con la pece, sebbene le ipotesi di sepolture intenzionali, arte e rituali restino dibattute e assai meno certe. Il Paleolitico medio si chiude con l'inizio del Paleolitico superiore, circa 40.000 anni fa, quando gli uomini moderni si diffusero ampiamente, gli utensili a lama e gli ornamenti intagliati si moltiplicarono e i Neanderthaliani scomparvero — le celebri pitture rupestri figurative appartengono a quell'età successiva, non a questa.","answerText":"Paleolitico medio"},"nl":{"question":"Gelegen tussen het tijdperk van de vuistbijl en dat van de grotschilders vormt het <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> het middendeel van de Oude Steentijd, dat loopt van ongeveer 300.000 tot 40.000 jaar geleden en wordt gekenmerkt door de levalloistechniek waarbij een vooraf ontworpen afslag van een bewerkte kern wordt geslagen — bovenal de wereld van de neanderthalers en hun moustérienwerktuigen.","answer":"Midden-paleolithicum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Tijdperk</span><span class=\"dt-v\">De middelste fase van de Oude Steentijd; van de verspreiding van de levalloistechniek met voorbewerkte kernen, ca. 300.000 jaar geleden, tot de opkomst van het Laat-paleolithicum, ca. 50.000–40.000 jaar geleden; het tijdperk van de neanderthalers en het Moustérien</span></div>","abstract":"Het <b>Midden-paleolithicum</b> is de middelste van de drie onderdelen van de Oude Steentijd, het lange hoofdstuk dat valt tussen de vuistbijlculturen ervoor en de kling-en-kunstculturen erna. Het loopt, volgens afspraak, van ruwweg 300.000 tot ongeveer 40.000 jaar geleden, hoewel beide grenzen geleidelijk zijn en van streek tot streek verschuiven in plaats van een enkel moment te markeren. Het begin ervan wordt niet bepaald door een datum maar door een techniek — de methode van de voorbewerkte kern, ofwel de levalloistechniek, waarbij een steenbewerker een kern vooraf zo vormt dat een afslag van geplande grootte en vorm er in één slag kan worden afgeslagen. Deze werktuigproductie van modus 3 verving de oudere Acheuléen-vuistbijl door lichtere, gestandaardiseerde afslagen die aan schachten konden worden bevestigd om samengestelde werktuigen zoals speren met stenen punt te maken. In Europa en West-Azië is de periode bovenal de wereld van de neanderthalers, wier typische gereedschapskist, rijk aan schrabbers en spitsen, het Moustérien wordt genoemd naar de Franse abri Le Moustier. <br><br> Toch waren de neanderthalers niet alleen: de denisovamensen leefden verspreid over Azië, en vroege vertegenwoordigers van onze eigen soort, Homo sapiens, waren al aanwezig en ontmoetten de neanderthalers in het Nabije Oosten op vindplaatsen zoals Skhul en Qafzeh. Doordat dezelfde levallois- en moustérienmethoden zowel door neanderthalers als door vroegmoderne mensen werden gebruikt, kunnen de stenen werktuigen op zichzelf vaak niet onthullen welk soort mens ze heeft gemaakt. Het overeenkomstige Afrikaanse verslag, dat toebehoort aan Homo sapiens en niet aan de neanderthalers, krijgt een aparte naam, de Middle Stone Age, en het bevat de sterkste vroege aanwijzingen voor een symbolisch leven — stukken oker met ingekerfde patronen en doorboorde schelpkralen van vindplaatsen zoals de Blombosgrot. Stevig bewijs toont aan dat zij vuur en het koken beheersten, op groot wild jaagden en stenen punten met teer aan schachten lijmden, hoewel beweringen over doelbewuste begravingen, kunst en rituelen omstreden en veel minder zeker blijven. Het Midden-paleolithicum eindigt wanneer het Laat-paleolithicum begint, ongeveer 40.000 jaar geleden, wanneer moderne mensen zich wijd verspreidden, klingwerktuigen en gesneden versieringen zich vermenigvuldigden en de neanderthalers verdwenen — de beroemde figuratieve grotschilderingen behoren tot dat latere tijdperk, niet tot dit.","answerText":"Midden-paleolithicum"},"ru":{"question":"Располагаясь между эпохой ручного рубила и эпохой пещерных художников, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> представляет собой средний отрезок древнего каменного века, продолжавшийся примерно от 300 000 до 40 000 лет назад и отмеченный техникой леваллуа — сколом заранее спланированного отщепа с подготовленного нуклеуса, — прежде всего это мир неандертальцев и их мустьерских орудий.","answer":"Средний палеолит","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Эпоха</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Средняя фаза древнего каменного века; от распространения леваллуазской обработки камня с подготовленным нуклеусом, около 300 000 лет назад, до становления верхнего палеолита, около 50 000–40 000 лет назад; эпоха неандертальцев и мустье</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Средний палеолит</b> — центральный из трёх разделов древнего каменного века, долгая глава, которая располагается между предшествующими ей культурами ручного рубила и следующими за ней культурами пластин и искусства. По принятому соглашению он длится примерно от 300 000 до около 40 000 лет назад, хотя обе границы размыты и смещаются от региона к региону, а не отмечают какой-либо один момент. Его начало определяется не датой, а техникой — методом подготовленного нуклеуса, или техникой леваллуа, при которой мастер заранее оформляет нуклеус, чтобы отщеп задуманного размера и формы можно было отделить одним ударом. Эта обработка камня третьего технологического уклада заменила прежнее ашельское рубило более лёгкими, стандартизированными отщепами, которые можно было крепить к древкам, создавая составные орудия вроде копий с каменными наконечниками. В Европе и Западной Азии эта эпоха — прежде всего мир неандертальцев, чей типичный набор орудий, богатый скрёблами и остриями, называется мустьерским по французскому скальному навесу Ле-Мустье. <br><br> Однако неандертальцы были не одни: по Азии расселялись денисовцы, а ранние представители нашего собственного вида, Homo sapiens, уже присутствовали, встречаясь с неандертальцами на Ближнем Востоке в таких памятниках, как Схул и Кафзех. Поскольку одни и те же леваллуазские и мустьерские методы применяли и неандертальцы, и ранние современные люди, каменные орудия сами по себе часто не позволяют определить, какой вид человека их изготовил. Соответствующие африканские находки, которые принадлежат Homo sapiens, а не неандертальцам, получили отдельное название — средний каменный век — и несут наиболее сильные ранние намёки на символическую жизнь — куски охры с гравированными узорами и просверлённые раковинные бусины из таких памятников, как пещера Бломбос. Надёжные свидетельства показывают, что они владели огнём и приготовлением пищи, охотились на крупную дичь и прикрепляли каменные наконечники к древкам с помощью смолы, хотя утверждения о преднамеренных погребениях, искусстве и ритуалах остаются предметом споров и куда менее достоверны. Средний палеолит завершается с началом верхнего палеолита, около 40 000 лет назад, когда современные люди широко расселились, пластинчатые орудия и резные украшения умножились, а неандертальцы сошли на нет — знаменитые фигуративные пещерные росписи принадлежат той более поздней эпохе, а не этой.","answerText":"Средний палеолит"},"ar":{"question":"يقع بين عصر الفأس اليدوية وعصر رسّامي الكهوف، ويمثّل <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> المرحلةَ الوسطى من العصر الحجري القديم، الممتدّة من نحو ٣٠٠٬٠٠٠ إلى ٤٠٬٠٠٠ سنة مضت، ويتميّز بطريقة ليفالوا في اقتطاع شظية مُخطَّط لها مسبقًا من نواة مُشكَّلة — وهو قبل كل شيء عالم النياندرتال وأدواتهم الموستيرية.","answer":"العصر الحجري القديم الأوسط","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">الحقبة</span><span class=\"dt-v\">المرحلة الوسطى من العصر الحجري القديم؛ من انتشار صناعة الأدوات بطريقة ليفالوا ذات النواة المهيأة، نحو ٣٠٠٬٠٠٠ سنة مضت، إلى ظهور العصر الحجري القديم الأعلى، نحو ٥٠٬٠٠٠–٤٠٬٠٠٠ سنة مضت؛ حقبة النياندرتال والثقافة الموستيرية</span></div>","abstract":"يُمثّل <b>العصر الحجري القديم الأوسط</b> القسم الأوسط من أقسام العصر الحجري القديم الثلاثة، وهو الفصل الطويل الذي يقع بين ثقافات الفأس اليدوية التي سبقته وثقافات الأدوات النصلية والفنّ التي تلته. ويمتدّ، بحسب الاصطلاح، من نحو ٣٠٠٬٠٠٠ إلى نحو ٤٠٬٠٠٠ سنة مضت، وإن كان طرفاه متدرّجين يتباينان من منطقة إلى أخرى بدلًا من أن يحدّدا لحظة بعينها. ولا تُحدَّد بدايته بتاريخ بل بأسلوب تقني — هو طريقة النواة المهيأة أو ليفالوا، حيث يُشكّل صانع الأدوات النواة مسبقًا لتُقتطع منها شظية ذات حجم وشكل مخطَّط لهما بضربة واحدة. وقد حلّت هذه الصناعة من الطراز الثالث محلّ الفأس اليدوية الآشولية الأقدم بشظايا أخفّ وأكثر توحيدًا يمكن تثبيتها في مقابض لصنع أدوات مركّبة كالرماح ذات الرؤوس الحجرية. وفي أوروبا وغرب آسيا كانت هذه الحقبة قبل كل شيء عالم النياندرتال، الذين تُسمّى عُدّتهم النمطية الغنية بالمكاشط والرؤوس المدبّبة بالثقافة الموستيرية نسبةً إلى الملجأ الصخري الفرنسي لو موستييه. <br><br> غير أنّ النياندرتال لم يكونوا وحدهم: فقد جاب الدينيسوفان أرجاء آسيا، وكان أبناء نوعنا الأوائل، الإنسان العاقل، حاضرين بالفعل، يلتقون بالنياندرتال في الشرق الأدنى في مواقع كالسخول وقفزة. ولأنّ طريقتَي ليفالوا والموستيرية نفسَيهما استُخدمتا لدى كلٍّ من النياندرتال والبشر المحدثين الأوائل، فإنّ الأدوات الحجرية وحدها كثيرًا ما تعجز عن الكشف عن أيّ نوعٍ من البشر صنعها. أمّا السجلّ الأفريقي المناظر، الذي يعود إلى الإنسان العاقل لا إلى النياندرتال، فيُعطى اسمًا منفصلًا هو العصر الحجري الأوسط، وهو يحمل أقوى المؤشّرات المبكرة على حياة رمزية — قطعًا من المغرة منقوشة بأنماط وخرزات من الأصداف المثقوبة من مواقع مثل كهف بلومبوس. وتُظهر أدلّة راسخة أنّهم أتقنوا النار والطهي، وصادوا الطرائد الكبيرة، ولصقوا الرؤوس الحجرية بالمقابض باستخدام القطران، وإن ظلّت الادّعاءات المتعلّقة بالدفن المتعمَّد والفنّ والطقوس موضع جدل وأقلّ يقينًا بكثير. وينتهي العصر الحجري القديم الأوسط مع بداية العصر الحجري القديم الأعلى، نحو ٤٠٬٠٠٠ سنة مضت، حين انتشر البشر المحدثون على نطاق واسع، وتكاثرت الأدوات النصلية والحُلى المنحوتة، وتلاشى النياندرتال — أمّا الرسوم الكهفية التصويرية الشهيرة فتعود إلى تلك الحقبة اللاحقة لا إلى هذه.","answerText":"العصر الحجري القديم الأوسط"},"zh":{"question":"介于手斧时代与洞穴壁画时代之间，<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>是旧石器时代的中间阶段，大约从30万年前延续到4万年前，其标志是从预制石核上剥离出事先设计好的石片的勒瓦娄哇技术——尤以尼安德特人及其莫斯特工具的世界为代表。","answer":"旧石器时代中期","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">时代</span><span class=\"dt-v\">旧石器时代的中间阶段；始于约30万年前预制石核勒瓦娄哇制石技术的传播，至约5万至4万年前旧石器时代晚期的兴起；尼安德特人与莫斯特文化的时代</span></div>","abstract":"<b>旧石器时代中期</b>是旧石器时代三大分期中居中的一段，这一漫长的篇章介于其前的手斧文化与其后的石叶与艺术文化之间。按惯例，它大约从30万年前延续到4万年前，不过其起止两端都是渐进的，且因地区而异，并不对应任何确切的时刻。它的开端并非由某个年代界定，而是由一种技术界定——即预制石核技术，又称勒瓦娄哇技术，制石者事先将石核修整成形，从而一击即可剥下预定大小与形状的石片。这种第三模式的制作工艺以更轻、更规整的石片取代了更古老的阿舍利手斧，这些石片可安装到木柄上，制成诸如石尖矛之类的复合工具。在欧洲与西亚，这一时期首先是尼安德特人的世界，他们典型的工具组合富含刮削器与尖状器，因法国的勒穆斯捷岩棚而得名莫斯特文化。 <br><br> 然而尼安德特人并非独处：丹尼索瓦人游荡于亚洲各地，而我们自身物种智人的早期成员也已出现，并在近东的斯虎尔、卡夫扎等遗址与尼安德特人相遇。由于尼安德特人与早期现代人都使用同样的勒瓦娄哇与莫斯特技术，石器本身往往无法揭示究竟是哪一种人所制。与之相应的非洲记录属于智人而非尼安德特人，被冠以另一个名称——中期石器时代，它保存着象征性生活最有力的早期线索——刻有纹样的赭石块，以及来自布隆伯斯洞穴等遗址的穿孔贝壳珠。确凿的证据表明他们掌握了用火与烹饪，猎取大型猎物，并用沥青将石尖粘接到木柄上，不过关于有意埋葬、艺术与仪式的说法仍存争议，也远不那么确定。旧石器时代中期在约4万年前旧石器时代晚期开始之际结束，那时现代人广泛扩散，石叶工具与雕刻饰物大量涌现，尼安德特人则逐渐消亡——那些著名的具象洞穴壁画属于其后的那个时代，而非这一时期。","answerText":"旧石器时代中期"}}}
];

